<P>
<TABLE border>
<TR valign=top><TD>
<P><IMG src="122_0.gif"></TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P><H2>World Congress Against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children</H2></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>
<P><IMG src="122_1.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<P><H2>Backgrounder 2:  Child pornography</H2><BR>
Child pornography is an element in the spectrum of commercial sexual abuse of children which occupies a distinct and reputedly lucrative niche in the growing global pornography market.<BR>

<P>Pornography -- the sexually explicit reproduction of a childs image (1) -- is a violation of childrens rights and an abuse with serious physical and emotional effects. These include the impairment of childrens psychosocial development, emotional withdrawal, anti-social behaviour, mood swings, depression, fear, anxiety, disease and injuries. It is however, a complex issue with varying degrees of abuse.<BR>

<P>The production of child pornography is often a clandestine and isolating activity, enveloped in an aura of shame and secrecy. Children coerced or lured into its production may experience a great sense of confusion, disorientation and alienation. A modeling effect has been observed, with the children often learning to associate sex with force and violence, and identifying with and becoming emotionally dependent on the exploiters. They also are at risk of becoming perpetrators or abusers themselves. (2)<BR>

<P>The simple fact that child pornography is recorded -- on film, videotape or increasingly computer disks -- gives it a wide range and scope. Children not involved in the production of pornographic material can be forced by adults to view it to wear down their inhibitions and resistance to sexual encounters. This makes pornography not only exploitative in itself, but  a tool for potential further exploitation.<BR>

<P>The technology needed to create child pornography is generally more available in industrialised countries, but such materials are made and viewed virtually all over the world. Child pornography can depict infants as well as older children. Both boys and girls are involved: more than 50 per cent of the child pornography seized in the United States depicts boys, while in Japan young girls are the subject. <BR>

<P>Many of the same factors leading to childrens involvement in prostitution drive their involvement in pornography. Those from poor, abusive, or broken homes are  most vulnerable to the combination of coercion, seduction and force used to recruit them.<BR>

<P><B>The Exploiters</B><BR>
Child pornography can be a lucrative business for the producers, middlemen, and distributors. However, it is widely circulated without cost among paedophiles and other users. Most of the child pornography seized in the United States, for example, has not been produced or distributed for commercial gain but was exchanged informally for personal consumption. (3)   Paedophiles -- defined as those who are primarily sexually attracted to prepubescent children -- account for a significant portion of the market. However, there is a new and growing segment of child pornography consumers.<BR>

<P>There is also a link between child pornography and sex tourism. A large proportion of the child pornography seized in Sweden and the Netherlands in the last few years, for example, was produced by sex tourists visiting Asia.<BR>

<P><B>Challenges posed by technology</B><BR>
Technology, as it makes rapid advances, has opened new possibilities for the producers, distributors and users of child pornography. Most dramatic have been the changes ushered in by personal computers. For legislators, social workers and the police, complex issues and daunting challenges have emerged.<BR>

<P>As recently as a decade ago, most pornographers relied on photographs and film, largely commercially processed, which led to regular tips about sexually explicit material to the authorities -- and many prosecutions -- from people working in the processing shops.<BR>

<P>With the advent of home videos, which eliminated the need for commercial film processing, such tips and prosecutions dried up. Video technology also now means that the studio is someones home, where perpetrators can film children  with minimum risk of discovery.<BR>

<P>More daunting still, the computer has further revolutionised transmission and distribution in the 1990s. Unlike photographs and videos, computer-transmitted pornography is much harder to detect (and knows no boundaries).  <BR>

<P>The Internet -- with nearly 30 million users -- makes pornography potentially accessible to anyone with a computer and a modem. Computers can scan pictures and capture video clips, and mail them electronically almost instantaneously. Detection is thwarted also, since electronic transmission helps mask the senders identity and ensures anonymity while routing messages anywhere in the world. The use of inexpensive, user-friendly encryption software also makes it difficult and time-consuming for police to ascertain exactly what is being transmitted.<BR>

<P><B>Legislation and enforcement</B><BR>
The international scale and underground nature of child pornography make legislative and police efforts especially difficult. So too does the variety and scope and non-complementarity of laws against child pornography that different countries have.<BR>

<P>In January 1995, the Netherlands government amended the Penal Code to make it an offence to distribute, make, import or possess pornographic materials depicting children manifestly under the age of 16; transfer or possession of such material on a data carrier is included.  In July 1994, the Austrian parliament passed an amendment to the Penal Code to outlaw the trade in child pornography and sanction even the possession of such material.  The possession of child pornography is also a criminal offence in Belgium, Canada, Denmark, Estonia, France, Germany, the United Kingdom and the United States. In 1994 the US Penal Code was amended to allow federal authorities to prosecute persons involved in the production overseas of child pornography if that pornography is intended for import into the US. <BR>

<P>The experience of police in enforcing this wide variety of laws relating to pornography has led INTERPOLs Standing Working Party on Offences against Minors to recommend that member countries enact legislation which would make it an offence to produce, distribute or possess child pornography in its present and future forms.<BR>

<P>New laws, or tougher enforcement and prosecution, have succeeded in curbing the production of child pornography in some countries, only to have it move elsewhere. A spate of legislation and crackdowns in the late 1970s and 1980s has driven many producers from Denmark and Sweden to former communist countries in Eastern Europe.<BR>

<P>In the largest international effort ever to curb the dissemination of child pornography over the Internet, six governments collaborated in Operation Starburst, an investigation spanning four continents over many months. It led to the arrest of more than 40 people accused of using the Internet to view and distribute child pornography (4)<BR>

<P>But many questions about civil liberties and privacy, as well as the limitations of existing legislation will challenge investigators and lawyers for some time to come. Ron Grady, international coordinator for End Child Prostitution in Asian Tourism (ECPAT), explains some of the difficulties in defining the issues that computer technology raises:<BR>

<P> &quot;At what point is the crime committed? Is the criminal the one who places material on the net, or is it the server who transmits the message? Or is it the one who downloads the material into their computer? The person sending the material may send it from a country where it is legal to do so, but it may go to a country where it is illegal, so who determines the standard for the crime?&quot; (4)<BR>

<P>The questions are likely to become even more complicated. Computers, for instance, will soon be able to simulate life-like images of children, which could be used to create pornography and thus eliminate the need for real life child &quot;actors&quot;. Such computer-generated child pornography will challenge much existing legislation, which is framed to prevent harm to real-life people. However, lawmakers in Australia's New South Wales have outlawed possession of such material, arguing that it can be used by abusers to harm and seduce children.<BR>

<P>Internet providers are launching their own schemes to cope with the threat. In May 1996, Unipalm Pipex, the largest provider of Internet access to British businesses, announced that it would stop supplying access to discussion groups that publish pictures of young children. It is also supplying software programmes that enable service providers as well as parents to control access to sexually explicit material.  That same month, a consortium of 39 Internet-related firms including giants such as CompuServe and America Online launched their own scheme for voluntary access restriction.<BR>

<P>REFERENCES<BR>
1	This definition is taken from Kenneth V.  Lanning, <I>Child Molesters: A behavioural analysis </I>(1992), and is the one adopted in working papers for the World Congress against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children. <BR>
 2	<I>Child pornography: an international perspective</I>, Margaret A.  Healy for the ECPAT working group on child pornography, May 1996, p.194  -- a working paper for the World Congress against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children.<BR>
3	Healy, <I>op.cit.</I>  P.8.<BR>
4	West Midlands Police Press Release, 31/10/95<BR>
5	 <I>Child pornography in the computer age</I>, Ron OGrady, undated speech [1996]. <BR>
 
