<P><IMG src="122_0.gif"></TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P><H2>World Congress Against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children</H2></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>
<P><IMG src="122_1.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<P><H2>Feature 4:  Mozambique</H2><BR>
<B>Sarita's new clothes</B><BR>

<P>Poverty increasingly drives children onto the streets of Mozambique's big cities.  There, they hope to survive.  There, they hope to earn a little money for themselves and their families.  UNICEF estimates the number of street children in Mozambique at 5,000.  For many girls, life on the streets leads to prostitution.<BR>

<P>Tine Larsen is Director of a centre for street children called &quot;Citadela das Criancas&quot;, located some 15 kilometres to the north of the capital, Maputo.  One hundred children live in the bright yellow stone houses of Citadela.  They go to school here and live either with foster parents in the nearby village or in Citadela itself.  About half the children are girls.<BR>

<P>&quot;Most of the girls earned money as prostitutes in Maputo,&quot; Larsen says.  &quot;We found most of them in the harbour district, working for a woman who forced them into prostitution.  We contacted the police, but they didn't help.  In the end we reached an agreement with the woman:  we took her own two children into Citadela and, in return, she promised to send us any girls who knocked on her door&quot;.<BR>

<P>Sarita plucks self-consciously at her pink dress. A shy smile flits briefly across her face. &quot;That's new.  And expensive,&quot; Larsen explains.  &quot;You can guess where she got the money for it.&quot;  Tine Larsen has learned to see things realistically.  It's much easier for boys to become accustomed to life behind the protective walls of Citadela than it is for the girls.  &quot;Our girls know how quickly and easily they can earn money, relatively big money, outside.  With their bodies, they earn more than a well-educated teacher.  The motivation to learn a real profession and go to school is consequently not high,&quot; Larsen says.<BR>

<P>Sarita has been in the custody of her caretaker for two weeks.  Before that she was away for three months.  &quot;Sometimes she goes two or three times a month to Maputo,&quot; Larsen explains.  She wants to go back to her friends.  Her friends are still on the street.  It's hard for her to stay at Citadela.<BR>

<P>What causes girls like Sarita to work on the streets?  Gloria Fernandez, the UNICEF programme director for street children and prostitutes in Maputo, suggests that an important cause is violence in the family.  &quot;Many Mozambican men were killed in the war, or left their wives in the country and began a new life in the city,&quot; she explains.<BR>

<P>Sarita's biological father was killed in the civil war. She was brutally beaten by her stepfather.  To escape, she ran away from home at the age of ten.  A year later, her mother died and Sarita found her way to the woman in the harbour district, who offered her housing, money and food.  She stayed in order to survive.<BR>

<P>Many of the girls who sell their bodies, though, have families.  In Beira, the second largest city in Mozambique, ninety per cent of the child prostitutes have families.  A recent study by UNICEF in Maputo and Beira shows that more than half the girls come from poor villages in surrounding provinces.  In these villages there is a battle for survival.  Often it is the parents themselves who send the girls to the big city, either to rid themselves of one mouth to feed or to increase the family income.  The study shows that nearly twenty per cent of the families are economically dependent on the incomes of their daughters.<BR>

<P>With the severe poverty in Mozambique and the money that can be earned on the streets, it is difficult to rescue the girls.  But the Citadela has a regular daily schedule that leaves each child enough room for creativity, play and conversation.  The children get up at 5.30 am to bathe and clean up their rooms.  Women from the village help them.  Breakfast is at 7.00 and then comes the morning ritual:  the singing of the national anthem, a symbol of the 1992 peace treaty.  The children go to school until midday.  It is free of charge.  <BR>

<P>After class, they eat lunch.  School continues in the afternoon, and the children learn practical lessons through play.  For example, they rehearse plays which touch on issues of hygiene and health.  Afterwards, they choose from an offering of workshops: pottery, agriculture, basket-weaving, sewing, bookbinding, carpentry, gardening or animal husbandry.  &quot;This training gives the children the possibility either of following a further course of study or, based on their training, taking a job,&quot; Tine Larsen says.<BR>

<P>In Mozambique, in addition to Citadela, UNICEF supports twenty projects for street children and child prostitutes.  Most of these houses are in Maputo and Beira.  Gloria Fernandez describes the challenge:  &quot;We have to clear the way for these girls, as difficult as that task is.  What we can give them for their future is a good education and a feeling of security within a community&quot;.<BR>

<P><CENTER><hr><P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="factsheets.htm">Factsheets</A> | <A HREF="theme.htm">Theme Papers</A> | <A HREF="declaration.htm">Declaration</A> | <A HREF="links.htm">Links</A> | <A HREF="press.htm">Press materials</A>  <BR><A HREF="reports.htm">Congress reports</A> | <A HREF="intpress.htm">Interesting press</A> <BR><A HREF="default.htm">CSEC Home Page</A></P></CENTER><hr>
