<P><IMG src="122_0.gif"></TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P><H2>World Congress Against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children</H2></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>
<P><IMG src="122_1.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<P><H2>Feature 5:  Europe</H2><BR>
<B>Europe's sexually exploited children: coming home</B><BR>

<P>
<P>In 1994 a 16-year old girl was deported from Israel back to her home country on the grounds that she was in possession of a false passport.  It transpired that she had been taken to Israel and forced to work as a prostitute in a brothel.  During her stay -- just three weeks -- she served some 200 men and US$3.000 changed hands.<BR>

<P>The girl was not from Thailand, the Philippines or Nepal.  She was not from Brazil or Colombia or the Dominican Republic.  She was not from any of the countries which have featured in the media over the last six years, since ECPAT (End Child Prostitution in Asian Tourism) first began its pioneering work with media and governments to put the issue of commercial sexual exploitation of children in Asia onto the public agenda.<BR>

<P>The girl was from Lithuania.  She was European.<BR>

<P>For many years, Europe has figured in the literature on commercial sexual exploitation of children as an area from where paedophiles and others sexually interested in children have travelled on jaunts to buy children for sex.  Now the issue has come home.<BR>

<P>Commercial sexual exploitation of children, which involves young people under 18 years of age coerced into prostitution by people or circumstances, used in pornography or trafficked across borders to be used in the sex trade, knows no national or cultural limits.  The UK-based Committee on Child Abuse Networks has called commercial sexual exploitation a major threat to Europes new generation.<BR>

<P><B>Europeans in Asia</B><BR>
Since 1993, more than 80 European nationals have been arrested in Asia on charges related to sex with minors.  Sweden was the first European country to jail a national convicted of sex crimes with a child while overseas; Germany, France, Denmark, Ireland, Iceland, Italy, Switzerland and Norway have also passed or extended extraterritorial legislation to allow the prosecution of nationals for offences committed overseas.<BR>

<P>But laws and law enforcement to protect children from sexual exploitation on European soil have not kept pace with the times.  In the past five years, commercial values have flooded new markets in Eastern Europe.  At the same time, the social services which protected children and helped families during the communist era have vanished.  In consequence, exploiters have found both the opportunity and the means to exploit circumstances and the children trapped by them.  Families living in poverty, broken apart by societies in disarray or conflict, and the globalisation of markets have led to an increase in the children available for exploitation and the exploiters ready to trade them.  <BR>

<P><B>Children of Eastern Europe</B><BR>
The destruction of rigid communist structures has in many cases come too fast to be replaced by new systems.  Some quarter of a million children in Eastern Europe live in childrens homes, with at least another 100,000 trying to survive on the streets.  Children who used to live around Moscows railway stations, for example, have been forced into the streets.  In Bucharest, Romanian children are cared for by pimps who sell them for a few dollars.<BR>

<P>Those in institutions are not necessarily better off.  Children are bought, or adopted in Poland, Romania and other eastern countries by British, Swiss and Scandinavian paedophiles.  Reports indicate that healthy Polish children can be bought outright for $25,000.  Others are adopted from cash-strapped orphanages whose directors may accept bribes to concoct the legal documents, or else let their charges be taken.<BR>

<P>And so the trafficking of children from Eastern Europe into the countries of the West has grown.  Once in Western Europe, the children are often passed through paedophile networks until they effectively disappear.  <BR>

<P>But the exploited children of Europe do not only come from the East.<BR>

<P><B>Children of the West</B><BR>
One of the most worrying trends to surface in recent years in Western Europe has been the number of convictions of adults who have sexually abused the children in their care.  In too many countries, care-takers are subjected to little scrutiny and children are treated with little respect. Social workers, schoolteachers, club leaders, priests and others whose job it is to take responsibility for vulnerable children figure prominently on the lists of those who have been charged or convicted of sexual abuse of children.  This makes helping the children even more difficult for the majority of such workers who are dedicated to protecting children but who face the hurdle of breakdown of trust.<BR>

<P>The number of children on the streets is, by nature, difficult to estimate. However, police, social workers and prostitutes all say more and more young boys and girls are selling themselves.  As many as 5,000 children are believed to be working in the sex trade in England.  Other numbers are scarce, but reports from childrens groups indicate that numbers are growing.<BR>

<P>Although most children in prostitution work on the streets, for most it is not the first time they have been sexually assaulted.  An estimated 60 per cent of children involved in prostitution in England were sexually abused before they began taking clients for cash.  Their sexuality and bodies devalued, the move to the sex trade was made so much easier.<BR>

<P>Loss of self-respect is a powerful factor amongst the factors contributing to commercial sexual exploitation of children.  Poverty is also a powerful indicator of vulnerability to abuse in the home and the risk of sexual exploitation on the streets.  The breakdown of the family, widening income gap, easy availability of drugs and under-funded social services all help to push children in to the sex trade.<BR>

<P>Once there, there is no shortage of clients.  These exploiters -- mostly men -- are involved in criminal behaviour.  Yet, even as the authorities become more aware of the dangers, laws still do not reflect the fact that the children are the victims, rather than the perpetrators, of the crimes.  Still many laws and law enforcers treat the children in prostitution as prostitutes first and children second.  Those caught soliciting in England are warned or prosecuted while their exploiters often are not.<BR>

<P>Richard Koser <I>is an Australian journalist who works also on information projects for humanitarian agencies.</I>
