<P>
<P><H2>World Congress Against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children</H2></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>
<P><IMG src="122_1.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<P><H2>Campaign or complicity/August 1996</H2><BR>
<B>Extract from </B><B><I>CROSSLINES Global Report</I></B><B> August 1996</B><BR>

<P><B>Campaign or complicity:</B><BR>
<B>Reporting commercial sexual exploitation of children</B><BR>
<B>June Kane, Media Advisor to the World Congress</B><BR>

<P>
<P>For five months, day in, day out, I have worked, eaten, slept, breathed the problem of children sold for sex.  Each day more horror stories have crossed my desk; each day the report that surely told the most gruesome story possible has been capped by another even more horrendous.  Each night I have gone home to the comfort and warmth of my little apartment, to open the mail, play with the cat, veg out in front of the television and try to remember that there are sane people left in the world and protective places to hide in.<BR>

<P>Each night, I have redrawn the lines which delineate my own morality as a sexual being, a woman, a mother.  I have checked my reactions to consumer goods, magazine articles, titillating media, friends caresses.  I have questioned motivations, analysed body language, rethought relationships.<BR>

<P>And each morning I have steeled myself again, confident of myself but aware that that confidence would be shaken when I picked up the latest report on what some people -- too many people -- are doing to innocent children in so many parts of the world.<BR>

<P><B><I>Journalists are human too</I></B><BR>
And I have experienced every journalist I have spoken to, on the phone, in person, by fax or e-mail, going through the same process of emotional reaction and personal and professional interrogation.  Many of them have waited until our conversation has moved off the record, or until weve exchanged our second or third e-mail, and have then dropped their guard, telling me of their families, their shock, their astoundment at the calm telling of tales, their panic that the issue is being treated in a sometimes banal manner.<BR>

<P>Commercial sexual exploitation of children is a hard subject to deal with, but it is a story that we have to work with.  And those of us -- journalists and information professionals -- who have somehow to cope with the issue on a professional footing maybe need to understand that we are not alone, that there is a rationale at work here as in all the issues we handle, and that it is the path we take through this logic that can either give us personal and professional satisfaction or leave us on the sidelines, the story hardly told, the emotional impact just a glitch on the smooth surface of our experience.<BR>

<P>In five months as the person responsible for media activities leading up to the World Congress against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children, I have watched enough journalists -- and others on the receiving end of information about commercial sexual exploitation of children -- now to identify three stages in the reaction to the horrific detail of this issue (undoubtedly this same model applies to other bodies of information which are so horrible to grasp):<BR>

<P><B><I>Three stages</I></B><BR>
The first stage is incredulity.  This cant possibly be true.  Who would want to have sex with a three year-old child and then beat it black and blue?<BR>

<P>The second stage follows research into the reports, photos and personal accounts of such horrors.  OK, so it happens.  But over there, not here.  This is the stage many journalists had reached before the information processes leading up to the World Congress began in March 1996.  It is what led journalists from Europe to go to Thailand and other parts of Asia looking for new angles on sexual exploitation of children, when they could have found the stories right on their doorsteps.<BR>

<P>Then comes stage three: realisation.  Oh my God, its happening here.  On the streets where I live.  And I have a five year-old...<BR>

<P>This third stage leads inevitably to fear.  Not anger first, not indignation, but fear.  It is all too tangible, too real, too close to home.  And there are really only two ways to handle fear: by action or acceptance.<BR>

<P>Action leads us to ask, what can I do to stop this?  In many ways, it is the easy option.  As information-providers, we have one of the most powerful tools possible at our fingertips.  We can research, write, campaign, inform, mobilise.  We know that the work we do can make a difference.<BR>

<P>Acceptance leads us to conclude that we cannot do anything, and should just side-step the problem as quickly and painlessly as possible, filing it away in the too hard basket or, worse still, filing it at the level of just another story.  It is the bland statement of fact that renders the topic banal, common-place, unremarkable and so easily ignored.<BR>

<P><B><I>Powerful tools</I></B><BR>
The job of both journalist and information worker, though, is also to deliver facts without prejudice, and this can be difficult when those facts are acknowledged as a powerful tool and the person wielding that tool is emotionally charged and personally committed to the results such power can bring.<BR>

<P>And so the challenge to the reporter or the information worker who wishes to act rather than accept is finding a way to deliver facts (not emotion nor reaction nor personal engagement) without becoming either a campaigner or complicit.<BR>

<P>How can we do that?  How can we report the issues surrounding commercial sexual exploitation of children factually and truthfully without falling into the trap of emotional engagement, editorialising and compromising our independence as information providers?<BR>

<P>I do not have the complete answer to that question -- and that is partly why I am writing this article in the first place: to prompt you to seek out your own personal answer -- but some obvious factors come to mind.<BR>

<P>The first is accuracy.  There is no doubt that the reporting of horrific acts or events with great accuracy and attention to detail is the strongest form of reporting.  With regard to commercial sexual exploitation of children, the details of what people do to children, how they do it, the factors that lie at the root of child sex and the gratification gained by perpetrators -- multiplied by the statistics of occurrence, the geographical spread, the percentage populations affected, the deaths and deadly consequences -- are in themselves potent carriers of the message that selling children for sex is wrong and must be stopped.  In many ways, adding to these details the emotion of personal engagement is in itself a dilution of the report.<BR>

<P>There is no better example of this than the balanced reporting of paedophile claims that their actions towards pre-pubescent children are done out of love and caring for the child, with motives of introducing the child to its sexuality in the arms of a tender adult.  To reason against this engages outrage, emotion and violent reaction.  To juxtapose it with the figures of children touched by HIV/AIDS, psychological trauma leading to suicide, dysfunctionality that hampers normal growth and death from bleeding and internal damage is enough to destroy such fatuous self-justification and consign it forever to the annals of the criminally insane.<BR>

<P>What also dilutes and banalises the reporting of children being sold for sex is the use of clich&eacute;, so easy to fall into when both sex and child are in the title of the story and the writer is emotionally involved in the issue.  Children are the adults of the future is a favourite.  So what are they now?  Do they have to wait until they become adult to earn our respect?  Is it only because they will one day be like us that we should consider them worthwhile?  A modern form of slavery is also much used.  Whats modern about child abuse?  Do we mean that its become fashionable?  Acceptable?  Trendy?  Shouldnt we rather be asking why it has been around for so long with so little action to stop it?<BR>

<P>The choice of vocabulary, too, can lift the story from the banal to the effective.  The difference between a child prostitute and a child sold into prostitution speaks volumes about who is the victim, the role of the exploiter and the likely reaction of the reader.<BR>

<P>Similarly, the names given to the criminals who exploit children are important.    Pimps and madames have an almost hierarchical finesse that is unfitting to the subject. These people are criminals, exploiters, traffickers, kidnappers, dealers, murderers.
<P><CENTER><hr><P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="factsheets.htm">Factsheets</A> | <A HREF="theme.htm">Theme Papers</A> | <A HREF="declaration.htm">Declaration</A> | <A HREF="links.htm">Links</A> | <A HREF="press.htm">Press materials</A>  <BR><A HREF="reports.htm">Congress reports</A> | <A HREF="intpress.htm">Interesting press</A> <BR><A HREF="default.htm">CSEC Home Page</A></P></CENTER><hr>
</BODY>
