<P><IMG src="122_0.gif"></TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P><H2>World Congress Against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children</H2></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>
<P><IMG src="122_1.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<P><H2>Not just a numbers game/October 1996</H2><BR>
<B>Extract from </B><B><I>CROSSLINES Global Report</I></B><B>, October 1996</B><BR>

<P><B>Not just a numbers game</B><BR>
<B>June Kane</B><BR>

<P><I>In the August edition of </I>Crosslines <I>and in a special edition published in September, the issue of commercial sexual exploitation of children was put under the spotlight as a contribution to the first World Congress Against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children.  Now</I><B><I> </I></B><B>June Kane</B><B><I>,</I></B><I> Media Advisor to the Congress, does the sums and takes a calculated look at what was achieved.</I> <BR>

<P>More than a million children entering the sex trade every year, two thousand children living on the streets of Romanias larger cities and vulnerable to exploitation, 500,000 children sold into prostitution in India, at least another half a million in the cities of South America, billions of dollars in profit going to those who feed off the bodies of children, ten to twelve million adult male customers every week sexually exploiting the children of Asia alone.   Estimates that horrify, mesmerise, numb. <BR>

<P>But now the figures are beginning to stack up on the other side: 718 government representatives, 105 members of United Nations and other intergovernmental organisations, 471 NGO delegates, 47 young people and organisers and, last but not least, 538 members of the worlds press.  These make up the 1,879 people who attended the first World Congress Against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children in Stockholm from 27 to 31 August 1996.  Add these to the 188 countries that have signed or ratified the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child, the 14 jurisdictions that have in place extraterritoriality laws, the 32 countries which run UNICEF-sponsored programmes to help prevent or rehabilitate children entering the sex trade, six regional preparatory consultations which formed platforms for action after the Congress, the 20 countries in which the ECPAT campaign has waged war for the past five years, and the 38 NGOs which belong to the NGO Group on the Convention for the Rights of the Child and, although the maths still dont seem overwhelmingly to favour those working with and on behalf of children, the scales definitely seem to be tipping.<BR>

<P>Perhaps the most important outcome of the Stockholm Congress was, in fact, almost mathematical.  For some time we have known that the only way to effectively combat the complex, multi-faceted problem of children being sold for sex was by international, multi-sectoral cooperation.  We cannot solve this problem by throwing money at it, by introducing isolated national legislation, by running programmes in some areas where donor funds are available and not in others, by focusing on one part of the problem and leaving the more difficult ones on the sidelines.  The solutions have to be as complex and inter-dependent as the problem, and this is what everyone agrees was achieved in Stockholm.  In formal workshops as well as informal coffee-and-cake meetings, people dedicated to doing something to stop commercial sexual exploitation of children exchanged experiences, formed alliances and began to build the networks which at last can start to match the organised rings and mafia-style structures of international child traffickers, pimps, procurers and clients.<BR>

<P>More tangibly, delegates at the Congress on 28 August unanimously approved and adopted a Declaration and Plan of Action which is more than just a wish-list to be filed away with the map of Stockholm and engraved invitation to the City Hall.  In the words of Professor Vitit Muntarbhorn, General Rapporteur of the Congress and a long-time campaigner for child rights, the Agenda for Action is a checklist, something that we can look through and mark off whether we have kept our promises or not.  The presence of many NGOs at the Congress -- on an equal footing with governments and inter-governmental agencies -- means that these police of the humanitarian world will not only themselves programme follow-up activity but also keep governments honest, lobbying public opinion, pointing to governments and agencies defaulting on promises and pushing for action wherever they can.<BR>

<P>The Agenda has two time-frames: by the year 2000, governments in Stockholm committed themselves to urgently strengthening comprehensive, cross-sectoral and integrated strategies and measures so that ... there are national agendas for action and indicators of progress, with set goals and time frames for implementation, targeted to reducing the number of children vulnerable to commercial sexual exploitation and nurturing an environment, attitudes and practices responsive to child rights.<BR>

<P>Also by the year 2000, local and national cooperation will result in urgent [development] of implementation and monitoring mechanisms or focal points at the national and local levels, in cooperation with civil society, so that ... there are data bases on children vulnerable to commercial sexual exploitation, and on their exploiters, with relevant research and special attention to disaggregation data by age, gender, ethnicity, indigenous status, circumstances affecting commercial sexual exploitation and respect for confidentiality of the child victims especially in regard to public disclosures.<BR>

<P>This tracking initiative has already received wide coverage, with several governments promising soon after the Congress closed to put in place registers of convicted abusers and to share these within the international law enforcement community.  <BR>

<P>The call for research on both vulnerable children and those who exploit them exemplifies another of the major issues to emerge from the Congress: that the emphasis on the child victim must shift to give equal weight in research and programming to the perpetrators of crime too.  The demand side of the equation, if you will, as well as the supply side.  It is the sex exploiters, the customers and the seedy side of the business sector and their chain of allies such as pimps, procurers, brothel owners and traffickers which must equally be countered and penalised, according to Professor Muntarbhorn.<BR>

<P>The call for penalties -- through the criminalisation of all forms of sexual exploitation of children, including production and possession of pornography, transmission of exploitative materials and information contributing to exploitation on the Internet -- was also loud and clear.  In a panel discussion and workshops on the role of the media, delegates recommended the establishment of a single body, potentially within the UN system, to regulate and monitor the global transmission of information which might be deleterious to child rights. <BR>

<P>On the question of regulation of the media, however, there was unanimous agreement that media professionals are best encouraged to self-regulate, with a call for existing support mechanisms for the ethics of journalism to be strengthened and for NGOs and UNICEF to collaborate in helping the professions of the media to incorporate an understanding of child rights into their work.<BR>

<P>The question of the image of the child, sexuality and childhood promulgated in the media also came under discussion.  Again, there was a call for sensitivity and personal and professional ethics in dealing not only with children subjected to exploitation in order not to exploit them anew, but also to allowing children to be children and not putting pressure on them, through advertising and the hard sell, to move too quickly into the world of consumer values and sex as a commodity.  The positive power of the media to advocate on behalf of children, report violations of their rights, reinforce values, educate and underpin democracy was also stressed.<BR>

<P>The interest of so many members of the worlds press -- 538 accredited journalists at the Congress, a hundred or so more who phoned in for interviews or documents, 700 on the mailing list for pre-Congress materials, and the hordes who ran stories from the wires and from syndication -- bodes well for keeping the issue of commercial sexual exploitation of children firmly on the public agenda, where it rightly belongs.  The Internet itself, a topic of hot debate at the Congress, also allowed the opportunity for the creation of a Congress Web site from which 19,000 Kilobytes of information were downloaded in the last week of August.<BR>

<P>Two memorable quotes to end this summary: first, from Vitit Muntarbhorn, who told delegates there can be no more delusions -- children are being sold for sex everywhere in the world, whether governments will admit it or not.  The media have played a major role in making this known.  And from Ron OGrady, International Coordinator of ECPAT, on the results of raised public awareness, not least amongst vulnerable children themselves: I say to exploiters everywhere, Beware.  Little sister is watching you.
<P><CENTER><hr><P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="factsheets.htm">Factsheets</A> | <A HREF="theme.htm">Theme Papers</A> | <A HREF="declaration.htm">Declaration</A> | <A HREF="links.htm">Links</A> | <A HREF="press.htm">Press materials</A>  <BR><A HREF="reports.htm">Congress reports</A> | <A HREF="intpress.htm">Interesting press</A> <BR><A HREF="default.htm">CSEC Home Page</A></P></CENTER><hr>
</BODY>
