<HTML> 
<HEAD>
<TITLE> DocumentDescriptions</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<P>
<P>
<TABLE border>
<TR valign=top><TD>
<P><IMG src="122_0.gif"></TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P><H2>World Congress Against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children</H2></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>
<P><IMG src="122_1.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<P><H2>KEYNOTE SPEECH Ofelia Calcetas-Santos,<BR>
UN Special Rapporteur on the Sale of Children,<BR>
Child Prostitution and Child Pornography</H2><BR>
The First World Congress Against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children is a milestone in child protection. History tells us that child abuse is nothing new, whether it partakes of physical, psychological or sexual nature.<BR>

<P>Commercial sexual exploitation of children is an assault on children on all fronts. It is considered to be a form of forced labour, yet it is worse than most forms of forced labour. It is considered a kind of slavery, yet it is worse than most kinds of slavery. It is totally vile and is the most contemptible violation of human rights imaginable.<BR>

<P>I would like to congratulate the organizers: UNICEF, ECPAT and Radda Barnen (<I>sic</I> =  NGO Group on the Rights of the Child). It is about time that the whole world regard children not from the point of power concomitant with ownership and dominion, but from the point of responsibility to see to it that the very vulnerability that is taken advantage of and makes children easy prey should be the same vulnerability that precisely gives them entitlement to special care and protection.<BR>

<P>The United Nations, in a series of international documents have tried to address this concern for several decades now. I will not go into these documents as they are among the papers given to you. Let me just say that these series of international documents culminated with the Convention of the Rights of the Child, which now serves as the international bible on child rights. What is remarkable about this Convention is the fact that it did not suffer the same lackadaisical acceptance of its predecessors. Instead, it does down in history as the first international document to receive universal acceptance in such a short period of time. The world is at long last sitting up and taking notice.<BR>

<P>In recognition of the importance of the protection of children from sexual abuse and exploitation, the UN Commission on Human Rights created the post of Special Rapporteur on the Sale of Children, Child Prostitution and Child Pornography in 1990, a post which I am privileged to hold today. The main function of this position is to serve as the UN focal point for both government and non-government organizations and individuals to report problem areas and recommend solutions.<BR>

<P>There are certain characteristics that typify most activities on commercial sexual exploitation of children. Some of these are the following:<BR>

<P>1.	It is invisible. Children drawn into the net of prostitution are for the most part hidden from public scrutiny, either physically (they are not placed on display as their adult counterparts), or under the guise of being of age, though the falsification of identification papers.<BR>

<P>2.	It is mobile. The invisible nature of the phenomenon necessitates not only deviation from the usual places of operation like brothels, hotels, bars, and the like, but also frequent changes in the areas of operation.<BR>

<P>3.	It is global. While the gravity of the situation for children may vary from region to region or from country to country, reports show that this kind of child abuse exists in practically all corners of the world. The contagious nature of the phenomenon causes the blurring of lines between sending and receiving countries. Some countries which used to be considered as supply countries are getting to be demand countries also. Likewise children of countries heretofore considered only as the demand side are starting to be victimized either in their own country or elsewhere.<BR>

<P>4.	It is escalating. Fear of AIDS and other STDs, inter alia, leads to a greater demand for younger sexual partners. Children used to be substitutes for adult prostitutes; now, however, there is marked increase of preference for children over adults, pushing up the worth of children in the sex market.<BR>

<P>5.	It is a highly profitable business. This is best borne out by the fact that not only does it involve ad hoc or individual entrepreneurs, it is very often conducted by international profiteers using systematic methods of recruitment within a highly organized syndicated network, often also involved in other criminal activities as drug dealing.<BR>

<P>The multifarious workshops scheduled for the duration of the conference will address specific topics crucial to our concern, and from which I am certain we will glean valuable recommendations. For this afternoon, therefore, within the time constraints, limit myself to some words of caveat:<BR>

<P>1.	Adult prostitution and prostitution involving children are two very distinct issues. While it may be granted that states may have the right to determine for themselves whether or not to legalize adult prostitution, that option is not open to them as far as children are concerned. There should be no ambivalence in declaring the illegality and immorality of commercial sexual exploitation of children. Neither should there be any doubt that in this particular aspect, children are never the perpetrators of the offence, but the victims thereof.<BR>

<P>Likewise, there should be no distinction drawn between children who are perceived to enter into prostitution voluntarily and those who are forced, deceived or misled. Voluntariness almost always does not imply free choice but rather lack of choice, taken in the context of the political, economic, cultural or social circumstances attendant.<BR>

<P>2.	Recovery or rehabilitation is much more expensive, more difficult to implement, and oftentimes fails to yield effective and sustainable results. The value of prevention cannot therefore be underestimated. But preventive measures should be coupled with strategies to sensitize and motivate political will. This is essential, because, unfortunately, governments tend to denigrate the value of prevention because it does not have as dramatic a political impact as recovery or rehabilitation.<BR>

<P>3.	There must be prioritization of strategies especially where resources are limited. Prioritization may be based on certain criteria, as first things first, worst things first, or catch as catch can. Each one of these approaches may have its pros and its cons, but whatever standard is adopted, it should be based on its do ability and implement ability. It should enhance feeling of gratification which would encourage intensification of further efforts.<BR>

<P>4.	There must be synchronization of penalties, both in their nature and in their gravity. The response of some countries, like the Philippines, is to significantly increase penalties for crimes committed against children. While this may work as a deterrent on the national level where the offender is also a citizen of the same country, this may have an adverse effect where foreigners are involved. International cooperation is difficult to achieve where there is a serious variance between the imposable sentence of the situs of the offense and the country of the offender.<BR>

<P>5.	Response processes should not further victimize the child. Multiple victimization can happen practically at all levels of response in the hands of untrained and insensitive assistance. Even programmes conceptualized to create heightened awareness on the existence of the abuse could backlash to cause damage not anticipated. I remember having seen a video film on pederasty. The well-intentioned project, while it achieved success in shocking people into awareness of the existence of the problem, has also catapulted the boys who were featured therein to instant stardom, generating demands for their services never before experienced.<BR>

<P>Where children are victims of trafficking across frontiers, victimization can start from the retrieval of the children from their employers, then to the referral to immigration authorities prior to their repatriation, then to the manner by which the children are transported, then to their reception by the immigration authorities of their country of origin, and even up to their release either to their families or to welfare organizations.<BR>

<P>Should actual cases be filed under the justice system in connection with the abuse, newer dimensions are added to the childs vulnerability. Abuse or ineptness of legal systems gives rise to further victimization made more deplorable by the fact that it works under the mantle of imperatives of the rule of law. The cruelty inflicted by and in court processes is more revolting than the crimes, leaving the child with an utter feeling of disillusionment and hopelessness.<BR>

<P>6.	Coherence is another very important factor to consider in the conceptualization of national policies, programmes and strategies. This requires the integration of concerns of children in all the aspects of government activities so that children are not unwittingly waylaid by efforts to find solution to other problems.<BR>

<P>Coherence should likewise be the guiding principle even on the international level, including the UN family. The peacekeeping activities of the UN, for example, should not provide a fertile ground for germination of commercial sexual exploitation of children in the name of providing the soldiers with rest and recreation.<BR>

<P>Another example is in the elimination of child labour, which should not result in driving children from the proverbial frying pan into the fire, so to speak. For while having children trapped in certain unhealthy working conditions may be far from ideal, simply closing this door to children without providing them with viable alternatives may drive them deeper underground into the much more hazardous world of commercial sexual exploitation.<BR>

<P>7.	Drying up the demand is an oft-forgotten facet of child protection. Attention is usually lopsided, focusing on the used rather than the user, seeking solutions addressing the source of supply without corollary measures to plug the demand for children. The fact that a country does not have children involved in prostitution cannot be a source of pride, for as long as it has adults promoting or contributing in anyway whatsoever to the existence of children in prostitution anywhere else in the world.<BR>

<P>8.	Strategies and programmes for children involved in prostitution should be sexually desegregated. There are very divergent paths taken by girls vis-a-vis boys in prostitution. This divergence usually are on the following points:<BR>

<P>	a)	modes of recruitment<BR>
	b)	manner of involvement<BR>
	c)	coping mechanisms<BR>
		d)	areas of operation<BR>
	e)	facility of extrication from the bondage of commercial sexual 			exploitation.<BR>

<P>9.	The search for solutions cannot be in isolation within the confines of a country, especially where there is cross-border trafficking or difference in nationality between the abused and the abuser. Regional and/or world-wide cooperation will oftentimes not only be desirable, but indispensable. At the same time, however, we should not fall into the trap of believing that there can be a single magic formula that can work for all countries. Every country will ultimately have to determine for itself how to remedy its own situation taking into account all the circumstances peculiar to the country, from causation, to political, social and cultural background of its peoples, to modes of recruitment, to modus operandi of the abusers, to the identification of other countries with which it has linkages, etc.<BR>

<P>10.	The leaps and bounds in the development of technology should not be overlooked especially in the fields of law enforcement and pornography. Lack of resources appropriated by most governments for law enforcement leave the latter far behind the up-to-date sophisticated means of communication and other equipment available to the syndicated sex operators, causing frustration and discouraging zeal in the pursuit of reported offenders.<BR>

<P>In the field of pornography, obsolescence of legislation is one of the greatest impacts of modern technology, necessitating upgrading the review of laws in the order of priorities.<BR>

<P>11.	Penalization and rehabilitation may not always be the answer. Where child abuse is caused by compulsive and maniacal psychological illness, for example, the length of sentence of imprisonment would be absolutely irrelevant and will not result into any remorse sufficient to deter a future repetition of the same offense. Two issues arise from this situation: first, whether the psychological deficiency will exculpate the offender from criminal culpability, and second and more importantly, what course of action can be taken to ensure that said compulsive or maniacal behavior does not give rise to victimization of other children.<BR>

<P>Excellencies, ladies and gentlemen,<BR>

<P>I hope I have been able to provide you with the parameters of the commercial sexual exploitation of children, for fruitful discussions of the Congress and concrete solutions to the problem. With strong determination and political will of all of us concerned, much can be achieved and the end of this millennium will hopefully provide a better future for the children in the world.<BR>

<P>Ladies and gentlemen, if there is any doubt in anybodys mind how desperate is the need of children for instant action, we only have to think of the two Belgian children, Melissa Russo and Julie Lejeune for whom, unfortunately, the World Congress came too late.<BR>

<P>Thank you very much.
<P><CENTER><hr><P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="factsheets.htm">Factsheets</A> | <A HREF="theme.htm">Theme Papers</A> | <A HREF="declaration.htm">Declaration</A> | <A HREF="links.htm">Links</A> | <A HREF="press.htm">Press materials</A>  <BR><A HREF="reports.htm">Congress reports</A> | <A HREF="intpress.htm">Interesting press</A> <BR><A HREF="default.htm">CSEC Home Page</A></P></CENTER><hr>
</BODY>
</HTML>
