<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>London Economics' Recruitment</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../images/paper.jpg" text="#0000A0">
<h1 align="center"><font color="#000080">Recruitment</font></h1>
<p align="center"><font color="#0000FF"><font size="4"><i>London
Economics offers outstanding opportunities for highly motivated
graduates to use their economic and quantitative skills in an
intellectually-demanding environment. Our well-regarded firm is
now one of the largest concentrations of professional economists
in the UK and continues to expand in a number of areas.</i></font></font></p>
<hr>
<p><font color="#0000A0">The firm was founded in 1986 by John Kay
and Nick Morris, who were previously Director and Deputy Director
of the Institute for Fiscal Studies. They started London
Economics with a clear objective: to develop the powerful tools
of microeconomics in ways which would help solve the problems
faced by decision-makers in business and the public sector.</font></p>
<p><font color="#0000A0">We currently employ over 80 full time
staff. A number of leading university economists and industry
specialists are also associated with the company and assist with
project work. In the last financial year we earned fees in excess
of &#163;6 million. We are located in offices in Chiltern Street,
London, W1.</font></p>
<p><font color="#0000A0">There is one thriving subsidiary in
Melbourne, which is a key advisor on the reform of Australian
utilities industries and markets; and another, more recently, in
Boston, which is servicing a number of clients facing the
challenges of deregulation in the US power market. LE's
expertise, particularly in legal cases, has been sold to the
European market, assisted by a small office in Brussels. </font></p>
<p><font color="#0000A0">We specialise in providing applied
economic analysis for clients in the UK and overseas. Our clients
include major private sector companies, international agencies,
trade associations, and government departments. A quarter of our
work is in Eastern Europe and the developing countries.</font></p>
<p><font color="#0000A0">Areas covered include regulation,
privatisation, energy, water, competition, strategy, financial
services, telecommunications, transport, intellectual property,
support for legal cases, health, environmental issues,
macroeconomics, and media.</font></p>
<p><font color="#0000A0">Our staff are drawn from a diversity of
economic backgrounds, from universities, the civil service and
business. But they all have two things in common - they are the
best in their field and they all believe in the power of economic
techniques to solve business problems. There is no better
qualified team anywhere. Our combination of expertise and
experience is unmatched. The way we utilise that expertise is
unique.</font></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h2><font color="#0000A0">Clients and projects</font></h2>
<p><font color="#0000A0">Our client list ranges from the Arts
Council to the World Bank. Over the last ten years, clients have
used our analysis to:</font></p>
<ul>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Understand the new structure of the
        UK electricity industry.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Present cases in the Courts and
        before anti-trust authorities in the UK, Brussels and
        overseas.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Learn how their activities affect
        the environment.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Analyse the demand for financial
        services until the end of the century.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Negotiate a new system of
        regulation of water charges, access charges and other
        tariffs.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Help government understand the
        effects of its tax policy.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Understand the effect of the
        exchange rate on their business.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">See how rivals might respond to
        pricing strategies.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Understand the skill shortages they
        face.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Reform the power sector in
        developing countries.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Help decide whether to diversify
        into a new market.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Assess the viability of new
        business decisions.</font></li>
</ul>
<p>&#160;</p>
<hr>
<h2><font color="#0000A0">Recent projects</font></h2>
<h3><font color="#0000A0">Competition Policy and Litigation
Support</font></h3>
<ul>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Providing economic expert witness
        evidence as part of a contractual dispute with an airport
        over the level of its landing and terminal charges for an
        international airline. </font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">An international cartel to organise
        and stabilise a commodity market went bankrupt and
        creditors launched a series of major law suits in the UK
        and Europe. We provided expert evidence on the client's
        market position under competition articles of EC law.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">When a major supplier of coffee
        faced an enquiry into anti-competitive behaviour, LE
        helped the client to refute the charge.</font></li>
</ul>
<h3><font color="#0000A0">Environmental Economics</font></h3>
<ul>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Poland: modelling the effects of
        alternative instruments for air pollution control in
        Krakow, and a study of the feasibility of tradeable
        permits.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">An assessment of the costs and
        benefits of the Central Scotland forest.</font></li>
</ul>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3><font color="#0000A0">European Electricity</font></h3>
<ul>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Impact on competition of trends
        towards vertical re-integration in the UK.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Evalutating the economic impact of
        completing the internal energy market in gas and
        electricity in the European Union.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Advising on the commercial and
        economic implications of proposed changes to regulatory
        price controls.</font></li>
</ul>
<h3><font color="#0000A0">International Energy</font></h3>
<ul>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Taking the lead in a consortium
        advising the Government of Bangladesh on the reform of
        the power sector, the establishment of a regulatory
        framework and the reform of electricity prices.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Advising on the reform and
        restructuring of power systems in countries as diverse as
        Croatia and Zambia.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Advising on the privatisation of
        hydro power stations in Slovenia.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">In Azerbaijan LE advised on the
        affordability of gas tariffs in the context of a tariff
        reform programme and helped design safety net options to
        protect the poor.<br>
        </font></li>
</ul>
<h3><font color="#0000A0">Macroeconomics</font></h3>
<ul>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Quantification of the effects of
        excise duties on crossborder trade. </font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Helping a public corporation to
        seek new freedom to invest and operate commercially in a
        changing regulatory environment.<br>
        </font></li>
</ul>
<h3><font color="#0000A0">Media</font></h3>
<ul>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">The impact of digitisation on the
        economics of the TV industry.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Implications for firms of changes
        in media ownership rules.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Causes and consequences of the
        rising cost of sports rights.<br>
        </font></li>
</ul>
<h3><font color="#0000A0">Strategy and Industrial Economics</font></h3>
<ul>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">An analysis of the pharmaceutical
        industry, emphasising the future structure of the
        industry and how the nature of competition may change in
        light of recent changes in regulatory regimes.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Assisting one of the UK's largest
        retailers with its submissions to the Treasury, calling
        for restraint when deciding the future levels of excise
        taxes on alcoholic beverages.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Assisting an operator in the
        cross-Channel passenger market in forming its price
        strategy.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">LE assessed the future prospect of
        the National Lottery in the UK.<br>
        </font></li>
</ul>
<h3><font color="#0000A0">Telecommunications</font></h3>
<ul>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Providing advice to the BBC on the
        application of regulation by OFTEL to its soon to be
        privatised transmission business.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">On behalf of the Cable
        Communications Association we prepared a submission to
        the Monopolies and Mergers Commission arguing that the
        introduction of number portability by British Telecom was
        in the public interest.</font></li>
</ul>
<h3><font color="#0000A0">The Water Industry</font></h3>
<ul>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Assessment of the relative
        efficiency of water companies, using advanced econometric
        techniques.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Preparation for Monopolies and
        Mergers Commission reviews for Portsmouth Water and South
        West Water.</font></li>
    <li><font color="#0000A0">Ongoing advice to the Water
        Companies' Association.<br>
        </font></li>
</ul>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h2><font color="#0000A0">More details about the company</font></h2>
<hr>
<h3><font color="#0000A0">How is the company structured?</font></h3>
<p><font color="#0000A0">The London office is divided into two
groups: Utilities and Industry. The Utilities Group comprises the
water, energy and international teams, while the Industry Group
is divided into two teams: industry and finance, and competition.
You will be working in a team that suits your skills and
interests. In addition, there is scope to move within the firm as
your career develops.<br>
</font></p>
<h3><font color="#0000A0">Career opportunities</font></h3>
<p><font color="#0000A0">Graduates are initially employed as
consultants and work on a variety of projects. Projects are
team-based, but from the outset you will have responsibility for
organising your own work under the direction and guidance of the
project leader. Senior colleagues will take a close interest in
your progress. The combination of dynamic, creative teamwork and
individual initiative plays a vital part in the success of London
Economics and provides a challenging work environment.</font></p>
<p><font color="#0000A0">You can expect to have contact with
clients at an early stage. Much of our project work is
international; we have worked in 53 countries around the world.
You may have opportunities to travel to Australia or to a
developing country to gather and analyse information. </font></p>
<p><font color="#0000A0">London Economics welcomes, and indeed
expects, responsibility for client and project work to be taken
at an early stage. You will be expected to supplement your
research capabilities with in-depth application of economic and
other analytical skills. You will be encouraged to undertake
further training and develop your skills.</font></p>
<p><font color="#0000A0">Promotion can be rapid: exceptional
consultants can be promoted to senior consultant within 2 to 3
years and most of our managing consultants are in their 30s. </font></p>
<h3><font color="#0000A0">Training</font></h3>
<p><font color="#0000A0">We feel that giving new staff a variety
of projects, with hands-on experience, allows them quickly to
develop a wide range of consultancy skills. We run several
internal training programmes, for example in econometrics, report
writing and presentation skills, as well as seminars for all our
staff. Our career development structure reviews your position
annually and we have a highly meritocratic approach to promotion. </font></p>
<h3><font color="#0000A0">Who do we want?</font></h3>
<p><font color="#0000A0">We are looking for applicants who have a
good first degree, ideally in a numerate discipline, and a second
degree in economics. Familiarity with/aptitude for the use of
computers in analysis and knowledge of spreadsheet and
econometric packages is useful, as is the ability to speak
another language. We also recruit senior economists who have
gained work experience in a consultancy or a commercial
environment.</font></p>
<h3><font color="#0000A0">The life of a consultant</font></h3>
<p><font color="#0000A0"><strong>Lea Paterson</strong>, London
School of Economics - Consultant, Competition Team</font></p>
<p><font color="#0000A0">When I was in my final year at
university, I had no clear idea of the type of career I wanted to
pursue. I decided to apply to LE for a temporary post, and worked
on a variety of competition, regulatory and strategic issues. Two
years later, after completing my postgraduate degree, I joined LE
on a permanent basis, as a consultant in the competition team.</font></p>
<p><font color="#0000A0">I now work exclusively on anti-trust
issues. In the past year, I have been involved in a wide range of
European and UK anti-trust cases, many of them extremely high
profile. During the course of these cases, I have worked closely
with senior partners of law firms, company directors and leading
academics. I believe that, through my work, the degree of
exposure that I have had to senior personnel is rare for someone
of my age and experience.</font></p>
<p><font color="#0000A0">For me, working at LE is an ideal
combination of academia and private sector consulting. I use the
economics I learned at university on a day-to- day basis, but my
job, like all consulting jobs, requires highly developed
interpersonal skills. Perhaps what I enjoy most about work is the
feeling that I am always learning. In my view, the challenging
work environment that LE provides is unique.<br>
</font></p>
<p><font color="#0000A0"><strong>William Derbyshire</strong>,
School of Oriental and African Studies - Consultant,
International Utilities Team</font></p>
<p><font color="#0000A0">When I joined London Economics I had no
idea what to expect. My only knowledge of water was that it came
out of a tap, and of electricity that you flick a switch.</font></p>
<p><font color="#0000A0">Since then, I've discovered a bit about
what goes on in the water, electricity and gas industries, and a
lot about the economics behind it. The big issues in the sector
are privatisation and regulation - and we advise on these
worldwide. It's exciting to have the chance to work in a rapidly
developing area of economics, as well as looking at issues which
affect people in their everyday lives. And, of course, there is
the chance to travel to a variety of countries.</font></p>
<p><font color="#0000A0">Currently, I'm developing a model to
forecast the financial impact on the electricity industry in
Bangladesh of separating the generation of power from its
distribution and sale. This model will be used to provide advice
to senior levels of government and donors such as the World Bank.
We are also working closely with local people and training them
in what we do. I've already spent four weeks in Dhaka for this
project, and will return for a further two. I've recently worked
on a financial appraisal of investments in the Bulgarian water
sector and a study of worldwide electricity privatisation
experience.</font></p>
<p><font color="#0000A0">The environment is relaxed but
stimulating and you are expected to work hard. The experience of
working with leading economists is extremely rewarding. I would
definitely recommend it.</font></p>
<h3><font color="#0000A0">How to apply</font></h3>
<p><font color="#0000A0">Please send your CV with a covering
letter to: </font></p>
<p><font color="#0000A0">Carmen Shemilt, Personnel Manager,
London Economics, 66 Chiltern Street, London W1M 1PR Telephone:
+44 171 446 8400 Fax: +44 171 446 8484/5</font></p>
<p><font color="#0000A0">email: </font><a
href="mailto:carmen@londecon.co.uk"><font color="#0000A0">carmen@londecon.co.uk</font></a></p>
<hr>
