<body background="../images/paper.jpg" text="#0000A0">
<h1 align="left"><font size="6">Strategy</font></h1>
<hr>
<h2><font size="5">The Issues</font></h2>
<p><font size="3">How can economists help businesses formulate an
appropriate strategy? How can past strategic decisions be
assessed in a rigorous way in order to learn for the future? How
can the benefit and compliance costs of a policy be evaluated?
How can the effect of a policy on a sector or a business be
assessed?</font></p>
<h2><font size="5">The Approach</font></h2>
<p><font size="3">London Economics takes economics a step closer
to the organisations we work with. We base our approach to
real-life business problems on a combination of economic theory
and state-of-the-art quantitative analysis and modelling. We
tailor our analysis to the needs of the client, presenting our
results in a digestible and easy-to-understand format, ensuring
that they are directly applicable to their business. Our
strategic analysis is based on a new approach, pioneered by
London Economics&#146; chairman, Prof. John Kay, for identifying
the competitive advantage of business. </font></p>
<p><font size="3">We specialise in:</font></p>
<ul>
    <li><font size="3">strategic audit and advice</font></li>
    <li><font size="3">policy evaluation and cost benefit
        analysis</font></li>
    <li><font size="3">compliance cost assessment</font></li>
    <li><font size="3">the evaluation of commercial strategy
        (pricing, advertising) effectiveness</font></li>
</ul>
<h2><font size="4">Experience</font></h2>
<p><font size="3">The following list of projects provides an
indication of the wide range of analysis we have conducted over
the last three years:</font></p>
<ul>
    <li><font size="3">the assessment of the impact of the
        National Lottery in the UK</font></li>
    <li><font size="3">strategic advice on the restructuring of a
        major multinational company</font></li>
    <li><font size="3">fiscal policy advice to the government of
        a former Soviet Union country</font></li>
    <li><font size="3">pricing strategy advice for a major
        international transport operator</font></li>
    <li><font size="3">the market structure and prospects of the
        retail sector in Europe</font></li>
    <li><font size="3">strategic issues in the development of the
        telecommunications sector</font></li>
    <li><font size="3">the potential for a major UK broadcaster
        entering the programming market in the US.<br>
        </font></li>
</ul>
