<html>
<head>
<title>Economics in Action Issue Four 1996</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h1 align="center"><img src="../../images/ecoact.gif"
align="bottom" width="300" height="78"></h1>
<h1 align="center"><tt>Issue Four 1996</tt></h1>
<hr size="4" width="45%">
<h5 align="left"><a name="Contents:"><font size="3">Contents:</font></a></h5>
<ul>
    <li><a href="#What's the use of economists?">Whats the use of
        economics?</a></li>
    <li>&#160;<a href="#The supply side strikes back">The supply
        side strikes back</a></li>
    <li><a href="whatsina.htm">What's in a decade?</a></li>
    <li><a href="#Power tools for hire">Power tools for hire</a></li>
    <li><a href="#Poachers and gamekeepers">Poachers and
        gamekeepers</a></li>
    <li><a href="#Simply add economics">Simply add economics</a></li>
    <li><a href="#The regulator cometh">The regulator cometh</a></li>
    <li><a href="#Taking time to specialise">Taking time to
        specialise</a></li>
    <li><a href="#Sending electric messages">Sending electric
        messages</a></li>
    <li><a href="#I'm sorry, that number is engaged ">I'm sorry,
        that number is engaged </a></li>
    <li><a href="#Competition means business">Competition means
        business</a></li>
    <li><a href="#The science of policy-making">The science of
        policy-making</a></li>
    <li><a href="#Reform rolls East">Reform rolls East</a></li>
    <li><a href="#The new frontiers">The new frontiers</a></li>
    <li><a href="#Learning global lessons ">Learning global
        lessons </a></li>
    <li><a href="#London Economics in Australia">London Economics
        in Australia</a></li>
    <li><a href="#Tax, trade and debt">Tax, trade and debt</a></li>
    <li><a href="#New markets, new business">New markets, new
        business</a></li>
</ul>
<p>&#160; </p>
<h2><a name="What's the use of economists?">What's the use of
economists?</a></h2>
<hr>
<p><em><strong>There is much more to economic life than fallible
macro-forecasts. In 10 years, London Economics has grown and
prospered providing decision-makers in industry and public policy
with microeconomic power: with the tools to assess costs,
pricing, investment decisions, the development of new markets,
competition and its abuses. In Britain and elsewhere, knowledge
of the way markets work has become ever more essential during the
first decade of LE's life.</strong></em></p>
<hr>
<p>Ask most businessmen what economists are for, and (if they say
anything printable at all) they will most likely mutter something
about the dollar and the deficit. Economists have become branded
with perhaps their most fallible product: macroeconomic
forecasts. That has done more for their fame than their
reputation. </p>
<p>A preoccupation with predictions for the whole economy had
four effects. First, it led to a misunderstanding of the
functions of economic models of all kinds. They can never provide
decision-makers with certainty about what the world will look
like one or five years ahead. What models can do is provide a
laboratory, in which to try out the effects of taking different
decisions. </p>
<p>Governments will often want to carry out &#147;macro&#148;
tests. What will happen if I raise interest rates, or cut taxes?
What will happen to inflation, and output? Businesses equally
need to be able to explore &#147;micro&#148; effects of their own
decisions. What will happen if I cut prices, or increase
production? What will happen to my profits? How will my
competitors react? Policy-makers and regulators need to ask the
same kinds of micro-questions. For this, they too need models,
informed by economic science. But the second damaging side-effect
of macro-mania is that it has overshadowed what was historically
a much more important function of economics - to explain how
markets work. Businesses, for whom such knowledge is literally
vital, have spun the economist's task of analysing costs, prices
and investment off to accountants, marketing departments, and
industrial &#147;strategists&#148;. </p>
<p>At the same time, government itself suffered the third
ill-effect of this macro-fixation. Through the middle years of
the twentieth century, it too became less and less interested in
microeconomics. The &#147;supply side&quot; was forgotten.
&#147;Demand management&#148; was all. Fourthly and finally,
therefore, microeconomic science itself lost momentum and
confidence in its ability to say new and profitable things about
the behaviour of either governments or firms. </p>
<h3><a name="The supply side strikes back">The supply side
strikes back</a></h3>
<p>By the 1980s, however, the pendulum was on the turn. And when
London Economics was founded in 1986, it both marked and profited
from a correction on all four scores. Macroeconomic forecasting
had taken a number of knocks in the 1970s.
&#147;Fine-tuning&#148; the economy was therefore (supposedly)
out of fashion politically. </p>
<p>The &#147;supply side&#148; was again in focus, with Britain
in the vanguard of a number of structural reforms which would
bring the need to understand markets back into focus. Meanwhile,
industrial economics had been undergoing some massive changes.
Its ability to explore competitive strategies has been boosted by
the development of game theory. The debate on issues concerned
with governance, the role of ownership, the nature of contracts
and the function of information had revived. All these had begun
to give new life to what had become something of a backwater of
economic science: its application to the analysis of the factors
underpinning corporate failure or success.</p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3><a name="Power tools for hire">Power tools for hire</a></h3>
<p>LE's two founding partners, John Kay and Nick Morris, started
London Economics ten years ago with a clear objective: to develop
the powerful tools of microeconomics in ways which would help
solve the problems faced by decision-makers in business and
public policy. With Nick Stern (now Chief Economist at the
European Bank for Reconstruction and Development) and Les Hannah
(now the Acting Director of the London School of Economics) they
had long been convinced that there was - as Nick Stern puts it -
a &quot;market for good micro&quot;. </p>
<p>Their skills, they believed, would be demanded most
particularly in areas where new markets were emerging, through
regulatory or technological or social change. This led them into
areas as diverse as water and power markets, the environment and
the media. </p>
<p>Analysing business costs and prices, designing market
structures and contracts, and modelling their effects, applying
game theory to illuminate the relationships between firms in
industries with a small number of participants - all these
techniques would be part of the tool-kit of a consultancy
specifically supplying &#147;economics for business&#148;.</p>
<p>Their timing, by design or good fortune, could hardly have
been better. Britain was in the throes of a series of reforms
which required both Government and the newly- privatised
utilities to think hard about monopolistic markets, price
regulation and investment incentives. The year 1986 alone saw the
privatisation of British Gas, &quot;Big Bang&quot; in the City,
and the final demolition of restrictive practices in Fleet
Street. New industries were being opened up to competitive forces
- public bodies charged with promoting and enforcing competition
were given a new impetus. With the start of the Single Market
programme in Europe, the Brussels Commission began to get into
the act, too. </p>
<p>Businesses, old and new, needed to understand the rules of the
game - which meant understanding the economics. Managers of the
new privately-owned utilities found that their revenues, and
hence their profits, depended on winning their battles with the
regulators. From the very beginning, therefore, much of LE's work
could be characterised as helping businesses resolve issues with
some kind of &quot;authority&quot; - be it a court, a regulator,
an institution, national or international - whose decisions are,
or are at least are supposed to be, founded on good economic
reasons. Sometimes, of course, it was the businesses themselves
which raised the issue, challenging the behaviour of other
companies (or, of course, of the regulators themselves).
Sometimes, equally, they needed to mount a defence of their
behaviour against others' challenges. </p>
<p><a href="#Contents:">[up to top]</a></p>
<h3><a name="Poachers and gamekeepers">Poachers and gamekeepers</a></h3>
<p>On many occasions, too, LE found itself working for the
gamekeepers rather than the poachers - advising regulators or
other institutions framing micro-policy, from UK government
departments to the European Commission. Increasingly, as LE's
international work expanded, the firm found itself invited by
other Governments, often in combination with the World Bank, to
help design regulatory regimes for economies following the UK
example (if not always the UK route) of privatisation and
deregulation. To date, LE has worked in a total of 52 different
countries, and the number is growing rapidly with the global
spread of microeconomic reform. To date, LE has worked in a total
of 52 different countries, and the number is growing rapidly with
the global spread of microeconomic reform.</p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3><a name="Simply add economics">Simply add economics</a></h3>
<p>Professional services are a strong sector of the British
economy, in which LE has identified and filled a niche as a
supplier of economic expertise and a clear understanding of the
principles and practice of public policy. Its main competitors
have been migrants from the US, where economic consultancy became
established earlier than in Britain. While many of the
accountancy firms have developed their own economics departments,
LE stands apart from these in terms of its size and single focus.
Many projects require economic skills to be added to the services
offered by other professionals: bankers, litigation specialists,
scientists, advertising agencies. In competition work, LE is
almost always working with lawyers, and has built up
relationships of mutual respect with some of the big commercial
firms. Projects concerned with water, power, transport and
environmental issues frequently require co-operation with
consultant engineers. Work for international organisations has
involved LE in new working partnerships, in the field of utility
reform.</p>
<p>But although concentrated expertise in economic regulation has
always been a strong LE suit, so has the use of microeconomic
tools to inform business strategies. So, helping companies win
price wars (or avoid starting them); to assess their markets; to
evaluate their investment plans; to weigh up mergers and
demergers; understand the dynamics of their industries - all
these have become core components of LE's work for its major
clients. The formation this year of LE's Strategy Club of blue
chip companies has created a workshop forum in which they can
debate the evidence on such issues across a number of sectors, as
well as apply LE's expertise individually.</p>
<p>And, from the beginning, LE's work involved participation in
the policy debate. Its very first piece of business, tapping into
the founders' fiscal expertise, was for Lloyd's of London, whom
LE helped prepare a submission for the Treasury on the treatment
of tax reserves. </p>
<p>&#160;<a href="#Contents:">[up to top]</a></p>
<h3><a name="The regulator cometh">The regulator cometh</a></h3>
<p>From the start, LE's modelling skills were used in a variety
of work. Almost immediately LE became involved in the debate over
the new regulatory systems being designed for the water, power
and telecommunications markets. 1986 was a milestone year on the
march towards privatisation: the Government announced its
intention to privatise the 10 water authorities separately,
British Gas was sold with Sid's aid and the privatised British
Telecom suffered its first reference to the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission (on its bid for Mitel).</p>
<p>Thus the spread of economic arguments addressed in different
projects has been huge. It is this diversity of intellectual
challenge that has attracted, and held, LE's key staff. A few
examples make the point. How should a Power Pool be designed, and
how could power companies maximise their profitability within
such pool systems? What were the implications of fiscal
harmonisation in Europe for cross-border shopping and duty-free
sales?</p>
<p>Should telephone numbers be &quot;portable&quot; - would
competition be inhibited if customers could not keep their phone
numbers when changing telecoms supplier, and who should bear the
switching costs? What is the right regulatory regime for water
privatisation in Eastern Europe? How should a betting levy be
framed, to create the right incentives for a healthy horse-racing
industry? Is BSkyB abusing its position in the market for
satellite television to control cable television's access to
programming? What is the best tax regime for the inflation-ridden
states of the former Soviet Union? Who should pay for higher
education? What sort of &quot;market mechanism&quot; would be the
most efficient way of reducing acid rain?</p>
<p>&#160;<a href="#Contents:">[up to top]</a></p>
<h3><a name="Taking time to specialise">Taking time to specialise</a></h3>
<p>In the early days, the small LE team had to be able to tackle
the full range of tasks, from acting as expert witness in
competition cases to modelling markets and demographics; from
understanding public policy to analysing financial flows. The
very first pieces of work illustrate the diversity. LE found
itself analysing the impact of ad valorem taxes and specific
duties on tobacco - work which flowed directly from its founders'
tax expertise; but also appearing for the London Metal Exchange,
against whom action was taken under Articles 85 and 86 of the
Treaty of Rome, over the impact on competition of its actions in
&#147;ringing out&#148; the market following the collapse in the
tin price. </p>
<p>Competition cases followed thick and fast: was the Milk
Marketing Board distorting competition, to the disadvantage of
the Irish Dairy Board, by selling milk more cheaply for
butter-making than for liquid consumption? Was Texaco breaching
fair trading rules in the pricing of its petrol? Was
Nestl&eacute; &#147;monopolising&#148; the soluble coffee market?
But so did strategic and policy work: LE was involved in helping
the TSB develop lifecycle products, in helping Tesco examine the
prospects for cross-border shopping, and - a forerunner of
substantial Antipodean utilities business - examining the costs
and benefits of gas contracts which had turned bad on the
government of Western Australia. </p>
<p><a href="#Contents:">[up to top]</a></p>
<h3><a name="Sending electric messages">Sending electric messages</a></h3>
<p>With &quot;The Case for Twelve&quot;, an early report on which
the electricity area board chairmen based their case for
flotation as separate companies, LE established its reputation
for expertise in the complex area of utility privatisation.</p>
<blockquote>
    <p><em>&quot;There are not many people who believe that the
    main reason why income levels in the West ended at levels
    more than twice as high as in the East was the Bundesbank's
    exemplary management ... What really mattered was the
    different ways in which the two zones organised their
    industries and their markets.&quot; -</em><font size="2"><em> </em></font><font
    size="3">John Kay, The Business of Economics, OUP, 1996</font></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Once the new competitive electricity market was launched in
Britain, the industry, and particularly the distributors, faced
an entirely new set of rules and had quickly to develop whole new
sets of skills. In assessing early Independent Power Projects, we
found that no software tools existed to help predict what might
happen in a competitive power pool over the next 20 years.
Together with their clients, Robin Cohen and Sam Lovick built a
number which are still used extensively by major players to model
pool prices, analyse contracts and understand complex hedging
mechanisms.</p>
<p>LE's set of PC-based models, with names like POOLMOD, PCEM and
POLLO, soon became the most widely-used software in the industry.
They combined innovative use of high-level languages with the
ease-of-use and cheapness of PCs. Perhaps more importantly, they
brought together financial analysis and an understanding of the
essential engineering of the power sector. Much of LE's power
sector work around the world today utilises the techniques the
firm began to develop then. Nationally and internationally, a
combination of knowledge of these industries and regulatory
expertise has remained a core competence of the firm.</p>
<p>As LE grew, so expertise became concentrated in a number of
different teams. Competition cases followed hard on each other's
heels. Professionalism in this market grew with the use of
economists as essential fire-power in such cases. In the early
1980s, British lawyers relied largely on a few freelancing
academics. But anti-trust work was a key area identified by Nick
Morris in researching the American market for economics in 1986. </p>
<p>Britain followed the American lead, as companies appearing
before the Office of Fair Trading, or the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission, or under investigation by the European Commission,
found that adding economists to their armoury increased their
chances of success - and over time, that has become clearer
still. When, for example, the MMC came to investigate the issues
involved in telephone number portability, it devoted a whole
chapter to the arguments of the protagonists' economists -
drawing on no fewer than eight economic studies, commissioned by
OFTEL, BT and (in the case of LE's own work) the cable companies.</p>
<p><a href="#Contents:">[up to top]</a></p>
<h3><a name="Sending electric messages">Sending electric messages</a></h3>
<p>With &quot;The Case for Twelve&quot;, an early report on which
the electricity area board chairmen based their case for
flotation as separate companies, LE established its reputation
for expertise in the complex area of utility privatisation.</p>
<blockquote>
    <p><em>&quot;There are not many people who believe that the
    main reason why income levels in the West ended at levels
    more than twice as high as in the East was the Bundesbank's
    exemplary management ... What really mattered was the
    different ways in which the two zones organised their
    industries and their markets.&quot; - John Kay, The Business
    of Economics, OUP, 1996</em></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Once the new competitive electricity market was launched in
Britain, the industry, and particularly the distributors, faced
an entirely new set of rules and had quickly to develop whole new
sets of skills. In assessing early Independent Power Projects, we
found that no software tools existed to help predict what might
happen in a competitive power pool over the next 20 years.
