<p>&#160;<a href="#Contents:">[up to top]</a></p>
<table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td width="100%">
        <h3><a name="I'm sorry, that number is engaged ">I'm
        sorry, that number is engaged </a></h3>
        <p>In 1989, LE was called by another consultancy, OVUM,
        which specialised in the telecommunications industry.
        They asked what we knew about systems of allocating
        telephone numbers. Our first answer was that we knew
        nothing about a subject that sounded about as interesting
        as reading the telephone directory. </p>
        <p>But just an hour's brain-storming was enough to make
        us realise how wrong we were. How telephone numbers are
        allocated, and by whom, are powerful influences on the
        structure of the telecommunications industry - crucial
        both to competition and to the way people use their
        phones. </p>
        <p>Our first report on the subject, prepared with OVUM
        for OFTEL, the regulator, highlighted some of the issues
        involved. Within a few years, we were to be involved -
        this time on behalf of the cable operators - in a heated
        argument before the Monopolies and Mergers Commission on
        the &#147;portability&#148; of phone numbers. </p>
        <p>If my telephone number belongs to the telephone
        company, then switching supplier is quite a costly
        business for me. I need new stationery, an announcement
        to friends and customers, and I miss social and business
        calls until everyone has learnt my new number - all of
        which is going to make me quite reluctant to move. </p>
        <p>If I own my telephone number, then I can change my
        telecoms supplier almost as easily as I can change the
        channels on the remote control of my television set. But
        then one or other of the two suppliers involved has to
        bear the cost of reallocating my number. Which of the
        three of us - me, my old or new supplier - should carry
        the can? </p>
        <p>In December, 1995, the MMC finally ruled in favour of
        number portability. It took the view that this would
        benefit not only the customer who wanted to move, but all
        phone users - by sharpening competition and so driving
        down prices. This coloured its view of how the costs
        should be shared out. Most, the MMC decided, should be
        carried by the telecoms supplier that I decide to leave. </p>
        <p>Looking further ahead, the implications of number
        portability are more radical still. We are all used to
        the idea that a telephone number is attached to a piece
        of equipment - a telephone instrument, or more recently a
        fax machine or a mobile phone. But we hardly ever want to
        call a specific piece of equipment. We either want a
        person, or a piece of information. I want to talk to
        John, or check the time of the next meeting, or learn
        about the structure of the telecoms market. </p>
        <p>It is because we have to ring machines, not people or
        functions, that most of the calls we make ultimately fail
        to achieve their object. Gradually, new types of hardware
        and greater software capabilities will enable us to use
        phone numbers to locate precisely who or what we want to
        contact. Until that day comes, the list inside the back
        cover of this newsletter will help you find your way
        around LE. </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>
<h3><a name="Competition means business">Competition means
business</a></h3>
<p>Petrol prices, soluble coffee, photocopiers, carbonated soft
drinks, airline reservation systems, vending machines, phone
directories and numbers - as each in turn fell under the
spotlight of competition authorities, so LE increased its
expertise in this area. John Kay built up a team of competition
specialists, headed first by Tom Hoehn. As LE's reputation
increased, so did the demand for its work as an expert witness -
by the regulatory authorities themselves, not just the
protagonists. When, in November 1995, OFTEL held the first public
hearing in the history of UK utility regulation - on the proposal
to introduce into operators' licences a general prohibition on
anti-competitive behaviour - John Kay was asked to provide an
independent contribution to the debate.</p>
<p>But regulators and courts are not the only form of authority
whom businesses have to take into account in their strategic
thinking. Government, too, takes a series of decisions based
(more or less) on the balance of economic argument. Here again,
perhaps, microeconomics has been maligned - in using it to ram
home important truths about the beneficial power of market
forces, politicians have sometimes obscured the framework it
provides for identifying instances of market failure, weighing up
the costs and benefits of policies, illuminating welfare effects,
both static and dynamic, to aid the process of decision-making. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3><a name="The science of policy-making">The science of
policy-making</a></h3>
<p>Through its lifetime, LE's work in this field has continued to
grow, particularly when Bill Robinson joined the firm in 1993.
Arguments over appropriate tax regimes; regulations for labour
markets, retail markets, planning permissions; appropriate
structures for semi-markets such as education and health - LE has
over time been asked to contribute to them all. </p>
<p>LE, which had carried out work for the Gulbenkian Foundation
on the impact of a lottery in the UK, was involved in advising
Camelot on its winning bid to run the hugely successful National
Lottery finally launched last year. It has helped the BBC to
analyse the pressures on its costs and revenues; worked for Tesco
to demonstrate the gain to consumers, in terms of the impact on
prices, from the retailing revolution; helped the Committee of
Vice-Chancellors and Principals to raise the issues involved in
the financing of higher education. </p>
<p>Frequently, as in this last example, it is an organisation or
association which wishes to engage in such public policy
argument: in similar vein, LE has worked for the Cable Companies'
Association, the British Screen Advisory Council, the Producers'
Alliance for Cinema and Television and the Water Companies'
Association. When working for protagonists in a public policy
debate, however, LE has evolved a clear set of rules designed
both to meet the needs of the client and preserve its much-prized
reputation for independent analysis. </p>
<p>But the dynamic of LE's rapid growth came most clearly from
the demand for its skills amongst the new privatised utilities,
particularly in the water and power sectors. An important piece
of work carried out by the firm in its early days was for the
Water Companies' Association, coupled with work for the smaller
companies, which helped them cope with the massive new
requirements for financial information in the new regulatory
world.</p>
<p>In 1990, when Mike Webb joined the firm from the World Bank,
LE began the process of exporting this expertise to the many
different regions of the developing world. This expansion began
in South Asia, with a major study into the long-term issues
facing the Indian power sector, followed by an examination of the
demand for gas in Pakistan and the feasibility of a gas pipeline
from the Middle East. </p>
<p>&#160;<a href="#Contents:">[up to top]</a></p>
<h3><a name="Reform rolls East">Reform rolls East</a></h3>
<p>Since then, LE's International Team has been at work across
the world in an extraordinary range of countries engaged in
changing the ownership or the market structure of the power,
water and telecoms sectors of their economies. To the original
batch of clients in South Asia was added a long list of
newly-independent countries as reform rolled east: Hungary, the
Czech Republic, Croatia, Slovenia, Uzbekistan, Kazakhstan,
Azerbaijan, Moldova, Romania, Bulgaria, Lithuania: everyone, it
seemed, from tiny Albania to still-critical Russia, whose role as
a gas exporter is still an issue of immense importance to the
European economies farther west. </p>
<p>Unlike many other organisations working in these fields,
however, LE does not offer a single template for reform; while
the same groundwork needs to be done to identify ways of
improving both productive and allocative efficiency, different
solutions may suit the political and economic circumstances of
the countries concerned.</p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3><a name="The new frontiers">The new frontiers</a></h3>
<p>In the United States, LE is now working for utilities rolling
towards the new frontier of power sector reform. At the end of
last year, the Public Utilities Commission of California finally
set out its ideas for the future of the energy market in
America's largest state. The new focus on competition, here and
elsewhere in the US, is stoking the ambitions of electricity
companies worldwide. Using expertise built up in the British and
Australian markets, LE is helping US utilities to understand how
competitive power markets work, and plan how best to develop
their own plans and strategies for the new market. Seabron
Adamson is heading up LE's first US office, supported in London
by Robin Cohen.</p>
<p>Back in Britain, meanwhile, LE's work at the interface between
the public and private sectors has moved on with the argument: we
have been helping a number of clients test the limits of the new
rules for a &#147;mixed economy&#148; launched under the heading
of the Private Finance Initiative, and to explore other ideas for
the achievement of greater commercial freedom.</p>
<p>So what does LE's business look like today? Most of our work
is done for major private corporations, in Britain, the United
States, Australia, continental Europe - and globally. Much of our
competition, regulatory and strategic work for them is
confidential - but amongst the current list of over 100 are a
number with whom our long-term relationships have become
well-known. They include such household names as Tesco, Scottish
Hydro-Electric, Philip Morris, the BBC, UIP and Camelot. In the
utilities field, we continue to work for a number of the Regional
Electricity Companies, and for individual water companies - as
well as their association. We are helping with strategic thinking
at Glaxo Wellcome, BP, Amoco, Orange, the Post Office and British
Airways. We have been retained to analyse the impact on
competition of BSkyB's strong position in satellite broadcasting,
and the issues involved in the sale of sports rights to
broadcasters.</p>
<p>&#160;<a href="#Contents:">[up to top]</a></p>
<table border="1" cellspacing="1" width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td width="100%">
        <h3><a name="Learning global lessons ">Learning global
        lessons </a></h3>
        <p>There is a lot to be said for &#147;unbundling&#148;
        power sectors - separating out generation, transmission,
        distribution and retail supply. Such reform makes it far
        easier to assess the efficiency of different parts of the
        system and to introduce competition. While continental
        Europe is home to some of the most unreformed power
        sectors around, with large integrated utilities like
        Electricit&eacute; de France and Italy's ENEL, a number
        of other countries, including of course the UK, have been
        racing ahead. Chile went ahead in the early 1980s. Other
        parts of Latin America, Australia and now the USA are
        getting in on the act. Even Africa, with the development
        of a competitive power pool in South Africa, is moving. </p>
        <p>Unbundling raises a number of key issues, whose
        resolution requires a combination of economic skills and
        knowledge of power sectors, which LE has built up
        globally. Following a number of important studies,
        beginning with the power sector in India, the World Bank
        asked LE to carry out a comparative study. The Bank was
        particularly interested in the methods used to price
        electricity at generation and transmission levels under
        different reform models. It wanted to draw lessons from
        experience in order to provide the right - not just the
        same - advice to its individual borrowers. Most reformers
        have introduced competition at the generation level - and
        World Bank advice, which had traditionally advocated
        cost-reflective tariffs, needed to be retuned in the
        direction of investment incentives and efficient use of
        resources. </p>
        <p>The results of our work were presented at a seminar in
        Washington, and are shortly being published by the World
        Bank. They are not just of academic interest. An
        estimated $100 billion per year is required to finance
        expansion in developing country power sectors. But
        despite the tidal wave of interest in Asian
        infrastructure, projects are stalling because of
        uncertainty as to whether such investment will actually
        be profitable. Setting in place market structures that
        reassure investors, without leaving all the risk with
        governments, will be the key to progress. </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>
<h3><a name="Tax, trade and debt">Tax, trade and debt</a></h3>
<p>In the third world, Eastern Europe and the former Soviet
Union, much advisory work for governments continues to be
financed by international agencies such as the World Bank or the
EBRD. Although this is heavily concentrated in the utilities
sector - spreading from advice on privatisation in Jamaica to
power sector reform in Southern Africa, the range is wider still:
we, have, for example, been helping design a tax system for the
government of Turkmenistan; designing a system of tradeable
permits to control the serious air pollution problems afflicting
Poland's historic city of Krakow; advising the British Overseas
Development Administration on the merits of commercial debt
buy-backs.</p>
<p>&#160;<a href="#Contents:">[up to top]</a></p>
<h3><a name="London Economics in Australia">London Economics in
Australia</a></h3>
<p>From its early days, LEA has been a key commentator and
adviser on the process of reform of Australian utilities
industries and markets. The Melbourne team is currently closely
involved in developing a regulatory framework for the electricity
industry in both Queensland and New South Wales.</p>
<p>LEA has for some time provided ongoing advice to the
Queensland Department of Mines and Energy on an appropriate
competitive market structure in the state. This has covered a
range of issues, including the timing and entry of Queensland
into the emerging National Electricity Market, the implications
of expansion of the inter-state interconnectors, regulation of
distributor/retailers, structural options for generation and the
financial implications of alternative reform options. Most
recently, our work on behalf of the Queensland Electricity
Structure Task Force has resulted in a detailed review of the
structure and current regulatory arrangements of the industry.<br>
In NSW we have focused on the extent to which the potential for
the exercise of market power in the NSW retail electricity sector
is likely to frustrate the aims of the electricity reform
process. Our job has been to identify appropriate regulatory
responses. We have been examining current operations of the
retail market, the nature of retail market competition and
barriers to entry into the retail market. </p>
<p>Other recent projects on behalf of State policy makers include
a review of the Tasmanian water and sewerage industry on behalf
of the Tasmanian Roles and Functions Committee. LEA reviewed
existing structural arrangements and technical, environmental and
operational issues in the industry and provided recommendations
for delivering services in a more cost-effective manner. We
followed this study up with a detailed appraisal of the likely
impact on local government councils of the recommendations. </p>
<p>Back in Europe, meanwhile, LE has been analysing the
implications of convergence in the media industries for the
European Commission, for which we are also engaged in a long-term
trans-European study of the market for digital television, an
analysis which helps to inform much of our media work for
corporate clients. For different arms of the Brussels octopus, we
have also just completed major studies of the impact of the
Single Market programme on competition, and the development of
the internal market in the energy field.</p>
<p>For the British Department of the Environment, we have been
developing a model of the area cost adjustments that determine
the distribution of central government grants; for the Department
of Health, we have been analysing the pricing of drugs and
medicaments. We are currently working for public bodies in media,
education and finance. For the Office of Fair Trading, we have
been working on an analysis of the concept of &#147;consumer
detriment&#148;; for many companies, we have been providing
analysis of possible changes in competition law and policy.
Trains and boats and planes are becoming as much a focus of our
business as water, electricity and gas: our portfolio of work in
the transport sector has built up steeply over the past few
months. </p>
<p><a href="#Contents:">[up to top]</a>&#160;</p>
<h3><a name="New markets, new business">New markets, new business</a></h3>
<p>So, too, have the challenges presented to our clients by
&#147;globalisation&#148;. Some of the dynamics are
technological: most notably, the digital revolution, allowing all
forms of information to be expressed - in both senses of the word
- electronically around the world, and delivered via satellite,
cable or terrestrial transmission or traditional telephone wires,
irrespective of national rules and frontiers. <br>
Some arise from the responses of policy-makers - the shift in
economic regulation from national to international authorities,
as domestic regimes come under pressure. Companies which have
barely come to terms with Brussels' role in the enforcement of
competition rules are now eyeing the development of a new, global
arbiter: the World Trade Organisation. </p>
<p>Adjudications are already streaming out of its new, tougher
procedures for settling trade disputes. For LE, Sarah Hogg was
invited to speak to an international conference of lawyers,
economists and policy-makers in Brussels this summer. This
familiar mix of interested parties is a sign that the market for
economic argument is yet again about to expand. &#160;</p>
<p><a href="#Contents:">[up to top]</a></p>
