<html>
<head>
<title>Press Release Chairman</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../images/paper.jpg" text="#000080">
<h1><font color="#FF0000"><tt>Press Release</tt></font><tt> </tt></h1>
<h2>New Chairman as London Economics enters its second decade</h2>
<hr>
<h3>London Economics today announced ...</h3>
<p><font size="4">London Economics, which celebrates its tenth
anniversary on Monday, announced that </font><a
href="sarahhog.htm"><font size="4">Sarah Hogg</font></a><font
size="4"> would be succeeding John Kay as its Chairman with
effect from January 1st, 1997. John Kay, who will remain a
director of London Economics, is leaving the London Business
School to become Professor of Management Studies and first
Director of the new Oxford University Management School (see
separate press release).</font></p>
<p><a href="sarahhog.htm"><font size="4">Sarah Hogg</font></a><font
size="4">, who joined London Economics as a Director in 1995,
said:</font></p>
<blockquote>
    <p><font size="4">&quot;London Economics&#146; first decade
    has been a tremendous success story - it has grown and
    prospered by providing business, regulators and public
    policy-makers with powerful tools. We offer the economic
    expertise to help them to assess markets, costs and prices,
    the impact of competition and its abuses, and the effect of
    regulating these in different ways. Nationally and globally,
    these issues will be still more important over its next 10
    years, as governments of all kinds focus on the structure of
    their economies, and both new technologies and changes in
    world trading systems heighten the pressures of competition
    on business.&quot;</font></p>
</blockquote>
<p><font size="4">London Economics is celebrating its 10th
Anniversary next Monday with a reception at which the Chancellor
of the Exchequer will be proposing the toast. LE was founded by
John Kay and Nick Morris, LE&#146;s Chief Executive, in 1986. It
is now Britain&#146;s largest independent economic consultancy,
with a professional staff of over 60 in London and subsidiaries
in Australia and the United States.</font></p>
<p><font size="4">John Kay said:</font></p>
<blockquote>
    <p><font size="4">&quot;We founded London Economics to
    demonstrate that economics could be effectively applied to
    business issues and I am very proud of our success. I intend
    to go on contributing to that success, which has been based
    on a combination of intellectual rigour and practical
    experience; and that is the combination I intend to bring to
    my new challenge of developing management education in
    Oxford.</font></p>
    <p><font size="4">I am delighted that Sarah Hogg has agreed
    to succeed me as Chairman. Sarah has experience of applying
    economics at the highest levels in government and business
    and has exceptional skills in communicating complex economic
    ideas. I am confident that she and Nick Morris will make a
    strong team to carry the firm forward. That is why I have
    just increased my equity investment in the company.&quot;</font></p>
</blockquote>
<p><font size="4">Nick Morris, LE&#146;s Chief Executive and
co-founder, said:</font></p>
<blockquote>
    <p><font size="4">&quot;LE&#146;s work now extends from South
    America to Turkmenistan, and from water supply to digital
    television. We are often involved at the most formative
    moments for markets and economies. The diversity of this work
    keeps our high-calibre staff interested and enables us to
    provide insight for clients in one industry from our
    experience in others. We now have strong teams in utilities,
    international energy, competition and industrial strategy.
    Each of these markets will see future growth, from which we
    expect to benefit as a firm.&quot;<br>
    </font></p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<h5>For Further Information Contact:<br>
<br>
London Economics<br>
66 Chiltern Street<br>
London W1M 1PR<br>
<strong>Tel:</strong> +44 0171 446 8400<br>
<strong>FAX: </strong>+44 0171 446 8484<br>
<strong>e-mail:</strong> <a href="mailto:info@londecon.co.uk">info@londecon.co.uk</a><br>
<strong>URL:</strong> http://www.londecon.co.uk</h5>
