<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>LE About London Economics</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../images/paper.jpg" text="#0000A0">
<h1 align="center"><font color="#000080">About LE</font></h1>
<p align="left"><font color="#000080"><font size="3"><cite><b>Would
you consider making a major corporate acquisition without
consulting your lawyer? Submit your returns to Companies House
without involving your accountant? Launch a rights issue without
using your financial public relations team? Probably not. Too
risky, if not downright impossible. The economic environment in
which you operate is just as important. In today's challenging
business climate, more and more companies are turning to
economists for detailed analysis, strategic advice and practical
solutions to business problems. </b></cite></font></font></p>
<p>Economics is no longer confined to government and academia. In
regulated industries, economic expertise is essential. And in the
wider commercial arena, it is a tool used by successful managers
to analyse everyday problems, issues and opportunities facing
companies and industry sectors around the world - to ensure that
all the pieces fit into place. </p>
<ul>
    <li><a href="http://www.connect.org.uk/lottery">Camelot Group</a>,
        for example, used economists to help prepare the
        competitive submission that won it the licence to operate
        the National Lottery in the UK - and become Britain's
        business success story of the 1990s. <br>
    </li>
    <li><a href="http://www.uip.com">UIP</a>, the international
        film distributor, used economic analysis as the
        cornerstone of its response to UK and EU competition
        authorities. <br>
    </li>
    <li><a href="http://www.businesswire.com/cnn/mo.htm">Philip
        Morris</a> employed economists to advise on the impact of
        indirect taxes on pricing strategy and demand, and likely
        competitive responses. <br>
    </li>
    <li>Melbourne Water in Australia worked with economists to
        explore how structural changes could create efficiency
        gains. </li>
</ul>
<p>These companies and many others have three important things in
common: they are all highly successful; they all recognise the
value of economics as a core business tool; and they all turned
for help to Europe's leading independent economic consultancy -
London Economics. </p>
<hr size="4" width="50%">
<h2 align="center">OUR BUSINESS</h2>
<p><i>Since London Economics was formed in 1986, the growth of
our economic consulting practice has itself become something of a
business phenomenon. Our turnover rose rapidly and, despite the
deep recession of the early 1990s, has trebled in the last five
years. Today, we are the largest and most successful independent
economics consultancy in the UK.</i> </p>
<p>Over that period, we have attracted some of the world's finest
economists and brightest graduates. They have applied economics
to help solve problems for over 100 of the world's leading
companies, international business organisations and governments
in 45 countries. </p>
<p>London Economics operates internationally, with a subsidiary
in Australia and representative offices in Boston, Brussels and
Edinburgh. More than 40 per cent of our business is outside the
UK. </p>
<p>We have over 70 full-time staff with a broad range of
specialist skills who provide advice on competition, regulation,
and financial and commercial strategy as well as more traditional
economic issues. </p>
<p>Our approach to business is both innovative and professional
and is carried out to the most rigorous intellectual standards.
Throughout we work closely with our clients, providing the right
team for the job, whatever your specialist needs. </p>
<p>Our solutions can lead to considerable cost savings and help
to maximise commercial opportunities and avoid expensive
misjudgements. </p>
<p>Our methods are often challenging - but we are confident we
will change the way you think about your business. </p>
<hr size="4" width="50%">
<h2 align="center">HOW CAN WE HELP YOU?</h2>
<p><i>London Economics can be particularly useful where
industries are changing and management needs help in refocusing
the business; where regulatory or fiscal structures have a strong
impact on performance; in complex industries where improving
efficiency requires sophisticated analysis; and where
understanding the possible actions of your competitors and their
key strengths and weaknesses is critical.</i> </p>
<p>We can provide help to companies in monopolies and mergers
enquiries or Treaty of Rome cases and create the framework for a
successful argument in court or before a regulator. Our modelling
skills can often produce key evidence which helps win an
argument. And we can predict the effects of change and thus
influence the policy debate. <br clear="left">
</p>
<hr size="4" width="50%">
<h2 align="center">SPECIAL SKILLS</h2>
<p><i>Our analytical skills and experience in dealing with
government institutions have made us the first choice in
industries where regulatory or fiscal structure have a strong
impact on performance. We are the regulatory advisers to much of
Britain's water, electricity and gas industries. We have been
active in key aspects of the complex transition to a more
market-orientated National Health Service in the UK.</i> </p>
<p>Our modelling skills have been used by numerous clients in the
broadcasting and advertising sectors. We have helped the BBC to
understand and improve its competitive position. And we have
worked with leading retailers to manage the dramatic changes in
their sector. </p>
<p>Obviously, we have a detailed knowledge of many industries but
if we have a unique skill it lies in the ability to understand
change and help our clients to manage it. <br clear="right">
</p>
<hr size="4" width="50%">
<h2 align="center">WHO USES LONDON ECONOMICS?</h2>
<p><i>We are an international business, with a wide variety of
clients, in a wide variety of industries, coming from more than
45 countries around the world.</i> </p>
<p>The bulk of our work comes from private corporations in
Britain and overseas. The international agencies finance much of
our overseas work in the Third World and the former Soviet Union.
Some of our clients are from representative organisations and
trade associations. The work we do for government departments and
regulatory agencies, although a small part of our turnover, is
important because our knowledge of these organisations, and the
respect they have for us, is central to our effectiveness. Over
40 percent of our business is located overseas, split in roughly
equal proportions between Western Europe, the former Soviet bloc,
and the rest of the world. </p>
<p>Many of our first major clients were the newly privatised
firms in the energy and water industries. But if we have a unique
skill it lies in our knowledge of any particular industry than in
our ability to understand, and help our clients cope with,
change. So our consultancy today covers a wide range of
industries in flux. </p>
<hr size="4" width="50%">
