<hr>
<p><a name="Competition Policy"><font size="5"><cite><strong>Competition
Policy</strong></cite></font></a></p>
<p><a href="../pubs/comp/issue.htm"><font size="3">An Issue In
Search Of A Policy</font></a><font size="3"> </font>Public policy
is in disarray when tackling attempts by suppliers to influence
the distribution of their product. In the six cases (beer,
petrol, gas, electricity, life insurance, airline reservations
systems) we looked at, the facts of the case in each pair are the
same, yet policy approach the problem in quite different ways.</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/comp/intelprop.htm"><font size="3">Intellectual
Property Rights</font></a><font size="3">. </font>Intellectual
Property permeates much of the modern economy, and forms the
basis of some important industries which contribute significantly
to national income. The protection of Intellectual Property
rights is essential for the functioning of these industries. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/comp/copycat.htm"><font size="3">Copycats
Products - a Fair Cop?</font></a><font size="3"> </font>We are
all becoming accustomed to supermarket shelves lined with
look-alike products. Are they simply cashing in on others ideas,
or are they providing helpful information? Are they denying
manufacturers a fair return to investment, or benefiting
consumers through fair competition? </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/comp/microsft.htm"><font size="3">The
Microsoft Antitrust Case</font></a><font size="3">. </font>An
economic perspective on Microsoft's recent antitrust troubles </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/comp/costall.htm"><font size="3">Cost
Allocation in Principle and Practice</font></a><font size="3">. </font>How
not to allocate the chairman's salary </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/comp/barrier.htm"><font size="3">Barriers to
Entry and Exit in Competition Policy</font></a><font size="3">. </font>Understanding
the analysis of competition and monopoly </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/comp/magill.htm"><font size="3">An Economic
Perspective on the Magill Case</font></a><font size="3">. </font>Should
competition policy override intellectual property rights? </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/comp/mmcelect.htm"><font size="3">The MMC
Investigation into the Electrical Goods Market</font></a><font
size="3">. </font>Why do firms ever refuse to supply? </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/comp/mergpol.htm"><font size="3">Merger
policy in Germany and the UK</font></a><font size="3">. </font>In
November 1995 London Economics held a major conference bringing
together experts and practitioners from the UK and Germany to
discuss merger policy in Europe. The discussions ranged from the
role of mergers in strengthening the competitive position of
European companies in global industries such as electronics,
chemical industries and automotive manufacturing, to the
comparative analysis of a number of merger cases in retailing,
media and defence industries. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/comp/books.htm"><font size="3">Are Books
Different?</font></a><font size="3"> </font>Only two goods are
exempted from the general ban in Britain on resale price
maintenance: books and medicaments. Last year, however, the
Publishers Association decided that it would no longer try to
enforce the Net Book Agreement, which prevented retailers from
competing with each other by discounting book prices. </p>
<hr>
<h2><a name="Corporate Strategy "><font size="4"><cite><strong>Corporate
Strategy </strong></cite></font></a></h2>
<p><a href="../pubs/strategy/sharhldr.htm"><font size="3">Shareholder
Value</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Emphasis on the
generation of shareholder value is a current business fad. Its
transatlantic origins are all too obvious. The efforts of
corporate raiders sent terror through many American boardrooms in
the mid 1980s. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/strategy/success.htm"><font size="3">Foundations
of Corporate Success</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Most
people think that the uses of economics in business are in
understanding macroeconomic developments - what will happen to
growth, inflation and the exchange rate - or in handling public
policy issues - dealing with competition policy or regulatory
agencies. In his book &quot;Foundations for Corporate
Success&quot;, London Economics' Chairman, John Kay, explains how
economic analysis can contribute to an understanding of the
central strategic issues of the business. In this article, he
explains his approach. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/strategy/leracing.htm"><font size="4">London
Economics Goes Racing</font></a><font size="4">: </font>Racing
may be the &quot;sport of kings&quot; but it is also an important
British industry. That was the view we took when we were asked by
the Jockey Club which regulates British racing to analyse the
economic issues involved.</p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<hr>
<h2><a name="Eastern Europe and Developing Countries"><font
size="4"><cite><strong>Eastern Europe and Developing Countries</strong></cite></font></a></h2>
<p><a href="../pubs/internat/prioriti.htm"><font size="3">Developing
Priorities</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Can the developing
countries of the world modernise their economies without
catastrophic environmental side effects? Analysis by LE suggests
that, if electricity generation is planned sensibly, it should be
possible. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/internat/markets.htm"><font size="3">Markets
Not Hierarchies</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Microeconomists
specialise in market analysis, and new markets are springing up
everywhere. the most dramatic change is in Eastern Europe, where
the creation of a stock market seems a priority second only to
the evolution of an electoral system.</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/internat/jamaicn$.htm"><font size="3">Freeing
the Jamaican Dollar?</font></a><font size="3"> </font>A current
theme in Eastern Europe is &quot;Liberalisation&quot; - of
prices, trade, and capital movements. A contentious aspect of
liberalisation is its &quot;sequencing&quot;: should
liberalisation of the domestic economy precede the liberalisation
trade and capital flows, or should all reforms be carried though
at one gulp (&quot;shock therapy&quot;, Polish style)? </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/internat/eastern.htm"><font size="3">Eastern
Approaches</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Western Consultants
rarely visited Eastern Europe and the Former Soviet Union until
recently. Now these countries are a growth area for consultants.</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/internat/ebrd.htm"><font size="3">The
&quot;New&quot; EBRD</font></a><font size="3">: </font>An
interview with Nick Stern. A founder member of London Economics.
Who took over as Chief Economist for the European Bank for
Reconstruction Development in 1994. He talks to Bill Robinson
about the work of the Bank following the replacement of Jacques
Attali by Jacques De Larosiere as its president.</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/internat/gaza.htm"><font size="3">Water
resources in Gaza</font></a><font size="3">: </font>In October
1995, London Economics was invited to participate in a World Bank
mission to the Gaza Strip to advise the Palestinian Authority on
options for upgrading the water and wastewater system. The
mission was in response to an urgent personal appeal for help
from Yasser Arafat to the President of the World Bank. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/internat/reform.htm"><font size="3">Reform
Rolls East</font></a><font size="3">: </font>As the reform of the
public utilities hots up in Eastern Europe, LE is providing
expertise for a number of innovative projects initiated by the
major donor organisations. The reform concepts born in the
Anglo-Saxon world of arm's length corporate governance
relationships and a clear separation of powers within the state
cannot always be straightforwardly transplanted to Eastern
Europe, let alone to the countries that formerly made up the
Soviet Union. </p>
<hr>
<p><a name="Education "><font size="4"><cite><strong>Education </strong></cite></font></a></p>
<p><a href="../pubs/educat/degree.htm"><font size="3">Marketing a
Degree?</font></a><font size="3"> </font>The first successful
&quot;market&quot; in higher education was introduced in 1990 by
the Polytechnics and College Funding Councils (PCFC), responsible
for allocating government funds to 84 polytechnics and colleges.
The new market was created to expand the number for students in
the sector at minimum cost: the PCFC is successfully funding 16%
more places each year, with reductions in unit costs. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/educat/highered.htm"><font size="3">Paying
for Higher Education: </font></a>Who should pay for higher
education? And why? These questions were brought into prominence
when the Committee of Vice-Chancellors and principals (CVCP) met
to discuss possible ways to increase the amount of funding
allocated to higher education. This article examines some aspects
of paying for higher education. </p>
<hr>
<p><a name="Environment"><font size="4"><cite><strong>Environment</strong></cite></font></a></p>
<p><a href="../pubs/environ/nitrate.htm"><font size="3">Least
Cost Nitrate Control</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Based on
the work we did for ICI, this examines the EC Directive that
limits nitrate level in water supply. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/environ/acidr.htm"><font size="3">Using the
Market to Control Acid Rain</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Government
seeking to control emissions have a basic choice: direct the
major power plant operators' actions, or leave control to the
market. Most governments prefer a &quot;command-and-control&quot;
approach. Our report suggests market mechanisms can be used to
meet the UK's emission target at a lower resource cost. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/environ/trees.htm"><font size="3">Seeing the
Wood for the Trees</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Britain is
poised to make several major new forest investments. recreation
and environmental benefits are their main economic justification.
LE faces the challenge of valuing recreational facilities and
landscape improvements.</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/environ/globwrm.htm"><font size="3">Global
Warming</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Environment problems
are making headline news increasingly often. One of them, Global
Warming, has been brought to public attention by the summit in
Rio de Janeiro. That showed how difficult it is to reach
international consensus on tackling what is, in effect, an
international problem. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/environ/tradep.htm"><font size="3">Have
Permit, Will Trade</font></a><font size="3">: </font>The
realisation that permit trading could harness market forces to
cut the cost of controlling pollution was described in the US
Congress as &quot; the one bright idea of the 1980s&quot;. Why
was it thought to be such a good idea? Are economists right to be
so conceited about it? </p>
<hr>
<p><a name="Government"><font size="4"><cite><strong>Government</strong></cite></font></a></p>
<p><a href="../pubs/gov/areacost.htm"><font size="2">Area Cost
Adjustment</font></a></p>
<hr>
<p><a name="Health"><font size="4"><cite><strong>Health</strong></cite></font></a></p>
<p><a href="../pubs/health/healthc.htm"><font size="3">What's
Different About Health Care?</font></a><font size="3"> </font>Can
the NHS learn from similar changes in other organisations? Has
the NHS its own specific requirements?</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/health/thenhs.htm"><font size="3">The NHS in
the Looking Glass</font></a><font size="3">: </font>The
watchwords for the introduction f the NHS market for 1991-92 are
&quot;steady state&quot; and &quot;block contracts&quot;. What do
these watchwords mean?</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/health/medprac.htm"><font size="3">Medical
Practice Variation</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Sickness is
unpredictable, so the need for health care, and its potential
costs, are uncertain. patients are anxious and poorly informed
about health care choices. even afterwards, they are often unable
to judge whether the most effective care has been provided Costs
of health care are financed through insurance (Mostly by
governments). Doctors act as the patient's agent in making
choices. This means that rationing is implicit with constant
arguments over &quot;underfunding&quot;. The costs of services
demanded always exceeds available funds.</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/health/hospheal.htm"><font size="3">Hospitals
and Health</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Hospitals are in a
period of great change throughout the Western World. Hospitals
used to care for the sick whilst nature took its course.
Improvements in knowledge and technology then changed them into
centres of curative medicine. Now these same treatments can be
provided as expertly, and as safely, outside these &quot;centres
of &quot;excellence&quot;.</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/health/regulat.htm"><font size="3">Regulating
the Market for Health Service</font></a><font size="3">: </font>The
introduction of a 'purchaser/provider' market in the Health
Service has been a key feature of policy in the 1990's, not just
in the UK. The belief is that such a move will improve
efficiency, and patients will gain. The argument runs that
experience and theory suggest that markets know best; when
sellers compete, on price and quality, to satisfy buyers, the
result is to drive standards up, and prices down. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/health/hospital.htm"><font size="3">Why We
Need Fewer Hospitals</font></a><font size="3">: </font>One of the
most difficult decisions faced by the Health Secretary, Virginia
Bottomley, has been whether or not to allow St Bartholomew's, the
famous London teaching hospital, to close. The disappearance of
venerable hospitals always causes an outcry but like the
disappearance of much loved steam trains, it is an inevitable
consequence of technical progress.</p>
<hr>
<p><a name="Legal Aid "><font size="4"><cite><strong>Legal Aid </strong></cite></font></a></p>
<p><a href="../pubs/legal/legaid.htm"><font size="3">Free Justice
for All</font></a><font size="3">: </font>What has been the
government's top spending priority since 1979? Fighting crime?
The National Health? The infrastructure? The answer is none of
the above. The programme which has recorded the fastest growth
rate over the period has been the provision of legal aid. There
are good micro-economic reasons for this as London Economics, who
has been looking at the economics of legal aid for the Lord
Chancellor's Department, discovered. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<hr>
<p><a name="Macroeconomics"><font size="4"><cite><b>Macroeconomics</b></cite></font></a></p>
<p><a href="../pubs/macro/plantool.htm"><font size="3">A Planning
Tool</font></a><font size="3">: </font>In a year when government
and City economist have hardly distinguished themselves by
getting their forecasts right it may seem strange to promote the
notion that economic forecasts are a valuable tool for corporate
planning. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/macro/postel.htm"><font size="3">Post-election
Prospects</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Post the 1992
election, the economy has shown distinct signs of revival. Estate
agents report increased interest and high street stores
experienced their first rush for months. Sales of products as
diverse as cars and replacement windows are bouncing back.</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/macro/gobust.htm"><font size="3">Can
Countries Go Bust?</font></a><font size="3"> </font>When the
Socialist economist Piero Sraffra received a small inheritance
immediately after WWII, he amused himself by buying the almost
worthless bonds of a defeated government. Implicitly, he was
betting that this was a country that, despite the odds, would
restore its international financial standing and repay its debts
in full. The country was Japan, and, against his political
convictions, Sraffra made a fortune. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/macro/whatind.htm"><font size="3">What is an
Index?</font></a><font size="3"> </font>LE's work includes
developing indices of process and costs for specific industries.
However, complex the inputs, the basic principles of index
construction always remain the same. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/macro/tworecs.htm"><font size="3">A Tale of
Two Recessions</font></a><font size="3">: </font>The worst
recession since the 1930's? Empirically, it isn't. Output fell
further, and faster, in the recession of the early 1980's, that
is has this time. But for many people, firms, sectors and some
regions, this is indeed the worst recession since the 1930's. The
distribution of pain is very different in this recession that in
the last. So are the causes, effects and future consequences.</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/macro/whaterm.htm"><font size="3">What
Happened to the ERM?</font></a><font size="3"> </font>The best
way to answer this question is to look at the difference in
structure between the current ERM and the &quot;old&quot; ERM.
Was the old system successful? How did it survive for so many
years? What has occurred recently to change this? The focus of
this article is on asymmetry and inflexibility. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/macro/slowgrow.htm"><font size="3">A Decade
of Slow Growth in Spending?</font></a><font size="3"> </font>Consumers
spending has been the driving force behind economic growth for
the past 15 years. But the rate of growth was exceptional in the
1980s, and we will have to get used to less buoyant consumption
for the rest of the century. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/macro/eurosing.htm"><font size="3">Europe's
Single Issues</font></a><font size="3"> </font>The Single Market
is at the heart of the political and economic debate about the
future of the European Union, live again with the approach of the
1999 deadline for the creation of a Single Currency. </p>
<hr>
<p><a name="Media"><font size="4"><cite><b>Media</b></cite></font></a></p>
<p align="left"><a href="../pubs/media/market2.htm"><font
size="3">BIDS - The future of Digital Television in Europe</font></a><font
size="3">: A major research project examining the future of
Europe's digital television and multimedia services has just been
launched and commercial organisations such as yourselves have the
opportunity both to guide and benefit from the outcome of this
study. </font></p>
<p><a href="../pubs/media/auctions.htm"><font size="3">The
Economics of Auctions</font></a><font size="3">: </font>As the
broadcasting industry awaits the results of the auction for the
new franchises for Independent Television (what we must learn to
call Channel 3), it seems that things have gone seriously awry. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/media/oscars.htm"><font size="3">Oscars For
London Economics</font></a><font size="3">: </font>In the last 10
yrs the structure of the film industry has undergone a radical
transformation, brought about by the emergence of video. VCRs are
becoming almost as commonplace as tvs and hi-fis. Nowhere is
Europe has this been more pronounced that in the UK, where VCR
ownership has risen to almost 70% of households. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/media/geog.htm"><font size="3">The
Competitive Advantage of Geography</font></a><font size="3">: </font>It
is 50 years since southern California became the centre of the
world's film industry . Film makers were attracted by the
benevolence of the climate and the sharpness of the light. With
modern technology, these factors are far less important. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/media/itvreg.htm"><font size="3">ITV:
Regulation, Recession and Crisis</font></a><font size="3">: </font>In
the wake of the Channel 3 auction, ITV may have retained its name
but everything else about the UK's commercial television system
has changed: more than either the legislators or the companies
themselves could have imagined or wanted. The primary source of
this change is not legislation, technology, nor market
globalisation, but the economic recession. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/media/cultprot.htm"><font size="3">Cultural
Protectionism in Europe</font></a><font size="3">: </font>The old
Common Market was created to promote free trade. The new European
Union has become increasingly protectionist. The 1989 Directive
requires broadcasters in the Member States to &quot;reserve for
European works a majority of their transmission time.&quot; Does
such protectionism serve any purpose? A recent the impact of the
quotas, suggests not. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/media/barons.htm"><font size="3">Reining-in
the Media Barons</font></a><font size="3">: </font>The government
wants to maintain a plurality of sources of information and
opinion in the media while allowing major companies to take
advantages of the opportunities provided by the multi-media
revolution. So cross media ownership will be no longer be
forbidden, but governed by new regulations based on market
shares. How can these be measured? London Economics was asked by
the BBC to Examine the alternatives. </p>
<p>BIDS - <a href="../pubs/media/market2.htm">Introduction</a> / <a
href="../pubs/media/bidsov2.htm">Overview of project</a>: The
Broadband Infrastructure for Digital TV and mulitimedia Services
project (BIDS) was launched in September 1995 by the European
Commission. it forms part of DGXIIIB's research and technical
development programme in advanced communication technologies and
services (ACTS).</p>
<hr>
<p><a name="National Lottery"><font size="4"><cite><b>National
Lottery</b></cite></font></a></p>
<p><a href="../pubs/lottery/gamble.htm"><font size="3">Gambling
for Good Causes</font></a><font size="3">:</font><font size="2"> </font>In
March 1992, the Government published a White Paper containing
plans to introduce a National Lottery in the UK in support of
&quot;good causes&quot;. This article is based on our work for
the Gulbienkien Foundation. (<i>Economics in Action</i> 1992/TWO) </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/lottery/camelot.htm"><font size="3">Camelot -
The Best Bet</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Eight consortia
battled it out to win the Licence to operate the Lottery,
spending millions of pounds putting their application together.
What did the Director General of the office of the National
Lottery look for when he assessed the bids? London Economics
worked on the Camelot bid. This article explains the basic
economics of lotteries. (<i>Economics in Action</i> 1994/TWO) </p>
<hr>
<p><a name="Pensions"><font size="4"><cite><b>Pensions</b></cite></font></a></p>
<p><a href="../pubs/pensions/pensionf.htm"><font size="3">Whose
Money in the Pension Fund?</font></a><font size="3"> </font>As
controversy over the Maxwell company pension funds continues to
grow, it seems inevitable that the relationship between pension
funds and their parent companies will come under close scrutiny. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/pensions/pensblue.htm"><font size="3">Pension
Blueprint</font></a><font size="3">: </font>&quot;Hard cases made
bad law.&quot; That is the danger of the Maxwell pensions affair.
Robert Maxwell was a ruthless crook who broke the law repeatedly
and with impunity. But moral outrage is a poor guide in the
search for a more rational system of occupational pension
regulations. What can be put in its place? </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/pensions/longtc.htm"><font size="3">Who pays
for long-term care?</font></a><font size="3"> </font>In his
Budget for 1996-97 the Chancellor has responded to widely-felt
anxiety about the rising costs of caring for the elderly. The
Government is to consult on further possible changes of great
importance to the financial services industry, including the
development of variable pensions and &quot;Partnership
Schemes&quot;. LE has developed a unique modelling capability in
this area. </p>
<hr>
<p><a name="Privatsation and Regulation"><font size="4"><cite><b>Privatisation
and Regulation</b></cite></font></a></p>
<p><a href="../pubs/privat/costcap.htm"><font size="3">The Cost
Of Capital</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Measuring the cost
of capital has been one of the key issues in the regulation of
British utilities. It was central to the determination of x for
the regional electricity companies and k for the privately owned
water supply companies. It featured in the redetermination of the
regulatory formula for British Telecom.</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/privat/elGames.htm"><font size="3">Electricity
Games</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Evolution of game theory
has been one of the most important recent developments in modern
economics. Whenever the behaviour of one agent determines the
preferred behaviour of another, or vice versa, game theory
provides the tool for the economist to analyse the problem. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/privat/realreg.htm"><font size="3">The
Reality of Regulation</font></a><font size="3">: </font>When
privatisation occurred, the affected industries were deeply
involved in the negotiation of regulatory rules and regulatory
structures. They mostly thought that, once the heady bust busy
period of flotation was over, regulation would be a much smaller
portion of their concerns. They were wrong. If anything, the pace
of regulatory activity has increased, and the degree of
regulatory pressure has intensified. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/privat/privtnec.htm"><font size="3">Is
Privatisation Necessary?</font></a><font size="3"> </font>Britain's
privatisation experiment is ten years old. While there were some
sales of public sector assets in the early Thatcher years, it was
a decade ago that the government decided to embark on the first
of the great utility privatisations - the sale of British
Telecom. That is time enough for some preliminary verdicts on the
success of the process. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/privat/bench.htm"><font size="3">Benchmarking</font></a><font
size="3">: </font>When benchmarking, comparisons must be
like-with-like. Efficiency comparison across firms are often
problematic: comparisons across countries make the challenge even
greater. LE tackled this issue recently, when a client asked us
to create robust and defensible performance indicators for its
electricity supply industry, to compare with international best
practice.</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/privat/benchart.htm"><font size="3">Benchmarking:
The State of the Art</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Benchmarking
allows companies to compare the efficiency of all or part of
their activities with others doing the same things. We introduced
this important technique in <i>Economics in Action</i>
1992/Three. London Economics is at the forefront of &quot;best
practice&quot; benchmarking in the UK and abroad. Advanced
techniques ensure efficiency comparisons are as accurate and
informative as possible. This article describes some of the
methods we use. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/privat/rightks.htm"><font size="3">The Right
&quot;Ks&quot; for the Water Industry?</font></a><font size="3"> </font>In
1994 Director General of OFWAT, Ian Byatt, has just announced
price limits for the water industry in England and Wales for the
next ten years. Will this prove a durable settlement? There is
room for doubt. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/privat/altpriv.htm"><font size="3">New
Alternatives to Privatisation</font></a><font size="3">: </font>What
should we do with publicly - owned organisations which trade in
the private sector? There are many organisations of this kind,
including some large high profile bodies like the Post Office and
the BBC. In the 1980s the conventional wisdom was that they
should all be privatised, and the sooner the better. But the
debate about the future of the Post Office last autumn, the
alternative solution of giving publicly - owned enterprises
&quot;more commercial freedom within the public sector&quot; was
widely discussed. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/privat/hotsum.htm"><font size="3">Regulation's
Long Hot Summer</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Privatised
utilities, in particular water, electricity and gas have been
subjected to an exceptional degree of public criticism. The
companies, the regulators and the system of regulation have all
been attacked. But the calls for reform of utility government are
largely misguided. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/privat/infrajam.htm"><font size="3">Privatising
Infrastructure in Jamaica</font></a><font size="3">: </font>In
Jamaica the population is increasing. The country is also aware
of rising environmental demands. Despite a socialist government,
Jamaica is now privatising its utilities. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/privat/discret.htm"><font size="3">Discretion
rules, OK</font></a><font size="3">: </font>In November 1995,
Oftel held the first public hearing in the history of UK utility
regulation, on the proposal to introduce a provision in
operators' licences prohibiting anti-competitive behaviour.
Oftel's suggestions were opposed by British Telecom, but
supported by most other operators. Oftel asked John Kay, Chairman
of LE, to provide an independent contribution to the debate. This
is an edited text of what he said. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/privat/wastew.htm"><font size="3">Cutting
waste in wastewater</font></a><font size="3">: </font>With 30
water companies in England and Wales, Ofwat is better placed than
most regulators to use comparative benchmarking techniques to
assess efficiency. It has pioneered the rigorous and systematic
collection of data and undertook a major benchmarking exercise
for the 1994 Periodic Review. This was an important input into
its determination of water prices for the next five years. </p>
<hr>
<p><a name="Product Liability"><font size="4"><cite><b>Product
Liability</b></cite></font></a></p>
<p><a href="../pubs/legal/prodliab.htm"><font size="3">The
Economics of Product Liability</font></a><font size="3">: </font>When
should a manufacturer face liability for the injury caused by his
product? Should he be liable only when proven negligent, or held
strictly liable for any defects? Can the law accurately
discriminate between defective and dangerous products?</p>
<hr>
<p><a name="Retailing"><font size="4"><cite><b>Retailing</b></cite></font></a></p>
<p><a href="../pubs/retail/sunday.htm"><font size="3">Born to
Shop on Sunday?</font></a><font size="3"> </font>An article
summarising London Economics' report on the main issues of the
Sunday trading regulations.</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/retail/grocret.htm"><font size="3">Grocery
Retailers - Heroes or Villains?</font></a><font size="3"> </font>Grocery
retailers have been under attack. Firms like Tesco, Sainsbury's,
Safeway and Asda have been regularly accused of making excess
profits, failing to pass on price cuts, exploiting cheap labour
and of running Britain's town centres.</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/retail/nextrev.htm"><font size="3">Retailing's
Next Revolution?</font></a><font size="3"> </font>Terry Leahy of
Tesco led the cast of experts debating the future of retailing at
LE's conference in February. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<hr>
<p><a name="Taxation and Public Expenditure"><font size="4"><cite><b>Taxation
and Public Expenditure</b></cite></font></a></p>
<p><a href="../pubs/taxation/cigboot.htm"><font size="3">Cigarette
Bootlegging</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Modelling work
undertaken at LE suggests bootlegging is likely to be more
prevalent in Europe that it is in the US, once boarder controls
are removed.</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/taxation/inflturk.htm"><font size="3">Curbing
Inflation in Turkmenistan</font></a><font size="3">: </font>London
Economics' international macro team have participated in an
EC-funded mission to examine the Turkmen tax system and recommend
practical reforms that will put the economy on the path to steady
growth with low inflation. The country faces a formidable
inflation problem which can be traced to an unusual source.</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/taxation/thebill.htm"><font size="3">Sharing
the bill for lunch</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Three years'
experience, plus a squeeze on public capital spending, have
brought the Private Finance Initiative into the consciousness of
every Government department, and should bring it on to the agenda
of every company with an interest in managing infrastructure
projects or running public services. The key issue in almost all
of these is the allocation of risk between public and private
partners - an issue on which LE has established expertise to
offer.</p>
<hr>
<p><a name="Transport"><font size="4"><cite><b>Transport</b></cite></font></a></p>
<p><a href="../pubs/trans/tunnel.htm"><font size="3">Tunnelling
for the Truth</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Despite
substantial setbacks, services through the Channel tunnel are now
in operation. Eurostar is an attractive new alternative mode on
one of the most travelled air routes in the world. The Shuttle
provides a smooth alternative to ferries for holiday makers.
These new market entrants provide a serious challenge to the
incumbents. Tunnelling for the truth about how competition will
unfold is a serious challenge to economists. London Economics
reports from the cutting edge. </p>
<hr>
<p><a name="Utilities"><font size="4"><cite><b>Utilities</b></cite></font></a></p>
<p><a href="../pubs/utility/drought.htm"><font size="3">Drought
in the Rain</font></a><font size="3">:</font>As the rain falls
with its usual intensity over most of England this winter,
thoughts of drought seem out of place. But water companies
throughout the South are spending this winter devising ways to
cope with water shortages. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/utility/dashgas.htm"><font size="3">The Dash
for Gas</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Since the privatisation
of the electric industry in 1989/90, 8.6 GW of new gas fired
power stations have been commissioned. This represents some 15% f
current total generating capacity. At the same time, the plans of
the old CEGB for the construction of further coal-fired plants
have been shelved, and the closure of around 5 GW of coal-fired
generating plants has been implemented or announced. The
so-called &quot;dash for gas&quot; is equally matched by a
decline in demand for coal in our power stations. </p>
<p><a href="../pubs/utility/ensov.htm"><font size="3">Energy
Strategy in the Former Soviet Union</font></a><font size="3">: </font>One
legacy of central planning is an economic structure based on
absurdly cheap energy. London Economics has worked on two large
projects funded under the EC's programme of Technical Assistance
to the Commonwealth of Independent States (TACIS).. These help
newly-independent countries develop economic strategies to raise
their energy prices to world levels, and deal with the
far-reaching economic consequences. The challenges are typical of
those facing many of the countries in the region.</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/utility/indpow.htm"><font size="3">Unleashing
India's Power Sector</font></a><font size="3">: </font>India was
the archetypal non-aligned developing country. Its historical
links with the west through the British Raj were balanced by the
strong influence of the former Soviet Union on its northern
borders. So the Indian political economy was a classic mixed
economy with a strong dirigiste element in certain sectors,
notably power, which shares some - but not all -of the problems
of Eastern Europe.</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/utility/austchal.htm"><font size="3">Dealing
with Challenges in Australia</font></a><font size="3">: </font>Five
different Governments, covering a population the size of greater
London in a continent larger than the United States: that is the
challenge posed by Australia.</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/utility/califrnt.htm"><font size="3">California's
New Frontiers</font></a><font size="3">: </font>As 1995 ended,
the Public Utilities Commission of California set out its
long-awaited vision for the future of the power industry in
America's largest state. As 1996 has progressed, London Economics
has found itself increasingly involved in the design of
competitive power markets in the United States.</p>
<p><a href="../pubs/utility/casefor.htm">The Case for Twelve</a>:
In November 1987, LE completed a landmark report for the twelve
electricity area boards. Most of them - indeed, 11 out of 12 -
wished to challenge the prevailing notion that they should be
privatised en bloc. LE provided them with the economic
ammunition.</p>
<hr>
