<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>What's in a Decade</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h1>What's in a decade?</h1>
<hr>
<blockquote>
    <p align="left"><em><strong>In 1986, the British economy was
    hotting up for boom and bust. Ten years later, we are at much
    the same point in the economic cycle - but policies and
    pressures look very different ...</strong></em></p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>Privatisation, contractorisation, de-regulation,
customerisation - 1986-96 was the key period for the Government's
&quot;supply side&quot; reforms. How have they affected the
economy as a whole? Placing 1986 and 1996 side by side highlights
some intriguing similarities - but also some important
differences.</p>
<p>Now as then, the economy has been growing for several years,
but inflation is (at least by British standards) very low. Then
as now, a Government facing a general election within less than a
year was hoping that mix would boost consumer confidence - the
famous &quot;feel-good factor&quot;. The index measure of this
will o' the wisp is today much where it was in the summer of
1986: still negative, but getting less gloomy by the month. And -
just as they were 10 years ago - people are debating the question
of whether the economic cycle and inflation have finally been
laid to rest.</p>
<p>One lesson from the gyrations of the decade however clearly
stands out. An understanding of markets offered the best clues to
economic performance. The boom and bust of the late 1980s were
signalled in asset markets at a time when many macroeconomic
models had not begun to sound the alarm. And even the Treasury -
forcing-house of the Government's supply-side reforms - seems to
have undervalued the impact of these changes on wage and price
flexibility, persistently underestimating the most important
shift of the decade: the dramatic fall in inflation.</p>
<p>While 1986's 3.6 per cent rise in the Retail Price Index was a
brief low point in the last cycle, today inflation has been
running at or below 3 per cent for three years, and is now below
the G7 average. The precipitate fall in the exchange rate,
following Britain's exit from the European Exchange-Rate
Mechanism in 1992, had much less effect on prices than forecast
at the time. </p>
<p>This exit, of course, came at the moment in the cycle when
businessmen felt least able to raise prices. Monetarists can
point to very slow rates of growth in one or more money measures
in the early 1990s. But what now, after four years of recovery?
Is this, as in 1986, just the calm before the storm? After all,
fiscal policy looks a good deal looser than it did then. In
1986-87, the Government was close to balance between its spending
and revenue. Today, its deficit is still large; today's
Chancellor clearly does not have the elbow room that Lord Lawson
filled with the tax cuts of the late 1980s.</p>
<p>Interest rates, too, are much lower than in 1986 - even in
real terms. Admittedly, monetary growth is less spectacular than
it was then. In 1986, although narrow money was growing very
slowly, broad money measures were racing away. M4 increased that
year by over 15 per cent, lending by banks and building societies
by about 20 per cent. Today, both measures are in single figures.</p>
<p>But it is in the functioning of markets that change shows
through most starkly. The labour market, in particular, has
behaved quite differently in the 1990s. While average earnings
never grew by less than 7&#189; per cent a year in the 1980s,
since 1993 they have been rising at half that rate or less. </p>
<p>Unemployment began to fall much earlier in this economic cycle
than in the last, when it went on rising through five years of
output recovery; today the unemployment rate is under 8 per cent,
as compared with over 11 per cent in 1986. This is true even
after changes in the rules, and an increase in the number of
people now registered as incapacitated, are taken into account -
there are a million more people in work today than in 1986. Yet,
despite a rash of summer strikes, there is still very little sign
that the labour market is &quot;hotting up&quot;.</p>
<p>There are, as the Bank of England recently pointed out, more
people now outside the labour force, whether temporarily or
permanently. Much of the increase in employment has been amongst
women, the majority of whom work only part-time; adjusted for
this shift, employment has not risen so positively. But it still
contrasts sharply with the behaviour of the highly-regulated
continental European economies. All of which encouragingly
suggests the British economy can run down its unemployment rate
further, without igniting inflation, than in the 1980s. </p>
<p>The housing market - a powerful transmitter of inflation in
the 1980s - also looks less of a flash-point. The tax incentives
for house purchase have been greatly reduced since the 1980s.
This summer house prices did finally begin to inch ahead of the
general rate of inflation - but after five years of static or
falling house prices, the market has quite a way to go to erode
the problem of &quot;negative equity&quot;. </p>
<p>Privatisation and regulation of the utilities have also played
their part. Under their networks of &quot;RPI-X&quot; price cap
formulae, the former nationalised industries have put much less
upward pressure on retail prices than they used to, when their
public-sector owners were hungry for revenue. </p>
<p>But these real price cuts are part of a much greater price
sensitivity amongst businesses in general. Deregulation, the
breakdown of restrictive practices in industries ranging from
newspapers to the City, have increased competition. Work done by
LE on the phenomenon of &quot;price wars&quot;, and reported in
our last newsletter, was triggered by the rash of outbreaks we
have seen in the 1990s.</p>
<p>Microeconomic changes have, in short, made the British economy
of the mid-1990s discernibly different from what it was a decade
ago. Inflation continues to be only a shadow of its former self.
Reports of its death can be greatly exaggerated. So too can
expectations of a supply-side miracle. But better microeconomics,
a more flexible economy, a more competitive market, offer hope of
longer bursts of steady growth in output and lower rates of
unemployment. </p>
<p>witness in competition cases to modelling markets and
demographics; from understanding public policy to analysing
financial flows. The very first pieces of work illustrate the
diversity. LE found itself analysing the impact of ad valorem
taxes and specific duties on tobacco - work which flowed directly
from its founders' tax expertise; but also appearing for the
London Metal Exchange, against whom action was taken under
Articles 85 and 86 of the Treaty of Rome, over the impact on
competition of its actions in &#147;ringing out&#148; the market
following the collapse in the tin price. </p>
<p>Competition cases followed thick and fast: was the Milk
Marketing Board distorting competition, to the disadvantage of
the Irish Dairy Board, by selling milk more cheaply for
butter-making than for liquid consumption? Was Texaco breaching
fair trading rules in the pricing of its petrol? Was
Nestl&eacute; &#147;monopolising&#148; the soluble coffee market?
But so did strategic and policy work: LE was involved in helping
the TSB develop lifecycle products, in helping Tesco examine the
prospects for cross-border shopping, and - a forerunner of
substantial Antipodean utilities business - examining the costs
and benefits of gas contracts which had turned bad on the
government of Western Australia. </p>
