<hr size="4">
<h2><a name="Price Wars.">Priced to kill</a></h2>
<hr size="4">
<p><a name="Price Wars."><font size="4"><em>Between January and
March 1980, the phrase `price war' appeared in the Financial
Times only 13 times. During the same three months of 1996, it
popped up 160 times. Why are so many businesses slashing their
profits in the battle for market share? What, precisely, is a
`price war'? And who are the winners and losers?</em></font></a></p>
<p><a name="Price Wars.">Price wars have broken out right across
the range of consumer markets. Some, such as the markets for
optical goods, books, telephony equipment, personal computers and
even property, are relatively `immature', in terms of the degree
of price competition that already existed. But others, such as
the petrol, DIY equipment, food, and newspaper markets, were
already 'mature' - pricing was already highly competitive before
war broke out.</a></p>
<p>For the first meeting of our <em>Strategy Club</em> (see box),
LE has undertaken research into the question as to why such very
different businesses as Esso, News International, Philip Morris
and P&amp;O should have chosen to destroy their profit margins by
slashing prices. For members of the Club, we have used this
research to identify strategies that may be used by firms to win
or avoid price wars. In this article, we summarise some of our
general findings.</p>
<table border="1" width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td width="100%">
        <h3><a name="Strategy Club"><font color="#FF0000">LE
        Strategy Club</font> </a></h3>
        <p><a name="Strategy Club"><font size="2"><strong>We held
        our first meeting of our innovative Strategy Club in May.
        The aim is to provide a forum where blue-chip companies
        can meet to discuss a variety of techniques for devising
        and implementing commercial strategies. Topics discussed
        at the first evening session were the importance of size
        and scale in determining competitive advantage, price
        wars and the commercial implications of a low inflation
        world.</strong></font> </a></p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>
<p>&#160; </p>
<h3>When do price wars happen?</h3>
<p>Predatory pricing, loss leading, and the launch of a price war
are different forms of aggressive pricing, which has a strategic
intent - prices are cut now in the pursuit of a future gain. The
aim of starting a price war could be to change the structure of
the market, by forcing the exit of a rival (or deterring
potential rivals from entering); or to change the nature of
competition - the `rules of the game'.</p>
<p>In most consumer goods markets there are implicit `rules' of
competition (explicit rules, such as price fixing agreements, are
generally illegal). Such `rules' may dictate, for example, which
firm is the price leader; whether competition is based on price
or advertising; the form in which competition takes place (e.g.
through discounts, coupons or 2-for-1 offers). These informal
rules may have evolved over a long period of time, through the
interaction of firms' strategies, to a point where they seem
relatively well established. </p>
<p>Sometimes, however, this stable form of competition breaks
down. One firm may `cheat' by undercutting the others. This may
spark off a price war, as others seek to punish the `cheat' in
order to re-establish a set of rules. Alternatively, if the
market changes, so that the initial set of rules no longer
generates the most profitable form of competition, firms may go
in for aggressive pricing until new rules are established.</p>
<table border="1" width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td width="100%">
        <h3><font color="#FF0000">The costs of a price war </font></h3>
        <p><font size="2"><strong>Suppose that unit costs of
        production are 5 and that fixed costs are 100. Suppose
        also that at a retail price of 10, you sell 100 units. At
        this price, total profits are, therefore, 400 (1000 of
        revenues minus 500 of variable costs and 100 of fixed
        costs). This implies a return on costs of 67%. Now,
        suppose that you cut the retail price by 2 to 8. If sales
        are unchanged because (say) your rival responds with the
        same price cut, profits fall by 50% to 200. Of course, it
        is unlikely that your sales will not increase with a 20%
        reduction in price, even if your competitor does copy the
        price cut. But how many extra sales do you need to make
        the price cut profitable? In this example, the answer is
        a sales increase of 67%, which implies a price elasticity
        of demand of over 3.3. Few products have elasticities as
        high as this. Moreover, even if you do manage to boost
        sales to this extent, the return on your costs will have
        fallen from 67% to 43%.</strong></font> </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>
<p>A classic example of a `cheat' is a new entrant to the market
who refuses to play by the established rules of the game. Of
course, this 'cheating' may be unintentional (if the informal
rules are simply not understood); some price wars (like their
bloodier military equivalents) have clearly started by mistake.
On the other hand, sometimes entrants are quite clear that
`cheating' is necessary - if the established rules of the game
are intended to keep them out. The fact that the supermarkets
have chosen to compete with the existing petrol retailers almost
entirely on price certainly runs against the rules of the game
established by the oil majors.</p>
<p>An equally clear example of a market trigger is a new
technology which changes the cost structure of at least one firm,
or reduces barriers to entering the market. The classic example
here is the entry of Eurotunnel into the cross-Channel market,
with a cost structure significantly different to that of the
ferries. Since Eurotunnel needs to achieve a high market share,
and since its marginal costs are much lower than the ferries', a
price war is almost inevitable.</p>
<p>Another common trigger is a reduction in product
differentiation. When products become more homogenous, pricing
becomes more important. This has occurred in the market for
personal computers, financial services, telephony equipment and
auditing. It may yet occur in the markets for medicaments sold
without prescriptions, mobile telephones and short-haul flights.</p>
<p>Pricing, even for the most basic of products, is a complex
business. It requires much thought and analysis, not only of
one's best strategy, but of one's rivals' best strategies. So
mistakes are easily and often made; actions easily and often
misunderstood. Our research demonstrates that it is a lot easier
to start a price war than to win one. A firm may make a temporary
price cut which its rivals think is permanent, and react
accordingly. The results may be extremely expensive. Or a `cheat'
may miscalculate the risks of punishment, triggering a price war
it never supposed would happen. Misreading rivals' degree of
commitment is also a common route to losing a price war.</p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>A war worth fighting?</h3>
<p>But assuming a firm starts a price war deliberately, it must
do so because it believes a short-term loss of profits will be
outweighed by a longer term gain. For such a strategy to work,
you must have the muscle to win - to do enough, for long enough,
to change the structure of the market. And, second, you must be
able to keep your `winnings'. A long-term gain can only be
achieved if the post-war rules of the game will generate a stable
(and profitable) outcome. You must feel confident that those
competitors which have exited as a result of your low pricing
policy cannot re-enter the market (or be replaced by others). Or
you must be sure that any gains made in market share will not be
lost when prices start to rise again. </p>
<p>These two criteria - the ability to win the war, and the
ability to keep the gains afterward - are not easy to meet. So
price wars may be extremely costly, and rarely result in outright
winners. Using prices to change the structure of the market is
much more difficult than is generally imagined. Pricing to force
the exit of a rival (often known as predation) may cross the
boundaries of legality. Predators found guilt of such practices
face heavy fines by the competition authorities. Moreover, firms
will often hang on in `their' markets much longer than it is
economic to do so. This may be due to pride, or to the belief
that the predator will lose heart and give up. Many commentators,
for example, thought that the objective of News International,
when it launched a price war in the newspaper market, was to
force<em> The Independent</em> out of the market. If this was
true, the battle plan failed.</p>
<p>Meanwhile, the cost of price wars tends to be felt in the
bottom line. That is, the short term costs can be extremely high
and only very large increases in market share, or post war
prices, can recover these losses (see box opposite). In practice
this rarely happens. Price wars also tend to focus the consumer's
attention more closely on prices, so that future price increases
are more difficult to achieve. </p>
<p>To win the war, a firm has to convince its rivals of its
absolute commitment to fight. This factor was critical to the
success of 'Marlboro Friday' (see below). Without commitment the
firm is unlikely to win; rivals will match its price cuts and
wait for it to withdraw. </p>
<p>The ability to hold on to price war gains depends on a certain
asymmetry between prices and profits. Falling prices must enable
you to capture more market share than you will lose when prices
go up again. Brand loyalty, barriers to entry and the existence
of a clear price leader are all helpful when trying to end a
price war successfully.</p>
<p>What does that tell us about the petrol price war? Esso (the
instigator) is undoubtedly committed, and many of the conditions
for a return to profits are present. However, there are a couple
of very important question marks. How will the supermarkets
behave? At the moment, they have not responded aggressively. Does
this mean that they are willing to behave less aggressively in
the future, or are they simply waiting? What are Esso's long-term
objectives? If it wanted to force the small independents to exit,
how long would it need to maintain low prices? Well, we may not
have long to wait for an answer to that question.</p>
<table border="2" width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td width="100%">
        <h3><font color="#FF0000">How 'Marlboro Friday' took the
        trick</font> </h3>
        <p><font size="2"><strong>Perhaps the most dramatic price
        war of recent years was the decision on Friday, April 2
        1993, by the American tobacco giant Philip Morris to cut
        the price of its best-selling cigarette in the US market,
        Marlboro, by almost 20 per cent. The news of this
        strategy echoed around the financial markets (the Dow
        Jones dropped 50 points on the day, as analysts worried
        about an infectious outbreak of price wars). </strong></font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><strong><img
        src="../../images/gamble.gif" align="right" hspace="10"
        vspace="10" width="386" height="284"></strong></font><font
        size="2"><strong>Repeated health warnings in the 1970s
        set in train a long term decline in the size of the US
        market. The price gap between the two segments (main
        premium and generic) widened, as prices were increased
        for premium brands (to capture higher revenues from a
        smaller volume). Smokers began to switch to cheaper
        cigarettes. In the 1980s, producers began to back their
        generic brands with advertising, creating a new middle
        market. The most aggressive player in this `cut-price
        premium' game was American Tobacco. In 1992, Marlboro's
        share began to fall rapidly. The firm decided to `punish'
        undercutting with a massive price cut of its own; and at
        a stroke, to destroy the middle market. The damage to
        American Tobacco was fatal. Within a few months of the
        price cuts they were acquired by B&amp;W (a US subsidiary
        of BAT), a company that was deeply rooted in the premium
        segment, with no incentive to begin another round of
        price cuts. By the end of 1994, the market share of
        Marlboro was back up again. So were cigarette prices.
        This time, however, premium and generic brands went up in
        line with each other. A two segment market of high and
        low-priced products was re-established in the US. The war
        was over.</strong></font> </p>
        <p><font size="2"><strong>The chart illustrates the
        choice that confronted Philip Morris. The price cuts
        followed a classical punishment strategy, aimed at
        recreating an ordered market, and many factors pointed
        towards success. Philip Morris was, in effect, the price
        leader. Brand loyalty is high in the cigarette market.
        Consumers who switched to Marlboro when prices were low
        were less likely to switch back as they rose again. There
        are enormous economies of scale in cigarette production,
        making it unlikely that firms driven out of the market
        would re-enter or be replaced. Finally, Philip Morris was
        clearly committed - with deep pockets to finance a war,
        and everything to lose from defeat.</strong></font> </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>
<p><em>&#160;Contact: </em><a href="mailto:simon@londecon.co.uk"><em>Simon
Gaysford</em></a></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<hr size="4">
<h2><a name="Digital Revolution">Small digits, big stakes</a></h2>
<hr size="4">
<p><a name="Digital Revolution"><font size="4"><em>Digital
television - the delivery of moving images via digital
communications networks or on digital media - is on its way. LE
is part of a consortium of European research organisations
carrying out a three-year study for the European Commission of
the economic and regulatory barriers to its development. </em></font></a></p>
<p><a name="Digital Revolution">Digital television will affect
not only the entertainment, information and education industries,
but all those providing information-based services to society.</a></p>
<p><a name="Digital Revolution">The `BIDS' - Broadband
Interactive Digital Services - project is a three- year study of
the economic and regulatory barriers to the introduction of
digital television in Europe. It forms part of the European
Commission's research programme underpinning its preparation for
the `Information Society'. Between now and 1998, the BIDS
consortium will be preparing a series </a>of reports analysing
the state of the market, regulation and the likely development
paths for digital television services. </p>
<p>As we approach the end of the first year of our work, it is
clear that digital television presents some formidable challenges
for public and private sector organisations seeking to position
themselves and to put in place effective strategies, not to
mention the policy-makers who will be responsible for overseeing
a fundamental restructuring of society's information-based
activities.</p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>Strategic directions</h3>
<p>The BIDS study has identified two main groups of players in
the digital television market: entrenched dominant incumbents
(e.g. broadcasters) with a position to defend; and organisations
looking to break into the prospective new markets, (e.g. telecoms
operators). These two groups are not mutually distinct. Telecoms
operators also have a defensive agenda, to make up for the
erosion of their existing businesses, while broadcasters are
looking to find new ways of extracting the value from the
programmes they produce and from their strong brand names.</p>
<p>The pattern emerging so far is of players forming into groups
based around the adoption of a common decoder technology. The
decoder is the piece of 'network terminal equipment' which
enables the digital signal to be un-scrambled (if necessary) and
converted to a standard that permits the information carried by
the signal to be presented on a normal TV set, a radio or a
personal computer. The commonest form of decoder at present - a
television `set-top box' - is the last link in a chain which
consists of content providers, publishers and packagers, network
operators, providers of conditional access and subscription
management services, marketeers and retailers.</p>
<p>The most powerful decoder group has as its members
Bertelsmann, for the time being the third largest media company
in the world; Compagnie Luxembourgeoise de
T&eacute;l&eacute;vision, Europe's biggest commercial TV company,
which is about to be taken over by Bertelsmann; Germany's two
public service broadcasters, ARD and ZDF, and Deutsche Telekom,
with its telecommunications and cable networks. Canal Plus, the
French pay-TV company, has also been involved, but BSkyB, the UK
satellite broadcaster, has recently pulled out, illustrating the
fragility of these alliances.</p>
<p>The competition to the Bertelsmann-led camp is another
German-led enterprise, DF1, which brings together the Kirch
Group, controllers of the German rights of most feature films and
operator of a number of TV channels; Nethold, the subsidiary of
the Richemont Group which controls pay television in the
Netherlands, Scandinavia and South Africa; Telepi&ugrave;, the
Italian pay-television network; Vebacom, part-owners of Cable and
Wireless and challengers to Deutsche Telecom; and the Metro
supermarket chain. </p>
<p>The Bertelsmann and Kirch-led consortia are in a race to bring
their mutually-incompatible decoders to the German market.
Whichever comes out on top in Germany will be in an almost
unassailable position with regards to the rest of Europe. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>Battle standards</h3>
<p>The audio-visual industry continues to be haunted by the
spectre of the home video standards battle which took place in
the first half of the 1980s between Sony, JVC and Philips.<br>
To avoid the delays in successful introduction of the new digital
television technology, two global fora have been established: the
Digital Video Broadcasting (DVB) group and the Digital
Audio-Visual Communications (DAVIC) group. The two groups, which
overlap, include most of the world's broadcasters, cable
companies, telecommunications operators, communications equipment
and component suppliers. Within the two groups, members try to
agree technical standards before these are submitted to the
official standards- setting process overseen by the International
Standards Organisation (ISO). </p>
<p>Having tried and failed to impose a High Definition Television
standard, (spending 4 billion ECU of public money, most of which
was funnelled to Philips and Thomson, in the process), the
European Commission is trying to encourage the emergence of
technical standards for digital television from the industry
itself. </p>
<p>DVB and DAVIC equally try to discourage the Commission and
national governments from wading in and imposing structures. But
the level of co-operation within these groups is limited; the
participants' principal concern seems to be to keep an eye on
their competitors and to prevent the adoption of standards which
might prejudice their individual commercial interests.
Superficial agreements may mask profound disagreements, for
example, in the area of systems architecture and network access. </p>
<p>The Bertelsmann/Kirch battle in Germany, for which the lines
are still being drawn, is more likely to determine the standards
issues than the 1990s' commercial equivalent of the League of
Nations. The European regulators need then to ensure access to
the dominant standard on a non-discriminatory basis.</p>
<p>But the European Commission is now widening its perspective.
The interim results of studies carried out in 1995 by several
directorates are focusing on the impact of change on business and
society. Key to this is access by citizens to the full range of
digital services; and this in turn, is leading the Commission to
concentrate more on the role of public service broadcasters.</p>
<p align="center"><img src="../../images/digitnet.gif"
align="middle" width="496" height="306"></p>
<p>&#160; </p>
<h3>Back to Auntie</h3>
<p>Ever since the mid-1980s, when the process of liberalising
Europe's television markets began, the outlook for the
traditionally dominant public service broadcasters has seemed
grim. In 1996, however, the prospect is changing. The recent
publication by the BBC of its manifesto, &lt;M&gt;Extending
Choice in the Digital Age, establishes an approach which is
likely to be adopted throughout Europe. Public service
broadcasters will be acutely involved in defining and driving
digital television. The participation of the German public
service broadcasters, ARD and ZDF, in the Bertelsmann-led MMBG
digital set-top box consortium is one example of public sector
participation - which should incidentally help to broaden the
standards discussion. The establishment in France of a digital
television consortium, T&eacute;l&eacute;vision Par Satellite,
involving the public sector's France T&eacute;l&eacute;vision, as
well as the two commercial terrestrial broadcasters, TF1 and M6,
is another. </p>
<p>The European Commission, for its part, should move away from a
view which plays down or is even antipathetic towards public
service broadcasters. Today, it should recognise their central
role in delivering new services, and mobilise their commitment in
the difficult task of setting the right regulatory framework for
the future.</p>
<p><em>Contact: Jonathan Davis</em></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<hr size="4">
<h2><a name="Singapore">Trading up for Singapore</a></h2>
<hr size="4">
<p><a name="Singapore"><font size="4"><em>The 122 founding
members of the new World Trade Organisation are preparing for
their first parents' meeting - the trade ministers' get-together
in Singapore this December. Although there have been
disappointments since the end of the Uruguay round of
negotiations, the WTO is bedding down with adjudications already
beginning to stream out of its new, tougher procedures for
settling trade disputes.</em></font></a></p>
<p><a name="Singapore">The General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade
was a supposedly provisional post-war arrangement which in fact
lasted nearly half a century. From the days of Bretton Woods,
western governments aspired to create a troika of international
institutions - an International Trade Organisation, an
International Bank for Reconstruction and Development and an
International Monetary Fund. It is not hard to understand why the
first got stuck on the launch-pad, while the World Bank and the
IMF flew. The founders amongst the rich world did </a>not expect
much threat to their sovereignty from organisations concerned
with giving aid or setting policy for economic basket-cases. An
organisation which might order them to change their trade
policies was a different matter.</p>
<p>Tariffs were still high when the second attempt to create such
an organisation was made in the 1950s. They were still
much-prized even by countries which theoretically opposed
protectionism - the disastrous habits of the 1930s died hard. So
GATT survived on sufferance, and without any real authority. Its
main purpose was to act as a clearing-house for talks between
governments on trade disarmament, in a succession of negotiation
`rounds' mainly focused on the reduction of tariffs on traded
goods.</p>
<p>Even when the Uruguay Round of negotiations began in the
mid-1980s, there was no serious talk of creating a new
institution. The scope of this round was considered to be quite
ambitious enough as it was, bringing in services for the first
time, making the first serious attempt to reduce distortions in
agricultural trade, and wrestling with such complex non-tariff
issues as intellectual property, government procurement policies
and investment restrictions. Even quite late on in the
negotiations, while breakthrough was being achieved in 1992-93,
the issue of a new institution was on the back burner. The
attitude of the United States Congress was considered to be too
hostile for it to be worth wasting negotiating firepower on
institutional change, when it was badly needed to secure progress
on the sensitive issues of farm trade, textiles and services.</p>
<p>While the Bush administration deserves credit for pursuing
trade negotiations right up to the 1992 election, and reaching
agreement with the Europeans on farm trade, it was the Clinton
administration which clinched the break through deal on
manufactured goods tariffs at the Tokyo summit in 1993. The
British Government's role was also critical, in its
Atlantic-bridging role. Britain used its European Presidency late
in 1992 to unblock the farm talks, and early in 1993 persuaded
President Clinton to accept the challenge of concluding
negotiations with Europe and Japan - the keys to a wider deal. It
was also Britain's EC Commissioner, Sir Leon Brittan, who carried
the responsibility for the European negotiating position.</p>
<p>There were still, at the end, some sharp disappointments. Much
of the services agenda remained unresolved. And the three big
pieces of unfinished business in this area have made depressingly
little progress since. There is now an outline agreement on
financial services, but the United States is not, so far, any
part of it. There is no agreement on telecommunications, beyond
an agreement to extend the deadline until next year. And
discussions on maritime services have - most predictably of all -
foundered on the rock of US resistance.</p>
<p>Moreover, the early days of the WTO were blighted by a clash
between the United States and Japan over automobiles which
threatened to demonstrate that the world's big boys would
continue to fight their own trade battles outside the
`multilateral' framework of the WTO. Perhaps fortunately,
however, this dispute arose before the ink was dry on the 26,000
pages of the new treaty signed at Marrakesh in April 1994: as the
godfather of the new agreement, the United States found it highly
embarrassing to be seen to be ignoring it so early, and backed
off its open confrontation into WTO procedures.</p>
<p>These procedures give the WTO greater authority than GATT
possessed, and the curiosity is that such important institutional
change slipped though so quietly at the end of the Uruguay round.
Admittedly, even the WTO does not possess direct enforcement
powers (something which would certainly have ensured early
abortion for the new body). It is up to the countries concerned
to come forward with proposals for abiding by its rulings, once
they have exhausted their right to appeal to the new appellate
body. But - unlike under GATT rules - these judgements cannot be
blocked by the `guilty party' in the trade organisation itself.</p>
<p>The procedures have been tested early. It is not merely the
number of issues now being reviewed by WTO panels, and by the new
appellate body that has been created, that is significant. The
first two judgements to emerge concern the practices of the
world's most powerful trading nations, the United States and
Japan.</p>
<p>In the first case to be adjudicated on by the appellate body,
concerning US environmental standards for gasoline that two Latin
American oil producers claimed discriminated against imports, the
appellate body found against the United States - though with a
number of wrinkles which blunt the humiliation. Japan's
preferential taxing of home-produced spirit compared with whisky
imports has been the next issue to reach the final stages of the
WTO procedures. A finding against both of the world's greatest
trade warriors would be a high-profile early start for the WTO.
The case-law that develops, which will have a kind of
step-child's relationship to the findings of the old GATT panels,
will be a new and important area of work for economists and
lawyers.</p>
<p>In the meantime, the WTO's members have been reviewing the
`new trade agenda' discussed at the WTO's christening party.
Three issues - environmental standards, labour standards and
competition policy - were argued by some to be so relevant to the
enforcement of trade rules that they should be embedded in the
WTO's ways of working. Only the first, however, was made the
subject of a formal WTO working group.</p>
<p>Many countries remain suspicious of the `new trade agenda',
and with good reason. Developing countries fear that concern with
labour standards by the United States and some European countries
is a barely-concealed attempt to re-erect protectionism barriers
against low-income countries with inevitably lower standards of
social protection. The environmental agenda arouses some of the
same suspicions. As for competition policy, it has not yet become
clear whether those who wish to see it reflected in trade rules
are really taking the argument further than it has already
reached in its review of non-tariff barriers.</p>
<p>So far, the WTO's concern with environmental issues seems to
have been sensibly focused on trying to ensure that international
treaty obligations (environmental on the one hand, trade on the
other) do not actually conflict. The issue of labour standards
was referred to the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and
Development for analysis; the resulting work is sensibly
sceptical about a link with trade policy.</p>
<p>There is, however, still a risk that the issue will hijack the
agenda at Singapore, antagonising many of the developing
countries whose greater involvement in trade negotiations has
been one of the most positive features of the new WTO. Another
sensitive issue which has come to the fore since Marrakesh is the
prevalence of bribery in trade deals with certain countries - but
here there is more prospect of a practical discussion of
proposals than an explosive argument about countries' rights to
determine their own social policies.</p>
<p>It will, however, be surprising if some of the most liberal
ambitions for Singapore, such as an acceleration of the tariff
reductions agreed during the Uruguay round, secure agreement -
although liberal governments will push for this. Nor is there
likely to be much serious talk about another `trade round' -
although Britain's President of the Board of Trade, for one, has
argued that WTO members should set themselves the ambition of
starting another before the turn of the century, and has talked
of trying to create a `global single market' by 2020. The `Cairns
Group' of farm producers, with the Australians to the fore, have,
meanwhile, been arguing for agricultural negotiations to be
restarted before the agreed date of 1999 - but none of the
Europeans are likely to respond with much enthusiasm to that.</p>
<p>Meanwhile, the WTO is at least enjoying the sincerest form of
flattery, in a long list of applications for membership. But few
observers expect there to be very rapid progress in processing
the three most sensitive applications - China, Taiwan and Russia
- even if the United States has now taken the important step of
renewing `most favoured nation' status for China. We are, after
all, in the year of the donkey and the elephant.</p>
<p><em>Contact: </em><a href="mailto:sarah@londecon.co.uk"><em>Sarah
Hogg</em></a></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<hr size="4">
<h2><a name="Commercial">What price commercial freedom?</a></h2>
<hr size="4">
<p><a name="Commercial"><font size="4"><em>The demand for more
commercial freedom within the public sector is in the main a
demand for greater freedom to borrow. Why is that freedom denied?
Does the Private Finance Initiative offer a solution? Are there
others? London Economics has been helping some of its clients
think about these issues. </em></font></a></p>
<p><a name="Commercial">Treasury scepticism, the source of so
much frustration amongst public sector managers, has its roots
deep in experience. In the late 1940s, the newly nationalised
industries had all sorts of plausible investment plans. Since
they were not subject to a market test, too many were approved.
The result was over-investment, at the taxpayers' expense, in
projects which produced a low return. The nation as a whole
suffered from this misallocation of scarce capital resources; an
echo of the much more dramatic misallocation in communist
countries, where no investment at all was subject to a proper
market test.</a></p>
<p>Investment in the public sector is funded with money which is
relatively cheap, because it is borrowed with an implicit
guarantee from the government. These cheap funds are limited by
overall controls on public borrowing, designed to protect the
taxpayer. But there are a number of organisations in the public
sector - the Post Office and the BBC are the best known - where
the management feels that it is unable to develop commercial
strategies properly because of restrictions on their borrowing
power.</p>
<p>Some projects, in fact, may be sufficiently profitable to be
financed with more expensive private money. Under the old rules
this was not allowed, on the grounds that such borrowing was more
expensive. Through the Private Finance Initiative (PFI), those
rules have now been relaxed. If a project can pass this market
test, it can now leave the queue for cheap public money and go
ahead with more expensive commercial funding available to
private-sector partners in a PFI project. This is a sensible, if
belated, recognition that it must be in the national interest for
profitable projects to go ahead. </p>
<p><img src="../../images/national.gif" align="right" hspace="10"
vspace="10" width="327" height="316">However the PFI does not
solve the problem faced by commercially- minded organisations in
the public sector who want to raise money to engage in new
activities themselves. The reason flows from the requirement that
PFI schemes must involve a genuinely risk-taking private partner.
This means that management control of PFI projects must pass
outside the public sector. For some organisations, this creates a
sort of Catch 22: you can only raise money to fund a bright new
idea if that idea is handed over to someone else to execute - not
a very attractive prospect for an entrepreneurial management in
the public sector.</p>
<p align="left">&#160;</p>
<h3>Ownership and control</h3>
<p>The PFI is a natural successor to the privatisation programme.
Privatisation reflected the belief that the only way to deal with
inefficient dinosaurs in the public sector was to transfer them
wholesale into the private sector. But in between full state
ownership and private ownership there are many intermediate forms
of corporate governance in which ownership and control of the
assets of the company, old and new, are treated differently. </p>
<p>The new options range from contracting-out, or separating the
role of purchaser and provider, through PFI and 'GoCo'
(Government owned, contractor operated companies), to full
privatisation. `Corporatisation' - designed to give state
organisations more commercial freedom but also more commercial
discipline - is a further variant receiving political attention. </p>
<p>In order to assess these ideas we need to understand the
problem that the plc was designed to solve. In primitive agrarian
societies the farmer owns and controls everything. There are no
plcs. But in advanced industrial societies it typically requires
the pooled savings of many individuals to pay the complex capital
for the equipment and the services of specialist managers to run
it. Immediately there are potential conflicts of interest between
the owners of the equipment, who are looking for a financial
return on their savings, and the managers, who are looking for a
salary and a quiet life. </p>
<p>The limited liability company is an ingenious device to
reconcile the conflicting interests of savers and managers.
Companies compete in the market for savings by offering a return
on capital. In the short run the <em>manager</em> of a company
has complete control over its assets. But if he consistently
fails to deliver an adequate return, the manager will be fired.
In the long term it is the <em>shareholder</em> who has control. </p>
<p>&#160; </p>
<h3>Corporatisation</h3>
<p>In the nationalised industries, there is no shareholder
looking for a proper return on capital. And the managers are
instructed to pursue a variety of objectives other than
maximising the return on capital (e.g. keeping prices down or
providing employment). Like the employee with two bosses who
always tells the one that he is busy doing something for the
other, managers with two objectives can end up meeting neither. </p>
<p>If public sector managers were given a clear remit to deliver
a market return on capital employed, and total freedom to achieve
that objective (subject to the constraint that they would be
sacked if they failed to deliver) then there is no reason in
principle why they should not perform as efficiently as private
companies. A neat way of achieving this set of incentives would
be to make the state the sole shareholder in what was otherwise a
perfectly normal independent corporation that was required to
deliver a normal stream of dividends to owners. </p>
<p>This model of corporate governance is used abroad, most
notably in New Zealand where the Post Office and the Electricity
Corporation are both organised along these lines. The Swedish and
Dutch Post Offices are also independent, but publicly owned,
corporations. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h3>Other options</h3>
<p>But corporatisation is not the only way of injecting private
sector disciplines or commercial freedom in to the public sector.
Contracting out the provision of certain public services - from
office cleaning to IT - was the earliest example of the new
`mixed economy'. Separating purchaser and provider became a
common form of public sector management - with the provider
sometimes inside, sometimes outside the public sector. Another
example is the GoCo. In this model a private sector company takes
over a public asset and runs it on commercial lines - as for
example Devonshire Management Ltd runs Devonshire Royal Dockyard.
Under these arrangements the asset remains in the public sector
but the management of the asset, and some incremental investment,
is transferred to the private sector. </p>
<div align="right">
<table border="2" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="50%">
</table>
<p></p>
</div><div align="left">
<table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td width="100%">
        <h3><a name="LE in Japan"><font color="#FF0000">LE in
        Japan </font></a></h3>
        <h3><a name="LE in Japan"><font size="2"><strong>LE is
        collaborating with </strong></font><font size="3"><strong>Esec
        International </strong></font><font size="2"><strong>of
        Tokyo in a venture to develop Japanese overseas
        development assistance work and also to develop
        opportunities in the Japanese domestic market. </strong></font><font
        size="3"><strong>Esec </strong></font><font size="2"><strong>is
        part of ETC, a Japanese engineering group, specialising
        in the environment, solid waste and water. Under the
        arrangement with Esec, LE expertise is available to major
        Japanese consultancies working in the development
        assistance market. Primary sectors are environment,
        water, solid waste, transportation and electricity. In
        the Japanese domestic market, the focus will be on the
        environment, utilities and other areas. </strong></font></a></h3>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>
</div>
<p>All these different ideas - contracting- out, corporatisation,
the GoCo, the PFI - have one thing in common. They show that it
is possible to divorce ownership from control. Under the
corporatist model, ownership remains with the state but control
is handed over to private sector managers. Under the GoCo model
ownership of the asset remains with the state, but the private
sector takes on the management. Under the PFI ownership and
control of existing assets may remain with the state, but new
assets are controlled in the private sector and jointly owned by
the public and private sector. </p>
<p>What are the advantages and disadvantages of these different
forms of governance? Obviously it depends what the objectives
are. At London Economics, our approach has been to identify the
incentives and constraints inherent in the current PFI rules, and
match these to the aims and objectives of the &#147;players&#148;
- the Government, the Treasury, the private sector bidders for
projects and the public sector organisations wishing to obtain
PFI finance. Are the current PFI rules appropriate for these
players? Should they be changed and if so, how? If not, are there
alternative forms of corporate governance for public sector
organisations that deliver the required commercial freedom,
including freedom to borrow, without the risk of wasting
taxpayers' money? </p>
<p>Many organisations in and on the boundaries of the public
sector will have to address these difficult issues and London
Economics is helping businesses work out the commercial
implications (and opportunities) of these profound changes in
corporate governance.&#160;</p>
<p><em>Contact: </em><a href="mailto:bill@londecon.co.uk"><em>Bill
Robinson</em></a></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<table border="1" width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td width="100%">
        <h3><a name="Czech Water"><font color="#FF0000">New
        democracies, new answers</font> </a></h3>
        <p><a name="Czech Water">Before the Velvet Revolution in
        1989, water companies in what is now the Czech Republic,
        like other utilities and industries, were owned and
        controlled by central government. The subsequent reform
        has followed a rather different route from the English
        privatisation pattern. Prices have risen much more
        spectacularly than in England. Yet, while the management
        of water companies comes under increasing attack here, in
        the Czech Republic it is going remarkably smoothly.
        Beginners' luck - or political skill? </a></p>
        <p><a name="Czech Water">On most objective measures,
        English water companies - including the foreign-owned
        ones - have done well by customers and shareholders.
        Efficiency, customer service, investment and profits are
        all up. Tariffs have risen only moderately to pay for the
        massive investment programme, and are still lower than in
        France or Germany. Yet water privatisation is
        increasingly unpopular, six years after the event,
        leading the Labour Party to promise regulatory reform and
        taxes on `windfall' profits. </a></p>
        <p>The Czech Republic faced many of the same problems as
        the UK did. Huge investments are needed to meet EU
        standards. Water utilities are overstaffed, and not
        responsive to customers. As in the UK, private management
        and finance are an attractive solution. But, given its
        history, the Czech Republic faced a tougher task than the
        UK in bringing in private managers. </p>
        <p><img src="../../images/czech.gif" align="right"
        hspace="10" vspace="10" width="265" height="209">To cope
        with the removal of state subsidies, and the backlog of
        maintenance and rehabilitation work, tariffs have doubled
        in real terms (see graph). Tariffs will increase further
        once new investment starts in earnest. These increases
        have hit pockets hard. While the average household in
        England and Wales now spends just over 1% of its income
        on water and sewerage services, in the Czech Republic the
        figure is currently over 2.5%. These changes have been
        accompanied by a direct infusion of management from the
        leaders in the field - UK and French water companies. In
        a country where even shops and restaurants had been
        state-owned for years, foreign private ownership of an
        essential service like water posed a political challenge. </p>
        <p>Reform has followed a three stage approach. First was
        decentralisation. Ownership of the water companies was
        devolved to municipalities, or to associations of
        municipalities in the case of regional water companies.
        Secondly, the operating company was separated from
        ownership of the pipes and other infrastructure.
        Municipalities own the infrastructure. The operating
        company employs the staff, owns the operating assets
        (office buildings and equipment, vehicles, workshops,
        etc.), and is responsible for operating the
        infrastructure to provide water services. </p>
        <p>The third step, which only some municipalities have
        taken, was to privatise the operating company. Typically,
        one third of the shares would be bought by local
        investment funds and individuals, one third would be
        bought by an international water operator, and the
        remainder would be retained by the municipality. </p>
        <p>The new public-private partnership has weathered its
        first challenges well. Neither the price increases nor
        the fact of foreign involvement has evoked serious
        protest. Of course, this maybe a honeymoon period. In
        time, when consumer groups are more organised, when the
        media become more aggressive, and when profits begin to
        be repatriated to foreign investors, the Czech model too
        may run into strife. But its distinctive approach offers
        certain advantages, at least in the Czech context. With
        public ownership of the infrastructure, foreign ownership
        of less than 50% of the operating company, and local
        democratic control over prices and investment, the Czech
        system is better armoured against public criticism.
        Whether this will provide the best long-term answer,
        however, still remains to be seen. </p>
        <p><em>LE visited the Czech Republic as part of a EBRD
        (Municipal and Environmental Infrastructure Team) study
        into ways to encourage private sector participation in
        municipal services in Central and Eastern Europe. </em></p>
        <p><em>Contact: </em><a href="mailto:davide@london.co.uk"><em>David
        Ehrhardt</em></a> </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>
<hr size="4">
