<h1 align="center"><tt>Issue Two 1996</tt></h1>
<hr width="45%">
<p align="left"><font size="3">Contents:</font></p>
<ul>
    <li><a href="1996_2.htm#1">Europe's single issues</a> </li>
    <li><a href="1996_2.htm#2">California's new frontiers</a> </li>
    <li><a href="1996_2.htm#3">Reform rolls East</a> </li>
    <li><a href="1996_2.htm#4">Are books different?</a> </li>
    <li><a href="1996_2.htm#5">Retailing's next revolution?</a> </li>
</ul>
<p>&#160; </p>
<h2><a name="1">Europe's single issues</a></h2>
<p><a name="1"><b><i>The Single Market is at the heart of the
political and economic debate about the future of the European
Union, live again with the approach of the 1999 deadline for the
creation of a Single Currency.</i></b> </a></p>
<hr>
<p><a name="1">Many - particularly in Britain - saw the Single
Market simply as the fulfilment of the old idea of a &quot;Common
Market&quot;: a tariff-free zone, benefiting business and
consumers, but carrying no implications of political integration
or the creation of a European superstate. Others - more dominant
in continental Europe - saw the abolition of national barriers to
trade within Europe as only part of a seamless web of economic
and political union, with a Single Currency the logical next
step. But how closely are the two really linked? Of course, the
Single Market programme itself has involved more than a mere
abolition of tariffs. To deliver the full benefits, estimated in
the Cecchini report in 1988 as equivalent to an additional 4.5
per cent of the combined national incomes of member states,
Europe needed to demolish less visible barriers, such as
protectionist national &quot;industry standards&quot;. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">The Cecchini report indicated that nearly a
quarter of the benefit to consumers would come from the effect of
intensified competition in a Europe-wide market; and over the
past decade, European competition policy has been one of the
primary weapons in the battle to create the Single Market. An
important focus has been on restrictions erected by firms to
prevent cross-border competition. Plainly, the fact that the
costs of business are coming down does not automatically mean
that consumers benefit. If competition is still restricted or
inhibited, the benefits associated with the brave new Single
Market may prove to have been overstated. So the Commission has
launched a programme of research on the impact of the Single
Market, in which LE figures prominently. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">National Governments have faced a conflict between
their desire to maintain their own armouries of regulatory
weapons and the ambition to create a &quot;level playing
field&quot;. In pursuit of the Single Market, Brussels was given
new powers. It was the Single European Act, in the mid-1980s,
which spread the use of &quot;Qualified Majority Voting&quot; in
European Councils, thus removing the veto from individual nations
in a number of economic areas. Whether QMV should be extended, or
cut back, is now a highly contentious political issue. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">Back in the mid-1980s, enthusiasm for the goal of
a genuine, barrier-free trading block over-rode concerns about
sovereignty, even in the minds of the British Government of the
time; but these came back into sharp focus with negotiations over
the Maastricht Treaty in 1991. The plan for monetary union
involved the creation of new, powerful European institutions,
notably a European Central Bank, along with pressures for the
European Commission to have more say over national budgetary
policies. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">But is a Single Currency necessary to
&quot;complete&quot; the Single Market? The evidence is hardly
compelling: estimates of the direct addition to transaction costs
on business within the European Union stemming from the need to
switch from one currency to another range as low as 0.1 per cent
of combined GDP. Proponents of a Single Currency believe it would
lead to greater efficiency in both portfolio and direct
investment decision-making in Europe, if allocation was not
complicated by exchange-rate risk. On the other hand, opponents
of a Single Currency point to the potentially very serious
effects on both the unemployment level and on the volatility of
business cycles of constraining within a single monetary policy a
number of still very divergent economies. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">Meanwhile, the debate has begun to focus more
sharply on political issues: the accountability of a European
Central Bank, and the willingness of nation states to accept
severe constraints on their freedom to tax, spend and borrow. Any
of these issues, it is coming to be recognised, could blow a
currency union apart if not properly resolved in advance - or if
the answers lack popular consent. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">The answers in the Maastricht Treaty are being
challenged as much by supporters of a Single Currency as by
sceptics. The German Government, in particular, is seeking to
reassure doubters in that country that profligate nations would
not be able to debauch the Euro - hence the talk of &quot;fiscal
stability pacts&quot;, new &quot;convergence criteria&quot; or a
souped- up Exchange-Rate Mechanism as a preliminary to full
union. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">Two deadlines for a Single Currency were slotted
into the Maastricht Treaty at the very last moment: 1997, for a
possible first shot at monetary union, 1999, for automatic
membership by all (except Britain) which met the financial
criteria, intended to ensure that candidates' economies had
&quot;converged&quot; before they were allowed to join in. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">The table below shows how far most member states
are from meeting the fiscal criteria, in particular. With
Germany, technically within the borrowing limit in 1995, now
running a much larger deficit, only Luxembourg meets the lot. </a></p>
<div align="center"><center>
<table border="1">
