        <th align="left"><a name="1">United Kingdom</a></th>
        <td align="center"><a name="1">3.0</a></td>
        <td align="center"><a name="1">8.3 &#135;</a></td>
        <td align="center"><a name="1">-5.1</a></td>
        <td align="center"><a name="1">52.5 &#135;</a></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <th align="left"><a name="1">EU 15</a></th>
        <th><a name="1">3.0</a></th>
        <th><a name="1">8.9</a></th>
        <th><a name="1">-4.7</a></th>
        <th><a name="1">71.0</a></th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <th align="left" colspan="5"><a name="1">&#135; = meets
        criterion, * = 3 with least inflation<br>
        Source for data: European Monetary Institute, April 1996</a></th>
    </tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<p><a name="1">Delay is in the air, and even in the mouths of
prominent German politicians and bankers: but the official
position of all the likely participants is still that 1999 means
what it says. The final moment of assessment - and decision -
does not come until early 1998. By then, proponents of a Single
Currency argue, the recovery of growth in continental Europe will
have cut government deficits. Since a Single Currency without the
Deutschemark is inconceivable, the key issue then is whether the
Germans actually want to go ahead. If they still do, then it is a
fair bet that the criteria will be made to fit. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">Some small countries may be able to argue their
way under the wire, if they want to: notably, Denmark and
Austria. But will the French? The table shows that they face
severe problems in meeting the budget test. However, outright
rejection would be a desperate blow to Europe's core
Franco-German alliance. Italy's failure to meet the criteria
would also be politically difficult, but less likely to be
papered over. Spain faces similar difficulties, while Greece
seems to be right off the convergence scale. As for Britain, with
its deficit forecast to decline, debt level low, and inflation
down again, it may well be one of the few to meet the Maastricht
criteria. But but thanks to its special &quot;opt-out&quot;
protocol, negotiated in 1991, Britain still does not have to sign
up. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">So whether anything at all happens in 1999 is
uncertain. An alternative to delay, less embarrassing to
Franco-German politicians, may be for a few continental countries
to go ahead with a weaker version of the first phase of monetary
union. What is actually intended to happen on the 1st January
that year is an irrevocable fixing of exchange rates between
members, so that - in the words of the EMI - they become
&quot;different expressions of what is economically the same
currency&quot;. Though the new euro will also become a currency
in its own right, it is not intended to start replacing marks and
francs and so on with new notes and coin until 2002. So this
first phase could easily be watered down into a kind of ERM-plus
- and, for that matter, extended. </a></p>
<h4><a name="1">Uncommon market</a></h4>
<p><a name="1">Nevertheless, the deadline may still divide the
European Union into two camps. And the ripple effects of such
division on the Single Market may be very serious. Not only will
the costs of transition be heavy, for would-be members, but the
strains may well make them less likely to steam ahead with
outstanding Single Market business - in particular, resisting
measures that would open their markets to the &quot;outs&quot; as
well as the &quot;ins&quot;. Already, protectionism is beginning
to emerge in a new guise - with demands, particularly by the
French, that those outside monetary union should not be allowed
to &quot;profit&quot; from a competitive exchange rate. Hence the
urgency of the debate at the IGC that Europe should resolve the
issue of relationships between &quot;ins&quot; and
&quot;outs&quot; before plunging ahead with a partial union. It
would be bitterly ironic if the Single Currency were actually to
damage European economic integration - if the Single Market were
to begin to fragment before the full benefits have even been
realised. </a></p>
<p><a name="1"><b>Contact: Sarah Hogg</b> </a></p>
<hr size="4">
<h2><a name="2">California's new frontiers</a></h2>
<p><a name="2"><b><i>As 1995 ended, the Public Utilities
Commission of California set out its long-awaited vision for the
future of the power industry in America's largest state. As 1996
has progressed, London Economics has found itself increasingly
involved in the design of competitive power markets in the United
States.</i></b> </a></p>
<hr>
<p><a name="2">The Energy Policy Act of 1992 set the scene for
the long-awaited reform of the power industry in the United
States. The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission then began
developing plans requiring all private electric utilities to open
up transmission access. </a></p>
<p><a name="2">The centrepiece of the Californian vision is the
introduction of consumer choice through the establishment of a
Power Exchange to facilitate open competition among generators.
This is now a fairly standard element in power sector reform, not
just in the UK but also in New Zealand, Australia, Argentina and
Scandinavia. However the US approach, while potentially solving
some problems not yet properly tackled in these earlier examples
of reform, also throws up some interesting new issues. </a></p>
<h4><a name="2">Transition costs</a></h4>
<p><a name="2">The transition to competitive markets exposes the
uncompetitiveness of many of the inherited assets constructed
under a more lenient regulatory regime. In the United Kingdom,
the asset values of the Central Electricity Generating Board were
written down prior to privatisation of the successor companies.
British Gas currently finds itself exposed to substantial
liabilities from its commitment to gas purchase contracts which
were signed before the introduction of competition in gas
retailing, and which are no longer competitively priced. </a></p>
<p><a name="2">However these inherited problems are dwarfed by
some estimates of the costs of uneconomic generation, contracts
and other regulatory assets in California. The utilities
themselves have suggested costs as high as $30 bn, while other
more conservative estimates have still reached figures of around
$10 bn. These estimates compare with a market capitalisation for
National Power of around $8 bn. </a></p>
<p><a name="2">Determining the exact scale of the costs of
transition to competition in California and deciding how they
should be split between consumers and shareholders are issues
which will cloud the vision of competitively priced power for
many years to come. </a></p>
<p><a name="2">American free-market culture is forcing out the
frontiers of accepted practices in power market liberalisation.
Many industry participants were horrified to learn that in power
markets such as Britain, generators are compelled to sell all
their power into the Pool (the United Kingdom's own spot market
for electricity). </a></p>
<p><a name="2">This they saw as an unacceptable constraint on
commercial freedoms. So in California, the Public Utility
Commission has proposed the continuation of a bilateral contract
market between generator and final consumer, alongside a
voluntary Power Exchange. Moreover, to emphasise the voluntary
nature of the Power Exchange, it will be separate from the
Independent System Operator (who, given the physical
characteristics of electricity, must have sole responsibility for
matching supply and demand minute by minute over the network). </a></p>
<p><a name="2">Norway provides the only example of a bilateral
contract market existing alongside a daily spot market. But in
Norway hydropower accounts for virtually all generation, which
means that balancing supply and demand at the margin is a simple
matter of water release. This allows easy co-ordination of the
contract and spot markets. The problems of co-ordination in a
predominantly thermal-based system are only just beginning to be
realised. </a></p>
<h4><a name="2">Trading between regional markets</a></h4>
<p><a name="2">The reforms in California are only the first steps
towards a wider liberalisation of power markets across all of the
US. Market liberalisation will allow generators full access to
the markets of neighbouring and even more distant states. This
opens up significant trading opportunities. For example,
utilities as far away as British Columbia are already sizing up
the potential to profit from their low-cost hydro output by
selling it into the new California Power Exchange. </a></p>
<p><a name="2">Other players in the United States have been quick
to see that the scale and risks associated with these trades
present opportunities for them as well. In January, NYMEX
received regulatory approval to trade electricity futures and
options based on delivery at the Palo Verde switchyard in Arizona
and on delivery at the California-Oregon border. Trading
electricity in the United States will be quite unlike trades in
the much more constrained British market. </a></p>
<h4><a name="2">Implementing reform</a></h4>
<p><a name="2">Lastly, the reform process itself in the US will
be quite unlike that of other countries which have liberalised
their power markets. In the United Kingdom, New Zealand,
Argentina and Australia, the government owned 100% of the
industry undergoing reform. As a result, the government was
itself able to have the final say on the detailed implementation
of the reform and so speed the process along. In the United
States, ownership of the industry is mainly private sector.
Moreover reforms have to be sanctioned not just by the Public
Utility Commissions but also by state legislatures and the
Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. Gaining approval of the
final reform package is likely to prove to be a tortuous process. </a></p>
<h4><a name="2">Global ambitions</a></h4>
<p><a name="2">The new focus on competition will no doubt further
stoke the ambitions of American electric utilities and other
industry participants in the global push towards private finance
and operation of power systems. American electric utilities have
already purchased a British regional electricity company and
distribution and generation assets in Australia, New Zealand,
Britain and Germany. </a></p>
<p><a name="2">American companies are also major investors in
private power development worldwide: in India, China, Indonesia,
Chile and elsewhere in the developing world. </a></p>
<h4><a name="2">LE's role</a></h4>
<p><a name="2">London Economics is currently assisting utilities
in California and across the United States to understand how
competitive power markets work, and how best to develop their own
plans and strategies for the new market. </a></p>
<p><a name="2">Our new Boston office is providing on-going advice
for two of the largest utilities in the United States, Pacific
Gas and Electric and Duke Power, and assistance to other American
electricity companies on purchasing major assets elsewhere in the
world, notably in the United Kingdom and Australia. </a></p>
<p><a name="2"><b>Contact: Seabron Adamson, Robin Cohen</b> </a></p>
<hr size="4">
<h2><a name="3">Reform rolls East</a></h2>
<p><a name="3"><b><i>As the reform of the public utilities hots
up in Eastern Europe, LE is providing expertise for a number of
innovative projects initiated by the major donor organisations.
The reform concepts born in the Anglo-Saxon world of arm's length
corporate governance relationships and a clear separation of
powers within the state cannot always be straightforwardly
transplanted to Eastern Europe, let alone to the countries that
formerly made up the Soviet Union.</i></b> </a></p>
<hr>
<p><a name="3">Broadly, the further East you go, the less easily
these ideas apply. Like Napoleon's Grand Arm&eacute;e, the reform
battalions tend to fall away as the going gets tougher.
Privatisation, which is well underway in parts of the former
Yugoslavia, in Hungary, Poland and the Czech and Slovak
Republics, is increasingly problematic in countries like Belarus,
Bulgaria or Uzbekistan. Ideas like commercialisation and
independent regulation are inclined to suffer similar fates. </a></p>
<p><a name="3">But at the end of the road lies the prospect of
Moscow; Russia`s huge and potentially dynamic market, with
enormous comparative advantages in the energy sector, is the big
prize which drives the search for reform solutions. Unlocking
that potential could change the entire energy map of Europe. </a></p>
<p><a name="3">In this article, we briefly present LE's recent
and ongoing involvement in the region. This spans the whole range
of issues confronting countries as they move from the command
economy to the market; restructuring their industries,
reorganising them internally and changing their ownership from
the public to the private sector. We also cover sectors ranging
from power to solid waste management, and important ancillary
issues ranging from the techniques of privatisation to the
measurement of the social impact of change. All of them
demonstrate our ability to apply high-quality, tailor-made advice
and analysis to situations of flux and opportunity. </a></p>
<h4><a name="3">The EU candidates</a></h4>
<p><a name="3">These Central European countries are making varied
and impressive efforts to involve the private sector in their
utilities industries, and to find new instruments to tackle a
range of problems. </a></p>
<p><a name="3">In <i>Slovenia</i> LE advised on the privatisation
of hydropower. Other recent projects include work in the <i>Czech
Republic</i> and <i>Hungary</i>. Last year LE examined ways that
municipal governments can ensure that they can get value for
money out of innovative mechanisms to allow private concession
holders in the water sector. Despite their limited resources and
technical capabilities, we found ways in which municipalities'
access to outside advice can play an important role in limiting
the market power of concessionaires. </a></p>
<p><a name="3">In a recently-published study for the World Bank
(See Economics in Action 1995/One), LE examined the possible role
of market based instruments in controlling the serious air
pollution problems of <i>Poland's</i> historic city of Krakow,
mapping out the resulting changes in pollution concentrations up
to the year 2010. </a></p>
<p><a name="3">We found that, though pollution taxes and tradable
permits offered significant cost savings for industrial sources,
direct regulation was the best solution for households and small
businesses. </a></p>
<p><a name="3">LE recently advised on the rationalisation and
reform of the energy sector in <i>Lithuania</i>, to help relieve
the drag its unpaid bills impose on the public finances and hence
on its newly-developing banking system. </a></p>
<h4><a name="3">Next in line</a></h4>
<p><a name="3">Many Eastern European governments are wrestling
with challenges ranging from war damage to macro-economic
instability and indeed near collapse of the basic economic
systems and structures needed for reform. </a></p>
<p><a name="3">LE (together with Rust Kennedy and Donkin) is
undertaking a study of institutional reform in <i>Croatia's</i>
power sector. After being reorganised into a vertically
integrated utility, the Croatian electricity company, HEP, has
survived the civil wars in remarkably good shape. But is vertical
integration the shape of the future, as Croatia seeks to become a
fully integrated member of the Western economic community of
nations? </a></p>
<p><a name="3">LE has been involved in a series of projects in <i>Bulgaria</i>
since 1993. We are helping to give the Committee of Energy the
skills they will need to reform the electricity sector, as the
Bulgarian Government's commitment to reform unfolds. In
conjunction with Safege and Lysa, we have advised on the
decentralisation of water services to municipal control, and are
currently helping with the appraisal of investment projects for
loan financing. </a></p>
<p><a name="3">In a project in <i>Romania</i> for the Japanese
International Cooperation Agency, undertaken with ExCorporation,
LE examined the institutional and financial aspects of solid
waste management in Bucharest. We have been designing a waste tax
and examining the financial implications of much-needed
investment in waste transportation and disposal. </a></p>
<p><a name="3">Following near-collapse at the end of the
communist era, <i>Albania</i> is transforming itself with
unexpected speed into a market-oriented economy. It is planning
to let electricity distribution franchises as part of the reform
programme, and has raised tariffs further than many of its
neighbours. LE was involved, with Lahmeyer International, in a
study of the level of power tariffs needed to ensure a
financially viable power industry. </a></p>
<h4><a name="3">The new republics</a></h4>
<p><a name="3">Some of the countries in the former Soviet Union,
like <i>Moldova</i>, have made unexpectedly rapid progress
towards the market. Others, like <i>Kazakhstan</i>, have
attracted investor interest because of their huge energy
resources. LE has worked in both these countries, and in others
that face deep-rooted economic difficulties. </a></p>
<p><a name="3">LE led a consortium of European companies in a
large-scale study spanning all aspects of the energy sector in <i>Belarus</i>.
The country has a key role to play in the future gas and
electricity economy of Europe because of its gateway position
between Russia and markets to the West. But as a small country
uncertain of its independence, energy security and affordability
are key issues as well. </a></p>
<p><a name="3"><i>Uzbekistan</i> lies on the cusp between import
dependence and export potential in oil and gas. Combined with the
very heavy transport costs it faces because of its remoteness
from most markets, this creates an almost unparalleled
uncertainty about the level of oil and gas prices, which affects
every segment of the economy. As part of a Greek-led team, we
advised on the social and economic impact of the reform of energy
prices. </a></p>
<p><a name="3"><i>Azerbaijan</i> is another country facing major
price adjustments, in this case because it is on the verge of
gaining access to Western markets for its oil. But at the same
time, its shortage of funds has led to a near-cessation of gas
imports from neighbouring <i>Turkmenistan</i>. LE helped to
explore the likely impact of getting prices to realistic levels,
and to design measures to mitigate it. In Turkmenistan itself, as
part of the European Expertise Service, LE undertook a project to
advise on the reform of the tax system. </a></p>
<p><a name="3">Meanwhile, <i>Russia</i> may be the beneficiary of
reforms further west. In its ongoing study of the European
Union's Internal Energy Market project, LE has been using game
theory approaches to analyse the impact of greater competition
inside a market that over the long term faces only three major
gas suppliers - Russia being the most significant. </a></p>
<p><a name="3"><b>Contact: Mike Webb, Robert Laslett</b> </a></p>
<hr size="4">
<h2><a name="4">Are books different?</a></h2>
<p><a name="4"><b><i>Only two goods are exempted from the general
ban in Britain on resale price maintenance: books and
medicaments. Last year, however, the Publishers Association
decided that it would no longer try to enforce the Net Book
Agreement, which prevented retailers from competing with each
other by discounting book prices.</i></b> </a></p>
<hr>
<p><a name="4">While the NBA remains gathering dust on the
shelves, the Office of Fair Trading is looming with duster and
trash-can. The Director of Fair Trading, John Bridgeman, made his
views clear last winter, in the OFT's own newsletter: &quot;In
general, RPM gives consumers a bad deal and I will pursue it
vigorously wherever I find it&quot;. But back in the 1960s, the
Restrictive Practices Court concluded in favour of a continued
exemption for books. If the NBA were abolished, the court
believed, there would be fewer and less-well-stocked bookshops;
fewer titles published; and they would in general be more
expensive. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">What has changed? According to the OFT, the
publishing industry has, to such an extent that the public
interest arguments of the 1960s can no longer be sustained.
London Economics has been developing an alternative set of
arguments. </a></p>
<h4><a name="4">Down with sales, up with prices</a></h4>
<p><a name="4">Following the Restrictive Practices Court's line
of reasoning in 1962, we started by distinguishing between the
effect of the NBA on sales, and its effect on prices. The Court
came to the view that price-cutting would not be likely to
increase book sales significantly. Demand for books in general,
and even for one title in particular, was not particularly
price-sensitive. Total book sales were much more dependent on the
number of booksellers, the stocks and range of books they held. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">By contrast, the demand for books at any
particular retailer was much more price-sensitive: if one
bookshop discounted prices, it would increase sales at the
expense of others. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">Without the NBA, popular or steady-selling titles
would be discounted, by one bookseller after another, starting
with those which did not themselves hold stocks (which, in those
days, meant the department stores). Retail margins generally
would fall, stockholding booksellers would lose trade, some of
them would go out of business altogether and others would reduce
their range or the quality of service provided. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">The overall effect, deemed the Court, would be to
reduce both sales and the number of titles published. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">The second argument on sales stemmed from the
difficulty of forecasting in advance which of a broad range of
titles would be successful. A squeeze on retail margins through
price-cutting, it was argued, would lead stockholding booksellers
to act more conservatively, focussing on the few sure-fire hits
and denying riskier titles the shelf-space needed to have a
chance of success. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">The Court also concluded that book prices would be
driven up by abolition of the NBA. Print runs would be reduced,
raising unit costs: for example, a cut in the print run of a
hardback first edition from 3,000 to 2,000 would, it was
estimated, raise unit costs by 29 per cent. </a></p>
<h4><a name="4">Have times changed?</a></h4>
<p><a name="4">Today, the OFT believes that demand has become
more sensitive to price. Stockholding bookshops are much better
placed to compete with non-stockholders (notably, today, the
supermarkets). The growth of wholesaling and computerised
stockholding allows more frequent deliveries and reduced risk; so
do sale-or-return provisions. The implication is that
price-cutting would have, overall, a more positive effect on book
sales. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">The OFT has also argued that the cost penalty on
smaller print runs has been reduced by technological progress,
eating into the economies of scale. The implication is that
prices would not be driven up by the end of resale price
maintenance. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">Both conclusions are questionable. It is not at
all clear that book-buyers have become more price-sensitive:
while books today face greater competition from other media
(which would tend to make them more price-sensitive), people have
become better off (which tends to reduce their price-sensitivity
on smaller purchases like books). The balance of these effects
needs to be tested empirically, and the difficulty of comparing
like with like - no title is exactly like another - greatly
complicates the analysis. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">This diversity lies behind another feature of the
market which has not changed: the fact that book sales depend
greatly on their sheer accessibility - the range on display, the
ability to browse, the quality of service. A recent study of the
German book industry found that an increase in retail margins -
which permits investment in retail service - actually resulted in
a more than proportionate increase in book sales. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">The OFT view on unit costs is also highly
debatable. While production techniques have been transformed,
there is still a substantial cost penalty on short runs. Finally
risk-sharing techniques such as sale-and-return are expensive in
terms of transport and administration. Their growth would
increase industry costs and so prices. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">It is too soon to reach conclusions on changes
since the NBA was put on the back shelf. Some initial reactions
were highly predictable. Supermarkets did indeed lead the way at
Christmas, discounting the most popular titles by 50 per cent or
more; bookshops followed suit, but did not feel able to discount
as much. Sales initially rose, though there is evidence
suggesting that this effect may now be evaporating; it is too
early to say whether a sufficient increase in volume will be
sustained to compensate for the reduction in retailers' margins.
Strong retailers are now trying to pass on the squeeze on
margins, demanding better terms from publishers, which puts the
smaller ones under pressure. </a></p>
<h4><a name="4">A new approach</a></h4>
<p><a name="4">It cannot simply be stated that resale price
maintenance is always anti-competitive and harmful to the
consumer. Like various other ways in which manufacturers seek to
exert control over the retailing of their products, it may in
some circumstances be employed for legitimate commercial purposes
which are in the interests of both producer and purchaser. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">We believe that the impact of resale price
maintenance on the public interest should be assessed in the same
way as the Monopolies and Mergers Commission approaches other
potential cases of vertical restraint, such as failure to supply.
This involves a two-stage analysis. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">The first step is to establish whether there is
evidence of market power at either the manufacturing or the
retail level, and whether this power is actually enhanced by the
vertical restraint in question: does it make collusion easier, or
entry into the market more difficult? Resale price maintenance
obviously raises the possibility of collusion, on which an
investigation should clearly focus. But this approach recognises
that, if vertical restraints are not purely directed at
increasing market power, they will be aimed at increasing sales,
are likely to increase public welfare and equally unlikely to
raise any public interest concerns. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">But it is necessary to take a second step, and to
test this proposition in the market concerned: to ask whether
higher sales do indeed go hand in hand with increased consumer
welfare. If the desire to win extra sales results in vertical
restraints which encourage too much investment in retailer
services, viewed from the perspective of the average consumer,
then the welfare afterglow may be somewhat clouded. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">So there are no easy answers, or even simple
questions, in this approach, either. But it is at least more
clearly focussed. Judging the effect on sales and prices is an
extremely difficult empirical process, involving a great deal of
second-guessing of the industry, even with the real-life
experiment of the abrogation of the NBA under way. And it hardly
scratches the surface of the underlying issues of competition,
consumer welfare and the protection of the public interest. </a></p>
<p><a name="4"><b>Contact: Zoltan Biro, Amelia Fletcher</b> </a></p>
<hr size="4">
<h2><a name="5">Retailing's next revolution?</a></h2>
<p><a name="5"><b><i>Terry Leahy of Tesco led the cast of experts
debating the future of retailing at LE's conference in February.</i></b> </a></p>
<hr>
<p><a name="5">In February, London Economics held a conference in
London on the future of retailing, against the background of
further analysis by Nick Morris and Bill Robinson of the impact
of the change in the industry over the past decade (commissioned
by Tesco). Massive investment, changes in technology, changes in
types of employment, a different and greater mix of goods
available to customers had gone hand-in-hand with the advent of
out-of-town grocery superstores - characterised as both heroes
and villains of this revolution. The key conclusions on the
&quot;heroes&quot; side of the argument were that consumers had
gained, to the tune of &#163;300 per household per year, from
lower prices. Employees had gained, through a rise in real wages
in retailing financed by increased efficiency. Shareholders had
also gained, if more modestly than consumers, to the tune of
&#163;100m. But the conference also enabled the case against
&quot;villains&quot; to be discussed: the impact of the
revolution on corner shops, city centres and the still-large
minority of consumers who cannot shop by car. </a></p>
<p><a name="5">Most interest was focused on future trends. LE's
chairman, John Kay, began by characterising the consumer's
problem in Hobbesian style. If their lives are no longer nasty,
brutish and short, they still suffer from disadvantages in the
market place: consumers are ignorant, small and immobile.
&quot;Middlemen&quot; are needed to solve these problems. They
search and select, bargain and buy, and get the goods to the
customer. These are the three key functions of retailing, carried
out separately or together. </a></p>
<p><a name="5">Terry Leahy emphasised the scope for retailers to
carry out even greater search and selection in the future:
&quot;Successful retailing is all about guessing what people
might want, trying it out, and responding quickly to people's
revealed preferences.&quot; New micro-marketing techniques, he
argued, would mean that the retailers of the future will be much
better able respond to consumers - to spot and fill gaps in their
product range. Part of the experience of running a &quot;home
shopping&quot; television channel, articulated at the conference
by Richard Burrell of QVC, is of instant, powerful information on
customer preferences: best-seller or flop, live television gives
the verdict with brutally immediate frankness. </a></p>
<h4><a name="5">Don't leave home?</a></h4>
<p><a name="5">Electronic shopping offers the opportunity for
home-based search and more organised personal selection.
Interactive systems enable the customer to search databases of,
for example, second-hand cars or houses for sale, in a way which
reflects their own personal preferences rather than some
rank-ordering imposed by others in a printed publication. But
even these systems still provide no answer to the third of the
consumer's problems: immobility. While some services (travel
agency, financial advice) and even some products (video, learning
materials) can be delivered down a cable, you cannot be delivered
a pound of cheese or a new carpet that way. And &quot;virtual
shopping&quot; is still some way from the experience of seeing,
touching and feeling what you are going to buy. </a></p>
<p><a name="5">But all speakers saw the potential for some
further dramatic shifts in retailing. Jim Rose of Nielsen pointed
towards diversification out of food. John Kay saw scope for full
&quot;retailing&quot; - firms bringing together the three key
functions - across a range of services currently outside the
retail sector. Terry Leahy told the conference to expect a
continual evolution in the format of outlets, ranging from large
food stores for car-borne shoppers to convenience express stores
for people shopping on their own two feet - and new schemes for
meeting the needs of those who cannot walk to the shops at all.
&quot;You should not expect us to go on opening large
edge-of-town stores largely after the need for new ones has
passed.&quot; </a></p>
<p><a name="5">Nor can the retail industry expect to be allowed a
free development hand. William de Winton of Hoare, Govett, Keith
Vaz, the Shadow Minister for Planning and Regeneration and Sarah
Hogg of LE discussed the planning policy background, starting
from the latest state of thinking at the Department of the
Environment. This reflected a hierarchy of planning preferences
for retailing, running from city centres through edge-of-centre,
with out-of-town at the bottom of the list. But this should not
be allowed to fossilise city-centre high streets, when a number
of different locations might fulfil such planning criteria as
good transport connections and regeneration potential. </a></p>
<p><a name="5"><b>Contact: Nick Morris, Bill Robinson</b> </a></p>
<hr>
