<p>&#160; </p>
<hr size="4">
<h2><a name="1">Who pays for long-term care?</a></h2>
<p><a name="1"><b><i>his Budget for 1996-97 the Chancellor has
responded to widely-felt anxiety about the rising costs of caring
for the elderly. The Government is to consult on further possible
changes of great importance to the financial services industry,
including the development of variable pensions and
&quot;Partnership Schemes&quot;. LE has developed a unique
modelling capability in this area.</i></b> </a></p>
<hr size="4">
<h4><a name="1">A financial timebomb?</a></h4>
<p><a name="1">The success of modern medicine means we are all
living longer. By 2031, 10.8% of the population will be aged over
75 compared with 7.2% this year; the number aged over 85 will
have more than doubled. The problem is exacerbated by a
population bulge, as the &quot;Baby Boom&quot; generation of the
1960s reaches retirement and old age. The chart below shows the
expected steep rise in all these age groups until about 2040. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">Although medical science has helped us to lead
active lives for longer, the costs of the kind of care needed in
fragile old age have become a matter of both individual and
national anxiety. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">The problem has become a political hot potato
because there is a growing awareness of the impact on family
finances. Current rules mean that all but the poorest will be
expected at least to contribute towards the cost of their care.
Even after the Budget changes, anyone with assets exceeding
&#163;16,000 will be expected to finance the entire cost of
residential care. As the average cost of residential care is
&#163;12,000 per year, this could quite quickly erode most
people's savings and require family property to be sold rather
than passed on to the next generation. </a></p>
<h4><a name="1">How big is the problem?</a></h4>
<p><a name="1">Most care of the elderly is not in fact provided
in residential and nursing homes. About 80% of total care hours
are provided <i>informally </i>by spouses, relatives and friends.
If this were to decline, then the requirement for <i>formal </i>care,
whether financed privately or by the state, could rise
dramatically. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">The availability of informal carers depends partly
on demographics, and partly on other factors such as economic
activity levels and patterns of social behaviour. Increased
divorce rates, and changing family structures also complicate the
picture. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">London Economics has constructed a sophisticated
model of what might happen in the market for long-term care. This
brings together demographic forecasts with estimates of likely
disability to determine who is likely to <i>need</i> care. Then
it determines the number of people available to <i>provide</i>
care, taking into account changing work patterns and family
structures. The model enables us to explore the effect of
changing any of the assumptions, thus illustrating the effects of
various policy changes. Our 'base case' assumptions are shown in
the chart above. These suggest that the number of people
requiring formal care may treble over the next 35 years. </a></p>
<h4><a name="1">What about the costs?</a></h4>
<p><a name="1">The costs of care depend principally on how many
people need to be cared for. The table illustrates the various
different costs involved, starting with formal care. The care
industry is likely to be rationalised as demands on it rise -
which include the cost of all residential, nursing and ancilliary
care. Savings can be achieved through purpose-built homes,
exploiting increased economies of scale and more effective use of
staff. Changes in regulation, social services and other policies
will also have an effect. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">However, even allowing for increased efficiency,
the sharp increase in the number requiring formal care indicated
by our analysis implies a real increase in costs from &#163;12
billion today to &#163;34.5 billion in 2031, in 1995 prices. This
can be split into costs met by private individuals or
institutional payments; and the cost that falls on the taxpayer,
through social security payments or local authority-financed
care. How this cost will be shared between public and private
sectors will depend on developments in both the National Health
Service and local authority social services, and on tax and
social security measures such as those in this year's Budget. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">Our 'base case' assumes a modest but steady
increase in the share met by the State; nevertheless, the cost to
the taxpayer more than doubles in the period. The next line adds
in the 'opportunity cost' of informal care - a valuation of the
time and effort given without payment in terms of how these
'resources' could otherwise be used, either for work or leisure.
The final line puts a 'replacement cost' on all this informal
care - valuing it at the pay rates of a home help or the cost of
providing a residential place. This gives some indication of the
potential total size of the market if the share of informal care
were to decline further than assumed in our base case. </a></p>
<div align="center"><center>
<table border="1">
    <tr>
        <th colspan="6"><a name="1">The cost of long-term care
        (&#163;m, 1995 prices)</a></th>
    </tr>
