        <td align="center"><a name="1">81,600</a></td>
    </tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<h4><a name="1">Solutions</a></h4>
<p><a name="1">The preponderance of informal care, and the
importance of making sure that the need for formal care does not
reach unsustainable levels, underline the need to support those
who do provide care for relatives or friends. Recent policy
decisions, such as the exemption from VAT of some types of care
provided in the home, have helped this process, but much more
will need to be done. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">Whether to care for a relative is an intensely
personal decision, and although those that do provide great
benefits to society we cannot assume they will go on volunteering
for ever. Small expenditures to make life easier for these unsung
heroes (or, mostly, heroines) could make a large difference to
their willingness and ability to care. Research is needed into
why people choose to care for relatives and what determines this
choice. </a></p>
<h4><a name="1">New savings products</a></h4>
<p><a name="1">Whatever happens, there is no doubt that a
substantial part of the rising cost of formal care will need to
be borne by individuals and their families. This presents a
challenge, and an opportunity, to the financial services
industry. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">The creation of <i>new insurance vehicles</i>,
partly encouraged by the Budget measures, is likely to be a part
of the solution. In the United States, <i>Partnership Schemes </i>permit
those individuals who plan ahead to meet a proportion of
long-term care costs to retain assets even if they turn out to
need extensive care. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">One solution currently being discussed is a <i>variable
pension. </i>Instead of paying into a pension throughout his or
her working life in order to receive an annual income upon
retirement, a plan member would be able to secure a higher income
stream in extreme old age. This could point the way towards the
development of a <i>combined product</i>. Such a product might
deliver a lower annual income than a conventional pension but<b> </b>might
also include long term care insurance. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">The attraction of this solution is its simplicity.
Many people take out private pensions; this might increase the
coverage of long term care insurance and would encourage
provision to be taken out earlier in life. </a></p>
<p><a name="1">Much thought will need to be given to how best to
help individuals provide for their own and for their family's
needs; to the development of appropriate financial products and
to corresponding changes in tax rules. Are simple savings and
investment vehicles most appropriate? Can we work out schemes
which incentivise people to insure? Are there ways of taking
charges over assets contingent on need? Can we help people decide
when in their lives they will be most able to put money aside?
What mix of tax incentives and social security rules will best
encourage a 'mixed economy' of formal care? </a></p>
<p>Contacts: <a href="mailto:nick@londecon.co.uk">Nick Morris</a>
and <a href="mailto:tim@londecon.co.uk">Tim Wilsdon</a></p>
<hr size="4">
<h2><a name="2">Discretion rules, OK</a></h2>
<p><a name="2"><b><i>In November 1995, Oftel held the first
public hearing in the history of UK utility regulation, on the
proposal to introduce a provision in operators' licences
prohibiting anti-competitive behaviour. Oftel's suggestions were
opposed by British Telecom, but supported by most other
operators. Oftel asked John Kay, Chairman of LE, to provide an
independent contribution to the debate. This is an edited text of
what he said.</i></b></a></p>
<hr size="4">
<p><a name="2">&quot;There are two issues in serious dispute. The
first is whether regulation is best conducted by reference to
general principles, with considerable discretion given to the
regulator in their application, or by means of specific rules.
The other, closely related, issue is whether the existing
procedures for challenging a regulatory decision are adequate. </a></p>
<p><a name="2">Everyone must sympathise with the demand from
regulated firms for clarity and certainty in regulation. There
would be much to be said for a structure in which managers had
full commercial freedom within a framework of unambiguous rules.
But in practice, an attempt to lay down clear specific rules is
likely to be more intrusive in the commercial freedom of
regulated companies than the exercise of regulatory discretion. </a></p>
<p><a name="2">Consider some of the issues with which a utility
regulator is faced, such as price discrimination or vertical
restraints. Are differences in tariffs which are not related to
differences in cost acceptable, or excessive? Are restrictions by
suppliers on the ways in which their goods can be resold
anti-competitive or pro-competitive in effect? What is the cost
of capital to a regulated utility? The answers to these questions
necessarily involve the exercise of judgement. Such questions
have to be answered from a deep and wide understanding of the
commercial context. If, for example, a company immediately
matches a competitor's low price, that decision may be
pro-competitive in some circumstances and anti-competitive in
others. </a></p>
<p><a name="2">There is a second aspect to this exercise of
judgement. There is what one might call a penumbra to all these
decisions. Take, for example, the issue of BT's cost of capital.
A 15% real return is obviously too high, and a 5% real return
clearly too low. But there is a range within which a reasonable
regulator might choose one figure or another. There can be no
definitive right or wrong answer. Similarly, some instances of
price discrimination are obviously unacceptable. But, in a
business like telecommunications it would be impracticable, even
if it were desirable, to relate the charge for every individual
service exactly to the cost of providing that service. </a></p>
<p><a name="2">So there is really no hope that regulation can be
conducted by reference to a set of definitive rules. The attempt
to achieve this in the financial services industry was not
successful and it became necessary to retreat to a regime which
allowed more subjective interpretation. I believe that the
process of defining general objectives, and allowing their
application to develop over time, is not just the best way, but
in practice the only way, of undertaking the regulation of
industry. Nor can we hope to avoid the need for ad hoc
investigation of particular cases. This is particularly true in
telecommunications, where rapidly changing technology and the
complexity of some of the issues mean that attempts to prescribe
in advance for all situations are bound to fail. </a></p>
<h4><a name="2">Judge or expert?</a></h4>
<p><a name="2">The real issue is whether discretion should be
exercised by judicial process through the courts, or by an expert
but non-judicial body, such as a regulatory agency, with
investigative powers. From my own experience of judgements on
economic and commercial matters made in both types of
environment, I have very little doubt that they are better made
by an independent, expert agency with powers to seek its own
evidence and advice. Adversarial procedures, in which one side
argues that black is white and another that white is black, after
which a judge has to decide which of these preposterous
contentions is closer to the truth, are not an effective means of
resolving these kinds of issues. Despite the length and expense
of legal processes, there is no guarantee that the relevant
issues will emerge. There is a tendency for the result to be
influenced by the capabilities of the advocates, and hence by the
resources of the parties. </a></p>
<p><a name="2">Moreover, contested process can only operate in
circumstances in which there is a competing contrary contention.
In matters such as the assessment of BT's costs of capital, there
is not. I therefore support Oftel's desire to regulate by
reference to general principles, rather than an ever-growing list
of specific prohibitions. I am also sure Oftel is right to prefer
provisions based on Articles 85 and 86 of the Treaty of Rome to
the development of British legislation within the context of the
Fair Trading Act. </a></p>
<p><a name="2">However, Articles 85 and 86 of the Rome treaty
were written 30 years ago, and we have learnt from experience.
Article 86 prohibits abuse of a dominant position; I believe it
is necessary to be more specific about what is meant by abuse.
Since BT's dominance of many telecommunications markets is beyond
dispute, anything BT does might be interpreted as abuse of a
dominant position. </a></p>
<h4><a name="2">Consumer unfriendly?</a></h4>
<p><a name="2">Abuse is indicated by actions which are directly
detrimental to consumers, or by actions which have the intention
or effect of restricting the ability of efficient competitors to
meet customer needs. Since in general only a dominant firm could
do these things, the separate requirement to establish dominance
serves little purpose. </a></p>
<p><a name="2">The second issue I identified at the beginning was
the adequacy of the system of appeal against the regulator's
decisions. British Telecom has put forward a list of eight
&quot;rights&quot; which it believes it should enjoy against its
regulator, starting with the proposition that no regulator should
be both judge and jury. I believe this analogy with the conduct
of criminal procedures is fundamentally misconceived. The
regulator is not a judge, but an executive agent, charged with
pursuit of a range of statutory obligations, such as the
development of competition and the promotion of an efficient
industry. </a></p>
<p><a name="2">It is right that those who make decisions should
be made accountable for the consequences of their actions, but
that is not the same as saying that their processes should mimic
the proceedings of the Old Bailey. This situation would change if
the regulator were to be entrusted with judicial authority: if
his principal duty were to impose penalties for illegal actions.
But there is no suggestion of this kind in the Oftel proposals. </a></p>
<p><a name="2">The need for accountability in such a framework
does require that a mechanism for challenging decisions should
exist, but it should be an exceptional rather than a routine
mechanism. The right of challenge should not be available simply
because some other person faced with the same facts might have
come to a different, equally reasonable, decision. It should be
restricted to decisions which are so bizarre as to lie outside
the penumbra within which reasonable men could come to different
views. The right of challenge should also relate to issues which
are of such central importance to regulation that there should be
an opportunity for full public debate and reconsideration. </a></p>
<p><a name="2">The two appellate mechanisms which exist at
present - the threat of judicial review and the opportunity to
debate licence amendments before the MMC - are directly relevant.
Indeed, the scope of judicial review may now be rather too wide.
Judges have increasingly been ready to review the substantive
merits of decisions, rather than to apply the Wednesbury test of
whether they lie outside the bounds of reasonableness. While
there have been no successful judicial reviews of Oftel's
decisions, the threat of judicial review is exerting an
increasingly paralysing effect on public agencies. </a></p>
<p><a name="2">However, regulatory decisions of major importance
will not always involve amendments to the licence. The MMC should
(and under existing powers could) be given a wider role. It may
be desirable to codify and extend the opportunities for broader
utility references, exemplified by the approach to British Gas.
Moreover, the appellate mechanism might be available to parties
other than licensees, notably consumers. </a></p>
<h4><a name="2">Conclusions</a></h4>
<p><a name="2">To summarise, therefore: I prefer general
principles to specific rules, and believe that Articles 85 and 86
of the Treaty of Rome provide an appropriate basis. I do,
however, think there is a strong case for specifying the nature
of practice which should be deemed to constitute an abuse of a
dominant market position. </a></p>
<p><a name="2">As to the question of appeal mechanisms, I am not
persuaded that there are fundamental weaknesses in the existing
British structure of regulation. Perhaps the most useful reform
would be to clarify and codify the opportunities for the MMC to
become involved in the process of utility regulation. In any
event, some standardisation of the different powers it has in
different industries would be desirable. </a></p>
<hr size="4">
<p>&#160; </p>
<h2><a name="3">Dealing with Challenges in Australia</a></h2>
<p><a name="3"><b><i>Five different Governments, covering a
population the size of greater London in a continent larger than
the United States: that is the challenge posed by Australia.</i></b></a></p>
<hr size="4">
<p><a name="3">London Economics began work in Australia in 1992,
setting up an Australian office with a staff of 2. Today the
Australian office has a full time staff of 8, led by Managing
Director Sam Lovick, and Deputy Director Danny Price. From our
Melbourne office we provide economic consulting services
throughout Australia and New Zealand. </a></p>
<p><a name="3">We work hand in glove with our London colleagues.
Modern technology allows us to be in constant communication
despite the 18,000 miles that separate us. There is a constant
interchange of staff, skills and experience from both sides. For
example, our advanced modelling skills are used in our London
office, and we benefit from the London office's experience of
regulatory periodic reviews. </a></p>
<p><a name="3">Australia is undergoing a period of utility reform
not unlike the UK experience of the 1980s. But many of the issues
are unique to Australia. Imagine, for example, constructing an
electricity pool from 5 independent state systems; or encouraging
competition in telecommunications where distances are so vast. </a></p>
<h4><a name="3">The case of Pacific Power</a></h4>
<p><a name="3">Pacific Power, the New South Wales generator, is
Australia's largest generator with one third of all capacity. The
NSW Government was concerned about its ability to exercise market
power in the proposed pool, and asked LE Australia how to deal
with it. </a></p>
<p><a name="3">LE Australia tested their likely behaviour using
game theory. This was done by including Nash gaming capabilities
in our electricity market model, PoolMod. This is the first time
such an approach has been used to solve a practical problem in a
transmission constrained electricity system. </a></p>
<p><a name="3">The results were unambiguous - Pacific Power has
market power in all cases. We concluded that the best way to deal
with this issue of market power is to split Pacific Power into a
number of competing generators. And it looks as though the NSW
Government will follow our recommendations. </a></p>
<h4><a name="3">It isn't all utilities ...</a></h4>
<p><a name="3">The Australian Government was concerned about
whether it was spending its money wisely in the charitable
sector, and asked us to find out. Is the money going to the most
efficient charities? </a></p>
<p><a name="3">It was challenging! What are the outputs of a
charity? How should we think about the charities' inputs? What is
the best way to compare a large number of individual and distinct
organisations carrying out a multitude of tasks? </a></p>
<p><a name="3">We found the answer in Data Envelopment Analysis
(DEA). This economic performance indicator allowed us to take
into account special features of the charitable sector, such as
the variety of services they offered, factors that might make a
particular charity's work more difficult, and the quality of the
care offered. And the conclusion: for charities above a certain
size, the more money they receive from the Australian Government
the less efficient they are likely to be. Larger charities that
depend on private donations are more likely to be efficient. </a></p>
<p align="left"><strong>Contact: </strong><a
href="mailto:sam@lonecon.co.au"><strong>Sam Lovick</strong></a><strong>,
London Economics Australia</strong></p>
<hr size="4">
<h2><a name="4">Sharing the bill for lunch</a></h2>
<p><a name="4"><b><i>Three years' experience, plus a squeeze on
public capital spending, have brought the Private Finance
Initiative into the consciousness of every Government department,
and should bring it on to the agenda of every company with an
interest in managing infrastructure projects or running public
services. The key issue in almost all of these is the allocation
of risk between public and private partners - an issue on which
LE has established expertise to offer. </i></b></a></p>
<hr size="4">
<p><a name="4">The Private Finance Initiative was intended to
fill the gap between privatisation - taking activities out of the
public sector altogether - and contracting out - the opportunity
to provide services for the public sector. Under the PFI, private
firms provide the capital asset (road, prison, hospital building)
as well as some or all of the services associated with it. The
potential was enormous. But when the PFI was launched in 1992,
sceptics expected to see only a handful of transport projects get
a - grudging - seal of Treasury approval. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">And for a time, the PFI languished on the
launch-pad, while private industry complained about the obstacles
in the way of securing Treasury approval. The Treasury, too, was
finding its way up the learning curve, trying to prevent the
initiative degenerating into creative accounting, or stacking up
unmanageable future running costs. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">Since then, however, the PFI approach has been
spreading beyond transport to health, education, prisons,
defence, water and sewerage, urban regeneration, information
systems and government property. (Even the Treasury decided to
avail itself of PFI techniques to finance the development of its
own inconvenient building - perhaps the most intriguing sign of
offical conversion to the initiative.) </a></p>
<p><a name="4">Today, state-of-the-art PFI is opening up
opportunities to any who can put together balance sheet strength,
operator skills, and ability to design a project which meets
public sector economic and social criteria while offering a
satisfactory rate of return. Above all, that requires know-how in
the economic analysis of risk, to achieve a split between public
and private sectors that will pass through the eye of the
Treasury needle. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">Although proposals may still fail to escape the
confines of public expenditure (see box), some of the more
cumbersome pre-conditions have been removed. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">The rules for &quot;value-for-money&quot; analysis
have been codified, and it is no longer necessary to construct
and price an artificial &quot;public sector comparator&quot; for
a project which was never going to go ahead out of public
expenditure, anyway. </a></p>
<h4><a name="4">Three kinds of PFI</a></h4>
<ul>
    <li><a name="4"><b>Free-standing</b>. The public sector acts
        as &quot;enabler&quot;, dealing with outline planning,
        licensing, providing ancillary works, etc. The private
        sector finances the project, and recovers costs from
        charges to the user. But the public sector may still
        carry some residual risk, if - for example - the asset
        transfers back to it at the end of a certain period. <i>Example:
        Queen Elizabeth II Bridge (Dartford-Thurrock).</i> </a></li>
    <li><a name="4"><b>Service provider</b>. The public sector
        acts as &quot;customer&quot;, buying services from the
        managers of the PFI project, who finance its construction
        and run its operations. Alternatively, the public sector
        may lease the capital asset from the private sector. The
        public sector may continue to carry some operating risk,
        if it flows from changes in policy that might undermine
        the project's viability. <i>Examples: Northern Line
        trains, re-development of the Treasury, private prisons.</i> </a></li>
    <li><a name="4"><b>Joint venture</b>. The public sector meets
        part of the capital costs - normally in pursuit of a
        wider social objective than the private sector could be
        expected to meet. The private sector has to have
        effective control - otherwise the project will fall back
        into the category of &quot;public expenditure&quot;. But
        the public sector may have an equity stake, or a public
        body may be part of an arrangement with a private company
        - or it may merely contribute grants, loans or existing
        assets. The distribution of risk obviously depends on the
        mix. <i>Examples: Channel Tunnel Rail Link, Croydon
        Tramlink.</i> </a></li>
</ul>
<h4><a name="4">Piggy-back business</a></h4>
<p><a name="4">The Treasury's latest schedule of potential PFI
projects runs to a total of over 1,000, with a capital value of
around &#163;25 billion. The estimated present value of the
payments throughout these projects' lives is &#163;40 billion or
more. More important than this official &quot;wish list&quot;,
however, are the signals to business to use PFI techniques in an
innovative way. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">In particular, these are opportunities to
piggy-back further business on a project for the public sector,
by developing private services in parallel, selling surplus
capacity or software systems, developing surplus land or
buildings. The gradual opening up of the local authority sector
to PFI offers particular scope for lateral business thinking. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">To begin with, both the Treasury and private
companies were somewhat inclined to see the PFI as a free lunch,
with the other side bearing all the risk. Anxious to defend the
purity of the concept of public borrowing, the Treasury was
reluctant to give the seal of approval to a PFI scheme which
involved any public-sector risk. Meanwhile, private companies
were equally keen to design PFI projects which left as much risk
as possible in public hands. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">On both sides, the debate has moved on. In its
latest handbook, the Treasury makes the crucial statement that
&quot;the aim is to achieve optimum risk allocation, not transfer
for its own sake&quot;. </a></p>
<p><a name="4">Of course, that leaves plenty of scope for
argument as to who should &quot;optimally&quot; carry which kind
of risk, and the detail of the Treasury handbook makes it clear
how much it believes to be the private sector's business: design
and construction risk, taxation risk, project financing, most
operating risks, even regulatory risk if it is general in its
application. </a></p>
<h4><a name="4">Paying for policy</a></h4>
<p><a name="4">The only two categories which the Treasury leaves
unequivocally in the Government's court are the risk of criticism
(since the Home Office cannot escape the flak if something goes
amiss in a privately-run prison) or of a wrongly specified
requirement. Nevertheless, the Treasury has now opened the debate
on the allocation of other kinds of risk - and formally
acknowledged that government should carry the risk for some
policy-related shifts in demand. The ground rules for the debate
have therefore been more clearly established. Economic tools can
be used to apply them to individual projects with greater
certainty, efficiency - and speed. </a></p>
<p><a name="4"><b>Contacts: Sarah Hogg and Bill Robinson</b> </a></p>
<p>Contacts: <a href="mailto:sarah@londecon.co.uk">Sarah Hogg</a>
and <a href="mailto:bill@londecon.co.uk">Bill Robinson</a></p>
<hr size="4">
<h2><a name="5">Water resources in Gaza</a></h2>
<p><a name="5"><b><i>In October 1995, London Economics was
invited to participate in a World Bank mission to the Gaza Strip
to advise the Palestinian Authority on options for upgrading the
water and wastewater system. The mission was in response to an
urgent personal appeal for help from Yasser Arafat to the
President of the World Bank.</i></b></a></p>
<hr size="4">
<p><a name="5">A 40 km by 10 km strip of land on the
Mediterranean coast, where Israel meets the Sinai Peninsula, has
had one of the most troubled histories of the 20th century. Under
the peace agreement between the PLO and Israel, day-to-day
administration of the Gaza Strip was transferred to a civilian
Palestinian Authority early in 1995. Water resources were one of
the most urgent political and economic issues confronting the new
authority. </a></p>
<p><a name="5">In 1948 Gaza had a population of 80,000. Today
that population has swollen to one million, making it one of the
most densely populated territories on Earth. One-third of this
population live in UN-run refugee camps. </a></p>
<p><a name="5">This population explosion has led to great
difficulties with water resources. Current water consumption is
estimated at 120 million cubic metres per annum, of which
three-quarters goes for agricultural use. To meet this demand,
Gaza's principal resource is a shallow aquifer which recharges at
approximately 60 million cubic metres per year. As a result, the
level of the water table is falling rapidly, with ground water
becoming increasingly saline and polluted with nitrates. </a></p>
<p><a name="5">Many regions of Gaza simply cannot produce enough
water from their own wells to supply their local population, and
therefore have to buy water in bulk from Mekoroth, the Israeli
water company. The only other foreseeable source of new water for
Gaza is from desalination, which would be prohibitively
expensive. </a></p>
<p><a name="5">Water problems have a direct effect on the quality
of life for the Gazans, and also on the economic prospects of the
Strip. The water shortage affects the quality of agricultural
output, reducing the scope of export earnings. It also reduces
the scope for the development of water-using industrial processes
and has a severe impact on the construction sector. </a></p>
<p><a name="5">The troubled political history of the area has
resulted in neglect of the water and wastewater infrastructure.
The water distribution system is in a poor state with high levels
of leakage and intermittent supplies. Treatment of water, even
simple chlorination, is inadequate, often not occurring at all,
due to a lack of funds to buy chemicals. Most well-head meters
are not functioning, while a high proportion of customer meters
are either not working or are not read regularly. </a></p>
<h4><a name="5">Losses and leaks</a></h4>
<p><a name="5">In addition, there are a significant number of
illegal connections to the system, resulting in major losses. As
a result, estimates of production and consumption are extremely
unreliable, while incentives to conserve water are virtually
absent. On the wastewater side, only 25% of the population is
connected to a sewerage system, with the rest being served by
septic tanks. In many cases these are leaking, polluting the
underlying aquifer. </a></p>
<p><a name="5">Water and wastewater services are provided by the
municipalities and village councils that make up the civil
administration of the Strip. There is no proper accounting
separation of the water departments. Revenues collected go into a
central local government fund, with no link to the amounts which
can then be spent on operations and investment. To add to these
problems, over 30% of revenue remains uncollected. </a></p>
<p><a name="5">The World Bank Mission reviewed the options
available to the Palestinian Authority, identifying priority
investments that were needed to upgrade the system. It
recommended a four-year management contract to bring in a private
sector contractor to upgrade water and wastewater infrastructure,
to bring together the sector in a coherent single operation under
the joint ownership of the Municipalities and Village Councils,
to improve revenue collection and to reduce losses from illegal
connections. The choice of a management contract rather than a
more long-term arrangement such as a concession or lease
arrangement was strongly influenced by the existing political
uncertainties in the region. </a></p>
<p><a name="5">LE provided an economic and financial appraisal of
these proposals, assessing the potential benefits of the
management contract in terms of its impact on water conservation,
quality and the potential for increased economic growth. </a></p>
<h4><a name="5">Costs and benefits</a></h4>
<p><a name="5">A key question in this appraisal was the extent to
which the sector would be able to retain the benefits resulting
from the successful completion of the contract. Clearly, the
benefit of the investment would be much reduced if the sector
were subsequently unable to maintain the network adequately,
allowing it to fall back into disrepair. </a></p>
<p><a name="5">LE conducted the first tariff study in Gaza. This
concluded that while the balance of tariffs between water and
wastewater services was skewed, with wastewater tariffs well
below costs, existing water tariffs were more than adequate to
cover current operating expenditures and make a significant
contribution towards investment. This highlighted the importance
of successful revenue collection and accounting separation in
providing the management of the sector with the resources to
maintain their system in good working order once the immediate
improvements of the management contract had been completed. </a></p>
<p><strong>Contact: </strong><a href="mailto:dan@londecon.co.uk"><strong>Dan
Elliott</strong></a></p>
<hr size="4">
<h2><a name="6">Cutting waste in wastewater</a></h2>
<p><a name="6"><b><i>With 30 water companies in England and
Wales, Ofwat is better placed than most regulators to use
comparative benchmarking techniques to assess efficiency. It has
pioneered the rigorous and systematic collection of data and
undertook a major benchmarking exercise for the 1994 Periodic
Review. This was an important input into its determination of
water prices for the next five years.</i></b> </a></p>
<hr size="4">
<p><a name="6">Now Ofwat is considering new benchmarking
techniques to compare water companies' efficiency. In the course
of previous studies, Ofwat had found little evidence of economies
of scale in the treatment of sewage. This surprised industry
experts, who believe there is strong operational and engineering
evidence for scale economies. </a></p>
<p><a name="6">London Economics recently compared the efficiency
of a British wastewater company with its peers, using some of the
new techniques Ofwat may be considering. To enhance the
comparison, LE drew on more recent data than Ofwat had used, and
on data we have collected from around the world. Our study showed
that overall economies of scale measured in two ways are
statistically significant, as the chart shows. </a></p>
<p><a name="6">The study provided the client with significant
re-ratings of British companies' efficiency in sewage treatment
and sewerage. LE was also able to calculate potential savings on
power, labour and other costs for the client and other wastewater
companies. </a></p>
<p><strong>Contact: </strong><a href="mailto:mark@londecon.co.uk"><strong>Mark
Hull</strong></a></p>
<hr size="4">
<h2><a name="7">Merger policy in Germany and the UK</a></h2>
<p><a name="7"><b><i>In November 1995 London Economics held a
major conference bringing together experts and practitioners from
the UK and Germany to discuss merger policy in Europe. The
discussions ranged from the role of mergers in strengthening the
competitive position of European companies in global industries
such as electronics, chemical industries and automotive
manufacturing, to the comparative analysis of a number of merger
cases in retailing, media and defence industries. </i></b></a></p>
<hr size="4">
<p><a name="7">The London conference followed a workshop held in
Berlin this spring and was jointly organised by London Economics
and the German Institute for Economic Research (DIW) with
sponsorship by the Anglo-German Foundation*. </a></p>
<p><a name="7">Debate focussed on three issues: </a></p>
<ul>
    <li><a name="7">conflicts, actual or potential, between
        competition authorities and governments at the national
        level, and the role of the European Commission in this
        mix; </a></li>
    <li><a name="7">conflicts, real or imagined, between
        competition policy at either the national or European
        level, and the global aspirations of multinational
        companies; </a></li>
    <li><a name="7">characteristics of the media industries in
        particular, and the question as to how these should
        affect the application of competition policy in these
        industries. </a></li>
</ul>
<p><b>Contact: </b><a href="mailto:tom@londecon.co.uk"><b>Tom
Hoehn</b></a> </p>
<hr size="4">
