<head>
<title>An Issue in Search of a Policy</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>An Issue in Search of a Policy</h2>
<p><i>Public policy is in disarray when tackling attempts by
suppliers to influence the distribution of their product. Take
the six cases described in the box. In each pair the facts of the
case are, superficially, the same. Yet policy has approached the
problem in quite different ways.</i></p>
<hr>
<table border="1">
    <tr>
        <th colspan="2">Supplier - Retailer Relations<br>
        <font size="2"><br>
        Different industries, different customers</font></th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Beer<br>
        <br>
        Petrol</td>
        <td>MMC report, pub disposals ordered<br>
        <br>
        MMC report, no change required</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Gas<br>
        <br>
        Electricity</td>
        <td>British Gas transferred to the private sector intact<br>
        <br>
        Transmission network removed from generator control</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Life Insurance<br>
        <br>
        Airline Reservation Systems</td>
        <td>Polarisation of insurance brokers imposed<br>
        <br>
        No significant regulatory intervention</td>
    </tr>
</table>
<h4>Beer and petrol</h4>
<p>In the beer and petrol industries retailers are mostly tied to
the major producers. This may be because the brewer or oil
company owns the pub or the service station, or because the
outlet agrees to the tie in return for a favourable long term
supply arrangement or a capital contribution. </p>
<p>The brewers received one of the most comprehensively critical
assessments the Monopolies and Mergers Commission have ever
delivered, and have been required to dispose of many of their
outlets. Yet the MMC made only the most minor criticisms of
petrol wholesalers, and no changes in their relationships with
service stations were required. </p>
<h4>Gas and electricity</h4>
<p>At nationalisation, both gas and electricity were integrated
utilities. The British Gas Corporation controlled the gas
transmission network, the Central Electricity Generating Board
the National Grid. </p>
<p>After privatisation, British Gas emerged with its vertically
integrated structure intact. The CEGB was not only split into
competing generators, but lost control of the grid to the
regional distribution companies. </p>
<h4>Life insurance and CRSs</h4>
<p>Both travel agents and insurance brokers are mainly
remunerated by commission they receive from suppliers whose
services they recommend. </p>
<p>Computerised reservation systems (CRSs) have given airlines
increasing influence over the choices made by travel agents. The
positions of the largest carriers, who have a major influence on
the principal reservation systems, have been substantially
reinforced. The UK competition policy authorities left the matter
to their European counterparts, who were not inclined to treat
relations between agents and suppliers as a major issue. </p>
<p>The life insurance market has been transformed by regulatory
intervention since the Financial Services Act. The SIB imposed
polarisation on insurance brokers, who are now required to be
either tied agents selling only the products of a single insurer
or independent agents offering `best advice' from the whole range
of goods available on the market. </p>
<h4>The verdict</h4>
<p>So why the differences in verdict? The reasons are good, bad
and indifferent. The MMC's distinction between the competitive
structures of the beer and petrol industries was based on the
incidence of new entry in the two markets. </p>
<p>In petrol, it was clear that new wholesalers had encountered
no real difficulties in finding locations from which to sell
their products. Many firms, small and large, had come into the
market since the Commission's last report on the industry in
1978. </p>
<p>In beer, no foreign brewer had entered the UK market except as
a joint venture partner of an established UK brewer; even the
mighty Guinness had complained to the Commission of the
difficulties they had encountered in securing distribution for
their low alcohol lager. </p>
<p>The difference in treatment of gas and electricity was pure
politics. </p>
<p>Gas privatisation was accomplished through a deal between
Peter Walker and Sir Dennis Rooke which transferred the industry
to the private sector, but gave it the weakest regulatory
structure of any privatised utility. </p>
<p>Electricity was pushed through by Cecil Parkinson, committed
to competition, and John Wakeham, committed to making it work,
both prepared to ignore and ultimately to accept the threatened
resignation of the CEGB chairman. And what of life insurance and
CRSs? In both industries, it does not seem that the regulators
have yet come up with the right answer. We shall be hearing a
good deal more of the relationships between regulators, producers
and their retail agents in the decade to come. </p>
<hr>
