<html>
<head>
<title>Copycat Products a Fair Cop?</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Copycat Products a Fair Cop?</h2>
<p><i>We are all becoming accustomed to supermarket shelves lined
with lookalike products. Are they simply cashing in on others
ideas, or are they providing helpful information? Are they
denying manufacturers a fair return to investment, or benefiting
consumers through fair competition?</i></p>
<hr>
<p>Nearly a year ago, Sainsburys hit the headlines when it
launched Classic Cola, its ownbrand cola drink. Packaged to
resemble the Coca Cola can, it was a daring challenge to the best
known soft drink in the world. Challenges like this are now
commonplace: from margarine to muesli, from lager to lemon juice. </p>
<p>Retailers and manufacturers have been battling over the rights
and wrongs of lookalike packaging. While everybody has an opinion
on the matter, economists have been slow to enter the debate.
London Economics has carried out a costbenefit analysis of the
effects of lookalike packaging. Commercial law should have a
sound economic footing: does it in this case? </p>
<p>The economic issue centres on the price premium enjoyed by
brands: is it a form of monopoly profit, which deserves to be
competed away? Or is it a legitimate return to development, which
deserves legal protection? </p>
<h4>The rise of ownbrands</h4>
<p>The last few decades have seen enormous changes in grocery
retailing. Retailers today do much more than select, store and
display goods. As established retailers have focused more on
quality, they have come to be regarded as brands in their own
right. Putting their own names on products made to their own
specification, retailers can give ownbrands all the qualities of
branded products, but without the price premium. </p>
<p>But the strategy that has caused concern is not simply the
selling of ownbrands: it is the close targeting of brand leaders
by ownbrands with very similar packaging. </p>
<h4>Why do they do it?</h4>
<p>Lookalike packaging is cunning. Retailers seem to be trying to
gain from the ideas and images of successful brands to make the
sales without making the investment. However, similarity of
packaging is a very common strategy, used by manufacturers as
much as retailers. </p>
<p>If the characteristics of a new product are similar to those
of a known product, a similar `getup' can signal this to
consumers. It's a fast way to convey information about a
product's characteristics, thus saving the consumer
experimentation costs. The getup of a particular brand becomes a
`standard'. Yellow bottles, for example, have become a standard
feature of the getup of lemonscented detergents. </p>
<p>So retailers, though accused of trying to fool consumers, may
in fact be trying to inform them. If two products (say, a brand
and an ownbrand) are packaged in a very similar way, consumers
can tell at a glance that they are in direct competition with one
another. The consumer can then make an informed choice. </p>
<h4>Imitation and passing off</h4>
<p>In order to assess the effects of lookalikes, it is necessary
to distinguish `imitation' from `passing off': </p>
<ul>
    <li><i>imitation</i> occurs when the getup of two products is
        similar, but consumers can readily distinguish the two
        products; </li>
    <li><i>passing off</i> occurs when the getup of a product is
        so similar to that of another product that consumers are
        confused. </li>
</ul>
<p>Imitation is a normal part of the competitive process. Passing
off is deceitful, and already illegal in this country. Imitation
has both short and long term effects. </p>
<h4>Short term effects</h4>
<p>Lookalike products compete closely with brand leaders. While
they may be of identical or superior quality, they are almost
invariably cheaper, as they do not have the price premiums
received by brands. Competing away these price premiums directly
benefits consumers. The brand premium is in effect a monopoly
profit, received when no other product is competing in quite the
same market. </p>
<p>Of course, the brand leader will lose profits (unless the
introduction of the ownbrand product boosts overall demand), but
these are monopoly profits. The gain to consumers from imitation
will therefore lead to a net increase in social welfare, in the
short run at least. </p>
<p>If passing off occurs, the story is rather different.
Consumers are then deceived into buying one product when they
intend to buy another. Consumers' demands are therefore not met,
and they do not benefit from competition. </p>
<h4>Long term effects</h4>
<p>Although competition clearly benefits consumers in the short
run, a full costbenefit analysis requires us to look at the long
run effects of this competition on manufacturers' incentives. </p>
<p>Brand leaders claim that they need to earn a return on their
investment in developing new products. They claim that there are
substantial costs involved in designing new products, and that
lookalike products compete away the returns that would cover
these costs. </p>
<p>However, we must distinguish between providing incentives for
future development, and compensating for past development. Once a
new product has been developed, the development costs are sunk.
They do not affect the manufacturers' decision to sell the
product. There is no case for compensating manufacturers for past
development. </p>
<p>If, however, lookalike products regularly compete away brand
premiums, manufacturers may revise downward their expectation of
future profits. Their incentives for future product development
may be reduced. </p>
<h4>Patents and brands</h4>
<p>This argument is very similar to that used to justify patents.
By allowing the existence of a monopoly for a limited period, the
patent system effects a compromise between the conflicting aims
of protecting consumers from monopoly power, and providing
incentives for future innovation. </p>
<p>Should commercial law provide an incentive for developing new
products, in the same way that patent law provides an incentive
for developing new technologies? Three considerations lead us to
conclude that it should not, at least as far as grocery products
are concerned: </p>
<ul>
    <li>the costs of developing new grocery products are low,
        except advertising costs; </li>
    <li>advertising, however, may be used strategically as a
        barrier to entry so should not be protected; and </li>
    <li>true innovation in grocery products may not be as common
        as brand leaders claim; many `new' products are simply
        line extensions. </li>
</ul>
<h4>A new law?</h4>
<p>We conclude that passing off is harmful, but the short run
benefits of competition from imitation outweigh the long run
effects on manufacturers' incentives. Our costbenefit analysis
suggests that the law should prevent passing off, but should not
protect manufacturers from imitation. </p>
<p>This is, in fact, exactly how the law in the UK stands. The
Trade Marks Act 1994 prevents the use of signs that are identical
to or &quot;likely to be mistaken for&quot; registered trade
marks. And under the tort of passing off, a supplier can be taken
to court for misrepresenting his goods as those of another
supplier. The law, then, prevents passing off, but not imitation.
We might even be tempted to conclude that the law was written by
an economist! </p>
<p><i>Contact: Tom Hoehn </i><a href="mailto:tom@londecon.co.uk"><i>(email:tom@londecon.co.uk)</i></a><i><br>
Simon Gaysford </i><a href="mailto:simon@londecon.co.uk"><i>(email:simon@londecon.co.uk)</i></a></p>
<hr>
