<html>
<head>
<title>The Microsoft Antitrust Case</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>The Microsoft Antitrust Case</h2>
<p><em><strong>In July this year Microsoft, one of the US's most
successful and prestigious high technology companies, agreed to
cease engaging in certain allegedly anticompetitive practices in
the sale of its computer operating systems, in the face of
co-ordinated antitrust action by the European Commission and the
US Department of Justice. The settlement made headline news on
both sides of the Atlantic. Microsoft, no doubt mindful of the
decline of IBM following its lengthy conflict with the US
antitrust authorities, took the pragmatic line of agreeing to
cease the disputed practices, whilst simultaneously claiming that
it had in fact done nothing wrong. </strong></em></p>
<hr>
<p>Microsoft's antitrust troubles began in 1990 when the US
Federal Trade Commission launched a private enquiry into
Microsoft's relationship with IBM. These investigations continued
inconclusively until June 1993 when Novell, one of Microsoft's
principal competitors, filed a complaint with the Competition
Directorate of the European Commission. Novell had recently
acquired Digital Research, which produces DR-DOS, an operating
system interchangeable with Microsoft's MS-DOS, and hence in
direct competition with it. The stalled US investigations were
taken over by the Department of Justice and were soon running at
a scale not seen since the 1984 break-up of AT&amp;T. In February
1994, with simultaneous enquiries underway on two continents, the
US and EU took the unprecedented step of collaborating. From then
on events moved rapidly, concluding with Microsoft being offered
a tight deadline to agree a settlement. </p>
<h4>The complaint against Microsoft</h4>
<p>The allegations against Microsoft centred on its contracts
with computer manufacturers for the supply of its operating
system, MS-DOS. Operating systems form a buffer between computer
hardware and applications software, such as word processors and
spreadsheets, and no computer will work without one. Most new PCs
come with an operating system installed, and over 3 million
copies of MS-DOS are issued each month, making this a highly
lucrative market for Microsoft. </p>
<p>The settlement restricted Microsoft from engaging in its
previous contracting arrangements. In particular, it addressed: </p>
<ul>
    <li>licensing arrangements which required manufacturers to
        pay Microsoft according to the number of computers they
        shipped, regardless of whether or not these computers had
        MS-DOS installed or a rival operating system; </li>
    <li>contracts which required the purchase of minimum
        quantities of operating systems; </li>
    <li>contracts that ran for long periods, usually two years;
        and </li>
    <li>discounts offered by Microsoft to retailers for the
        purchase of MS-DOS, when purchased together with other
        Microsoft products, especially Windows. </li>
</ul>
<p>A principal line of attack for Novell was to make a case under
Article 86. This involves a series of arguments: the relevant
market needs to be demarcated; the firm must be shown to have a
dominant position within that market; and finally, the firm must
be shown to be abusing this dominant position. </p>
<h4>Market definition and Microsoft's dominant position</h4>
<p>Market definition is not straightforward in this case.
Operating systems for PCs can be divided into two types: </p>
<ul>
    <li>DOSs (disk operating systems), of which Microsoft's
        MS-DOS, Novell's DR-DOS and IBM's PC-DOS are particular
        brands; and </li>
    <li>other non-DOS operating systems (such as OS/2, UNIX,
        Nextstep, and Windows NT). </li>
</ul>
<p>If the relevant market is wider than just DOS for PCs and
includes non-DOS operating systems, then this would have the
effect of reducing Microsoft's market share. To decide whether or
not DOS and non-DOS operating systems should be treated as being
in the same market, it is necessary to assess the ease with which
consumers can substitute between the two products. </p>
<p>Two key characteristics of the market for operating systems
affect consumers' demand and their ability to substitute between
operating systems. First, there are so-called <b><i>network
externalities </i></b>. As the total number of users of a
particular operating system increases, so does the benefit to any
individual of using that operating system. A user will be able to
exchange data and programs with a larger group of other users,
and there is likely to be an increased range of applications
software available for an operating system with a larger user
base. </p>
<p>Second, there are <b><i>consumer switching costs</i></b>. It
is costly to switch between operating systems. Consumers must
both learn to operate the new system, and buy new applications
software. Both network externalities and switching costs
drastically limit the ability of individual consumers to
substitute a non-DOS operating system for a DOS operating system.
These arguments suggest that the relevant market for an
application of Article 86 should be DOSs only. </p>
<p>Another important factor in determining dominance </p>
<p>is <b><i>barriers to entry.</i></b> If Microsoft faces
significant potential competition then its dominance in the DOS
market may be less than its high market share suggests. Barriers
to entry, which protect Microsoft from such potential
competition, will thus increase its dominance. This is true even
if the barriers to entry are intrinsic to the market, and not
strategically erected by Microsoft. </p>
<p>To enter the DOS market, an operating system would need to be
interchangeable with MS-DOS and DR-DOS, so as to be compatible
with existing hardware and applications software. However,
consumers may be wary of interchangeability claims. Operating
systems are what economists call<b><i> experience goods</i></b>;
the only way to be sure that a DOS does what it claims is by
trying it. Since this is costly, and potentially risky, consumers
face switching costs even between different types of DOS. In
addition, network externalities can act as a barrier to entry.
Consumers benefit from using the most prevalent DOS, since this
DOS will lead in the setting of technical standards, as does
Microsoft at present. </p>
<h4>Microsoft's alleged anti-competitive practices</h4>
<p>Microsoft's system of contracts with equipment manufacturers
almost certainly made entry into the DOS market more difficult.
The supply of new PCs is highly competitive, and most new PCs are
shipped with an already installed operating system. Since
manufacturers generally pay lower prices than retail customers
for operating systems, there are strong incentives to bundle the
sale of PCs and operating systems. </p>
<p>Microsoft offered contracts to manufacturers under which
payments were conditional on the total number of PCs shipped,
regardless of whether MS-DOS or a rival operating system was
installed. A possible justification for such contracts is that
they are necessary to control piracy. However these contracts
also raise the costs to manufacturers of offering a variety of
operating systems. If manufacturers want to ship PCs with a rival
DOS, this is likely to be cost effective only if all their PCs
are installed with the rival DOS, a risky prospect if consumers
have compatibility fears concerning the competitor's product. </p>
<p>Microsoft's contracts also specified minimum quantities which
manufacturers were required to take, forming an exclusive dealing
arrangement in all but name. While it is clearly not in the
collective interests of manufacturers to have a near-monopoly
supplier of operating systems, competitive pressures may force
individual manufacturers to accept these contracts. </p>
<p>A recent analysis by Rasmusen et al has shown how buyers may
be induced to sign exclusionary contracts - through offering them
some small benefit (in this case, per system licences which are
cheaper than per copy licences) - which may foreclose the market
to further entry, even where this is to the collective detriment
of buyers. </p>
<p>By running contracts for long periods, Microsoft could also
effectively prevent entrants from building up demand for their
products quickly. To enter successfully, new operating systems
need to gain markets sufficiently quickly to be able to benefit
from network externalities and to convince customers of the
product's quality. Long-term contracts prevent this. </p>
<p>More controversial is the issue of whether Microsoft could use
its dominance in other markets to gain leverage on the DOS market
where it faced competition. Microsoft's Windows, a graphical
extension to DOS, faces little direct competition, though this
situation is now changing. Microsoft offered discounts to
manufacturers who took both MS-DOS and Windows, and is alleged to
have threatened not to supply Windows to manufacturers who did
not purchase MS-DOS. It was argued that this enabled Microsoft to
use its dominance in the Windows market to induce the exit of
Novell and IBM from the DOS market. </p>
<p>This issue is controversial, not least because there has been
much debate in economics concerning whether tying can be an
anticompetitive strategy. The Chicago School argued that tying a
monopolised product to one facing competition is not harmful as a
monopolist cannot increase its profits in this manner. However,
Whinston has recently shown that tying may be used, in certain
circumstances, to commit the dominant firm to competing more
aggressively in the market for the competitive product, and hence
to induce exit of rivals. Under such circumstances tying may
indeed become an instrument of market foreclosure. </p>
<h4>The settlement</h4>
<p>The settlement to which Microsoft agreed in July prohibits it,
for the next 6&#189; years, from: </p>
<ul>
    <li>charging for its operating system on the basis of
        computers shipped rather than on copies of MS-DOS
        shipped; </li>
    <li>imposing minimum quantity commitments on manufacturers; </li>
    <li>entering into contracts with durations of greater than
        one year; and </li>
    <li>tying the sale of MS-DOS to sale of other Microsoft
        products. </li>
</ul>
<p>This would appear to be a sweeping indictment of Microsoft's
practices. However, many commentators believe that Microsoft got
off lightly. There have been complaints from software developers
that Microsoft both sets technical standards for DOS and Windows
and also writes applications software to run under these systems.
It has been alleged that Microsoft has deliberately gone out of
its way to create compatibility problems between Windows and
rival applications software. Such advantages may secure
Microsoft's dominant position for some time to come. </p>
<p>Although the settlement has sent a clear signal that such
&quot;anticompetitive&quot; practices will not be tolerated by US
or EU antitrust authorities, it may have come too late for
Microsoft's competitors. Network externalities and switching
costs have the effect that, once a particular operating system
becomes the standard, it can be hard for competitors to get a
toe-hold. Thus the battle of the operating systems is for the
present over, with Microsoft the decisive winner. </p>
<p><i>Daniel Maldoom is an Academic Associate of London Economics
and is Fellow in Economics at University College, Oxford. London
Economics assisted Novell with its complaint against Microsoft. </i></p>
<hr>
