<html>
<head>
<title>Cost Allocation in Principle and in Practice</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Cost Allocation in Principle and in Practice</h2>
<p><em>A single expenditure within a firm can often support more
than one activity. Examples range from investment in a company
library or computer network, which will benefit many different
parts of the business, to the construction of a joint oil and gas
production platform. In the absence of these &quot;common&quot;
or &quot;joint&quot; costs, it is relatively straightforward to
establish the specific costs of the different products and
services supplied by a firm. Where there are common or joint
costs, however, the allocation of these costs to individual
products can be highly controversial, and the subject of intense
dispute. </em></p>
<hr>
<h4>The extent of the problem</h4>
<p>Competition authorities, arbitrators and utility regulators
frequently face exactly this problem. Consider, for example, the
recently liberalised UK telecommunications market. Competition is
being introduced at every level - retail, local and long distance
- where BT was formerly the monopoly supplier. However, removing
legal and regulatory barriers to entry in this industry is not
sufficient to ensure that effective competition will emerge. The
terms on which new entrants are allowed access to BT's customers
and its network, and the terms on which BT is permitted to set
retail prices, are critical. Only if these terms accurately
reflect costs will appropriate levels of entry occur. Hence
failure on the part of OFTEL to correctly allocate BT's common
and joint costs could lead to inefficient new entry in some
markets, and deter efficient entry in others. </p>
<p>Similar problems arise in competition authority
investigations. A few years ago the Competition Directorate of
the European Commission investigated a complaint of predatory
pricing against AKZO Chemie, a large chemical manufacturing firm.
The case hinged upon determining the relationship between AKZO's
costs and its prices. This involved identifying the separate
costs incurred by AKZO in the simultaneous manufacture and
marketing of organic peroxides for the plastics industry and
benzoyl peroxide for use as a flour additive. The solution to
this cost allocation problem was clearly crucial for the firms
involved, and in this case resulted in large fines being levied
against AKZO Chemie. </p>
<p>Unfortunately, accounting theory has not fully resolved the
issues underlying these cost allocation problems. Two common
fallacies are frequently encountered in the management accounting
literature: </p>
<ul>
    <li>All common and joint cost allocations are arbitrary. </li>
    <li>All common and joint costs can be attributed to
        individual products if only one employs enough hard
        working engineers and accountants. </li>
</ul>
<p>Neither of these propositions is correct. </p>
<h4>Paying for the chairman</h4>
<p>Let us begin with the first. Consider the salary of the
company chairman. This is typically treated as an overhead cost
and is allocated on some arbitrary criteria. And at first sight
it is easy to see why. The company chairman is not employed for
the benefit of any single customer or individual service. When we
ask how much time the chairman gives to worrying about any
particular customer or service, the answer is none whatever. </p>
<p>Does this mean that it is impossible to allocate the
chairman's salary in anything but an arbitrary way? Over the last
decade, an important development in accounting theory and
practice - the growth of systems of activity-based costing - has
addressed this problem. The essence of activity-based costing is
to seek chains of causality by modelling the firm's consumption
of resources. </p>
<p>We begin by asking: what does the chairman actually do? It is
usually possible to define a set of corporate activities such
that the whole of the chairman's working week can be separated
into the time he or she spends on these individual activities.
These various activities are then examined to see how they
benefit the company. Allocation of the chairman's salary is then
straightforward. </p>
<p>For example, suppose that the chairman spends one day in five
talking to shareholders. The aim of this is presumably to enable
equity financing to be obtained more cheaply. So one fifth of the
chairman's salary should be considered a cost of raising equity
finance. Equally, if the chairman spends time motivating
employees, then one ought to add a part of his or her salary
costs to the direct wage costs of the individuals concerned. </p>
<p>This may not seem so different from what conventional
accounting systems already do. However, when judged in this
light, few accounting systems emerge well. The vast majority of
cost allocation systems take inadequate account of causality.
Instead, a significant proportion of costs is simply allocated
pro rata, either to revenues or to other, more easily measurable,
costs. In reality, there are very few common costs in any
business that are incurred in direct proportion to either
revenues or direct costs </p>
<p>The above example shows that allocations of common and joint
costs need not be arbitrary. Many common costs can, in principle,
be fully attributed to individual activities, and through these
to individual products and services. However, in practice,
detailed engineering and accounting studies may be necessary to
carry out the proper allocation. </p>
<h4>Paying for chambers</h4>
<p>This leads us to the second of our common fallacies: that all
common and joint costs can be attributed to individual products
providing one employs enough hard working engineers and
accountants. </p>
<p>This fallacy can be illustrated by a simple example. Suppose
that it costs 100 to build chambers for one barrister and 180 to
build chambers for two barristers. What proportion of the costs
of building chambers for two barristers should properly be
attributed to each barrister? </p>
<p>A technical approach to this cost allocation problem would
attribute costs of 90 to each barrister, since both chambers are
physically identical. However, this split may not reflect
commercial reality. To see this, suppose that the first barrister
earns only 88, while the second earns 98. A 90:90 split would
prevent the first barrister from practising. Moreover, the second
barrister could not afford chambers on his own for 100, so
neither barrister would practise. A 85:95 split would thus leave
both barristers better off than the apparently sensible 90:90
split. </p>
<p>What the simple 90:90 split fails to consider is that there
are economies of scale or scope in the construction of
barristers' chambers. Building several barristers' chambers
together is cheaper than constructing each of the chambers
separately. While activity-based costing systems are wholly
appropriate for the attribution of overhead items such as the
chairman's salary, they are unable to allocate adequately the
value of scale and scope economies. However hard we look, and
however eminent the engineers we bring in to answer the question,
no physical attribution of scale and scope economies is ever
possible. </p>
<p>Two basic rules of allocating joint costs - frequently
referred to as the <b><i>Baumol-Willig conditions</i></b> - are
now well established. These require that the costs allocated to
any activity should never be: </p>
<ul>
    <li>less than the costs that would be saved by discontinuing
        that activity (its incremental cost), nor </li>
    <li>more than the costs that would be incurred if only that
        activity was undertaken (its stand-alone cost). </li>
</ul>
<p>In our case of the barristers' chambers, the stand-alone cost
is 100 (the cost of building chambers for one barrister), and the
incremental cost is 80 (the cost of chambers for two, 180, less
the cost of chambers for one, 100). An appropriate cost
allocation will therefore assign costs of not less than 80 and
not more than 100 to each barrister. </p>
<p>The Baumol-Willig conditions do not fully solve the cost
allocation problem; there is an area about which allocation
uncertainty remains. However, they show that this area is not
equal to the totality of the joint costs, but only to the value
of the economies of scale and scope. In our example, the extent
of possible argument is limited to 20. </p>
<p>In most real-world situations, the value of scale and scope
economies is small relative to the total costs of production.
Occasionally, however, the opposite may be true. What are the
relative costs of oil and gas from a joint production platform,
if total production costs would double if each of these
activities were to be pursued separately? </p>
<p>The Baumol-Willig rules are not, on their own, particularly
helpful in such cases. These rules simply define the size of the
&quot;pie&quot; - the value of scale and scope economies - to be
allocated. In order to narrow these bounds, it is necessary to
introduce additional principles. London Economics is currently
using economic bargaining theory to develop such principles in
its work in telecommunications and other industries. </p>
<p>Zoltan Biro, Senior Consultant at London Economics, is the
author of &quot;Utility Cost Allocation in Principle and
Practice&quot;, with John Kay, delivered at the CRI/ICAEW
conference <i>Effective Utility Regulation - The Accounting
Requirements</i> in London in October 1994. The paper was
published in the conference volume and copies are available on
request. </p>
<hr>
