</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Barriers to Entry and Exit in Competition Policy</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Barriers to Entry and Exit in Competition Policy</h2>
<p><i>&quot;A correct analysis of entry or barriers to entry lies
at the heart of an assessment of monopoly power. ... [This is]
the single most misunderstood topic in the analysis of
competition and monopoly&quot;1</i> </p>
<p>The analysis of barriers to entry and exit is fundamental to
the assessment of market power. In the long run, a firm or firms
may exercise market power only if barriers to new entry exist.
Thus in determining whether or not a proposed merger is against
the public interest, or whether a firm is abusing market power in
antitrust cases, analysis of entry conditions is of primary
importance. </p>
<ol>
    <li>Franklin M. Fisher (1979) &quot;Diagnosing
        monopoly&quot;, in J. Monz (ed.)<i> Industrial
        Organisation, Economics and Law: Collected Papers of
        Franklin M. Fisher</i>, New York, Harvester, 1990. </li>
</ol>
<p>One might therefore expect to see extensive and sophisticated
analyses of entry conditions, and barriers to entry, in monopoly
and merger cases that come before competition authorities in the
UK or member states of the European Union. However this has not
typically been the case. This is at least partly due to the
complexity of the issues involved and the lack of a consistent
and accepted method of analysing them. </p>
<p>In March this year, the Office of Fair Trading published
London Economics' report <i>Barriers to Entry and Exit in UK
Competition Policy</i> that evaluates, and proposes a methodology
for, the assessment of barriers to entry and exit in UK
competition policy. The report surveys the relevant economic
theory and addresses the practical application of the theory of
entry barriers to actual competition cases. </p>
<p>The publication was aimed at stimulating debate on an issue
that is central to many competition policy decisions made by the
main investigating authorities in the UK: the OFT and the MMC. As
the press release by the OFT stated: </p>
<p><i>&quot;It is in line with the intention of the Director
General of Fair Trading, Sir Bryan Carsberg, that there should be
greater transparency on how the OFT approaches cases and reaches
decisions.&quot; </i></p>
<h4>Harvard versus Chicago</h4>
<p>One reason for the absence of a generally accepted methodology
for the assessment of entry barriers has been the long history of
controversy between the two main schools of thought in antitrust.
The so-called &quot;Harvard School&quot; of industrial
organisation was developed in the 1940s and 1950s and dominated
antitrust thinking in the US for many years. During the 1970s,
however, the views of the Harvard School were subject to the
provocative and influential critique of Posner, Bork, Stigler and
others from the &quot;Chicago School&quot;, and recent practice
in both the US and Europe has clearly reflected this shift in the
debate. </p>
<p>Followers of the Harvard School tended to admit a great many
things as barriers to entry and abuses of market power, including
economies of scale and capital requirements. On the other hand,
the Chicago School could be accused of admitting no entry
barriers at all, other than those created by government policy or
regulation. Explicit price fixing and very large horizontal
mergers (i.e. &quot;mergers to monopoly&quot;) were the sole
areas of serious concern to followers of the Chicago School.
Persistent concentration was taken to imply either that the
market in question was simply not large enough to sustain many
firms (economies of scale), or that some firms were able
persistently to obtain abnormal profits via cost reductions or
product improvements that competitors and new entrants were
unable to duplicate. Neither case was viewed as an appropriate
area for public intervention designed to change market structure. </p>
<p>The debate has been particularly heated with respect to
vertical issues where the influence of the Chicago School has
probably been strongest. The Chicago view was that vertical
integration, refusal to supply and exclusive dealing arrangements
should not be a concern because they were motivated solely by
efficiency considerations. Antitrust problems were held to arise
only from a lack of horizontal competition. </p>
<p>During the past two decades however, advances in the theory of
industrial organisation have thrown new light on these
controversial issues and clarified to a great extent the
analytical approach that should be taken with respect to entry
conditions and barriers to entry. In particular the so-called
&quot;new industrial organisation (IO)&quot;, using
game-theoretic techniques, has brought strategic issues to the
fore and has contributed greatly to our under-standing of the
interaction between traditional &quot;Bainian&quot; barriers to
entry and strategic behaviour by both incumbent firms and
entrants. It has also shown that the Chicago analysis, while
provocative, was based upon overly simple economic models that
were not robust to changes in simplifying assumptions. </p>
<h4>A new methodology</h4>
<p>London Economics' report makes use of the key insights of
modern IO theory and identifies a number of criteria by which to
judge whether a market is open to potential competition. The
first step is to examine whether there are firms in
&quot;nearby&quot; markets that could quickly and easily enter
the market in question should prices rise. Evidence of past entry
is also important, if it can be shown that market conditions have
not changed substantially. Next, it is necessary to test for the
existence of a number of different types of barrier to entry: </p>
<ul>
    <li><b><i>absolute cost advantages,</i></b> which include
        many legal and regulatory entry barriers; </li>
    <li><b><i>strategic (first-mover) advantages,</i></b> which
        firms enjoy as a consequence of being first into the
        market; </li>
    <li><b><i>vertical relationships and exclusionary practices</i></b><i> </i><b>,</b>
        which include refusal to supply and exclusive dealing as
        well as formal vertical integration; and </li>
    <li><b><i>predatory pricing behaviour</i></b><b>.</b> </li>
</ul>
<p>Finally it is important to examine potential <b><i>entry
impediments </i></b>- factors which are not barriers to entry in
the long run, but which may nevertheless delay the effectiveness
of potential competition in the short term. </p>
<p>The report's analysis is based on two key insights from modern
IO theory that must inform any assessment of barriers to entry.
First, the importance of <i>strategic interaction between
incumbents and entrants</i>, and, in particular, <i>the nature of
post-entry competition.</i> These are crucial in determining
entry conditions, and hence market structure. Second, the
fundamental role played by <i>sunk costs</i> in the calculations
of potential entrants. Sunk costs are costs that cannot be
recouped on exiting the market, and, combined with strategic
behaviour and post-entry competition, are an important
determinant of market structure via their effects on entry and
exit decisions. </p>
<p>The report also distinguishes between different types of
entrant, ranging from <i>production substituters</i>, who can
switch production activity to the relevant product or
geographical market speedily and without significant sunk costs,
to the <i>new entrant</i> whose entry will typically entail some
significant sinking of costs. Of course, there are no clear-cut
distinctions between types of entrant; rather there is a
continuous scale. As one moves along this scale, from simple
production substitution to fully-fledged new entry, the
importance of &quot;expected post-entry prices&quot; increases
relative to that of current price levels as a determinant of
entry decisions, and hence of entry barriers. </p>
<p>These are all issues that have figured prominently in the
economics literature of the past decade or so. They have been
slow, however, to find their way into the thinking of the
regulatory and competition authorities and courts. </p>
<h4>Applying the methodology</h4>
<p>The methodology proposed in the report is illustrated by case
studies. One of these deals with the acquisition by the Gillette
Company of Parker Pen Holdings Limited in 1992. Parker was the
leading supplier in the market for refillable pens, with an
overall market share of 54.6% in 1991. Gillette owned the two
well-known brands, PaperMate and Waterman. It was feared that the
merger of the two businesses would lead to an unacceptable
increase in market concentration, and to the abuse of market
power. The OFT referred the merger to the MMC. However, the MMC
allowed the merger, and published its findings in a report that
focused on the importance of <i>potential </i>competition in the
market for refillable pens. </p>
<p>Was the MMC correct? With Parker, PaperMate and Waterman
operating as a single force in the market, with a combined market
share of 62%, would potential competition be sufficient to
prevent the abuse of market power? If entry barriers are high
then a dominant firm may enjoy profits that are due to its market
power, rather than an efficiency advantage or superior product.
Competition policy aims to prevent the reduction of competition
through mergers that are against the public interest. But if
there are no barriers to the entry to new competition then there
is no obvious case for intervention, even where the market share
of the dominant supplier is very high. Excess profits that are
not due to superior performance will attract new entrants, who
will compete them away. The public is protected from excessive
pricing by the possibility of new entry. </p>
<p>London Economics conclude that, against each of their
criteria, the Parker Pen merger case passed the test. Several
successful entry episodes, which had taken market share from
established firms, were cited by the MMC. In addition major
retailers were starting to assemble and sell their own brands. No
obvious cost advantages were evident; on the contrary, the MMC's
report emphasised that technologically it was very easy to
manufacture pens and that there were no patents on refillable
technology. Neither did it appear that major sunk investments in
design, brand promotion or the establishment of a reputation were
necessary before entry into the pen market could be undertaken. </p>
<p>Why then did the OFT refer the case to the MMC in the first
place? Obviously the high market share enjoyed by Parker seemed a
good reason to look more closely at the potential
anti-competitive effects of the merger. But the case is an
interesting and important illustration of the fact that first
appearances can be deceptive. Firms that have a high market share
in markets that can easily be contested by new entrants have
little scope to exploit their dominant position. It is ease of
entry, not market share, that really matters. </p>
<p>David Harbord is Senior Associate and Tom Hoehn is a Director
of London Economics. They are the authors of &quot;Barriers to
entry and exit in European competition policy&quot;, which
appears in the December issue of the <i>International Review of
Law and Economics</i>. Copies of the report are available from
the OFT or London Economics free of charge. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1994 </p>
