<html>
<head>
<title>An Economic Perspective on the Magill Case</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>An Economic Perspective on the Magill Case </h2>
<p><em>The legal world is currently trying to make sense of a
recent ruling by Europe's highest court, the European Court of
Justice (ECJ), in the infamous Magill case, with every side
claiming at least a partial victory. Magill TV Guide Ltd., a
small Irish publisher, lodged its original complaint with the
European Commission's Competition Directorate in 1986. Magill has
long since gone out of business, yet big legal battles have been
fought over the issues that the case raises. What then are the
principle issues that make this case both fascinating and
potentially very important to the future application of
competition law? </em></p>
<hr>
<p>In 1986 the BBC, ITV and the Irish Broadcaster RTE held
copyrights in their respective TV listings, and exploited these
copyrights to become only providers of weekly TV listings
magazines, each of which featured solely the programmes of that
broadcaster. Magill saw a demand for a comprehensive TV listings
magazine. However, Magill was unable to meet this demand because
the copyright holders refused to grant it licences to use their
listings. </p>
<p>Using the provisions of Article 86 of the EC Treaty, Magill
challenged the right of the copyright holders to behave in this
way. The European Commission and the Court of First Instance
ruled that the copyright holders were abusing their respective
dominant positions in refusing to grant licences to Magill, and
the ECJ has now confirmed this finding. </p>
<p>The Magill case is controversial because it brings into focus
the potential for conflict between two different legal regimes.
On the one hand there is the legal protection that intellectual
property rights afford to holders of copyrights. These are
governed by the national laws of member states. On the other
hand, there are the provisions of the EC Treaty that are
concerned with the protection of competition and the integration
of the common market. Does the ruling in Magill imply that
European competition law now overrides national laws protecting
intellectual property rights? </p>
<p>From an economist's point of view, the ECJ's ruling in Magill
appears to make sense. As the ECJ has recognised, the exclusive
right of reproduction forms an essential part of a copyright
holder's rights, so that <i>refusal to grant a licence cannot in
and of itself constitute abuse of a dominant position</i>.
However, if copyright holders use the exclusivity that copyright
law grants them in order to &quot;leverage&quot; the market power
they have in one market, into a secondary market, it is not at
all obvious that their behaviour should be free from competition
policy considerations and sanctions. </p>
<p>This is precisely what the Magill case is about. It concerned
a de facto monopoly in programme information that was valuable
because there were very few TV channels in 1986 for viewers to
watch. The primary problem is the market power of the
broadcasters. Without that market power the Magill case would
never have arisen or, at least, would not have been taken
seriously </p>
<p>The distinction between the acceptable exploitation of market
power conferred by copy-right and the abuse of a dominant
position is made clear by the following example. </p>
<p>Let us imagine a world of 100 equal-sized broadcasters,
instead of two or three. Viewers would like a comprehensive
weekly listing but will be unwilling to buy 100 different
listings magazines. Each broadcaster still has a copyright over
its own TV schedule information and will still have a right to
exploit it. However, they will all be eager to supply their
weekly TV listings to a comprehensive TV guide in order to raise
their viewing figures in the primary market, the market for TV
broadcasting. </p>
<p>The economics of this example are similar to the Magill case,
except the broadcasters individually have no market power in the
market for TV broadcasting, and hence in the market for TV
schedule information. Without this market power, they have no
incentive to refuse licenses. Indeed, quite the opposite is true:
it is in their interests to grant them so as to disseminate their
programme information as widely as possible. The example thus
makes clear that it is the ability to exploit their market power
in a secondary market that is challenged by Magill, rather than
the simple exploitation of copyright protection. </p>
<p>This distinction can be made even clearer by continuing our
example. Suppose now that the 100 broadcasters join together and
decide to exclusively license their weekly TV listings to
&quot;TV Guides Unlimited&quot;. TV Guides Unlimited is then the
monopoly publisher of TV guides and will be able to earn, on
behalf of its licensees, a considerable profit. Few would deny
that such a collusive agreement by copyright holders would be
potentially anti-competitive. </p>
<p>In its reasoning, the ECJ recognises the distinction between
the legitimate exploitation of copyright and the abuse of market
power. Firstly, the Court defines the relevant market as being
the basic information in TV schedules. In doing so, it goes
against the findings of the Commission and the Court of First
Instance, which defined the relevant market as the market for TV
guides. The Court then establishes the dominant position of the
copyright holders BBC, ITP, and RTE by virtue of their de facto
monopoly in this relevant market. </p>
<p>Finally, the court accepts that while refusal to supply by a
copyright holder does not in principle represent an abuse of the
dominant position, it may still do so under certain
circumstances, all of which are satisfied in this case, viz: </p>
<ul>
    <li>that the refusal to supply prevents the appearance of a
        new product for which there is latent demand (here, that
        the broadcasters' behaviour prevents the formation of a
        secondary market in the comprehensive weekly TV guides); </li>
    <li>that there is no justification for refusal to supply,
        other than the exploitation of market power; and </li>
    <li>that there is no substitute for the intellectual property
        (here, the basic weekly TV schedule information), so that
        refusing to supply the intellectual property allows its
        owners to reserve for themselves the secondary market
        (here, the weekly TV guides), by excluding all potential
        competition. </li>
</ul>
<p>These conditions are relatively stringent, and will not apply
to the majority of situations in which copyrights are invoked.
The judgement of the ECJ in Magill therefore appears to be an
appropriate application of competition law to a situation where
market power exists, and is abused. </p>
<p>One of the questions raised by Magill is whether the judgement
has wider application to similar situations. From our reading of
the case, the economic argument in Magill appears to be quite
general: firms should not be permitted to &quot;leverage&quot;
market power from a primary market (e.g. programme information)
into a secondary market (e.g. TV guides) via the exploitation of
intellectual property rights. </p>
<p>The Magill judgement could therefore potentially affect some
aspects of behaviour by royalty collecting societies, or the
arrangements between broadcasters and organisers of major
sporting events. For example the power to control the
broadcasting of sports events could be potentially considered in
the same manner as in Magill. Any investigation by a competition
authority would then need to establish whether the relevant
conditions of Magill would be met. In particular: </p>
<ul>
    <li>that there is a de facto monopoly in major sporting
        events; </li>
    <li>that there is no adequate substitute for these
        broadcasts; </li>
    <li>that there is no justification for exclusivity other than
        the exploitation of monopoly power. </li>
</ul>
<p>What Magill does not do, in our view, is to undermine the
right of creative artists and innovators to exploit the value of
their artistic works or innovations through the exclusive use of
copyrights or patents. The market power that the creator of a Top
Ten single, a television programme, or an innovative drug,
obtains over its product's use and dissemination, is the direct
result of costly and risky innovative or creative effort. The
function of patents and copyrights is to provide an incentive for
undertaking such efforts by affording to their creators the
ability to reap high rewards for successful &quot;products&quot;
or works. The taking of high risks merits high rewards, and is
sufficient justification for refusal to supply. <i>Tom Hoehn is a
Director of London Economics Ltd. </i></p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1995 </p>
</body>
</html>
