<head>
<title>The MMC Investigation into the Electrical Goods Market</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>The MMC Investigation into the Electrical Goods Market</h2>
<h3>Introduction</h3>
<p>On April 27th, in his last few weeks before leaving the Office
of Fair Trading (OFT) Sir Bryan Carsberg referred another
vertical restraints case to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission
(MMC). Following his disappointment at the MMC's decisions on <i>New
Motor Cars</i> (1992), <i>Fine Fragrances</i> (1993), and <i>Ice
Cream</i> (1994), will he now finally get the result that he is
looking for? The answer seems far from clear. </p>
<p>The OFT has referred eight separate categories of electrical
goods: televisions, videos, hi-fi systems, camcorders, washing
machines, tumble dryers, dishwashers, and refrigerators. </p>
<p>This makes the case one of the largest that the MMC has had to
carry out. All significant manufacturers and retailers in any of
these categories will be investigated. These include household
name manufacturers such as Sony, Philips, Electrolux, Hoover, and
Toshiba, as well as well-known retailers such as Dixons, Comet,
and the Regional Electricity Companies. </p>
<p>The OFT's principal allegation appears to be price-fixing in
the form of refusal to supply to cut-price traders (that is,
traders who attempt to sell products at below the maker's
recommended retail price). It has received complaints about this
from the 'warehouse clubs' Costco and Cargo Club (now closed).
For example, Sony refused to supply Cargo Club with larger
electrical goods, claiming that it did not have adequate staff
training, after-sales service, and display facilities. The
observed uniformity of retail pricing has been suggested as
evidence of collusion to maintain retail prices. </p>
<p>Against this allegation, Dixons has argued that electrical
goods retailing is extremely competitive, and that the observed
uniformity of prices is - on the contrary - the result of
cut-throat competition. Although Dixons is currently making
profits, its competitors have suffered: Comet made losses last
year, Rumbelows (formerly the third largest retailer) was
recently closed down by its parent Thorn EMI, and Clydesdale (the
fourth largest) went into receivership in January 1994. </p>
<h3>The Economic Issues</h3>
<p>Simple economic theory suggests that sales of a product should
increase as its price to consumers falls. If so, for given
manufacturer prices, manufacturers will do better when retailers'
margins are reduced, because they sell more units. The supply of
goods to cut-price traders would therefore be expected to expand
total sales and hence increase manufacturers' revenues and
profits. </p>
<p>Why then would electrical goods manufacturers ever wish to
refuse to supply cut-price traders? </p>
<p>Three alternative explanations for this are frequently
offered: </p>
<ol>
    <li>Demand depends on more than just price </li>
    <li>Price can act as a 'signal' of product quality </li>
    <li>Refusal to supply may facilitate or maintain collusion. </li>
</ol>
<p>If 1 or 2 is valid then refusal to supply is not necessarily
against the public interest; rather it may be a competitive
response by manufacturers to cut-price retailers, in order to
protect their product's reputation and market position. If 3 is
true however, then the MMC should act. A great deal thus depends
upon the MMC's ability to distinguish between these three
alternative explanations. The rest of this article discusses
these possible explanations in more detail. </p>
<h3>1. Demand Depends on More Than Just Price</h3>
<p>In many retail markets price is only one factor in determining
a product's sales. Sales may also be highly dependent on: </p>
<ul>
    <li>various dimensions of non-price competition between
        retail outlets; </li>
    <li>the brand image of the product; and </li>
    <li>the number of retail outlets. </li>
</ul>
<p>Increased price competition and lower retail margins may have
a negative impact upon one or more of these factors, and
consequently reduce the demand faced by manufacturers at any
given wholesale price. If this negative effect is sufficiently
strong relative to the positive effect on sales of lower prices,
then total sales may actually decrease. </p>
<p><b>Dimensions of non-price competition</b> </p>
<p>Consumers' purchasing decisions are based upon various factors
and hence retailers tend to compete with each other in several
dimensions, including: </p>
<ul>
    <li>price </li>
    <li>geographical location </li>
    <li>product range and selection </li>
    <li>retailer service (including the general ambience of the
        shopping environment and the retailer's image, as well as
        the more direct forms of retailer service) </li>
</ul>
<p>If competition between retailers in one of these dimensions
becomes vigorous, it may be pursued at the expense of competition
in the other dimensions. In particular, if price competition
becomes strong, resulting in reduced retailer margins, product
range and retailer service may suffer. So long as consumers care
sufficiently about variety of choice and retailer service, this
can result in reduced total sales. </p>
<p>This point is particularly important for products where there
is potential for the so-called 'free-rider' problem to arise.
When some retailers invest in promoting a product's image (see
below) or provide a high level of retailer services, they may be
providing a benefit to other retailers which they cannot fully
capture for themselves. Consumers may make use of the services
provided by one retailer and subsequently purchase the product
from another retailer which does not provide the same level of
service, and can thus afford to sell the product more cheaply. In
economics this is called an 'externality', and typically results
in a reduced willingness on the part of retailers to make such
investments or provide these services. </p>
<p>The 'free-rider' effect may be important for electrical goods.
For example, consumers may go to Comet, use its sales staff to
help them pick out the washing machine which is most appropriate
to their needs, and then actually purchase that model from a
cut-price trader (where prices are cheaper because a lower level
of retail services is provided). Where consumers value retail
services, social welfare may be reduced by this 'free-rider'
effect, unless all retailers can be induced to provide similar
levels of service. Refusing to supply cut-price retailers may be
one means manufacturers have of placing a check upon such
retailer 'free-riding'. </p>
<h4>Brand image </h4>
<p>Retailers can play an important role in the promotion and
maintenance of a manufacturer's brand image. For example: </p>
<ul>
    <li><b><i>Instore promotions</i></b>: Retailer in-store
        product promotion (and generally the way in which the
        product is displayed) can be essential for raising the
        image of a product. This point was made very strongly in <i>Black
        and Decker</i> (MMC, 1989), where it was argued that
        lower retail margins on Black and Decker (B&amp;D)
        products reduced retailers' incentives to promote B&amp;D
        products, thus lowering retail brand image. </li>
    <li><b><i>Exclusivity cach&eacute;</i></b>: Manufacturers are
        sometimes concerned to achieve a cach&eacute; of
        exclusivity and high quality by distributing their
        products through only a few choice retailers. This was an
        important consideration in <i>Fine Fragrances</i> (1993),
        where retailers were chosen according to often stringent
        qualitative criteria. </li>
    <li><b><i>Product range</i></b>: The product range provided
        by a retailer can also be important. In <i>New Motor Cars</i>
        (1992), the MMC accepted that manufacturers' use of
        exclusive dealerships which stocked their full range was
        necessary to ensure sufficient control over manufacturer
        brand image. In <i>Fine Fragrances</i>, on the other
        hand, it was noted that perfume manufacturers frequently
        stipulate that a retailer should also supply certain
        other perfumes, in order to ensure that their products
        are being sold in the 'right' sort of environment. </li>
</ul>
<p>In each of these examples, retailers can provide an important
benefit to a manufacturer, in terms of promoting and protecting
its brand image. Thus there is again an 'externality', but this
time it is between manufacturers and retailers rather than
between retailers. </p>
<p>To overcome this externality, and to achieve their desired
brand image, manufacturers may need to be able to distribute
their product selectively, to impose certain conditions on
retailers concerning service, ambience and product range, or to
restrict price competition between retailers in order to induce
competition in these other dimensions. Refusal to supply certain
retailers may thus be necessary for achieving the 'right' brand
image. </p>
<h4>The number of retail outlets</h4>
<p>For many products, sales will be highly dependent on the ease
with which consumers can purchase the product, which will in turn
depend on the number of retail outlets in which it is sold. This
means, for example, that if some retail outlets switch from
stocking Hotpoint's products to stocking those of Zanussi, then
sales of Hotpoint's products should fall. Similarly, if the total
number of retail outlets falls due to retailers exiting the
market, then total sales in the market may also fall. </p>
<p>At first sight it is not clear how this point can provide a
justification for refusal to supply. On the contrary, it would
appear that refusal to supply can only result in a reduction in
the number of retailers, and hence reduce total sales. </p>
<p>Suppose, however, that Sony had agreed to supply Cargo Club,
and that this had resulted in reduced retail margins for its
other retailers. This could potentially induce some of these
retailers to stop stocking Sony's products, and to focus on
products which are not supplied through cut-price traders. The
reduction in the number of non-cut-price outlets stocking Sony's
products could then result in reduced sales through these
outlets. </p>
<h3>This reduction in sales must be traded off against the
increase in sales in the cut-price outlets, but there is no
reason to expect that, on balance, Sony's total sales would
increase. Moreover, if there are economies of scale in
distribution, the reduction in the number of outlets may make the
manufacturer's current distribution network less efficient. This
argument was made in <i>Black and Decker</i>. </h3>
<h3>2. Price May Act as a Signal of Quality</h3>
<p>When consumers cannot easily observe the quality of a product
prior to purchase, manufacturers will try to signal quality in
various ways. The provision of warranties, a reputation for
providing high quality products, and high levels of advertising
are all commonly used methods. Price is another: if high product
quality is associated with high manufacturing costs then a low
price can act as a signal of low quality. That is consumers know
that high quality products cannot be profitably provided at low
prices. Thus the perceived quality of a manufacturer's product
may be negatively affected by price-cutting. </p>
<p>If consumers care sufficiently about a product's quality, a
reduction in price may actually reduce demand via this 'quality
signalling' effect. Of course, for price to provide information
concerning quality in this way, it must be the case that
providers of low quality products cannot 'mimic' the pricing
behaviour of high quality providers, and thus reduce - or
ultimately eliminate - the informational value of the signal.
This topic has been addressed by a number of economic models over
the past decade, and the broad conclusion is that price may
indeed act as a quality signal, at least in certain
well-specified circumstances. </p>
<p>This point was made in <i>Black and Decker </i>where it was
suggested that reduced retail prices for B&amp;D's products gave
consumers the impression that they were of significantly lower
quality than its competitors' products, resulting in a reduction
in demand for B&amp;D's products. A similar - though not
identical - argument was made in <i>Fine Fragrances</i>, where it
was argued that consumers value perfume partly <i>because</i> of
its high price, so that a reduction in retail price would lower
sales. </p>
<h3>3. Refusal to Supply as an Anti-Competitive Practice</h3>
<p>The above arguments suggest that refusal to supply may, in
certain circumstances, actually increase industry sales and
promote consumer welfare. In particular price discounting and
loss-leading may reduce levels of retailer service and product
variety, damage brand image, and interfere with consumers'
ability to distinguish high from low quality products. However an
alternative, and less benign, motive for such behaviour involves
the exploitation of market power, or &quot;price fixing&quot;. </p>
<p>If firms individually have market power - or if they are able
to collude - then refusal to supply may be part of an
anti-competitive strategy to raise prices. This may occur in
essentially three ways: </p>
<ol>
    <li>retailer coercion; </li>
    <li>manufacturer collusion; or </li>
    <li>retailer and manufacturer collusion (joint profit
        maximisation). </li>
</ol>
<h4>i) Retailer coercion</h4>
<p>When a manufacturer supplies cut-price retailers, other
retailers may be forced to reduce their prices - and profit
margins - in order to compete. If these other retailers are
sufficiently important in terms of the manufacturer's total
sales, they may be able to prevent this by threatening to
discontinue stocking the manufacturer's products if it continues
to supply cut-price traders. Hence if retailers have sufficient
market power relative to manufacturers, refusal to supply to
cut-price traders may be the result of retailer coercion. </p>
<p>The MMC has generally found the retailer coercion hypothesis
difficult to sustain. In <i>Contact Lens Solutions</i> (MMC,
1993), for example, there was evidence of attempted retailer
coercion. Boots the Chemist had allegedly attempted to use its
influence over CIBA Vision (UK), a supplier, in order to
influence the pricing behaviour of Dollond &amp; Aitchison, a
competing retailer. However the MMC found that Boots had not in
fact been successful in achieving this. </p>
<p>An article on the electrical goods market in the May 1995
issue of Which? has raised the possibility of retailer coercion
in this market. Which? researchers claimed to have heard of
several cases in which a retailer informed a manufacturer that a
rival retailer was selling the manufacturer's products at below
RRP. The implication here seems to be that stronger retailers may
be using manufacturers' refusal to supply in order to achieve
collusion at the retail level. </p>
<h4>ii) Manufacturer collusion</h4>
<p>In order for price collusion between manufacturers to be
effective, it is crucial that any attempts to 'cheat' on the
collusive arrangement can be detected. For this, it must be
possible for the colluding firms to observe whether any
manufacturer cuts its prices to below the implicitly agreed-upon
price. Manufacturers' wholesale prices are generally difficult to
observe, but retail prices may serve as a useful proxy. </p>
<p>If many competing retailers all sell the same product at
different prices, then it can be difficult to detect cheating,
because it is difficult to separate out a reduction in a
manufacturer's wholesale price from a reduction in retail margin.
However, adherence by retailers to recommended retail prices
(RRPs), which are highly visible, can facilitate the detection of
cheating and hence collusion. </p>
<p>If manufacturers have sufficient market power relative to
retailers, they may be able to induce retailers to observe RRPs.
In particular, there may be an implicit, or even explicit, threat
to refuse to supply any retailer which undercuts the
manufacturer's RRP. This maintenance of RRPs - as a means of
facilitating price collusion - would clearly be threatened if
manufacturers were forced to supply cut-price retailers. </p>
<p>In <i>Fine Fragrances</i>, it was considered important that
refusal to supply be permitted only on qualitative - and not
quantitative - grounds. That is, a refusal to supply should not
be based upon the pricing policy of the retailer, but rather only
upon features such as the retailer's sales environment and
service provision. The aim of this condition was essentially to
ensure that refusal to supply was not used to facilitate price
collusion by manufacturers. </p>
<h4>iii) Joint retailer-manufacturer collusion</h4>
<p>In many markets both manufacturers and retailers have some
degree of market power. This means that collusive behaviour may
not be completely explained by the simple dealer coercion or
manufacturer collusion arguments. Rather, exploitation of market
power is as likely to be the result of manufacturers and
retailers colluding together in the setting of prices, through
the use of RRPs, so as to maximise their joint profits. </p>
<p>Joint manufacturer-retailer collusion is usually considered to
raise prices, because it permits collusive behaviour at both
levels, where none would otherwise be possible. In particular,
manufacturers may be unable to induce retailers to adhere to RRPs
(and so facilitate manufacturer collusion) unless both levels
collude and share the resulting monopoly profits between them. </p>
<p>Refusal to supply cut-price traders can be crucial for
maintaining such an implicit arrangement. If entry by cut-price
traders is possible, other retailers will have an incentive to
cheat on the arrangement in order to maintain sales, and
collusion will tend to break down. </p>
<p>However, joint manufacturer-retailer collusion can
theoretically result in lower prices. Suppose that there is
significant market power at both the manufacturer and retailer
levels. In the absence of collusion <i>between</i> the two
levels, prices may actually be too high for joint profit
maximisation, due to both levels individually trying to make a
monopoly mark-up. Thus, by colluding with each other in the
setting of retail prices through the use of RRPs, prices may
actually be lowered rather than increased (although it should be
noted that prices under this joint collusion would still be
higher than they would be with competition at each level). </p>
<h3>Conclusions</h3>
<p>We have discussed several possible rationales for
manufacturers refusing to supply cut-price traders. Some are
pro-competitive and beneficial to consumer welfare, whereas
others are anti-competitive and act against the public interest. </p>
<p>The outcome of this latest case rests upon which of these
rationales are found by the MMC to best describe the refusal to
supply behaviour in the electrical goods market. This in turn
will depend on the answers that are given to a number of critical
questions, including: </p>
<ul>
    <li>How important are retailer services to manufacturers and
        consumers in this market? </li>
    <li>How important is retailer image (including consumers'
        perception of retailer services)? </li>
    <li>How important is retailer product range? </li>
    <li>Do total sales depend significantly upon the number of
        retail outlets? </li>
    <li>What degree of market power are individual manufacturers
        and retailers able to exert? </li>
    <li>Is there evidence of manufacturers or retailers using
        RRPs to facilitate collusion? </li>
</ul>
<p>In recent years, the MMC has been criticised for being rather
more ready to accept the pro-competitive arguments than to accuse
firms of behaving anti-competitively. This is no doubt partly due
to the complexity of the subject, and the fact that the same
types of evidence can be used to support several competing
hypotheses. </p>
<p>In general however, the MMC tends to be less willing to allow
refusal to supply on quantitative grounds (such as price
discounting) than to allow it on qualitative grounds (such as low
retailer service and product range). These selection conditions
have been taken to indicate the rationale behind the selective
distribution: with qualitative conditions suggesting
pro-competitive aims and quantitative conditions suggesting
collusion. However this distinction is not always valid: the two
forms of retailer selectivity may have very similar economic
implications, and it can be inappropriate to treat them
differently. </p>
<p><i>Zoltan Biro and Amelia Fletcher are both members of London
Economics' competition team</i>. </p>
<hr>
