<head>
<title>Merger policy in Germany and the UK</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Merger policy in Germany and the UK</h2>
<p><b><i>In November 1995 London Economics held a major
conference bringing together experts and practitioners from the
UK and Germany to discuss merger policy in Europe. The
discussions ranged from the role of mergers in strengthening the
competitive position of European companies in global industries
such as electronics, chemical industries and automotive
manufacturing, to the comparative analysis of a number of merger
cases in retailing, media and defence industries. </i></b></p>
<hr>
<p>The London conference followed a workshop held in Berlin this
spring and was jointly organised by London Economics and the
German Institute for Economic Research (DIW) with sponsorship by
the Anglo-German Foundation*. </p>
<p>Debate focussed on three issues: </p>
<ul>
    <li>conflicts, actual or potential, between competition
        authorities and governments at the national level, and
        the role of the European Commission in this mix; </li>
    <li>conflicts, real or imagined, between competition policy
        at either the national or European level, and the global
        aspirations of multinational companies; </li>
    <li>characteristics of the media industries in particular,
        and the question as to how these should affect the
        application of competition policy in these industries. </li>
</ul>
<p><b>Contact: Tom Hoehn </b></p>
<hr>
