<head>
<title>Are Books Different?</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Are Books Different?</h2>
<p><b><i>Only two goods are exempted from the general ban in
Britain on resale price maintenance: books and medicaments. Last
year, however, the Publishers Association decided that it would
no longer try to enforce the Net Book Agreement, which prevented
retailers from competing with each other by discounting book
prices.</i></b> </p>
<hr>
<p>While the NBA remains gathering dust on the shelves, the
Office of Fair Trading is looming with duster and trash-can. The
Director of Fair Trading, John Bridgeman, made his views clear
last winter, in the OFT's own newsletter: &quot;In general, RPM
gives consumers a bad deal and I will pursue it vigorously
wherever I find it&quot;. But back in the 1960s, the Restrictive
Practices Court concluded in favour of a continued exemption for
books. If the NBA were abolished, the court believed, there would
be fewer and less-well-stocked bookshops; fewer titles published;
and they would in general be more expensive. </p>
<p>What has changed? According to the OFT, the publishing
industry has, to such an extent that the public interest
arguments of the 1960s can no longer be sustained. London
Economics has been developing an alternative set of arguments. </p>
<h4>Down with sales, up with prices</h4>
<p>Following the Restrictive Practices Court's line of reasoning
in 1962, we started by distinguishing between the effect of the
NBA on sales, and its effect on prices. The Court came to the
view that price-cutting would not be likely to increase book
sales significantly. Demand for books in general, and even for
one title in particular, was not particularly price-sensitive.
Total book sales were much more dependent on the number of
booksellers, the stocks and range of books they held. </p>
<p>By contrast, the demand for books at any particular retailer
was much more price-sensitive: if one bookshop discounted prices,
it would increase sales at the expense of others. </p>
<p>Without the NBA, popular or steady-selling titles would be
discounted, by one bookseller after another, starting with those
which did not themselves hold stocks (which, in those days, meant
the department stores). Retail margins generally would fall,
stockholding booksellers would lose trade, some of them would go
out of business altogether and others would reduce their range or
the quality of service provided. </p>
<p>The overall effect, deemed the Court, would be to reduce both
sales and the number of titles published. </p>
<p>The second argument on sales stemmed from the difficulty of
forecasting in advance which of a broad range of titles would be
successful. A squeeze on retail margins through price-cutting, it
was argued, would lead stockholding booksellers to act more
conservatively, focussing on the few sure-fire hits and denying
riskier titles the shelf-space needed to have a chance of
success. </p>
<p>The Court also concluded that book prices would be driven up
by abolition of the NBA. Print runs would be reduced, raising
unit costs: for example, a cut in the print run of a hardback
first edition from 3,000 to 2,000 would, it was estimated, raise
unit costs by 29 per cent. </p>
<h4>Have times changed?</h4>
<p>Today, the OFT believes that demand has become more sensitive
to price. Stockholding bookshops are much better placed to
compete with non-stockholders (notably, today, the supermarkets).
The growth of wholesaling and computerised stockholding allows
more frequent deliveries and reduced risk; so do sale-or-return
provisions. The implication is that price-cutting would have,
overall, a more positive effect on book sales. </p>
<p>The OFT has also argued that the cost penalty on smaller print
runs has been reduced by technological progress, eating into the
economies of scale. The implication is that prices would not be
driven up by the end of resale price maintenance. </p>
<p>Both conclusions are questionable. It is not at all clear that
book-buyers have become more price-sensitive: while books today
face greater competition from other media (which would tend to
make them more price-sensitive), people have become better off
(which tends to reduce their price-sensitivity on smaller
purchases like books). The balance of these effects needs to be
tested empirically, and the difficulty of comparing like with
like - no title is exactly like another - greatly complicates the
analysis. </p>
<p>This diversity lies behind another feature of the market which
has not changed: the fact that book sales depend greatly on their
sheer accessibility - the range on display, the ability to
browse, the quality of service. A recent study of the German book
industry found that an increase in retail margins - which permits
investment in retail service - actually resulted in a more than
proportionate increase in book sales. </p>
<p>The OFT view on unit costs is also highly debatable. While
production techniques have been transformed, there is still a
substantial cost penalty on short runs. Finally risk-sharing
techniques such as sale-and-return are expensive in terms of
transport and administration. Their growth would increase
industry costs and so prices. </p>
<p>It is too soon to reach conclusions on changes since the NBA
was put on the back shelf. Some initial reactions were highly
predictable. Supermarkets did indeed lead the way at Christmas,
discounting the most popular titles by 50 per cent or more;
bookshops followed suit, but did not feel able to discount as
much. Sales initially rose, though there is evidence suggesting
that this effect may now be evaporating; it is too early to say
whether a sufficient increase in volume will be sustained to
compensate for the reduction in retailers' margins. Strong
retailers are now trying to pass on the squeeze on margins,
demanding better terms from publishers, which puts the smaller
ones under pressure. </p>
<h4>A new approach</h4>
<p>It cannot simply be stated that resale price maintenance is
always anti-competitive and harmful to the consumer. Like various
other ways in which manufacturers seek to exert control over the
retailing of their products, it may in some circumstances be
employed for legitimate commercial purposes which are in the
interests of both producer and purchaser. </p>
<p>We believe that the impact of resale price maintenance on the
public interest should be assessed in the same way as the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission approaches other potential
cases of vertical restraint, such as failure to supply. This
involves a two-stage analysis. </p>
<p>The first step is to establish whether there is evidence of
market power at either the manufacturing or the retail level, and
whether this power is actually enhanced by the vertical restraint
in question: does it make collusion easier, or entry into the
market more difficult? Resale price maintenance obviously raises
the possibility of collusion, on which an investigation should
clearly focus. But this approach recognises that, if vertical
restraints are not purely directed at increasing market power,
they will be aimed at increasing sales, are likely to increase
public welfare and equally unlikely to raise any public interest
concerns. </p>
<p>But it is necessary to take a second step, and to test this
proposition in the market concerned: to ask whether higher sales
do indeed go hand in hand with increased consumer welfare. If the
desire to win extra sales results in vertical restraints which
encourage too much investment in retailer services, viewed from
the perspective of the average consumer, then the welfare
afterglow may be somewhat clouded. </p>
<p>So there are no easy answers, or even simple questions, in
this approach, either. But it is at least more clearly focussed.
Judging the effect on sales and prices is an extremely difficult
empirical process, involving a great deal of second-guessing of
the industry, even with the real-life experiment of the
abrogation of the NBA under way. And it hardly scratches the
surface of the underlying issues of competition, consumer welfare
and the protection of the public interest. </p>
<p><b>Contact: Zoltan Biro, Amelia Fletcher</b> </p>
<hr>
