<html>
<head>
<title>Shareholder Value</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Shareholder Value</h2>
<p><strong><i>Emphasis on the generation of shareholder value is
a current business fad. Its transatlantic origins are all too
obvious. The efforts of corporate raiders sent terror through
many American boardrooms in the mid 1980s. </i></strong></p>
<hr>
<p>It is no coincidence that the emphasis on the creation of
shareholder value in the annual report grew at very much the same
time. Now Michael Milken is in prison, Drexel Burnham Lambert is
in liquidation and the position of American managers is
strengthened by poisonpill defences and new legislative
enactment. The shareholder value movement has passed the crest of
its wave. </p>
<p>Business fashions come and go, but substantive issues remain.
Concern for shareholder value has struck a chord with managers of
many of the sprawling conglomerate businesses hastily put
together in the 1960s and 1970s. The emphasis on core businesses,
widespread in the 1980s, has been an important factor in
redressing the balance. </p>
<h4>Al Rapoport</h4>
<p>The guru of shareholder value is American business school
professor Al Rapoport. And when the packaging and the portentous
pronouncements from chief executives are stripped away, Rapoport
has two principal theses which every financially oriented manager
ought to consider. </p>
<p>One concerns his identification of the many ways in which
firms can improve their accounting numbers without strengthening
their underlying businesses. Some of these like the tricks that
surround merger accounting simply transfer profits from one
period or set of accounts to another. Others appear to improve
the company's performance by ignoring the opportunity value of
the company's capital. Reinvesting in projects yielding less than
the cost of equity capital, or buying businesses with a lower
priceearnings ratio, increase earnings per share, even if they
create no added value in the businesses concerned. </p>
<p>Rapoport's second thesis is his emphasis on cash flow as the
underlying source of all performance in the long run. There is
nothing very new here. Finance courses have been urging the use
of discounted cash flow techniques since business education
began. </p>
<p>The difficulties of actually applying these techniques in
circumstances where the most important elements in a cash flow
forecast are the subject of wide speculation are legion. But
there is no harm in being reminded of the primacy of cash flow
generation from time to time. </p>
<h4>The relevance of finance</h4>
<p>Yet there is a stronger message from shareholder value
analysis contradicts the inference of many managers. It is that
there are no clever ways of increasing shareholder value by
company reconstruction or through complex financing instruments
and structures. These arrangements, put together with spiralling
ingenuity in the 1980s, are coming unstuck. Every measure of
corporate performance rests on the strengths of the businesses
that create it. Without these strengths there is no shareholder
value in the long run. </p>
<p>Merton Miller was awarded the last Nobel prize for economics
for his contributions to the theory of corporate finance. The
Modigliani Miller theorem helped earn that accolade. It
demonstrates that the value of a business depends only on its
underlying earnings stream, and cannot be altered by changes in
financing. Such an insight would hardly deserve a Nobel prize had
not so many corporate financiers thought otherwise. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1991 </p>
</body>
</html>
