<html>
<head>
<title>Foundations of Corporate Success by John Kay</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Foundations of Corporate Success by John Kay</h2>
<p><i>Most people think that the uses of economics in business
are in understanding macroeconomic developments what will happen
to growth, inflation and the exchange rate or in handling public
policy issues dealing with competition policy or regulatory
agencies. In his new book &quot;Foundations for Corporate
Success&quot;, London Economics' Chairman, John Kay, explains how
economic analysis can contribute to an understanding of the
central strategic issues of the business. In this article, he
explains his approach.</i> </p>
<hr>
<p>The most successful management book of 1992 was <i>Liberation
Management</i>, by Tom Peters, the American management guru. With
its emphasis on 'marketising, fashionising, and &quot;glow!,
tingle!, wow!&quot;' it justifies its subtitle, &quot;Necessary
disorganisation for the nanosecond nineties&quot;. </p>
<p>Foundations to Corporate Success is different, both in theme
and in style. It contains no words which are not already in the
dictionary, and very few diagrams in which boxes are linked by
arrows whizzing back and forward. </p>
<p>Three themes are central to <i>Foundations of Corporate
Success </i>: </p>
<ul>
    <li>Corporate success is measured by 'added value'. </li>
    <li>Corporate success is based on distinctive capabilities. </li>
    <li>Corporate success owes much to stability and continuity
        of relationships within and outside the firm. </li>
</ul>
<h4>Added value</h4>
<p>This is the ability to reproduce &#163;1 of output for less
than &#163;1 of input. Europe's most successful firm of the 1980s
Glaxo did it for an average of 58p. That &#163;1 of output costs
Reuters 67p. But to produce &#163;1 of output cost Asda
&#163;1.02 and Philips &#163;1.07. </p>
<h4>Distinctive capabilities</h4>
<p>This is the ability to do things that others cannot reproduce
even when it becomes clear what they are. So there are no
recipes, no generic strategies for corporate success. Most
successful firms benefit from at least one of four primary
distinctive capabilities: innovation (Glaxo); reputation (Marks
&amp; Spencer); architecture a distinctive structure of
relationships (Benetton); or strategic assets licences,
regulation and related weapons (Cable &amp; Wireless). Sustained
success is not based on scale, vision, leadership, or market
position other firms with real distinctive capabilities can
acquire these. </p>
<h4>Stable relationships</h4>
<p>One of the key weaknesses of thinking in the 1980s and,
indeed, of 'necessary disorganisation in the nanosecond nineties'
is a failure to appreciate the role that stability and continuity
of relationships both within the firm and around it play in
corporate success. That is why architecture most effectively
illustrated by Liverpool Football Club is the most common (but
also the most elusive) source of corporate success. It is
especially important in markets where flexibility of response,
and honest flows of information, are important. Some business
environments like those of Japan are strongly supportive of that
type of architecture; others like the United States emphasise
individualism and encourage opportunism. Europe lies in between,
with Italy at one end of a spectrum and Britain at the other. </p>
<p>Analysis is unfashionable in corporate strategy at the moment.
&quot;Formulation is easy, it's implementation that's the
problem&quot; is the phrase of the moment. This is partly a
response to the phase in the 1960s and 1970s when companies
confused planning and strategy and prepared elaborate and
extensive corporate plans that had little impact on what they
actually did. But it is principally a reaction to a more recent
phase in which strategy is about conceiving visions and
formulating mission statements. If that's what strategy is, then
its obvious that it's implementation that's the problem, because
all the interesting and difficult questions of strategy have been
redefined as problems of implementation. &quot;Foundations&quot;
emphasises that strategy starts from where a company is, not from
where it would like to be, and in that context the distinction
between formulation and implementation largely falls away. </p>
<p>So success in business rests not on doing what others already
do well, but on doing those things they cannot do well. Many
distinctive capabilities, especially those based on architecture,
are the product of a particular historical environment and cannot
be reproduced in its absence. Creating distinctive capabilities
is necessarily difficult. Success is most often based on
maximising the value of those the firm already holds. This is as
true of the industrial policy of nations as the business policy
of companies. </p>
<p>John Kay email: <a href="mailto:john@londecon.co.uk">john@londecon.co.uk</a></p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1993 </p>
</body>
</html>
