<html>
<head>
<title>London Economics Goes Racing</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>London Economics Goes Racing</h2>
<p><i>Racing may be the &quot;sport of kings&quot; but it is also
an important British industry. That was the view we took when we
were asked by the Jockey Club which regulates British racing to
analyse the economic issues involved. </i></p>
<hr>
<p>Like other businesses, racing has a variety of customers
spectators who attend raceday meetings, radio and television
services which broadcast its events, sponsors who put prize money
into races and find racegoing a useful form of corporate
hospitality. And then there is the offcourse betting industry.
About three quarters of betting shop turnover is on horse racing,
and without racing's lists of runners, announcement of results,
and public confidence that racing was run honestly, none of this
would exist. </p>
<p>Yet racing loses money. These sources of revenue only cover
half of racing costs. Raceday revenues are the most important
source of income, but betting contributes through the Horserace
Betting Levy, administered by a Board, established in 1960 to
raise revenue for the racing industry. The deficit is covered by
the losses made by breeders and trainers, by racecourses and
principally owners of racehorses. </p>
<h4>Changes in racing</h4>
<p>Most industries, faced with losses of this magnitude, would
soon contract and disappear. Certainly there are signs of this in
British racing the number of young horses in training has fallen
sharply. Yet an analysis of the racing industry twenty or fifty
years ago, would still have shown that the industry was
unprofitable. Racing continues because it is an exciting sport,
and few of those who take part in it are motivated by commercial
criteria alone. </p>
<p>But that does not mean that there is no limit to the losses
that racing might incur, or that it does not need to be run on a
commercial basis. Our model analyses the financial flows into and
out of the racing industry, and shows how they respond to
different variables like changes in the economic environment or
changes in the fixture list. In this way we apply to racing
precisely the techniques we use in other industries. </p>
<p>The model is proving a key element in racing's case for
negotiating a higher price for the product from one of its
principal customers the betting industry. The Home Affairs Select
Committee supported this case in its report to Parliament earlier
this year. The argument will be developed in negotiation over the
determination of a new levy. </p>
<p>Our team found the field work particularly enjoyable: visiting
trainers, betting shops, and racecourses. LE rose to the
challenge of the work on every front save one. In spite of the
hours spent in an unheated betting shop and the complex analogies
to financial markets, LE's highly efficient information
processing capabilities failed in the final test: we picked only
the odd stray winner! </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1991 </p>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT11-B06-77</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA036-000712-B014-18</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.londecon.co.uk:80/pubs/internat/prioriti.htm 194.193.150.111 19970111013716 text/html 3364
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 11 Jan 1997 01:32:11 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 3193
Last-modified: Sat, 14 Sep 1996 15:05:33 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Developing Priorities</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Developing Priorities</h2>
<p><i>Can the developing countries of the world modernise their
economies without catastrophic environmental side effects?
Analysis by London Economics suggests that, if electricity
generation is planned sensibly, it should be possible.</i></p>
<hr>
<p>In their quest for development, the developing nations will
greatly increase their electricity consumption. Many plan to
double their generating capacity over the next ten years. What
will this do to global warming and local environments? </p>
<p>Electricity generation can pose a real threat to the
environment. At the local level fly ash from coal plant chimneys
can damage public health. All the other ash, stored on site, can
pollute ground water. At the regional level, SO2 from coal and
oil plant, and NOX from plant with older boilers, can damage
public health, agriculture and forestry. And at the global level,
CO2 emissions account for over half the gases implicated in
global warming. </p>
<p>Nonfossil generation is not without environmental sideeffects.
Hydroelectric generation uses vast tracts of land, and dislocates
entire communities. Biomass, growing forests for burning in power
stations, also eats up land. And nuclear power is fraught with
difficulties, particularly in developing countries. </p>
<h4>Who pays?</h4>
<p>The industrialised nations have enjoyed growth and polluted
freely since 1750. So why should the developing countries now pay
for higher environmental standards? They will set their own
priorities. They will focus on local rather than global problems. </p>
<p>A balanced investment plan is therefore essential. Neglect of
the transmission and distribution networks simply increases
losses and prevents efficient use of installed capacity, however
much new plant is built. An effective transmission network can
keep polluting generation away from areas where the emissions
cause most damage cities, forestry and farming regions. </p>
<p>Aim for relative, rather than absolute, standards of security
of supply. It may be economically efficient to have power
shortages where the consumer does not value the lost load very
highly. Analytical models, such as London Economics', can help to
guide developing countries to realistic goals. They can identify: </p>
<ul>
    <li>least cost ways to operate power systems given
        environmental targets; </li>
    <li>least cost ways to expand power systems, to meet growing
        demand and long term environmental standards; and </li>
    <li>policies that will achieve environmental objectives
        without costly enforcement or regulation. </li>
</ul>
<p>Our analysis provides a basis for a rational assessment of
environmental priorities. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Back to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1991 </p>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
