<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Markets not Hierarchies</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Markets not Hierarchies</h2>
<p><i>It's a good time for microeconomists. Market analysis is
their specialisation and new markets are springing up everywhere.
The most dramatic change is in Eastern Europe, where the creation
of a stock market seems a priority second only to the evolution
of an electoral system. </i></p>
<hr>
<p>In Britain, new markets have been created in health, in
education, in electricity, and in the environment. London
Economics is involved in all of these. </p>
<p>Although these marketrelated reforms all look very different,
they share several key elements. Each involves replacing
hierarchical dealings where one party tells the other what to do
with negotiable contracts. Most people think a contract is
drafted by lawyers and bound in pink tape. But there are many
kinds of contract. </p>
<p>In every longterm contract there are three key economic
questions. What incentives does the contact offer for each party?
How does it influence the allocation of risk between them? And
what is the contract price? </p>
<p>Take the new electricity market, for example. The price of
electricity in every half hour period is fixed in a series of
spot contracts, whose outcome is reported in the national daily
newspapers. The objective is to give each generator incentives
both to cut costs and to offer power to the national grid at a
price which reflects his own costs of supply. And if there were
many generators, the system would do exactly that. Yet two firms
dominate the pool, so each has an incentive to manage contract
offers strategically. The pool is surrounded by longerterm
contracts allocating risks between the different parties.
Securing the least cost risk allocation demands sophisticated
modelling of the relationship between these contracts and of all
the other contracts which a regional electricity company holds.
And that combination of incentives and risk allocation underlines
the price that each party to the contract will be ready to pay. </p>
<p>The same issues incentives, risks and price arise in every
other new market. The new internal market in health care is
designed to encourage health authorities to keep costs down and
to choose between alternative providers of treatment. Yet
contracting exposes both authorities and hospitals to risks the
incidence of illness is every bit as uncertain as the demand for
electricity. As the market develops, the health business, like
the electricity business, will have to learn techniques of
portfolio optimisation previously used mainly in financial
markets. The price of health care services will be determined in
the light of the relative costs which the new structures reveal,
and the set of contracts which match public needs with available
resources. </p>
<p>So too in education and environment, where incentives, risk
allocation and price figure increasingly as resource allocation
responds to market mechanisms. They are new terms for
professionals in these areas but they must grasp them. In this
newsletter, we describe some of the ways in which this can be
done. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
</body>
</html>
