<html>
<head>
<title>Freeing the Jamaican Dollar?</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Freeing the Jamaican Dollar?</h2>
<p><i>A current theme in Eastern Europe is
&quot;Liberalisation&quot; of prices, trade, and capital
movements. A contentious aspect of liberalisation is its
&quot;sequencing&quot;: should liberalisation of the domestic
economy precede the liberalisation of trade and capital flows, or
should all reforms be carried through at one gulp (&quot;shock
therapy&quot;, Polish style)?</i></p>
<hr>
<p>This issue has been a live one for the management of
developing countries for some time. How do they control rampant
inflation and manage weak balance of payments positions, while
keeping electorates happy? Controls are the conventional
response, but they stifle growth. Liberalisation encourages
growth, but carries the risk of going wildly out of control,
leading to massive devaluation, accelerating inflation, and civil
unrest. </p>
<p>London Economics was recently asked to look at Jamaica's
exchange controls. Lurking behind the exotic charm of Jamaica
lies a history of failure of economic management. Over the period
197388, developing countries as a whole raised their GDP by over
80%, yet Jamaica's fell by 10%. </p>
<p>Like most countries in the developing world, Jamaica operates
exchange controls. Many experts would support this policy. The
arguments are finely balanced. On the one hand, Jamaica is a
small open economy relying heavily on imports for capital
equipment, energy and food. All these deserve priority over the
acquisition of real estate and equities overseas. Capital flight
would destabilise the currency, and fuel inflation. The
depreciation which would probably accompany the abolition of
controls would depress national income. On the other hand,
exchange controls sustain an overvalued exchange rate, taxing
those industries which export, or which compete with imports,
providing investors with a one way bet against their currency.
They discourage much needed foreign investment, as investors fear
that they could not repatriate their capital. </p>
<p>We modelled the Jamaican economy, to simulate how it would
behave if exchange controls were liberalised. Our model suggested
that the economy was not sufficiently responsive to price signals
to respond to a devaluation; and that even if real investment did
result from liberalisation, this would not have much effect on
economic growth. Capital liberalisation would not work if the
domestic economy is unresponsive. </p>
<p>So we suggested that the priority was to make the economy more
responsive to price signals of all kinds. The Government should
press on with its deregulation programme. </p>
<p>Since completing our report, in March 1991, the Jamaican
dollar has depreciated sharply, even without exchange rate
liberalisation. Despite exchange controls, many Jamaicans appear
to have arranged their own &quot;liberalisation&quot;. Large
capital assets are reputedly held overseas by Jamaican residents. </p>
<p>This underlines one of the conclusions of the study,
concerning the vulnerability of the exchange rate. A policy
dilemma for the authorities is whether to perservere with capital
controls when they lack the means or the will to enforce them
fully. Such a policy may combine the worst of both worlds. The
controls distort the economy, but because they are not fully
effective, high interest rates are necessary to retain funds in
Jamaica. These high rates discourage real investment. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
</body>
</html>
