<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Eastern Approaches</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Eastern Approaches</h2>
<p><i>Western consultants rarely visited Eastern Europe and the
Former Soviet Union until recently. Now these countries are a
growth area for consultants. </i></p>
<hr>
<p>The reasons are familiar. A political desire to assist (and
stabilise) countries close to Western Europe has been translated
into a high level of consultancy funding. Advisory inputs are
seen as an appropriate way of transferring technology, while
avoiding the dependency that has been created in some aid
recipients in the developing world. </p>
<p>London Economics has been one beneficiary of this approach,
with contracts under way or about to start in Lithuania,
Bulgaria, Poland, Kazakhstan, Belarus and Russia. Most of our
assignments are to do with our international utility work, in
energy and water. Are there any threads which tie together a
diverse group of studies in a diverse group of countries? </p>
<h4>Energy costs</h4>
<p>One common theme is pricing. Prices have come to be seen as a
problem for various reasons. The real resource cost of energy
coming out of Russia has risen sharply, and there are problems in
paying the new bills. Utilities are required to become more
autonomous and financially viable, although they have not
generally featured in the first wave of privatization. And as the
real resource costs of energy have become more apparent, it has
also become clearer how inefficiently energy is being used. </p>
<p>A number of London Economics consultants have found some truth
in the old story that room temperatures in Eastern Europe are
regulated by opening the window. That impression can be made more
precise. In Bulgaria, for example, household energy use per m2
per degree day is 75% above the average in Sweden, and 3.5 times
the average achieved by the new housing stock in Sweden. </p>
<p>Countries have responded in a variety of ways. In some cases
prices have been deregulated, and set by market forces. This is
possible for energy sources such as coal or petroleum products
that can to some extent be transported, even given the
infrastructure problems. It is not an option for the natural
monopolies such as power transmission, district heating or water
distribution. </p>
<h4>Rate of return regulation</h4>
<p>Another approach, adopted by a number of countries, is to move
to some form of regulation for utilities operating natural
monopolies. For example, in some countries a crude form of rate
of return regulation has been applied to the utility. The
rationale for rate of return regulation is that price should be
such that utilities are allowed a fair rate of return on capital. </p>
<p>The problems with this are well known. A fair rate needs to be
determined. This creates periodic arguments in Western countries.
It creates a new set of problems in countries with very
undeveloped capital markets. </p>
<p>The measure of the capital base also needs to be decided, and
the capital base appropriately valued. In some East European
utilities, ownership of the capital base is not yet clear. The
value of the capital base is even less clear. Asset registers
often exist, and in some cases some revaluation exercises have
been attempted. Because of the scale of the problem, these have
tended to be very general exercises. Lithuania, for example,
recently revalued the asset base by a factor of 35, depending on
the year of construction. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Back to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1993 </p>
</body>
