<html>
<head>
<title>The `New' EBRD</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>The `New' EBRD</h2>
<p><strong><i>Our leading article is an interview with Nick
Stern, a founder member of London Economics, who took over as
Chief Economist at the European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development a year ago. He talks to Bill Robinson about the work
of the Bank, following the replacement of Jacques Attali by
Jacques de Larosi&egrave;re as its President.</i></strong></p>
<hr>
<p><b>You were hired by Attali, but never worked for him. What is
life like in the new regime?</b> </p>
<p>M. de Larosi&egrave;re came to us with a formidable
reputation. He had guided the IMF through a turbulent period when
it was rocked by the Third World debt crisis, and as Governor of
the Bank of France, implemented the franc fort policy which
brought French inflation below the German rate. His first act was
to reorganise the administration of the Bank, and bring together
the development and merchant banking sides of our business. Our
priorities were reviewed and reformulated, emphasising our role
in financing private sector activities, and our willingness to
take an equity share in projects. And the culture of an
organisation which had acquired an unfortunate reputation for
extravagance has changed. Staff numbers have been very tightly
controlled, the smart dining rooms have been closed, and we all
fly economy class these days. </p>
<p><b>You mention bringing together the development and merchant
banking sides of the business. What is the business of the EBRD? </b></p>
<p>We are a regional bank, devoted to the 25 countries of Eastern
Europe and the former Soviet Union. Our mission is &quot;to
foster the transition towards open marketoriented economies, and
to promote private and entrepreneurial initiatives&quot;. We do
that largely by providing <i>project</i> finance for investment
in the <i>private </i>sector, and we are very flexible in
straddling the public private divide. </p>
<p><b>Isn't that the sort of thing the World Bank and the IMF do?
Why do we need yet another international lending organisation? </b></p>
<p>We play a completely different role from the IMF, whose
mission is to promote sound macroeconomic management. It goes in
for fastdisbursing loans, typically made to tide countries over
their balance of payments difficulties, and conditional on their
meeting the IMF's recommendations on the conduct of macroeconomic
policy. The World Bank also makes its Structural Adjustment
Loans, which are fast disbursing and with policy conditions, but
is more like us in the sense of being also in the business of
project finance. However, it mainly concentrates on large
infrastructure projects within the public sector. It is our focus
on the private sector that is unique. We were in danger of losing
that focus when the development and merchant banking arms were
separated, which is why it was so important to bring them
together. </p>
<p><b>There has been a lot in the press in recent years about the
proper roles of the IMF and World Bank. Doesn't this cast doubt
on EBRD's future?</b> </p>
<p>Not at all. The IMF and World Bank are now having to redefine
their roles because they were set up in the mid1940s, when the
experience of a wartime command economy, which had delivered
victory and full employment, contrasted favourably with mass
unemployment of the 1930s. So the architects designed a framework
for development which was distinctly <i>dirigiste</i>. </p>
<p>Forty years later, it has become apparent that the command
economies behind the Iron Curtain were not very successful in
generating growth. And the performance of the more
tightlycontrolled developing economies has generally been
unimpressive. Development economists are increasingly embracing
the market. You see that in everything written by the World Bank.
Yet it remains an organisation which analyses and finances large
public sector projects. The EBRD, by contrast, is a child of its
time, created to deal with the special problems of command
economies making the transition to market economics, and
specialising in making loans to the private sector. </p>
<p><b>But if you mainly finance private sector projects, what
distinguishes you from an ordinary commercial bank? </b></p>
<p>Our distinctive contribution lies in the combination of our
expertise and our willingness to take risks. We have the
resources to analyse projects in areas of activity, and in
countries, that commercial banks would be reluctant to consider.
But where we lead, they often follow. Our presence is a large
comfort factor encouraging other lenders, not least because once
a project or sector has the EBRD `seal of approval', the
political risk for other lenders is reduced. </p>
<p><b>How much money do you have, where does it come from, and
where do you spend it?</b> </p>
<p>We have authorised and subscribed capital of 10 billion Ecu.
This represents a commitment from our members of which 3 billion
Ecu must be 'paid in' and the rest is 'callable'. Our capital is
subscribed by 59 members, which include the European Union
countries, the United States and Japan. We spend it in all 25
countries of Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union. </p>
<p><b>A `paidin' capital of 3 billion Ecu a stock not a flow is
not a great deal to spread over 25 countries. Can you really
achieve anything?</b> </p>
<p>Yes, because this `paidin' capital serves as seedcorn. That
capital gives us the resources to undertake the analysis of areas
which the commercial banks cannot afford to look at. Further, our
power to support projects is based on our access to the world
capital markets, where we are able to borrow on favourable terms
against the guarantee of our 'callable' capital. </p>
<p>The EBRD enjoys a triple A rating. We can borrow at nearly
&lt;$E1/2&gt; per cent below LIBOR. We lend on at anything from 1
per cent above LIBOR for a government project to 4 per cent above
for more risky projects in the private sector. This in turn pays
our bills, and funds the less profitable activities we undertake
in pursuit of our mission. </p>
<p><b>Could our clients approach you for a loan in the same way
they might approach their bank?</b> </p>
<p>Projects have to be a certain size. We would be reluctant to
look at loans under 4 million Ecu. In that respect, we are more
like a merchant bank than a clearer. But we do have a major
commitment to financial intermediaries (absorbing about one third
of our loans) which lend to much smaller projects. So in that way
we help to get small projects off the ground as well as large
ones. </p>
<p><b>Do you assess projects in exactly the same way as a
commercial bank?</b> </p>
<p>Not quite. We have a broader remit. We look beyond the purely
financial returns to the longerterm economic and social returns.
We have to consider the environmental impact. And, of course,
given our mission to promote market economics, we are very
concerned about the impact of our projects on market structure
and entry conditions. </p>
<p><b>In which countries do you do most business?</b> </p>
<p>There is a steady stream of business in the Eastern European
countries that are already making rapid progress towards a market
economy the Czech and Slovak Republics, Hungary, Poland,
Slovenia, the Baltic States. If we were profit maximisers, we
would probably focus exclusively on those countries. But we are
not. In pursuit of our mission to foster transition we make a
special effort to support projects in those countries of which
some people may be only vaguely aware, such as Turkmenistan or
Uzbekistan. </p>
<p><b>How many staff do you have for these appraisals? What role
do the economists play?</b> </p>
<p>The Bank has a total staff of around 800, with some 400500
professionals. My own economics unit examines the economics of
each project (over 100 per year); works on country and sector
strategies; provides the basic information on each of the
countries we deal with; assesses country risk; helps the Bank
think about its overall lending strategy; produces the Transition
Report (the first of which came out in October 1994 and will be
an annual event) and even finds time to do a bit of research and
all with a staff of 12 people, plus myself. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1995 </p>
</body>
</html>
