<html>
<head>
<title>Water resources in Gaza</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Water resources in Gaza</h2>
<p><b><i>In October 1995, London Economics was invited to
participate in a World Bank mission to the Gaza Strip to advise
the Palestinian Authority on options for upgrading the water and
wastewater system. The mission was in response to an urgent
personal appeal for help from Yasser Arafat to the President of
the World Bank.</i></b></p>
<hr>
<p>A 40 km by 10 km strip of land on the Mediterranean coast,
where Israel meets the Sinai Peninsula, has had one of the most
troubled histories of the 20th century. Under the peace agreement
between the PLO and Israel, day-to-day administration of the Gaza
Strip was transferred to a civilian Palestinian Authority early
in 1995. Water resources were one of the most urgent political
and economic issues confronting the new authority. </p>
<p>In 1948 Gaza had a population of 80,000. Today that population
has swollen to one million, making it one of the most densely
populated territories on Earth. One-third of this population live
in UN-run refugee camps. </p>
<p>This population explosion has led to great difficulties with
water resources. Current water consumption is estimated at 120
million cubic metres per annum, of which three-quarters goes for
agricultural use. To meet this demand, Gaza's principal resource
is a shallow aquifer which recharges at approximately 60 million
cubic metres per year. As a result, the level of the water table
is falling rapidly, with ground water becoming increasingly
saline and polluted with nitrates. </p>
<p>Many regions of Gaza simply cannot produce enough water from
their own wells to supply their local population, and therefore
have to buy water in bulk from Mekoroth, the Israeli water
company. The only other foreseeable source of new water for Gaza
is from desalination, which would be prohibitively expensive. </p>
<p>Water problems have a direct effect on the quality of life for
the Gazans, and also on the economic prospects of the Strip. The
water shortage affects the quality of agricultural output,
reducing the scope of export earnings. It also reduces the scope
for the development of water-using industrial processes and has a
severe impact on the construction sector. </p>
<p>The troubled political history of the area has resulted in
neglect of the water and wastewater infrastructure. The water
distribution system is in a poor state with high levels of
leakage and intermittent supplies. Treatment of water, even
simple chlorination, is inadequate, often not occurring at all,
due to a lack of funds to buy chemicals. Most well-head meters
are not functioning, while a high proportion of customer meters
are either not working or are not read regularly. </p>
<h4>Losses and leaks</h4>
<p>In addition, there are a significant number of illegal
connections to the system, resulting in major losses. As a
result, estimates of production and consumption are extremely
unreliable, while incentives to conserve water are virtually
absent. On the wastewater side, only 25% of the population is
connected to a sewerage system, with the rest being served by
septic tanks. In many cases these are leaking, polluting the
underlying aquifer. </p>
<p>Water and wastewater services are provided by the
municipalities and village councils that make up the civil
administration of the Strip. There is no proper accounting
separation of the water departments. Revenues collected go into a
central local government fund, with no link to the amounts which
can then be spent on operations and investment. To add to these
problems, over 30% of revenue remains uncollected. </p>
<p>The World Bank Mission reviewed the options available to the
Palestinian Authority, identifying priority investments that were
needed to upgrade the system. It recommended a four-year
management contract to bring in a private sector contractor to
upgrade water and wastewater infrastructure, to bring together
the sector in a coherent single operation under the joint
ownership of the Municipalities and Village Councils, to improve
revenue collection and to reduce losses from illegal connections.
The choice of a management contract rather than a more long-term
arrangement such as a concession or lease arrangement was
strongly influenced by the existing political uncertainties in
the region. </p>
<p>LE provided an economic and financial appraisal of these
proposals, assessing the potential benefits of the management
contract in terms of its impact on water conservation, quality
and the potential for increased economic growth. </p>
<h4>Costs and benefits</h4>
<p>A key question in this appraisal was the extent to which the
sector would be able to retain the benefits resulting from the
successful completion of the contract. Clearly, the benefit of
the investment would be much reduced if the sector were
subsequently unable to maintain the network adequately, allowing
it to fall back into disrepair. </p>
<p>LE conducted the first tariff study in Gaza. This concluded
that while the balance of tariffs between water and wastewater
services was skewed, with wastewater tariffs well below costs,
existing water tariffs were more than adequate to cover current
operating expenditures and make a significant contribution
towards investment. This highlighted the importance of successful
revenue collection and accounting separation in providing the
management of the sector with the resources to maintain their
system in good working order once the immediate improvements of
the management contract had been completed. </p>
<p><b>Contact: </b><a href="mailto:dan@londecon.co.uk"><b>Dan
Elliott</b> </a></p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1996 </p>
</body>
</html>
