<html>
<head>
<title>Marketing a Degree?</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Marketing a Degree?</h2>
<p><i>The first successful &quot;market&quot; in higher education
was introduced in 1990 by the Polytechnics and Colleges Funding
Council (PCFC), responsible for allocating government funds to 84
polytechnics and colleges. The new market was created to expand
the number of students in the sector at minimum cost: the PCFC is
successfully funding 16% more places each year, with reductions
in unit costs. </i></p>
<hr>
<p>London Economics analysed this market, comparing the
theoretically expected outcome with the objectives of the PCFC,
and what happened in practise. </p>
<p>The Universities Funding Council (UFC), the equivalent of the
PCFC for universities, had attempted to force universities to bid
for funds, but failed at the first hurdle. The universities
clubbed together and all bid at the guide price which the UFC had
set for the different subject areas. The project was abandoned. </p>
<p>The relative success of these two attempts to introduce a
market where none previously existed highlights the importance of
risk and incentives in the structure of new markets. The
universities were bidding for their entire funds in each subject
area. By contrast, polytechnics and colleges were required to bid
for only a small proportion of funds in each subject area. They
were assured the majority of their historic funding. The risk of
failure in competing was correspondingly lower. Polytechnics and
colleges have indeed bid competitively in the first years of the
new market, leading to a rapid increase in student numbers at
ever lower unit cost. </p>
<h4>Wages in the Single Market</h4>
<p>Will the European single market lead to convergence in wage
levels across the Community? As European consumers move towards
paying in ecus for their Euro-lager or their Euro-holidays int he
Alps or the Mediterranean, will they all be earning Euro-wages?
This subject is dealth with by Douglas McWilliams of LE-MES in a
book published by London Economics in January 1992. </p>
<p>So the PCFC market is achieving its main aim: to reduce the
price it pays institutions for providing education, by balancing
incentives and the associated risk. The new market is, however,
intended to provide other incentives. Quality is an important
element of the supply of education. In electricity, one kilowatt
is very much like another: quality is irrelevant. So a new market
only needs to give suppliers incentives to provide kilowatts as
cheaply as possible. The PCFC incorporated an element in the new
market which rewards higher quality suppliers with more funds,
providing the necessary incentive to maintain or raise quality. </p>
<p>The PCFC bidding system is very much a &quot;partial&quot;
market; it is also interesting in that, unlike contracts for
consumer goods or electricity, competition results in a number of
different prices. With bidding in 9 programme areas and for 3
types of students (Fulltime, Parttime and Sandwich) the market
yields several hundred prices. </p>
<p>One question remains: does even a partial market in the UK
provide the right incentives to suppliers of higher education? At
present there is clearly demand for more places than can be
supplied within the PCFC and UFC budgets. In the US, higher
education is bought and sold in a free market. Institutions have
the incentive to expand to meet excess demand. But individuals in
the US pay far more for their education than in the UK, funded by
borrowing money, usually from commercial banks. </p>
<p>The PCFC bidding system shows that the desirable incentives
created in a normal market can be introduced effectively by a
partial opening up of the market to competition. Indeed, the
experience of the UFC suggests that this may well be the only
solution within the context of UK higher education as it stands. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
