HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 11 Jan 1997 01:35:17 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 6946
Last-modified: Wed, 04 Sep 1996 17:41:12 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Paying for Higher Education</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Paying for Higher Education</h2>
<p><strong><i>Who should pay for higher education? And why? These
questions became prominent recently when the Committee of
ViceChancellors and Principals (CVCP) met to discuss possible
ways to increase the amount of funding allocated to higher
education. </i></strong></p>
<hr>
<p>At present, 28% of school leavers go to university. This
proportion has doubled since 1987, as the polytechnics have
become universities. The government plans for growth to continue,
to reach 1 in 3 by the year 2000. The &#163;5bn cost of tuition
is met by the Department for Education, and, ultimately, the
taxpayer. </p>
<p>The growth in student numbers, and the current squeeze on
public spending, has led universities to look for new sources of
funding for higher education. One obvious potential source is the
consumers themselves, students. But should students pay for
higher education? </p>
<h4>Return on investment</h4>
<p>From the point of view of the individual, going to university
can be seen as an investment (see chart). The student forgoes
three years of working income (shaded area A) in return for a
stream of income in the future which is higher as a result of
(hopefully) obtaining a degree (shaded area B). There may also be
benefits in terms of higher quality of life from being better
educated. The years at university may themselves be a pleasurable
experience. Leaving these considerations to one side, the return
on the financial investment can be calculated. Most studies show
that the returns are good: as high as 25%. </p>
<p>This prompts two questions: why don't more school leavers go
to university? And why should students not pay for all their
tuition, if the benefits are so great? The answer to the first
question is straightforward: there aren't enough places. Supply
is constrained by the size of the government budget. If supply
were free, more students would attend university. There would
then be more graduates, graduate salaries would fall, and so
would the return, until it was closer to the market return on
financial investment. Few school leavers carry out this
calculation when choosing whether to go to university, so they
are not aware of the benefits (do you know anyone who did?). </p>
<h4>Who benefits?</h4>
<p>It is not only students who benefit from their investment in
university education. The productivity of people who work with
university graduates may be increased by the greater expertise of
the latter. And society at large may value better educated
citizens. Since society at large benefits from the individual's
higher education, society should contribute to the cost. However,
it is hard to say how the cost should be divided. Noone has
derived an empirical basis for the split. </p>
<p>Do students already pay towards the cost of higher education
when they graduate, because they pay more income tax than they
would without a degree? A degree generally leads to higher
income, and higher taxes. But rich people who did not go to
university also pay high taxes. General taxation should not
therefore be seen as payment by graduates for higher education. </p>
<h4>Graduate loan</h4>
<p>How can students contribute some of the cost? What might the
effects be? One scheme which has received much attention involves
paying for higher education after graduation. Students take out a
loan while they study. This might be of the order of &#163;1,000
for each year. The capital could be provided by the government,
or the private sector, as with the existing student loan scheme.
After the course, graduates pay back around 3% of their income
each year through the tax or national insurance systems until the
loan is paid off, as long as their income in that year tops a
certain minimum threshold. The interest rate on the loan could be
anything between zero and the market rate of interest. Such a
scheme started in Australia in 1989; so far it seems successful. </p>
<p>London Economics has modelled the effects of a similar scheme
on the financial return for students from higher education. Loans
typically take about 8 years to pay back, longer if graduates
experience a period out of the workforce soon after graduation.
The extra cost to the student has little impact on the return,
partly because repayments are small in comparison with the
earnings differentials between graduates and nongraduates, and
partly because payments are deferred to the future. The effect of
such a scheme on demand for higher education should therefore be
minimal, and this seems to be borne out by the experience in
Australia to date. </p>
<h4>Repayments</h4>
<p>By setting the payment threshold high enough, worries about
affording payments can be assuaged. If a graduate's income never
rises above this level, he or she ends up paying nothing. The
repayment is related to the graduate's actual financial benefit.
The level of interest on the loans is also important. Our model
showed that real interest rates of the order of 5% could
dramatically increase the total repayment of a graduate who
cannot repay for a number of years following graduation, because
of the build up of interest over this period. </p>
<p>This problem can be reduced, however, by subsidising the loans
through a low, or zero, real interest rate. The longer repayment
is deferred, the greater the subsidy. This should comfort those
who fear difficulties in repaying. However, experience from other
countries shows that some students do not understand that low
interest rates are a subsidy. </p>
<p>The number of parttime and mature students in higher education
is increasing. They already make up a third of the student body.
For these students, the rate of return to higher education is
lower, since they enjoy fewer years of higher income when they
graduate. For them, the impact of the scheme on the rate of
return could be considerable, unless the payment threshold is set
at a high enough level. </p>
<h4>The way forward</h4>
<p>Some of the university student bodies in the UK think that
taking some of the purchasing power out of the hands of the
government will allow expansion of the higher education sector.
There will of course always be anomalies: a future Mick Jagger
might ask why he should pay for a course at the London School of
Economics, as it did not contribute to his higher subsequent
earnings. But then, satisfaction can never be guaranteed. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1994 </p>
</body>
