<html>
<head>
<title>Least Cost Nitrate Control</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Least Cost Nitrate Control</h2>
<p><i>Over onethird of the land area of England and Wales has
excessive levels of nitrates in water supplies. This is according
to limits set by a draft 1988 European Directive on nitrates in
fresh, coastal and marine water. An earlier (1980) Directive
already imposes strict limits to drinking water content, which
the UK has yet to meet. </i></p>
<hr>
<p>Rainwater, effluent, decaying plants and farming are all
sources of nitrates. Farming is the largest source. Arable crops
and grassland release (or &quot;leach&quot;) nitrate. The amount
depends on the crop, the rainfall, and the method of farming.
East Anglia and the East Midlands are the areas most affected. </p>
<h4>The environmental tradeoff</h4>
<p>All environmental policies involve changing economic
behaviour, which has costs like higher unemployment, the decline
of rural communities and possible bankruptcies. The trick is to
make sure that these costs are more than outweighed by the
benefits. In the case of nitrates, this costbenefit calculation
is very complicated. </p>
<p>Nitrate levels in water supplies are the result of complex
interactions between climate, geology, crop patterns and farming
methods. London Economics has sought to understand each component
with the aid of: </p>
<ul>
    <li>a water model tracing the flows into, through, and out of
        each of the 114 40 x 40 kilometre squares into which
        England and Wales is divided for meteorological analysis
        (MORECS squares). It takes account of the geology and
        hydrological gradients of each square; </li>
    <li>a database of 567 farms which simulates variations in
        farming practice by region, type, size and ownership
        structure; </li>
    <li>data on the rate at which each crop leaches nitrogen into
        the soil. </li>
</ul>
<p>All these elements are then brought together into a model of
the environment. </p>
<p>The model can: </p>
<ul>
    <li>predict how rapidly different policies to reduce nitrogen
        applications reduce nitrate concentrations in water
        supplies; </li>
    <li>estimate the economic effect of such policies on farming; </li>
    <li>compare the costs of complying with the Directive by two
        different means: water treatment and changes in land use,
        farm practice, and the use of nitrogen fertilisers. </li>
</ul>
<h4>Least cost solutions</h4>
<p><b><i>A farming solution</i></b>, involving switching from
arable crops to woodland or to rough grazing, would require the
cessation of profitable agriculture in much of East Anglia. The
overall cost, when knockon effects through the economy are
counted, would exceed &#163;500 million. </p>
<p>An obvious solution is to ban or reduce fertiliser usage. This
could prove disastrous. Modern seed varieties are designed to use
specific amounts of nitrate; variations in fertiliser application
can have dramatic effects on yields. Livestock farming requires
nitrate to grow the grass on which animals feed; lower
application rates imply lower stocking densities. </p>
<p>And this proposal overlooks an important feature of the
nitrate problem: the areas in which farmers apply most nitrogen
happen to lie on chalk. Water percolates very slowly through
chalk, so the aquifers in these regions have accumulated nitrogen
over decades. Outlaw nitrogen fertilisers now, and there will be
no speedy results in these areas. Nitrate levels in ground water
supply here will only reduce over many years. </p>
<p><b><i>The water treatment solution</i></b> would cost at most
&#163;100 million a year in the UK (at 1990 prices). The
leastcost solution for the eastern arable areas lies in water
treatment, not in drastic changes in farming practice. Curative
solutions include water storage (to facilitate denitrification),
blending, and treatment. </p>
<h4>A change of policy?</h4>
<p>London Economics' analysis suggests that: </p>
<ul>
    <li>&quot;Prevention is better than cure&quot; is not always
        good environmental economics. The marginal productivity
        of modern fertilisers means it can be more efficient to
        fertilise and treat water supplies than to ban
        fertilisers; </li>
    <li>the optimal solution needs to be quite subtle changes in
        land use, changes in farm practice, and water treatment
        all have a role, but their relative merit depends on
        local geology and farming practice; </li>
    <li>a tax, or levy, on fertiliser would be ineffective
        because fertiliser demand is insensitive to price; yields
        are also in many cases sensitive to fertiliser
        application. </li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1991 </p>
</body>
