<html>
<head>
<title>Using the Market to Control Acid Rain?</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Using the Market to Control Acid Rain?</h2>
<p><strong><i>Governments seeking to control emissions have a
basic choice: direct the major power plant operators' actions, or
leave control to the market. Most governments prefer a
&quot;command-and-control&quot; approach. Our report suggests
market mechanisms can be used to meet the UK's emission target at
a lower resource cost.</i></strong></p>
<hr>
<p>The European Community's Large Combustion Plant Directive
requires the UK to reduce SO2 emissions by 60% below its 1990
baseline. SO2 emissions can be reduced in different ways - by
reducing the sulphur in fuels by switching to lower sulphur coal
or to gas, or by removing SO2 from the exhaust gases. There are
two &quot;market mechanisms&quot; in this context: taxes on SO2
emissions and tradable permits to emit. Permits would provide the
certainty needed to meet the UK's target. It would be difficult
to judge the tax level which would achieve this. </p>
<p>Technologies now available make it possible for new power
stations to control emissions at little extra cost. Even older
ones can achieve quite substantial environmental improvements
with only a small increase in running cost. But the cost of
enforcing environmental policy can be high. Why are market
mechanisms cheaper and more efficient than direct control? </p>
<p>One reason is that the location of acid rain matters. There is
a &quot;critical load&quot; of acidity which in habitats can
bear. Geography has been unkind to the UK: the habitats in the
country's upland regions are particularly vulnerable to acidity,
and also receive higher doses of acidity due to their high
rainfall. Market mechanisms could focus the control policy on
these regions. Sources whose emissions are deposited as rain in
those region as could be required to buy more permits per tone of
emissions. </p>
<p>Market mechanisms will only prove cheaper than governmental
control if an efficient permit market can be established. London
Economics makes recommendations to maximise the savings in this
area. Permits would d be denominated by year, and to assist
investment planning, would be available several years in advance.
It would be preferable to auction permits, rather than to issue
permits on the basis of existing emissions. However, there would
be too much uncertainty if the totality of permits were auctioned
at once. A market could be allowed to develop by auctioning only
a fraction of each year's permits, with that fraction increasing
for the longer dated permits. </p>
<p>What are likely savings from efficient market mechanisms? Our
report concludes that if the government issued emissions permits
to the generators and industry, based on the National Plan, and
allowed trade in permits: </p>
<ol>
    <li>the English generators could reduce the cost of meeting
        the 2003 target by &#163;15 million a year from 2003,
        just by trading with each other; </li>
    <li>if trade were permitted between the generators , with a
        net resource saving of &#163;30-40 million a year from
        2003 onwards; and </li>
    <li>additional savings of &#163;13-25 million a year could be
        achieved if the Scottish electricity industry were also
        allowed to buy permits. </li>
</ol>
<p>The savings arise principally because it would be cheaper, by
virtue of economies of scale, for the English generators to
reduce emissions than for industry to do so. </p>
<p>The Government's National Plan, influenced by LE's interim
report, already incorporates a strong market mechanism. It sets
quotas for National Power and PowerGen, allowing them to decide
how to meet them. By measuring the potential saving, this new
report establishes the economic efficiency of tradable permits. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
</body>
</html>
