<html>
<head>
<title>Seeing the Wood for the Trees</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Seeing the Wood for the Trees</h2>
<p><strong><i>Britain is poised to make several major new forest
investments. Recreation and environmental benefits are their main
economic justification. London Economics faces the challenge of
valuing recreational facilities and landscape improvements.</i></strong></p>
<hr>
<p>New forests are planned in several areas of the country. LE
has been asked by the Countryside Commission to do a cost-benefit
analysis of the most politically salient of them, the National
Forest being created over 154m2 in the heart of England. </p>
<h4>The National Forest</h4>
<p>The National Forest is a major landscape initiative which will
afforest an area of about 50,000 hectares around Burton-on-Trent.
As this is a large scale project, it raises many issues. All are
potentially relevant to the cost-benefit balance. </p>
<p>Some of these are local: How will it affect land values or
local industrial development? Or the reclamation of derelict
opencast mine sites? How will the farming community be affected?
Will there be major effects on water quality? </p>
<p>Other questions are of national importance: Will there be a
loss of output? What will be the net costs to the Exchequer? Will
it affect the balance of payments? </p>
<p>And still others are European or even global in nature: What
will be the effect on the European Community's agricultural
support budget? Will the Forest act as a sink for carbon dioxide
and help slow global warming? What will be its impact on acid
rain? </p>
<p>An additional hurdle in this project is the rate of return
requirement, since Forestry Commission projects and private
forestry investments typically yield cash returns of only 3-4%.
The rate of return currently established for all publicly-funded
projects in the UK is 6%. </p>
<h4>Valuing the Environment</h4>
<p>LE established which changes are really attributable to the
Forest project by looking at how the area would develop without
it. We then decided which issues are of greatest quantitative
importance. </p>
<p>To calculate how much it will cost the Forest organisation -
in incentive payments- to induce each of the 660 farmers in the
area to plant trees, we modelled the decisions of 15 typical
farms. This included different assumptions about agricultural
prices, rates of return and cash flow constraints, and the
returns from four different types of forest planting. The same
analysis was used to find out how much agricultural output will
be lost, how much forestry output gained, how much spent through
existing forest subsidy schemes, and how much public expenditure
saved on agricultural subsidies. </p>
<h4>The Answer</h4>
<p>But the problem of valuing the recreational resources that the
Forest will provide remained. How do you value landscape
improvements, when you cannot market them directly? Two-thirds of
area residents are keen to see an increase in afforestation
locally, but how much are their preferences worth? LE combined
the major approaches developed in environmental economics -
contingent valuation through questionnaires, effects on house
prices, and estimates of visitors' travel time - to come up with
a robust analysis. </p>
<p>The political decision to create the Forest was made and the
site firmly established before LE's advice was sought. So we
focused on how to gain most benefit out of the project - what
types of trees to plant, which sections of the area to forest
most heavily, what instruments to use to encourage landowners to
plant trees. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
</body>
</html>
