<html>
<head>
<title>Global Warming</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Global Warming</h2>
<p><i>Environmental problems are making headline news
increasingly often. One of them, Global Warming, has been brought
to public attention by the summit in Rio de Janeiro. This showed
how difficult it is to reach international consensus on tackling
what is, in effect, an international problem.</i></p>
<hr>
<p>Global warming is caused by an increased in human produced
emissions of Greenhouse Gases; the most important being Carbon
Dioxide. Carbon Dioxide is the product of burning fossil fuels.
Policies to reduce the emission of greenhouse gases figure large
for countries with an energy intensive industrial structure, or
for those where energy production plays a central role in
economic development. </p>
<p>Australia is in a special position in this respect.
Australia's economy is resource based and energy intensive, so
any policy aimed at reducing the emission of Carbon Dioxide will
bite deeper and harder than elsewhere. Any such policy will also
affect the cost of energy to industrial consumer and final
customer alike. Many Australian industries compete in markets
where small changes in costcompetitiveness can make large
differences in trade balances. </p>
<p>So the discussion about appropriate policy measures to tackle
this problem has found a particularly receptive audience in
Australia. Australia is among a mere handful of other countries
who have chosen to commit to reducing greenhouse gas emissions. </p>
<p>London Economics contributed a study on &quot;The Impact of
Global Warming Policies on Australian Industry&quot; to the
Australian debate. The report, partly sponsored by a consortium
of Australian multinational companies and other local entities,
was presented at the ABARE conference in Canberra earlier this
year and received wide coverage by the national media. Our
captions give an idea of its reception they are all courtesy of
the Australian press. </p>
<p>The study sought to build up a picture of the costs of CO2
abatements at sectoral level and the consequences in terms of
international competitiveness, from a rigorous and detailed
analysis of Australian industry. </p>
<p>The results are based on a comprehensive modelling of the
demand supply relationship in the energy market, as well as in
the main energyintensive and energyproducing sectors: steel,
aluminium, iron ore, coal, oil and gas. </p>
<p>The electricity sector is a key element in the analysis. The
channels of causation by which a carbon tax affects the price of
electricity, and the level of CO2 output from the generating
sector, are multiple, interactive and complex. We therefore
analyzed the electricity generating sector by applying the London
Economics' Least Cost Expansion Model (LELCEM) to the Australian
system. </p>
<p>LELCEM is a multiregion, multiperiod linear programming model.
It is designed to calculate the least costly way of meeting
current and future electricity demand, given a set of financial,
environmental and physical constraints. By changing the relative
price of primary fuels, a carbon tax leads, in the short run, to
plant substitution in generation within states and, if
transmission capacity permits, between states. In the longer run,
as old plant retires, a carbon tax also affects the technological
investment choices in meeting the growing demand. </p>
<p>Variation in the overall economy's energy requirement and fuel
substitution were simulated through an elasticity approach. At
the sectoral level international supply curves were derived from
detailed data on cost and characteristics of worldwide capacity. </p>
<p>So what does the study conclude? It allows for different
scenarios, depending on the degree of international consensus
that the carbon policy attracts: unilateral implementation, OECD
agreement, worldwide consensus. In all cases, a large carbon tax
would be necessary to meet Australia's commitment to CO2
reduction. </p>
<p>However the effects on Australian industry will be more severe
in the case of a unilateral tax: the steel and aluminium industry
would not survive, while production of thermal coal would be
reduced by 29%, gas by 13%, coking coal by 8% and iron ore by 4%.
The message is a stark one: a unilateral tax would particularly
affect Australian industry's competitiveness, and spell the end
of steel production and most of the aluminium smelting in
Australia by the year 2005. </p>
<p>A OECDwide or worldwide consensus would reduce the negative
effects on most sectors. In the latter case the aluminium sector
would still be wiped out, but the steel industry would be able to
earn positive cash margins on its most profitable business,
although these margins would be less than those required to
sustain competitiveness. Iron ore would fare better than in the
unilateral scenario, while thermal coal would suffer from the
increased worldwide substitution away from coal. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
