<html>
<head>
<title>Have Permit, Will Trade</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Have Permit, Will Trade</h2>
<p><i>The realisation that permit trading could harness market
forces to cut the cost of controlling pollution was described in
the US Congress as &quot;the one bright idea of the 1980s&quot;.
Why was it thought to be such a good idea? Are economists right
to be so conceited about it? </i></p>
<hr>
<h4>The idea</h4>
<p>Governments usually try to control pollution by limiting how
much of a given substance firms can discharge into the
environment sulphur dioxide into the air for instance. Economists
realised that those limits, like all permit systems, waste
resources. Limits force all firms to cut their discharges,
however much it costs them. </p>
<p>The bright idea was that, if the limits are made into permits
not tied to particular firms, and firms are allowed to trade
these permits , then those who cut their discharges will be those
who find it cheapest to do so. The other firms will buy permits
from them. The pollution control objectives will be met at the
least possible cost. Other schemes, such as pollution taxes, can
achieve leastcost results, but not with the same precise control
on total discharges. </p>
<h4>The problems</h4>
<p>Governments are, quite rightly, concerned about what happens
when bright ideas are put into practice. Ideas are cheap, but
policies, when they run into difficulty, can be very expensive
witness the cost of building Concorde, or the fast breeder
reactor. Economists' bright ideas can sometimes prove as costly
as engineers' and scientists' as the advocates of monetary union
and membership of the ERM have discovered. Permit trading needs
to be approached with care. Closer examination reveals several
key difficulties. </p>
<p>It creates uncertainty about who will cut discharges and
where. It is no consolation that other parts of the country are
cleaner, if your local factory buys permits and continues to
belch filth. Permit markets also interact with product markets,
and can both fail in themselves and weaken competition
downstream. For instance, the electric power industry often
dominates sulphur dioxide emissions, and the electricity market
is not fully competitive. Firms that are oligopolists in
electricity supply are likely to be oligopolists in the sulphur
permit market too. </p>
<h4>LE's experience</h4>
<p>Expert policy advice is clearly essential, and LE has played a
significant role. In particular, we have written two key studies,
which have been the basis of several presentations in the UK and
Europe. </p>
<p>In 1991, LE advised the Department of the Environment about
the potential role of market mechanisms in the control of acid
rain in the UK. This included an investigation of how to design a
workable permit market. Permits are preferable to charges in this
case, both because the UK was seeking to meet its quantitative
obligations under EC directives, and because it is concerned to
prevent the acid pollution at vulnerable sites from rising above
&quot;critical load&quot; levels. Trading them could offer
savings of up to 16% in the cost of controlling acid rain (see
Economics in Action 1993/FOUR). </p>
<p>More recently, as part of the World Bank's programme of
environmental research for Poland, LE worked on the costs and
effects of different air pollution control mechanisms in Krakow.
Using a model bringing together an inventory of sources,
pollutant dispersion matrices and control costs, we produced maps
of polluted concentrations like the one shown here. These showed
the anticipated air quality under pollution control policies
ranging from existing administrative controls to pollution taxes,
fuel taxes and tradeable permits. </p>
<p>We also calculated overall control costs under these policies.
Tradeable permits for firms, combined with sensible regulation of
households, was found to offer savings of up to 20% on the cost
of meeting existing environmental standards. </p>
<p>A more detailed project for the Polish Ministry of
Environmental Protection will design a tradeable permit system
for a trial region. With engineers from Poland's Atmoterm
company, we helped select a suitable site, and are leading the
design of the permit system itself. </p>
<p>This project represents one of LE's most challenging
assignments. It involves analysis in a relatively new field of
economics. And it bears on the politicallycharged issue of
protecting the environment. Poland's economy is in transition,
competitive markets are far from fully established, and the
government is tiring of &quot;soft advice for hard
currency&quot;. The project is typical of LE reaching for new
challenges and achievements as it consolidates its position as
one of the most interesting places to practice economics in the
UK. </p>
<h4>Where next?</h4>
<p>So will tradeable permits work? Our studies show that they
would offer considerable cost savings in both the UK and Eastern
Europe similar to the actual savings found in the USA, where
permit trading has been applied. Designing a system that actually
achieves these cost savings will require as much thought as
analysing the effects. LE will have to grapple with the issues of
policy credibility, market manipulation and auction design. These
have to be solved before a bright idea can see the light of day. </p>
<p><i>Contact point: Robert Laslett</i> </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
