<html>
<head>
<title>What's Different About Health Care?</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>What's Different About Health Care?</h2>
<p><b><i>Can the NHS learn from similar changes in other
organisations? Has the NHS its own specific requirements?</i></b> </p>
<hr>
<p>Major changes in the finance and organisation of hospital and
community health services in the NHS took effect on 1 April 1991.
In the previous system each district health authority received a
global allocation based on services provided (for its residents
and residents of other districts) and then divided this
allocation between its different units. In the new system,
districts receive allocations for their residents only, and then
make service contracts between providers. </p>
<h4>Beyond the steady state</h4>
<p>Although an objective of the provider market is to introduce
supplyside competition, during the first year purchasers are
being funded on past patterns of service and are expected to
maintain these on a contractual basis. As the NHS moves beyond
the steady state, what lessons are there from similar changes in
other organisations (eg electricity and water), and in what ways
is health care different and has its own specific requirements? </p>
<h4>Common problems</h4>
<p>Like electricity, the NHS faces uncertainty in demand for its
services. Contractual structures need to be developed to cope
with risk in fair ways for both purchaser and provider. This has
been done through option contracts for electricity. Similar means
may be developed for health care. </p>
<p>The NHS can learn from regulation of utilities in two ways: </p>
<ol>
    <li>regulating small numbers of purchasers and providers; and </li>
    <li>careful guidance of changing from the 'steady state' it
        may, for example, make more sense to pay higher prices if
        this produces a small number of purchasers. </li>
</ol>
<h4>Different problems</h4>
<p>The NHS is different from other public utilities in two
important respects. </p>
<p>Firstly, the &quot;consumer&quot; does not pay directly for
services and relies on agents (GPs and hospital doctors) who are
traditionally allowed clinical autonomy from resource decisions.
Patients are referred by GPs to hospital doctors who are
typically independent of both purchasers and providers. Ways have
to be developed of preserving the good features of the agency
relationship within the new systems of contracting. </p>
<p>Secondly, health care is a highly heterogeneous commodity
which is difficult to measure. Contracts are currently based on
patient numbers, so drawing up the new contracts will prove an
exciting challenge. A system of measuring casemix must be
developed which adequately captures the variety of cases treated. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1991 </p>
</body>
</html>
