<html>
<head>
<title>The NHS in the Looking Glass</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>The NHS in the Looking Glass</h2>
<p><strong><i>&quot;When I use a word,&quot; Humpty Dumpty said
in a rather scornful tone, &quot;it means just what I choose it
to mean neither more nor less.&quot;</i></strong><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong><i>&quot;The question is,&quot; said Alice
&quot;whether you can make words mean so many different
things.&quot;</i></strong></p>
<hr>
<p>The watchwords for the introduction of the NHS market for
199192 are &quot;steady state&quot; and &quot;block
contracts&quot;. What do these watchwords mean? </p>
<p>In the years leading up to April 1991, each NHS hospital was
allocated a global budget from its district. So each year,
hospitals were caught in an &quot;efficiency trap&quot;: as they
treated more cases, total costs increased but global budgets did
not. The global budget did, however, give hospitals complete
flexibility in identifying where to make savings. </p>
<p>From April 1991, NHS hospitals are funded through contracts
with a number of purchasers. The main purchasers are districts,
which receive a cash limit to pay for care for their populations.
For 199192, the transition to this new system was intended to be
achieved through preserving past patterns of funding and services
by using &quot;block contracts&quot; to maintain a &quot;steady
state&quot;. </p>
<p>The &quot;steady state&quot; was intended to mean that
purchasers ought not to use the new NHS market to change
hospitals, because data on costs are poor and there are virtually
no data on quality. The flexibity of the old system of global
budgeting was intended to be secured in &quot;block
contracts&quot; which were intended to mean the the puchaser
bought &quot;access&quot; to hospital services. The question is,
what does &quot;access&quot; mean? </p>
<p>Purchasers and hospitals have interpreted &quot;block
contracts&quot; to mean indicated volumes of cases. These volumes
were based on unreliable 198990 data. Hence the &quot;steady
state&quot; developed to mean no change. </p>
<p>Predictably, what is now happening is that, for some block
contracts, the contracted volumes of services are already being
exceeded, and the financial year ends in March 1992. The new NHS
market has not put an end to the &quot;efficiency trap&quot;. The
watchwords of the &quot;steady state&quot; and &quot;block
contracts&quot; have created a looking glass in which the
&quot;efficiency trap&quot; is encountered by purchasers as well.
Indeed, for each hospital, there are as many looking glasses as
there are purchasers. Hence the new market has created a
kaleidascope of the efficiency trap. </p>
<p>For the new NHS market to work, new contractual structures are
urgently needed which cope with the intrinsic variability of
health care, so that risk is shared between purchasers and
providers. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
</body>
</html>
