<DOCNO>WT11-B06-94</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA036-000712-B016-320</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.londecon.co.uk:80/pubs/health/medprac.htm 194.193.150.111 19970111014530 text/html 3644
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 11 Jan 1997 01:40:19 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 3473
Last-modified: Sat, 14 Sep 1996 15:05:01 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Medical Practice Variation</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Medical Practice Variation</h2>
<p><i>Sickness is unpredictable, so the need for health care, and
its potential costs, are uncertain. Patients (and their
relatives) are anxious and poorly informed about health care
choices. Even afterwards, they are often unable to judge whether
the most effective care has been provided. Costs of health care
are financed through insurance (mostly by governments). Doctors
act as the patient's agent in making choices ( with doctors
themselves regulating selection and membership of the
profession). This means that rationing is implicit with constant
arguments over &quot;underfunding&quot;. The costs of services
demand always exceeds available funds. </i></p>
<hr>
<p>Doctors' role as gatekeepers to limited resources has
naturally attracted attention. But the prior issue has been
curiously neglected. How well-informed is the doctor of the
benefits of health care? There is disturbing evidence of medical
practice variation (MPV) because of professional uncertainty for
much of medical care: in both GP's rates of referral to hospital
and in rates of hospital admissions. </p>
<p>In the 1903s in the US, a group of children suffering from
tonsillitis were taken to another specialist, who said that half
of these would benefit from the operation. Each time this
experiment was repeated, the same outcome resulted. </p>
<p>In the 1930s in the UK, Glover discovered up to fivefold
variations in rates of tonsillectomies and concluded that it
tended &quot;to be performed as a routine prophylactic ritual for
no particular reason and with no particular results&quot;. Since
then, evidence throughout the world has accumulated to show that
significant variations in hospital admissions for surgery and
medicine are the norm. For example, a study in Maine found only
one percent of cases had low variation. </p>
<p>MPV exists because much of health care has not been evaluated.
Measuring outcomes is difficult and costly. Subtle differences in
clinical practice, consistently applied, result in substantial
variations in treatment. So there are no ready answers to the
problem posed by MPV. Guidelines on medical practice, and
scrutiny of doctors' decisions on a case by case basis, are
unlikely to alter subtle differences in practice. </p>
<p>What is needed is a system which can translate data on
treatment into information on MPV. The Codman Research Group has
developed such a system, which has been used extensively in the
US by purchasers and providers of hospital services. We are
working with them to make this available in the UK. </p>
<p>The sheer extent of MPV suggests that most hospital treatment
has uncertain benefits. What price the ways commonly used to
appraise hospitals' performance? Do we invariably want more
admissions and reduced waiting times? Extensive use of systems to
analyse MPV in the UK will help change the culture from assuming
that quicker and increased access to hospital always means
increased gains in health. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
