<DOCNO>WT11-B06-95</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA036-000712-B017-28</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.londecon.co.uk:80/pubs/health/hospheal.htm 194.193.150.111 19970111014551 text/html 2802
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 11 Jan 1997 01:40:41 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 2631
Last-modified: Sat, 14 Sep 1996 15:04:56 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Hospitals and Health</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Hospitals and Health</h2>
<p><i>Hospitals are in a period of great change throughout the
Western World. Hospitals used to care for the sick whilst nature
took its course. Improvements in knowledge and technology then
changed them into centres of curative medicine. Now these same
treatments can be provided as expertly, and as safely, outside
these &quot;centres of excellence&quot;.</i></p>
<hr>
<p>In big cities, there has been a movement of residents out of
the centre, with the development of new hospitals locally. In
city centres, the existence of so many hospitals has led the
local population to use them more. </p>
<p>Consequently the development of primary and community services
has been poor and uneven. Resource pressure on the city centre
hospitals has led to the smaller hospitals, which often
concentrated on a specialised range of illnesses, being absorbed
into larger multispecialty centres. </p>
<p>These characteristics are illustrated by changes in London.
Medical advances, population changes, and the health reforms
initiated by the UK government require further rationalisation,
with some urgency. Otherwise the National Health Service may fail
to meet the needs of different sections of the population fairly,
without unnecessary loss of expertise. </p>
<p>This is an extremely complex problem. Other cities and
countries are watching closely, knowing that London's problems
today are theirs tomorrow. </p>
<p>Decisions on future patterns of care need to be based on
factors of quality, ease of access, cost, and the tradesoff
between them. It is vital to identify the consequences of
hospitals increasing or decreasing their bed capacity. The
effects of changes in one part of the service can be felt in
apparently unrelated specialties, and many miles away. These
knockon effects are difficult to predict. </p>
<p>London Economics has developed modelling techniques which
allow the important and relevant data to be analysed, and the
consequences of each potential change to be identified. Choices
can then be made on the basis of explicit priorities, so that the
optimal contribution to the health of the population can be
pursued. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1993 </p>
</body>
</html>
