<html>
<head>
<title>Regulating the Market for Health Services</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Regulating the Market for Health Services</h2>
<p><i>The introduction of a 'purchaser/provider' market in the
Health Service has been a key feature of policy in the 1990's,
not just in the UK. The belief is that such a move will improve
efficiency, and patients will gain. The argument runs that
experience and theory suggest that markets know best; when
sellers compete, on price and quality, to satisfy buyers, the
result is to drive standards up, and prices down. </i></p>
<hr>
<p>But the market in health care is quite different from the
traditional street market which inspired Adam Smith's doctrine of
the invisible hand. The main difference is that (compared with
food or clothing) health care is both very expensive, and needed
comparatively rarely. It is thus typically provided through some
form of insurance system a private insurance system as in
America, or a social insurance system paid for out of taxes, as
in this country. So there is no direct connection between payment
for health care and use of the system. </p>
<p>A further difference between buying health care and buying
food or clothes is that individuals typically do not know what
they need. So they rely on doctors to make choices for them. The
doctors are well placed to choose between competing treatments on
medical grounds, but have little notion of their relative costs.
So the usual mechanisms for allocating scarce resources where
they are most needed is absent. </p>
<h4>Rationing health care</h4>
<p>The introduction of the purchaser provider market is a first
step towards remedying that. Under the old system, a doctor was
asked to recommend the best treatment for each patient who came
to him. Cost was not an issue. Under the new system, health
professionals are forced to confront the fact that an extravagent
treatment of one patient will leave less to spend on another. The
question is not </p>
<ul>
    <li>How do I treat this patient?&quot; </li>
</ul>
<p><b><i>but </i></b></p>
<ul>
    <li>&quot;How do I best improve the health of the community
        with a given sum of money?&quot; </li>
</ul>
<p>That is a much more difficult question. It requires a radical
change in the habits of thought of the highly qualified and
motivated NHS staff. They have traditionally responded to the
ideal of best medical practice regardless of cost. There is a
risk that introducing market forces disrupts this tradition,
based on idealism, and damages morale, particularly if the
process takes many years. Unless this transition is managed with
subtlety and care, there is a danger that the whole process may
fall into disrepute, with inevitable pressure for the whole or
partial reversal of the process. </p>
<h4>New techniques</h4>
<p>The new ideal which is to put necessarily limited health
resources to the best possible use will take time to achieve.
Purchasers and providers both have to learn the new techniques of
the marketplace. </p>
<ul>
    <li>Information systems need to develop sufficiently for
        their decisions to be properly informed. </li>
    <li>Capital markets must eventually develop to permit
        purchasers and providers to invest to ensure security of
        supply and cover risk. </li>
    <li>Rules need to emerge to prevent abuse of market power by
        those who have particular incumbent advantages. </li>
</ul>
<h4>A complex market</h4>
<p>The market in health care is a complex one. The products are
difficult to define. The information on costs and prices
necessary to create an efficient market will not immediatley
become available. Complex markets of this sort rarely develop
without the need for regulation. </p>
<p>Firm action has been needed by regulators to sort out the
teething problems in electricity, water, gas and
telecommunications. It has been a feature of the
postprivatisation era. Other markets, like broadcasting and
financial services, have sophisticated systems combining
selfregulation with a number of bodies which deal with potential
abuses of market power, or franchise scarce resources like
airtime. </p>
<p>It would be surprising if the health market, at least in
transition, did not need regulation. Yet, at present, the role of
a potential regulator has barely been articulated. Such a body
will need to: </p>
<ul>
    <li>guide the industry towards the market by setting examples
        of prices, structure of contracts and benchmark costs; </li>
    <li>set quality standards, and take the lead in standardising
        clinical practice; </li>
    <li>encourage the much needed development of suitable
        information systems; </li>
    <li>arbitrate where misunderstandings or conflicts arise; and </li>
    <li>take a view on the speed of introduction of new facets of
        competition, like introducing private sector capital or
        the role of private sector providers and insurers. </li>
</ul>
<p>So far the NHS market is emerging from a system based on an
hierarchical system of global budgeting. Major structural changes
in London are being driven by direction rather than the market.
The organisational environment of the market is now being
subjected to radical reform. We believe that a key to this reform
must be decisions on the role and nature of regulation of the
structure and conduct of the NHS market. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1994 </p>
</body>
