http://www.londecon.co.uk:80/pubs/health/hospital.htm 194.193.150.111 19970111014627 text/html 7063
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 11 Jan 1997 01:41:22 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 6892
Last-modified: Sat, 14 Sep 1996 15:04:59 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Why We Need Fewer Hospitals</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Why We Need Fewer Hospitals</h2>
<p><strong><i>One of the most difficult decisions faced by the
Health Secretary, Virginia Bottomley, has been whether or not to
allow St Bartholomew's, the famous London teaching hospital, to
close. The disappearance of venerable hospitals always causes an
outcry but, like the disappearance of much loved steam trains, it
is an inevitable consequence of technical progress. </i></strong></p>
<hr>
<p>Since the National Health Service (NHS) was set up in 1948,
the number of hospital beds has fallen dramatically. The chart
shows this fall over the past 30 years. </p>
<p>This is a puzzling phenomenon, especially when we know there
are people waiting for admission to hospital, and that NHS
expenditure has continued to rise in real terms. </p>
<p>However, there are strong social and medical trends which make
treating the sick out of hospital an effective and efficient
alternative to inpatient care. </p>
<h4>Better homes; better drugs</h4>
<p>When the NHS was set up, home living standards were much
poorer than they are now. Few homes had effective heating, many
had no running hot water and no inside W.C. Very few had
telephones, and those that did were often ill advised to rely on
them. It made good sense, then, for people who were ill, and at
risk from infections, to be cared for in hospitals, not at home.
It is worth noting that before World War II, the rich tended not
to go to hospitals. </p>
<p>Effective treatments were relatively few. Many admissions were
aimed at nursing and caring for people whilst nature took its
course, for either good or ill. The developments in effective
drugs have drastically changed this. Some drugs (eg modern
antibiotics) speed up recovery. Others (eg ulcer healing drugs)
avoid the need for surgery altogether. </p>
<p>Medical knowledge, and some would say fashion, have changed. A
spell in bed with its lack of exercise is now regarded as bad for
health. Not many years ago, people who had suffered a heart
attack were kept in bed for three weeks. Now they may be
&quot;mobilised&quot; within days. Patients tend to stay in
hospital beds for much shorter periods than in the past. </p>
<p>The Audit Commission, in its review of hospital beds, pointed
out that the average length of stay for England and Wales had
fallen from 10.2 days in 1974 to 6.7 days in 1989. Improved
management efficiency reduced the number of days a bed stayed
empty between successive patients from 3.9 days to 2.3 days in
the same period. Overall, the number of patients each bed could
accommodate in a year rose from 26 to over 40: more than a 3%
increase in efficiency every year! </p>
<h4>More day care</h4>
<p>At the limit, a technical programme can eliminate the need for <i>any</i>
overnight stay in hospital. The increase in daycare has been
achieved through improvements in surgical and diagnostic
technology. Miniaturisation of instruments, the use of fibreoptic
microscopes, and safer and shortacting anaesthetics, have enabled
much more day surgery to be performed. The patient is now well
enough to return home the same day. </p>
<p>The Royal College of Surgeons has suggested that 50% of all
surgery could, and should, be carried out on a daypatient basis.
This view has been endorsed by the NHS Executive. It should be
seen against the current percentage of 35%, suggesting that there
is further scope for change. Most people, of course, have no
particular problems after day surgery. There remains a risk that
a complication, on rare occasions serious, will occur. </p>
<p>This is where the availability of telephones has enabled
practice to change. Patients are given the number of a
&quot;hotline&quot; which they (or a relative) can call for
advice, or to summon help. Even if patients do not have their own
telephone, at current prices it is cheaper to lend them a mobile
one, even if they forget to return it, than to incur the costs of
an unnecessary hospital stay. </p>
<h4>Fewer hospitals; fewer beds</h4>
<p>The fall in the number of beds is unsettling for the medical
profession. For a long time, the hospital bed was the currency of
the NHS, and in some places the status of medical consultants was
related to the number of beds they were allocated. The current
practice of describing the activity of the NHS in terms of
numbers of patients treated is one step towards measuring the
real effectiveness of the service. </p>
<p>Fewer beds means a smaller number of hospitals. There are
obvious economies of scale and scope within hospitals, both in
the financial and in the medical senses. As the number of beds
falls, some hospitals are bound to become economically unviable.
Their services are more sensibly combined with neighbouring
hospitals. This process has been going on in parallel with the
fall in the number of beds, as the chart shows. </p>
<h4>Population shifts</h4>
<p>In London and the other big cities, the closure of hospitals
has been particularly noticeable. Two other factors have been at
work here. The first is that the core of the provision was
established before the NHS was set up, largely through voluntary
and Local Authority initiatives. It tended to be concentrated in
city centres, with people travelling in from more rural areas.
With the establishment of the NHS, and its commitment to equity
of provision nationally, new hospitals were built where none had
existed before. People needed to travel less far for care. There
has since been a depopulation of the cities, and consequently a
fall in the natural catchment populations of the city centre
hospitals. </p>
<p>Hospital closures are emotive and politically sensitive.
Hospitals can be a focus for a variety of activities in any
community. They are often the biggest single employer. Their loss
can be significant, but, perhaps surprisingly, not particularly
so for the health of the local population. Communities are
naturally upset when a local hospital closes, because it means a
longer journey in the event of an emergency. But, in practice,
this has little effect on the outcome. In life or death crises,
what matters is the speed with which the ambulance arrives: that
is when the emergency life support is started. Thereafter, the
effectiveness of the care one receives is related to the quality
of the services in the hospital, not how long it takes to get
there. </p>
<hr>
