Content-length: 7069
Last-modified: Sat, 14 Sep 1996 15:05:53 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Free Justice for All</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Free Justice for All</h2>
<p><i>What has been the government's top spending priority since
1979? Fighting crime? The National Health? The infrastructure?
The answer is none of the above. The programme which has recorded
the fastest growth rate over the period has been the provision of
legal aid. There are good microeconomic reasons for this as
London Economics, who has been looking at the economics of legal
aid for the Lord Chancellor's Department, discovered.</i></p>
<hr>
<p>Clearly, the government has not set out deliberately to
increase the public spending allocated to the Lord Chancellor's
Department. Legal aid has grown rapidly because, like
unemployment benefit, it is a socalled demandled programme. It is
available to all those who meet certain conditions. If crime
rates soar, then the amount of legal aid will rise inexorably,
just as unemployment benefit rises with the number of jobless. </p>
<p>However, a striking feature of the increase in legal aid is
that it has actually been far more rapid than the increase in
crime. A simple measure of the volume of legal aid is the number
of Acts of Assistance. These have more than tripled since 1986,
reflecting an explosion of <i>civil</i> legal aid. Society has
become more litigious; more marriages have ended in the courts.
Total spending on legal aid has nearly quadrupled in the last
seven years, as the chart shows. </p>
<h4>A bane to the taxpayer</h4>
<p>This increasing tendency to go to law at public expense is a
bane to the taxpayer, but a boon to the legal profession. So any
attempt to curb spending on legal aid is bound to be resisted by
lawyers. The parallels with health are striking. Free justice for
all, like free health for all, is a powerful rallying cry.
Controlling the costs of legal aid will, like controlling health
costs, be an uphill political battle. </p>
<p>Legal aid cases provide a solid base load of work for the
legal profession. They account for around 10 per cent of
solicitors' incomes and nearly two fifths of barristers' incomes.
Lawyers have some control over the amount of legally aided work.
They decide in the first instance if there is a case to be
answered. When private work slackens off, they can expand their
public work. And although the fee rates for legally aided work do
not match the top rates for private work, there is very little
risk involved. Lawyers do legally aided work on a
timeandmaterials basis, so the longer a case drags on, the more
they are paid. Nice work if you can get it, and every
consultant's dream! </p>
<h4>Economic pressures</h4>
<p>London Economics was engaged by the Lord Chancellor's
Department to develop indicators to show whether legal aid fees
represented market rates. As part of this, we looked at the
economic pressures behind the rise in the legal aid bill. The
work was done by the health team because the market for legal
services has much in common with the market for medical services,
especially in the US. In both cases, the client goes to the
professional with a problem. The professional decides what
treatment is appropriate, and typically goes on to supply it, to
Rolls Royce standards. </p>
<p>The client has no incentive to question whether the level of
provision is excessive. He does not pick up the bill. So in
America we observe very high standards of medical practice, paid
for by insurance companies. In the UK, we observe very high
standards of legal advice, paid for by the taxpayer. In both
countries, worries about the escalating cost has caused people
increasingly to question a set of arrangements which delivers
these results. </p>
<h4>Tendering for work</h4>
<p>In most spheres of economic activity, the buyer specifies what
he wants, and the seller quotes a price for providing it. The
seller has every incentive to quote a reasonable price, because
if he overcharges, the buyer will go to another supplier. This is
the way tendering works in the building industry, from the
smallest domestic decorating job to the construction of the
Channel tunnel. Once a tender is accepted, the supplier again has
a strong incentive to control costs, because the profitability of
the job depends entirely on his success in so doing. </p>
<p>None of these pressures apply to the provision of legal
services paid for by legal aid. So both the number of legally
aided cases and the costs per case have risen steadily. Public
spending on legal services, where the costs fall on the taxpayer,
has risen faster than private spending on legal services, where
the costs fall on the client. </p>
<p>This publicly funded demand for legal services has been an
important factor contributing to the rise in the number of
solicitors. The roll has risen by a third since 1983. It is also
rising at an accelerating rate, since the number of new
admissions to the roll has been increasing since 1981. Obviously
legal aid has not been the only source of demand for legal
services, but it has been an increasingly important source. The
proportion of total solicitors' earnings coming from legal aid is
rising, as is the number of solicitors' offices receiving legal
aid. </p>
<h4>Fixed fee rates</h4>
<p>The Lord Chancellor's Department is grappling with the problem
of rising legal aid costs by introducing fixed fee rates per
case. The rise in the number of lawyers and in the number of law
firms receiving legal aid suggests that fee rates for legal aid
have been attractive to lawyers in the past. The problem now is
to find objective criteria by which to set the fee rates in
future. </p>
<p>Fixed fee rates create an incentive to skimp. The move towards
fixed fee rates thus needs to be complemented by some form of
payment by results, to provide an incentive in the other
direction. Payment by results which would typically mean a
smaller fixed fee per case, topped up with a sizable win bonus
would make lawyers much more choosy. They would only be
interested in taking on cases they were likely to win. This would
reduce the amount of nohope litigation being conducted at public
expense. It would also ensure that, having taken on the case, the
lawyers would have a strong incentive to devote time and effort
to winning it. </p>
<p>These changes would bring fewer legally aided cases, but a
better service at a lower cost. The winners from the changes
would be poor litigants with genuine grievances, and the
taxpayer. The losers would be mediocre lawyers who currently make
a comfortable living arguing marginal cases at undue length, and
at the public expense. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1994 </p>
