<html>
<head>
<title>A Planning Tool</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>A Planning Tool</h2>
<p><i>In a year when government and City economists have hardly
distinguished themselves by getting their forecasts right it may
seem strange to promote the notion that economic forecasts are a
valuable tool for corporate planning.</i></p>
<hr>
<p>Yet if there were firms that believed themselves immune to
changes in the overall economic environment, there are certainly
many fewer than a year ago. In the meantime, some have gone out
of business, others have learnt crucial lessons. </p>
<p>This recession has been very different from the last major
recession a decade ago. That was focussed on exporters and
importcompeting sectors of the economy, this one focuses on
industries and firms which are particularly vulnerable to
movements in interest rates. It is all too easy for firms to
confuse trend and cycle, and simply to project last year's
performance several years to the future. For some sectors, the
cyclical downturn is an indicator of trend there will be no sharp
recovery in financial services or retailing, for example, where
over investment in the 1980s will take years to work through.
Others can expect to recover rapidly as the general economy does. </p>
<h4>Why LE - MES?</h4>
<p>Our objective in LE - MES is not simply to provide another set
of macroeconomic forecasts to put on the shelf along with those
which companies already recieve from the Treasury model,
independent institutes, city economists and commercial
forecasting groups. It is to adapt knowledge of macroeconomic
events to the specific needs of individual firms and sectors, to
feed back into our analysis the lessons of our own extensive
contacts with business, and to educate clients in the margins of
error which surround all forecasts and to see which expectations
are robust and which may be quickly, and expensively, falsified. </p>
<p>The biggest lessons for economists from the past cycle is how
uncertain both data and the estimated relationships in the
economy are. So LE- MES crosschecks carefully the predictions
emerging from our economic models with reallife information
business data and consumer surveys. </p>
<p>The economic variables that matter for particular industries
vary widely. We have found, for example, that the information
technology industry is influenced by the business investment
cycle and the home improvements industry by interest rates. By
making careful forecasts of these variables and relating them in
a systematic way to the industries and businesses concerned we
have provided a basis for one company to plan manpower reductions
in the light of depressed sales prospects and for another company
to phase its investment plans in line with a projected recovery
in its sales. </p>
<p>In these and other cases our forecasts have provided a
credible basis for taking difficult business decisions. </p>
<p>And for those who really want to know what is going to happen,
our central view is that a modest recovery in the UK began in the
summer, driven by a slower rate of run down of inventories and a
positive effect on consumer spending from lower interest and
inflation rates. But we do not expect economic growth to return
to its trend level before 1993. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1991 </p>
</body>
</html>
