<html>
<head>
<title>Post-election Prospects</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Post-election Prospects</h2>
<p><i>Post-election, the economy has shown distinct signs of
revival. Estate agents report increased interest and high street
stores experienced their first rush for months. Sales of products
as diverse as cars and replacement windows are bouncing back.</i> </p>
<hr>
<p>It is ironic that, after all the attempts to talk up the
economy pre-election, there should be a spontaneous recovery
after the ballot boxes had closed. The electorate ended up voting
for stability and continuity. That is what they will get for the
macro economy. The economy will be kept inside the strait-jacket
to hold down tax levels in the face of electoral pressure for
improved public services. </p>
<p>Business surveys suggest the underlying trend for the economy
had started to improve before the election was over. The large
increases in government spending announced last autumn have been
feeding through. Inventories are now down to levels which leave
no more scope for the mass destocking of the past two years. </p>
<p>The real question is: will this year's incipient revival
spread through to something more sustained in future years? On
the plus side, inflation is down, though not out. But high
European interest rates as a result of German unification may
short-circuit the mechanism through which low inflation should
lead to low UK interest rates. And the weakness of property
prices allied to the nervousness about lending will damp down any
tendency for rapid growth in borrowing. It would be prudent to
plan a sluggish, through probably long-lasting, economic
recovery. </p>
<p>Looking forward, the re-elected government will want to focus
on a number of important issues scarcely mentioned during the
election. These include the enlargement of the EC to include the
EFTA countries and provide access to Western markets for the
Eastern European countries. This will have consequences for
industries with competitors in these countries. </p>
<p>The Conservatives have set out radical plans to change the
government from being a service provider to a purchaser. Much of
the Civil Service will be given agency status - a prelude to
competition with private contractors. The pattern of moves to
create independent hospital trusts, GP budget holders and
directly funded schools will become the norm, not the exception.
A wide range of business opportunities for the private sector to
supply public services should emerge here. </p>
<p>Finally, the entire issue of pro-environmental taxation was
ducked during the election. But moves to shift the tax base to
pollution instead of production are likely, raising the costs of
processes deemed to be &quot;dirty&quot; and cutting those of
processes considered &quot;clean&quot;. </p>
<p>So while the aggregate economy is likely to move slowly (and
perhaps predictably), underneath the surface the rate of change
will continue and might even speed up. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT11-B06-101</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA036-000712-B017-275</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.londecon.co.uk:80/pubs/macro/gobust.htm 194.193.150.111 19970111014807 text/html 5671
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 11 Jan 1997 01:43:00 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 5500
Last-modified: Sat, 14 Sep 1996 15:06:34 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Can Countries Go Bust?</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Can Countries Go Bust?</h2>
<p><i>When the Socialist economist Piero Sraffa received a small
inheritance immediately after World War II, he amused himself by
buying the almost worthless bonds of a defeated government.
Implicitly, he was betting that this was a country that, despite
the odds, would restore its international financial standing and
repay its debts in full. The country was Japan, and, against his
political convictions, Sraffa made a fortune.</i></p>
<hr>
<p>With the boom and bust of lending to developing countries in
the last 20 years, the markets have been filled with wouldbe
Sraffas, taking bets first that countries like Nicaragua and Peru
would continue to pay, then that they would resume payments. Not
all investors are as successful as he was bets on the USSR have
recently cost a great deal of money. What these investors are
betting on is <i>country risk</i>, the risk that a government
will default (either wholly or partially through mechanisms such
as rescheduling or restrictions on capital flows) on its payments
to creditors abroad. </p>
<p>There is some chance of such developments even in the high
income OECD countries, so all lending across international
borders carries some risk premium for country factors to the
interest rate is added an amount proportional to the risk of a
default during the loan period. Obviously the chance of a default
by the USA, for instance, is very small. But investors are making
a financial version of Pascal's wager, and praying just in case
there is a hell: even a tiny probability of avoiding a large loss
makes it worth paying a premium. </p>
<h4>How is it measured?</h4>
<p>Country risk is hard to model. The one secure theoretical
result is that it is rational for a country to default if it can
foresee no net transfers from lenders in the future. This makes
confidence and credibility allimportant, and it is not surprising
that much of the motivation for actual defaults is political. The
lending is effectively unsecured (the Midland Bank cannot seize
the assets of the government of Brazil, for instance), so the
degree of risk cannot be measured by the collateral. And one
rarely if ever observes lending to countries where the risk of
default is at all considerable, because the risk premium involved
would be penal. </p>
<p>There have been plenty of attempts at country risk assessment,
mostly based on economic conditions in the borrowing countries,
but very little real success. Risk assessment was in vogue in the
late 1970s and early 1980s when among others British highstreet
banks made huge amounts of government guaranteed and sovereign
loans to developing countries. Then, in 1982, a combination of
unsustainable refinancing requirements and high real interest
rates led Mexico to suspend repayments on its foreign commercial
bank debt. Commercial banks' perceptions of the risks posed by
developing countries abruptly increased, to the point where
almost all of them were deemed uncreditworthy, and lending slowed
to a trickle. This provoked further defaults, and it became
obvious that the machinery of risk assessment had failed to
protect the banks. </p>
<p>The debt crisis has greatly simplified the country risk
assessment decisions facing commercial lenders they hardly make
any new loans to non-OECD countries. It also makes it obvious
that country risk is a complex two-way process, reflecting
lenders' perceptions as much as borrowers' economic constraints.
Starting in the late 1980s, countries such as Chile and Mexico
have taken advantage of this to regain access to international
lending through rigidly conventional economic reform programs to
improve their balance of payments and restore lender confidence,
and debt reduction programs which cut the face value of their
debt to the point where servicing could be resumed in full. </p>
<h4>Why should I care?</h4>
<p>Country risk may seem arcane to most people, but it is part of
the story behind the poor profits and high charges of banks in
the 1980s. Banks which saw the risks of developing country
lending, and especially those in countries such as Germany (which
enforced early provisioning against such exposure) have performed
substantially better than those which were more credulous.
Country risk is also a potential issue in any cross border
investment or acquisition, being one of the informational
problems in establishing a business away from the home base. </p>
<p>The behaviour of lenders in the 1982 debt crisis clearly
violated the conditions needed to sustain creditworthiness. It
made it impossible for most countries to refinance their external
debt as it fell due. This problem of co-ordinating action among
lenders has been alleviated for commercial banks by the formation
of the so-called London Club. For many of the new types of
lending, the problem is still very much alive. As crossborder
lending accelerates, the country risk question will reemerge as
an important issue facing commercial lenders. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Back to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
</body>
