<html>
<head>
<title>What is an Index?</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>What is an Index?</h2>
<p><strong><i>London Economics' work includes developing indices
of prices and costs for specific industries. However complex the
inputs, the basic principles of index construction always remain
the same. </i></strong></p>
<hr>
<h4>Establishing an index</h4>
<p>An index indicates something output, wages, prices, cost,
efficiency, competitiveness, technological progress. It looks at
comparisons, not absolute levels. These might be across
countries, sectors, firms or, particularly, over time. So the
first number in an index series will always be 100 . </p>
<p>Any index has two crucial aspects: it is usually an aggregate
of several different components and it has a specific purpose
which tries to answer a particular question. Price indices will
be familiar to the reader. Suppose we need to know how much the
costofliving for pensioners has gone up from last year to this,
to contribute to a discussion of how much pensions should be
raised. The index would then have to look in detail at the normal
consumption patterns of pensioners and changes in prices over the
last year. So the question at issue governs the conceptual
approach to index construction. </p>
<h4>How is an index computed?</h4>
<p>Equity requires in this case that the pensioner should be as
well off as before, despite price increases. We are therefore
looking for a number, say 110, such that, given the price
increases faced, if the pensioner's income went up by 10%, or by
a factor of 1.1, the pensioner would maintain his living
standard. </p>
<p>Economic theory entirely accords with common sense on this
question. The percentage increase in the costofliving index must
be equal to a weighted average of the percentage price increases
faced by pensioners. The weight for a price increase should be
equal to the fraction of the expenditure by the pensioners on the
good. So if food increases by 5% and nonfood items by 8% and
pensioners spend 40% on food and 60% on nonfood then the increase
in the index is 0.05 ' 0.4 + 0.08 ' 0.6 = 6.8%. </p>
<p>The change in the costofliving index for students, or for
families, would clearly be different. They face the same price
increases, but their expenditure patterns are different. </p>
<h4>Cost indices</h4>
<p>Developing a cost index involves the same basic economic
principles. Inputs of the costs of different activities and of
capital are required. Such indices have to allow for regional
variations, as different regions can involve different balances
of tasks, and technical progress. </p>
<p>By linking these inputs to the tasks carried out, the index
can be kept appropriate to the industry concerned and also take
into account regional variations and technical progress (which
changes inputs required for tasks). Combining this approach with
data specific to the industry, we can develop an index which is
both feasible and plausible. </p>
<p>Cost indices are an essential management tool, and form an
important input into strategic and financial planning. London
Economics has developed such indices for industries, such as
water, electricity, mineral resources, health and tobacco. In
some cases these are intended to assist the regulatory debate, in
others they help clients to understand their competitive
position. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
