<html>
<head>
<title>A Tale of Two Recessions</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>A Tale of Two Recessions</h2>
<p><i>The worst recession since the 1930's? Empirically, it
isn't. Output fell further, and faster, in the recession of the
early 1980's, than it has this time. But for many people, firms,
sectors and some regions, this is indeed the worst recession
since the 1930's. The distribution of pain is very different in
this recession than in the last. So are the causes, effects and
future consequences. </i></p>
<hr>
<p>There are some patterns which are common to all recessions, as
Figure 1 shows. In both periods investment fell substantially and
the trade balance - the difference between what we export and
what we import - improved. Government spending increased; partly
because it usually does, and partly because recession lead to
extra spending on social security and other benefits. </p>
<p>But in the last recession, consumption actually rose slightly.
This time it has fallen. It is a matter of simple accounting
arithmetic that what happens to total output is the sum of what
happens to consumption, investment, government and the trade
balance. </p>
<p>However, behind these basic similarities there are important
differences. Start with the causes. We went into the last
recession with a large and growing trade surplus, as North Sea
oil came on stream. So the exchange rate appreciated. The hike in
the oil prices, which followed the growing instability in the
Middle East, added further to this upward pressure on the Pound.
The resulting overvalued currency forced domestic wages up to a
level where it was becoming impossible for domestic manufacturers
to compete with their international competitors. </p>
<p>This time we entered the recession ( and the ERM) with an
unsustainable trade deficit and a weak currency. The improvements
in the balance of payments have not been enough to make a
continued link to the rising Mark feasible. The result was high
interest rates, which, rather belatedly, broke the asset price
boom and consumer spending explosion. (Black Wednesday was the
climax of this unsustainable attempt to maintain a high exchange
rate to the Mark). </p>
<p>So the key element in generating and propagating the last
recession was the high value of the exchange rate. The culprit in
this recession is high interest rates, caused primarily by the
low value of the exchange rate. </p>
<p>The consequences of that difference are very evident in the
distribution of the burden. </p>
<ul>
    <li>Last time, the recession as concentrated in trade
        orientated manufacturing industry, whilst service output
        actually rose. This time both manufacturing and services
        are sharing the burden of reduced demand (Figure 2). </li>
    <li>Last time the recession was felt most sharply in the
        North and only distantly in the South. This time it is
        the other way around (Figure 3). </li>
    <li>Last time industrial shares were hit but the financial
        sector continued to grow. This time it is the other way
        around (Figure 4). </li>
</ul>
<p>These difference influence the nature of the recovery. Last
time the squeeze on internationally uncompetitive manufacturing
was the basis of the efficiency improvements which led to the
productivity miracle of the late 1980's. This time our
domestically created recession will not have similar
consequences. Perpetually optimistic commentators are still
looking for a recovery which will recreate the rapid growth that
we enjoyed from 1983 through 1987. They may have a long wait. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
