<html>
<head>
<title>What Happened to the ERM ?</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>What Happened to the ERM ?</h2>
<p><strong><i>The best way to answer this question is to look at
the difference in structure between the current ERM and the
&quot;old&quot; ERM. Was the old system successful? How did it
survive for so many years? What has occurred recently to change
this? The focus of this article is on asymmetry and
inflexibility.</i></strong></p>
<hr>
<p>The Exchange Rate Mechanism is a single (if large) part of the
more wide ranging European Monetary System (EMS). This formally
came into operation in March 1979. All Community members
participated, although the UK did not initially form part of the
ERM. The basic idea of the ERM was to create a system of quasi
fixed exchange rates to ensure greater stability in the foreign
exchange markets. Stable exchange rates are thought to increase
foreign trade, domestic price stability, and promote economic
growth. </p>
<p>When the ERM was constructed each member currency was required
to establish a central parity against the European Currency Unit
(ECU). This is made up from a weighted basket of participating
currencies. A bilateral parity grid of exchange rates between
member countries was thus derived. Member countries were obliged
to maintain these parities by carrying out the appropriate
intervention if the currency moves to one of the limits. In order
to do this, unlimited amounts of credit were available between
central banks. </p>
<p>The idea behind this system was to avoid what was seen as the
main problem of the Bretton Woods system of exchange rate
control: namely, that of <i>asymmetric adjustment</i>, which had
often forced adjustment on the weaker currencies. By creating a
bilateral parity grid it was hoped that all currencies would
share the burden of adjustment equally. The system would then be <i>symmetric</i>. </p>
<p>In practice, the evolution of the ERM appears to have taken
quite a different course. The DM is now widely acknowledged as
the <i>de facto</i> nominal anchor of the system, just as the
Dollar became the <i>de facto</i> nominal anchor under Bretton
Woods. Furthermore, many commentators have alleged an asymmetry
in the ERM's operation with the burden of adjustment, as under
Bretton Woods, carried disproportionately by the weaker
currencies. The evident reliance placed on maintaining parity
with the DM, rather than with the ECU, lends evidence to this
theory. </p>
<p>Prior to 1987, the underlying philosophy within the ERM was to
create a zone of <i>stable</i> exchange rates as opposed to <i>fixed </i>exchange
rates. Thus, realignments were possible when necessary; the whole
system was fairly flexible. In the first eight years of the ERM
there was, on average, one realignment a year. These are shown in
the table. Only one more occurred before Black Wednesday, and
that was only to let the Lira move to a narrow band. </p>
<p>This period of exchange rate stability provided support for
those claiming that control of the exchange rates was a simple
matter. It also led to the misguided belief that EMU was just
around the corner. </p>
<p>There is no clear proof that the ERM actually <i>contributed</i>to
this exchange rate stability. Evidence is mounting to suggest
that this stability was partly &quot;accidental&quot;, and partly
due to the policies of the French government (who were stubbornly
maintaining the Franc/DM parity). Of course, if this latter
theory is true then EMU is certainly not imminent, and even
dangerous to attempt. Once the &quot;accidental&quot; stability
ceases, the whole system becomes unstable. </p>
<p>More recently, the underlying philosophy of the ERM has been
to create a system of fixed exchange rates in preparation for the
introduction of the single currency, or European Monetary Union
(EMU). The result of this is the reluctance of member countries
to seek realignment of their currencies, even when these
realignments were necessary. </p>
<p>However, the impact of these minor misalignments (even though
they were compounding) were insignificant. A major misalignment
was about to take place the reunification of Germany. The cost of
this process has far exceeded anything even the Germans had
planned for. There has been a major structural change in the
economy of the ERM's largest member. The massive costs of
reunification required large inflows of capital to finance them.
This, in turn, required high interest rates, and thus an
appreciation of the currency. </p>
<p>In the &quot;old&quot; ERM, a revaluation of the DM, if not a
complete realignment of the whole system, would have been sure to
follow, and the parities against the ECU anchor would be
unchanged. However, in the current system this was not thought
necessary, even though, it now appears, the Germans requested
such a move. </p>
<p>Now, given that countries have put emphasis on the DM rather
than the ECU, these high interest rates had to be implemented in
each country, and the nonGerman currencies were now shadowing a
&quot;dragging anchor&quot;. But higher interest rates in
nonGerman countries were not only unnecessary, they were
incompatible with economic conditions in those countries. </p>
<p>The money markets soon realised that the nonGerman economies
could not sustain such high interest. They knew that unilateral
devaluations must take place. This knowledge put downward
pressure on the most vulnerable currencies, and made their
devaluation imminent. One by one the weaker currencies have been
devalued (peseta, escudo and the punt), or have exited the system
(sterling and the lira). Those which remain are fighting an
uphill battle, and increasing interest rates further will not
help. </p>
<p>For the ERM to survive, it needs to become more like its
former self. There needs to be greater flexibility to realign
whenever a structural or long term change takes place. The
survival of the current system would appear to rest on the
survival of the French franc. After the recent French elections,
we are likely to see developments soon. </p>
