<DOCHDR>
http://www.londecon.co.uk:80/pubs/macro/slowgrow.htm 194.193.150.111 19970111014949 text/html 7049
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 11 Jan 1997 01:44:31 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 6878
Last-modified: Sat, 14 Sep 1996 15:06:41 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>A Decade of Slow Growth in Spending ?</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>A Decade of Slow Growth in Spending ?</h2>
<p><strong><i>Consumer spending has been the driving force behind
economic growth for the past 15 years. But the rate of growth was
exceptional in the 1980s, and we will have to get used to less
buoyant consumption for the rest of the century. </i></strong></p>
<hr>
<p>For a brief period in the mid1980s, it looked as though the
problems of macroeconomic management and forecasting had been
licked. The official forecasts were always right. Growth
proceeded at such a steady pace that Nigel Lawson claimed to have
abolished the cycle. </p>
<p>It all started to go wrong in 1987, when the Treasury, the
London Business School and the National Institute all
underestimated the growth of consumer spending by around 1.5%.
That was a large error by the standards of the day, but next year
was even worse. The mainstream forecasters predicted growth of
34%, but the outturn was 6.5%. For all the mainstream forecasters
to make, simultaneously, errors of this size was extraordinary. A
typical forecasting error then was only 1% for consumer spending. </p>
<p>The reasons why consumer spending grew so much faster than
expected in the late 1980s have been endlessly discussed. The
forecasts which proved so wrong were based on the growth of
incomes. Consumers in the late 1980s spent far beyond their
incomes. Financial deregulation gave them new opportunities to
borrow. They took them with both hands. The result was a huge
surge in spending and in debt. Nobody minded about the debt as
long as their incomes were growing, and their houses were rising
in value. </p>
<h4>A gigantic mistake</h4>
<p>But the sad truth is that the boom was based on a gigantic
mistake. People collectively overestimated their wealth and
future growth prospects. They spent money they did not have.
There had been relatively rapid growth in the 1980s, made
possible by the arrival of our oil wealth, and by the improvement
in economic performance under a more market oriented government.
Since these changes occurred over a long period, they were built
into future growth expectations. But these were oneoff changes.
The growth performance of the 1980s will probably not be repeated
for many years to come. Meanwhile, consumers will have to adjust
their spending to their reduced circumstances. That is the main
economic message of the reemergence of Britain's twin deficits,
the budget deficit and the balance of payments deficit. </p>
<h4>The debt burden</h4>
<p>The adjustment has already begun. In the recession of the
early 1990s, house prices started to fall, and people were
frightened of losing their jobs. Their response was to save more
and reduce their debt. The savings ratio the proportion of
disposable income saved virtually doubled in the space of three
years. But although consumers did succeed in reducing their
collective debttoincome ratio during the recession, the level of
debt is still very high by historic standards. If consumers wish
to reduce the ratio back to the levels seen before the late
1980s, we could be in for a long period of low growth of consumer
spending. That is the first reason for doubting the vigour of
consumer spending in the 1990s. </p>
<h4>Higher taxes</h4>
<p>The second reason for doubt lies in the behaviour of
government finances. The most important single determinant of
consumer spending is the real disposable income of households.
That is a function both of the rate of growth of the economy, and
of the government's tax and spending policies. In the 1980s,
disposable incomes were boosted as the benefit of North Sea oil
(in the form of taxes and royalties) and cuts in public spending
were passed on to consumers through lower taxes. </p>
<p>In recent years oil revenues have started to shrink. It has
become increasingly clear that the underlying burden of public
spending is greater than it appeared in the boom years. The
evidence for this is the sharp rise in the budget deficit. A
&#163;50 billion public sector borrowing requirement is simply
not sustainable. The government has announced its intention of
bringing its finances back to balance in the medium term. It has
accordingly announced, in the two Budgets of 1993, tax increases
building up to some &#163;15 billion by 19956. </p>
<h4>Inflation</h4>
<p>The effects of the high debt burden and the increasing tax
burden may now be compounded by falling inflation. The recession
of the 1990s was only the third since the war in which output
actually fell. The major recesssions of 1975 and 1980 each
reduced inflation by something of the order of 10%. The recent
recession has been just as large. If it were to reduce inflation
by an equal amount, it would take us into the uncharted territory
of falling prices. </p>
<p>Falling prices are bad for business. Nobody will buy today if
prices might be lower tomorrow. Those worrying about their levels
of debt would also see those debts and the cost of servicing them
increasing in real terms. If enough people respond by selling
assets to lighten the load of debt, they may drive down asset
prices even faster than the general price level. So the average
real burden of debt may actually rise overall, as a result of
individual attempts to lighten it. This is what true debt
deflation means. </p>
<p>We are still some way from that point. Mainstream forecasters
expect inflation to rise, not fall. Yet inflation has
persistently surprised the forecasters by coming in lower than
expected last year. In the year after the 15% devaluation of
1967, wage inflation accelerated from 3 to 8 per cent. After the
Black Wednesday devaluation, wage inflation has continued to
fall. Prices are falling across a range of goods and services. </p>
<p>One thing is certain: the buoyant growth of consumer spending
over the 1980s, which many still regard as a norm to which we
will shortly return, is unrepeatable. For a period of almost 15
years, consumer spending grew nearly 1% per annum faster than
output. That was mainly a consequence of the arrival of our oil
wealth and a fall in the tax burden, which in the end proved
unsustainable. As our oil wealth shrinks and the tax burden
rises, consumer spending is from now on likely to grow more
slowly than output. Businesses would do well to factor that
gloomy truth into their forward planning. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1994 </p>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
