    </tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<p>Delay is in the air, and even in the mouths of prominent
German politicians and bankers: but the official position of all
the likely participants is still that 1999 means what it says.
The final moment of assessment - and decision - does not come
until early 1998. By then, proponents of a Single Currency argue,
the recovery of growth in continental Europe will have cut
government deficits. Since a Single Currency without the
Deutschemark is inconceivable, the key issue then is whether the
Germans actually want to go ahead. If they still do, then it is a
fair bet that the criteria will be made to fit. </p>
<p>Some small countries may be able to argue their way under the
wire, if they want to: notably, Denmark and Austria. But will the
French? The table shows that they face severe problems in meeting
the budget test. However, outright rejection would be a desperate
blow to Europe's core Franco-German alliance. Italy's failure to
meet the criteria would also be politically difficult, but less
likely to be papered over. Spain faces similar difficulties,
while Greece seems to be right off the convergence scale. As for
Britain, with its deficit forecast to decline, debt level low,
and inflation down again, it may well be one of the few to meet
the Maastricht criteria. But but thanks to its special
&quot;opt-out&quot; protocol, negotiated in 1991, Britain still
does not have to sign up. </p>
<p>So whether anything at all happens in 1999 is uncertain. An
alternative to delay, less embarrassing to Franco-German
politicians, may be for a few continental countries to go ahead
with a weaker version of the first phase of monetary union. What
is actually intended to happen on the 1st January that year is an
irrevocable fixing of exchange rates between members, so that -
in the words of the EMI - they become &quot;different expressions
of what is economically the same currency&quot;. Though the new
euro will also become a currency in its own right, it is not
intended to start replacing marks and francs and so on with new
notes and coin until 2002. So this first phase could easily be
watered down into a kind of ERM-plus - and, for that matter,
extended. </p>
<h4>Uncommon market</h4>
<p>Nevertheless, the deadline may still divide the European Union
into two camps. And the ripple effects of such division on the
Single Market may be very serious. Not only will the costs of
transition be heavy, for would-be members, but the strains may
well make them less likely to steam ahead with outstanding Single
Market business - in particular, resisting measures that would
open their markets to the &quot;outs&quot; as well as the
&quot;ins&quot;. Already, protectionism is beginning to emerge in
a new guise - with demands, particularly by the French, that
those outside monetary union should not be allowed to
&quot;profit&quot; from a competitive exchange rate. Hence the
urgency of the debate at the IGC that Europe should resolve the
issue of relationships between &quot;ins&quot; and
&quot;outs&quot; before plunging ahead with a partial union. It
would be bitterly ironic if the Single Currency were actually to
damage European economic integration - if the Single Market were
to begin to fragment before the full benefits have even been
realised. </p>
<p><b>Contact: Sarah Hogg</b> </p>
