<h1 align="left"><font size="5"><img src="../../images/bids.gif"
align="left" hspace="0" width="138" height="129"></font></h1>
<h1 align="left"><font size="7">BIDS</font></h1>
<p align="left">&#160; </p>
<h1 align="left"><font size="6"><em>The future of Digital
Television in Europe</em></font></h1>
<p><font size="2">A major research project examining the future
of Europe's digital television and multimedia services has just
been launched and commercial organisations such as yourselves
have the opportunity both to guide and benefit from the outcome
of this study. </font></p>
<p><a href="bidsov2.htm"><font size="2">Project overview</font></a></p>
<p><font size="2">The Broadband Infrastructure for Digital TV and
Multimedia Services project (BIDS) was launched in September 1995
by the European Commission. It forms part of DGXIIIB's research
and technical development programme in advanced communication
technologies and services (ACTS).</font> </p>
<p><font size="2">BIDS aims to provide a comprehensive analysis
of the future of broadband digital television and interactive
multimedia services across Europe. It is intended to present an
authoritative picture of the market for the use of businesses,
regulatory bodies and legislators. </font></p>
<p><font size="2">In particular, the study explores:</font> </p>
<ul>
    <li><font size="2">the economics: the evolution and dynamics
        of demand, costs and revenues, investments and returns;</font> </li>
    <li><font size="2">the impact of technological and regulatory
        factors on infrastructure, competition, service content
        and distribution; and</font> </li>
    <li><font size="2">how regulatory structures should be
        changed to suit the requirements of a changing,
        converging market.</font> </li>
</ul>
<p><font size="2">At the end of this two-year study the
summarised findings will be widely disseminated within ACTS. The
final report is due to be presented in June 1997, accompanied by
a series of workshops.</font> </p>
<h2>An opportunity for commercial participation </h2>
<p><font size="2">Unlike other EU studies of this type, it was
never intended that the BIDS project should be closed or
confidential. The ACTS research programme aims to strengthen
co-operation between government bodies and the media industry,
and DGXIII has fully endorsed involvement from private sector
organisations in this strategically important study.</font> </p>
<p><font size="2"><i>This raises the opportunity for
organisations external to ACTS to become central participants in
the outcome of the study.</i></font> </p>
<p><font size="2">External subscribers will benefit from:</font> </p>
<ul>
    <li><font size="2">five quarterly confidential briefings and
        presentations over the two year period addressing their
        specific needs and interests, such as an in-depth focus
        on individual countries, regulatory or technical
        standards issues;</font> </li>
    <li><font size="2">the opportunity to participate at BIDS'
        steering-group meetings, with an opportunity to
        contribute to the focus of the study and, in turn, to
        strengthen the quality of the research;</font> </li>
    <li><font size="2">advance viewing of, and opportunity to
        comment on working papers of the project.</font> </li>
</ul>
<p><font size="2">External participants are entitled to these
benefits as members of the &quot;BIDS Club&quot; for an
individual subscription fee of 30,000 ECU over the project's
two-year period.</font> </p>
<p><font size="2">Confidentiality between individual sponsors and
BIDS will be respected as required.</font> </p>
<h2>Management of the Study</h2>
<p><font size="2">Conducting the study are four of Europe's
leading media consultants and industry organisations: <i>IDATE </i>(from
France) is a world leader in the analysis of media corporations
and markets. <i>Fundesco</i> (from Spain) has considerable
experience in the study of social and economic trends in the
media.<i> London Economics</i> is Britain's leading independent
economic consultancy; its media practice pioneered quantified
modelling of demand and employment in the audio-visual sector
across Europe. <i>T&eacute;l&eacute;diffusion de France, TDF,</i>
will contribute its considerable research and technological
knowledge to the project.</font> </p>
<h3>For further information on how to subscribe to BIDS, your UK
contacts at London Economics are:</h3>
<p><font size="2">Sarah Hogg <br>
</font><a href="mailto:sarah@londecon.co.uk"><font size="2">email:
sarah@londecon.co.uk</font> </a></p>
<p><font size="2">Jonathan Davis <br>
</font><a href="mailto:jdavis@londecon.co.uk"><font size="2">email:
jdavis@londecon.co.uk</font> </a></p>
<p><font size="2"><b>Address</b></font> <br>
<font size="2">66 Chiltern Street, London, W1M 1PR</font> <font
size="2">Tel: +44 171 446 8400 Fax: +44 171 446 8484/5</font> </p>
