<html>
<head>
<title>The Economics of Auctions</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>The Economics of Auctions</h2>
<p><strong><i>As the broadcasting industry awaits the results of
the auction for the new franchises for Independent Television
(what we must learn to call Channel 3), it seems that things have
gone seriously awry. </i></strong></p>
<hr>
<p>Some bidders reportedly TVS may have paid too much. Others
reportedly STV and Central may have won a valuable franchise for
virtually nothing. And still others reportedly Granada may have
lost the contest by making an error in their bidding strategy. In
each case, the government risks embarrassment. There may be
franchisees whose financial viability is in doubt, others with a
newly issued 'licence to print money'. Britain's best regarded
commercial broadcaster may be taken off the air. </p>
<p>If both government and bidders had understood fully the
principles of auction bidding matters would have worked out
better. This area of study was pioneered by American economist
William Vickrey. Auction theory has been applied commercially
most often in the US government auctions for offshore oil
drilling rights. But it has applications in many other contexts
in mergers and acquisitions, the property market, and now
television. An auction is not necessarily a process conducted by
an auctioneer with a hammer in a plush W1 saleroom. Every time a
single seller confronts a number of competing buyers, an auction
is in progress and the lessons of auction theory are relevant. </p>
<h4>Uncertainty</h4>
<p>Auctions are used when there is uncertainty about how much an
item is worth. These uncertainties are of two main kinds.
Different bidders may attach different values to the object of
the auction. The seller does not know what the distribution of
values is (and the buyers will be unwilling to tell him). This is
the usual pattern in the saleroom, when Sotheby's sell a valuable
picture or piece of furniture. Everyone agrees on what the object
is but some buyers value it more highly than others. </p>
<p>This <i>private value</i> auction can be contrasted with what
is known as a <i>common value</i> auction, where the object is of
the same value to all the bidders and the uncertainty is about
what that value is. Oil companies make different bids for the
same offshore block because neither they nor the government can
be sure how much oil is actually out there. If they did know, all
would bid much the same price. </p>
<p>The distinction is important to bidders because common value
auctions are characterised by what is known as the &quot;winner's
curse&quot;. Your geologists will sometimes overestimate,
sometimes underestimate, the potential of an offshore block.
These errors do not cancel each other out. You are much more
likely to be successful in the auction if you have overestimated
the value than if you have underestimated it. If you bid up to
your full valuation in a common value auction, you will on
balance lose money. TVS may have fallen victim to the winner's
curse, and so have many British firms making US acquisitions. </p>
<h4>Extracting full value</h4>
<p>On the seller's side, there are different mechanisms for
extracting full value from the auction. Two of the most common
are the open outcry system, as used in the saleroom, and the
sealed bid system, which is the government's chosen method for
television franchises. In the open outcry method, the winner gets
the object for a little more than the second highest bidder was
willing to pay. </p>
<p>Open outcry has the advantages that it rarely pays bidders to
behave strategically, to try to pull the wool over the eyes of
their rivals or to stop bidding. It works against the seller
because it invites buyers to conspire together (the notorious and
illegal auction rings) and it does not get the maximum the buyer
might have been willing to pay. But the neither does a sealed bid
auction, precisely because welladvised buyers will behave
strategically, and bid a carefully calculated sum less than they
believe the object is worth. </p>
<p>Vickrey showed that for a private value auction (but not a
common value one) open outcry and sealed bid methods are, on
average, equally rewarding to the seller. With an element of
common value, however, open outcry will usually yield a figure
closer to the true value, because the auction process itself
yields information which makes bidders more confident in their
valuations. </p>
<h4>Why sealed bids?</h4>
<p>So why did the government choose the sealed bid system? The
basic problem is that it surrounded the auction by political
constraints which made it difficult for any auction to work well. </p>
<p>Three are particularly significant the quality threshold,
which made bidding expensive; the government's own fear of
derision if the procedure too clearly resembled those of
Sotheby's; and the restriction on franchisees selling on their
rights before 1994. </p>
<p>There are several procedures which would have worked a good
deal better, both in extracting revenue and in putting the right
broadcaster in the right slot. The auction saleroom has always
been a dangerous place for the unwary to enter. An inexperienced
auctioneer the British government and its Independent Television
Commission and some naive bidders among the would be
broadcasters, are learning that lesson the hard way. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1991 </p>
</body>
</html>
