<html>
<head>
<title>Oscars for London Economics</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Oscars for London Economics</h2>
<p><i>In the last 10 years the structure of the film industry has
undergone a radical transformation, brought about by the
emergence of video. In 1980 ownership of video cassette recorders
(VCRs) was relatively uncommon, but in the last 10 years this has
changed: VCRs are becoming almost as commonplace as televisions
and hifi. Nowhere in Europe has this been more pronounced than in
the UK, where ownership of VCRs has risen to almost 70% of
households. </i></p>
<hr>
<p>The growth of VCR ownership has opened up a completely new
market for film makers, which they have been quick to exploit. In
1980 the value of the video feature film market was almost zero.
By 1989 this had grown to a staggering &#163;560 million in the
UK alone, outstripping by a ratio of more than 2:1 the value of
the traditional market for feature films: cinema. </p>
<p>In other more conventional markets, such an increase in the
size of the market would normally lead to an increase in the
number of products being supplied to the market. Analysis
undertaken at London Economics suggests that this has not been
the case in the film industry. The number of feature films
released in the UK in 1980 was 219. By 1989 this had hardly
changed, with 230 films released in total. How can this be
explained? Where is all this additional revenue going? </p>
<p>Average revenue per film is certainly higher than it has ever
been. However, this does not mean that profits earned on films
are correspondingly higher. On the contrary, films continue to be
a high risk investment with few of them covering their costs, let
alone making profits. At least part of the answer lies in the
increased budgets of feature films, especially US
&quot;blockbuster&quot; films designed to appeal to the mass
market across the world. </p>
<p>As revenue per film has increased, so film makers have
increasingly used these funds to make higher budget films, with
more expensive special effects. Moreover, to ensure that their
films have the highest possible chance of success they have
increasingly focused on &quot;branding&quot; their films, by
using well known directors, producers and actors. The large US
film makers used to operate a &quot;studio&quot; system whereby
actors and directors were tied to one particular studio, and were
not free to negotiate deals on a film by film basis. This system
has now broken down, so there is increased competition among the
large studios for a relatively small number of &quot;star&quot;
actors and directors whose reputations mean their films will
automatically attract large audiences. This has had the
additional effect of increasing the number of agents, as their
job is to negotiate the best deals they can for their clients.
Agents representing the most successful names in the industry are
themselves able to earn significant sums of money, and are also
responsible for appropriating some of this additional revenue. </p>
<p>At present, cinema attendances are falling in the US.
Hollywood is teetering on the brink of recession. <i>Hook</i>,
the new Spielberg blockbuster, will signpost the path for the
future. If it is as popular as its megabudget predecessor, <i>Terminator
2</i>, then high budget films may continue to be seen as the
foremost vehicle for success. If not, studios may need to reduce
their exposure to box office failure by cutting budgets again. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
</body>
</html>
