<html>
<head>
<title>The Competitive Advantage of Geography</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>The Competitive Advantage of Geography</h2>
<p><strong><i>It is fifty years since southern California became
the centre of the world's film industry. Film makers were
attracted by the benevolence of the climate, and the sharpness of
the light. With modern technology, these factors are far less
important.</i></strong></p>
<hr>
<p>Yet why is the dominance of Hollywood stronger than ever? The
answers, contained in a London Economics report, provide an
understanding of how films are made, and show how particular
geographical locations come to have, and lose, competitive
advantage in particular industries locations from Manhattan to
the Brescia Valley, industries from financial services to metal
working. </p>
<p>Michael Porter's <i>The Competitive Advantage of Nations</i>
focused on geographical clusters. Porter's 'diamonds' of
competitive advantage arise, he argues, when local industries are
reinforced by demanding customers and the growth of supporting
supply relationships. These factors are important to Hollywood,
but they are not the heart of the matter. </p>
<p>Above everything, Hollywood is a market. Creating a film
requires a long list of services screenplay and music; production
and direction; stars and extras; camera crew and lighting
expertise. (Stay for a moment at the end of the next film you
watch and see just how long that list is). The 'thickest' market
the market with the largest volume of trade is generally the most
attractive for both buyers and sellers. It offers the keenest
prices and the widest range of products. That in turn brings in
more trade. So the initial attraction is reinforced. And with the
presence of markets comes the exchange of information. Hollywood
gossip is notorious, but it has a serious function. Without
access to it, anyone who wants to make, or participate, in a film
suffers a disadvantage. So although Britain, and Australia, have
developed distinguished film talent, much of that talent has
recognised that the best market to sell its services is in
Hollywood. </p>
<p>The competitive advantage of Hollywood is remarkably like the
competitive advantage of London in eurobonds or in insurance, of
Chicago in derivative securities, of Wall Street in American
stocks and of the Northern Italian valley of Lumazzone with its
metal working capabilities. The historical reasons why markets
should have developed there are no longer relevant. The market
developed where it did, and it requires exceptional strength, or
exceptional weakness, for the incumbent to be displaced. The
advantages of the incumbent the depth of market and the
information exchange and services that surround it remain real.
Even if monetary authority were to drain from London, as smog has
obscured the light of Los Angeles, these factors would remain
potent. </p>
<p>But the force of incumbent advantage is not ground for
complacency. The Swiss watch industry once enjoyed analogous
benefits, which vanished as technical change made the
organisational knowledge of the Swiss watch markets irrelevant.
Fifty years earlier, the craft stalls of the British shipbuilding
industry and the internal market it supported enjoyed a similar
nemesis. Some of the competitive advantages of geography are
enduring. Others die, as technology changes the nature of that
advantage or renders its supporting systems of knowledge and
information obsolete. To understand the nature of competitive
advantage it is necessary to understand its basis, and to
distinguish one case from the other. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
</body>
</html>
