<html>
<head>
<title>ITV: Regulation, Recession and Crisis</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>ITV: Regulation, Recession and Crisis</h2>
<p><i>In the wake of the Channel 3 auction, ITV may have retained
its name but everything else about the UK's commercial television
system has changed, and changed more than anyone could have
imagined or wanted. The primary source of this change is the
economic recession. </i></p>
<hr>
<p>The plans to open up commercial television in the UK were
forged in the heat of the Lawson boom. They were predicated on
that boom going on forever and being predictable. </p>
<p>The fragility of the plans to open up ITV can already be seen:
in May 1991 when applicants submitted their bids, it was
generally believed that advertising revenues would increase in
real terms by 20 per cent or more between 1991 and 1994. In
eighteen months, the outlook has been transformed. </p>
<h4>Advertising</h4>
<p>In 1991, ITV advertising revenues fell in real terms by 6.3
per cent, followed by a further 0.5 per cent fall in 1992. It is
now anticipated that, at best, 1993 will be flat and the
prospects for 1994 are not much more promising. This outlook in
line with November's Treasury forecasts and with the Centre for
Economic Forecasting's October figures for consumer expenditure
growth (which tends to correlate with advertising expenditure).
So instead of the 20 per cent rise anticipated by ITV companies
in calculating their bids, there will be, in all likelihood, a 5%
reduction. </p>
<p>Overall, the expected value of the sector has fallen by more
than half since the new regime was established. </p>
<p>Under the old regulatory system, a government levy creamed off
a progressively increasing share of advertising revenue. So the
government shared booms and busts with the companies. No longer.
Under the auction system introduced last year, each company's
costs are largely fixed. The 25% advertising shortfall is
unlikely to reduce the industry's costs by more than 2%. </p>
<h4>Winners and losers</h4>
<p>When the winning bids were announced some companies had
committed virtually nothing. Central Television had bid
&#163;2,000 against annual advertising revenues of &#163;220
million. Other companies had bet the far - Yorkshire/Tyne Tees
bidding &#163;52.8 million against revenues of &#163;177 million.
This is the background to the current fall in revenues. Companies
which bid low would see their margins considerably eroded while
those which bid high would see anticipated profits reduced by
80%. in some cases losses would quadruple. For the system as a
whole, from a late-1992 vantage point, it looked as if ITV's net
present value had fallen 58% relative to the way it looked in
October 1991. </p>
<p>The ITV system could not survive this change of economic
circumstances without an accommodation being made, in terms of
reduced programme obligations, more concentrated ownership (to
reallocate profits and losses), or a reduction in payments to the
Treasury. </p>
<p>What has happened is that the ITV companies (with the tacit
approval of the regulators, the Independent Television
Commission) have cut their network programme budgets by around
&#163;100 million - 20% from the levels they promised in May 1991
and the Commission certified in October 1991. </p>
<p>The moral of the situation - which could be the verdict on ITV
throughout its history - is that it is impossible to impose a
regulatory framework at odds with the economic circumstances in
which the activities to be regulated take place. The flaw of the
regulatory framework established for ITV in 1990 is that it is to
brittle, in the face of economic hardship, to do anything but
break. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
</body>
</html>
