<html>
<head>
<title>Cultural Protectionism in Europe</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Cultural Protectionism in Europe</h2>
<p><i>The old Common Market was created to promote free trade.
The new European Union has become increasingly protectionist. The
1989 Directive requires broadcasters in the Member States to
&quot;reserve for European works a majority of their transmission
time&quot; . Does such protectionism serve any purpose? A recent
London Economics project, commissioned by Sony Entertainment to
review the impact of the quotas, suggests not.</i></p>
<hr>
<h4>TV without frontiers</h4>
<p>The television quotas proposed in the European Directive
&quot;TV without frontiers&quot; are intended to make
broadcasters switch from imported, probably US, fiction and
documentaries to locally made production. The aim is to protect
local culture, and indeed local TV programme production. Yet due
to vast discrepancies between first run and secondary rights
costs, the programmes are not strictly substitutable. Faced with
a large potential increase in costs, many broadcasters will
simply avoid the quota by switching out of the programming genres
subject to quotas. They could drop &quot;oeuvre&quot; output like
drama and documentaries and schedule sport or gameshows instead. </p>
<p>Or the broadcasters might meet the quota by running lowcost
European soap operas, with low audience appeal, in offpeak
periods. In either case, the hopedfor substitution of imports
with expensive newlycommissioned &quot;oeuvre&quot; programming
simply will not happen. </p>
<h4>Harmful quotas</h4>
<p>The protective measures are also <i>anti competitive.</i>
Quotas do not affect the programme output of wellestablished
channels such as the BBC, ZDF or TF1 (which are already in
compliance). Only the new entrants, such as BSkyB, RTL2 and M6,
are affected. Quotas make it more difficult for them to compete.
They will have to replace cheap and popular imported material
(mainly American) with much more expensive locally commissioned
programming. </p>
<p>As a result, quotas may force new entrants out of business.
This is <i>harmful to the promotion of European television
production </i>. New entrant channels will increasingly
commission new local programming (which attracts the highest
audiences) as soon as they become established and can afford to
do so. </p>
<p>The quotas also inhibit <i>the creation of jobs in the
audiovisual sector</i>. The anticompetitive effects of quotas
will delay (and in some cases prevent) the introduction of new
channels especially subscription and payperview channels. It is
these new channels which will encourage increased consumer
spending on television and higher employment in the sector. More
new channels form an important part of the recipe for the
development of the muchheralded and economically significant
&quot;digital super highways&quot;. </p>
<p>Our report is based on an analysis of the television sectors
in France, Germany and the UK. These markets are currently worth
over ECU 14 billion each year. The report shows that their future
growth is compromised by the quotas. The cost of quotas on future
growth could be in the range ECU 420 billion. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Back to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1994 </p>
</body>
</html>
