<html>
<head>
<title>Reining in the media barons</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Reining in the media barons</h2>
<p><strong><i>The government wants to maintain a plurality of
sources of information and opinion in the media while allowing
major companies to take advantages of the opportunities provided
by the multi-media revolution. So cross media ownership will be
no longer be forbidden, but governed by new regulations based on
market shares. How can these be measured? London Economics was
asked by the BBC to examine the alternatives.</i></strong></p>
<hr>
<h4>Market share as a measure of influence</h4>
<p>The use of market share is borrowed from competition policy
where it plays an important role. A high market share, typically
measured by share of revenue, indicates market power and (if the
market is not easy to enter) the opportunity for abuse (excessive
margins, restrictions on supply). In the media markets (e.g. for
game shows, soaps and sitcoms) ordinary competition rules should
generally suffice to prevent any abuse of market power. But in
the market for news and information there may be excessive
influence at much lower levels of market share. For this reason
it is important to recognise that the market for news is
different from the market for entertainment and use measures of
market share which reflect that difference. </p>
<h4>Alternative measures of influence</h4>
<p>There are many different ways of measuring market share, and
many different ways of exerting influence. There is no single
measure of market share that captures all the dimensions of
influence of a medium of communication. That depends on the <i>number</i>of
people reached; on <i>who</i> those people are - whether they, in
turn, are influential; on the amount of <i>time</i> they spend
absorbing the messages transmitted; on the amount they will <i>pay </i>for
that information and how much <i>attention </i>they give it. Some
of these elements are captured by the three principal ways of
measuring market share: by counting heads, time spent or money.
Others are more difficult or impossible to measure. </p>
<h4>Audience share</h4>
<p>For some measures (e.g. numbers of viewers, listeners or
readers) it is quite easy to compute shares in each medium. But
if a particular controller has a large share of television and a
much smaller share of the press, what is his overall share of the
market? Some judgement is needed on the relative influence of
television, radio and the national and regional press. Under
different weighting systems we find that the BBC share of the
total media audience/ readership is 19-20 per cent, compared with
11-13 per cent for News International, 7-8 per cent for the
Mirror Group. </p>
<h4>Reach</h4>
<p>An alternative way of counting heads is to look at the number
of people who have contact with a medium over a given time period
(usually a week). On this measure, the so-called reach of the
BBC, with its varied output, is higher than its audience share,
at 26 per cent of the total, compared with 7 per cent for News
International and 5 per cent for the Mirror Group. </p>
<h4>Time use</h4>
<p>Data on time use provides an alternative unit of measurement,
which has the advantage of applying across all the media. But the
amount of time spent consuming a particular media product is a
poor proxy for its influence - newspaper headlines for example,
taken in at a glance, have influence out of all proportion to the
time taken to absorb them. And people can have the television or
radio playing for much of the time without paying much attention
to it. The fact that the BBC accounts for 45 per cent of all the
time spent consuming media products, whereas News International
accounts for 4 per cent and the Mirror Group for less than 2 per
cent, is not an accurate reflection of their respective
influence. </p>
<h4>Time use weighted by money</h4>
<p>Advertisers are in the business of buying influence, and what
they spend on different media is another way of measuring
influence. Total advertising spending on television is only 20
per cent more than in the newspapers, even though the nation
passes seven times as many hours each week in front of the
television as reading the newspapers. Advertisers clearly believe
that the press is more influential (per unit of time spent) than
television. They will spend four times as much for a contact
minute in the press as on television. If we give the time use
figure for each medium a premium which reflects the value placed
on it by advertisers, we find the BBC share shrinks to 30 per
cent, while News International increases to 12 per cent and the
Mirror Group to 7 per cent. </p>
<h4>Revenue</h4>
<p>Influence depends not just on how many receive the message,
but on who they are. The media which reach the better off and the
opinion-formers are able to command much higher advertising
rates. A page in the Financial Times costs more than a page in
the Sun, which has 14 times as many readers. Clearly FT readers
are valued much more highly than Sun readers. For this reason
advertising revenues, which are common to all the media, are a
good proxy for influence. They reflect both the number of people
reached and how influential they are. </p>
<p>The other major sources of revenue, the cover price of
newspapers and subscriptions to television channels, also
indicate the value of media products to those consuming them -
which in turn probably bears some relation to their influence. On
the revenue measure the BBC accounts for only 17 per cent of all
media output, whereas News International accounts for 12 per cent
and the Mirror Group for 6 per cent. </p>
<h4>Conclusions</h4>
<p>Each of the above measures reveals something about the
influence of different media companies. They should be applied to
different product markets, distinguishing news and opinion, where
pluralism is vital, from entertainment, where normal competition
law should suffice. The measures should probably be computed
excluding the BBC, whose Charter provides a separate guarantee of
pluralism. </p>
<p>There is a strong case for applying market share thresholds to
local markets and to individual media outlets. The rationale in
both cases is to prevent those who live in certain locations, or
those who depend exclusively on one medium, from the undue
influence of a single media company. </p>
<p>There is clearly no unique measure of influence. The market
share of each company can be very different under the different
measures. Most measures have something to tell us but there is no
mechanical computation which will reveal whether a company is
exerting excessive influence. The regulator will need to look at
all the measures before he or she decides that a company's market
share is too high, just as the Chancellor of the Exchequer looks
at a variety of measures of inflation before deciding whether or
not to tighten monetary policy. </p>
<p><i>Contact: Stephen Banks, <br>
Bill Robinson</i> </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1995 </p>
</body>
</html>
