<html>
<head>
<title>Bids project overview</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/paper.jpg" text="#000080">
<h1 align="center"><font size="5"><img
src="../../images/bids.gif" align="left" hspace="0" width="138"
height="129"></font></h1>
<h1 align="left"><font size="7">BIDS</font></h1>
<p align="left">&#160; </p>
<h2 align="center"><font size="2">Broadband Infrastructure for
Digital TV and Multimedia Services (ACTS Project AC025)</font><br>
<font size="2">An Overview of the B.I.D.S Project by LONDON
ECONOMICS in association with IDATE, FUNDESCO AND TDF</font></h2>
<hr>
<h2 align="left">Contents </h2>
<ol>
    <li><a href="#bIntroduction ">Introduction. </a></li>
    <li><a href="#bA background">A background to BIDS' role in
        the ACTS programme. </a></li>
    <li><a href="#bAims ">BIDS Aims. </a></li>
    <li><a href="#bStructure ">Structure of the BIDS project . </a></li>
    <li><a href="#bDissemination ">Dissemination. </a></li>
    <li><a href="#bThe BIDS Consortium ">The BIDS Consortium. </a></li>
    <li><a href="#bFinancing ">Financing. </a></li>
    <li><a href="#bAdditional Participants">Additional
        Participants to the BIDS project. </a></li>
    <li><a href="#bContacts">Contacts for further information
        about BIDS. </a></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2><a name="bIntroduction ">Introduction </a></h2>
<p><font size="3">BIDS or &quot;The Broadband Infrastructure for
Digital TV and Multimedia Services&quot; project was formally
launched in September 1995 by DGXIIIB of the European Commission
under its research and technical development programme in
advanced communication technologies and services (ACTS).</font><font
size="4"> </font></p>
<p><font size="3">A part of the European Commission's strategic
research programme Framework Four, the ACTS programme was
launched in September 1994 with a budget of ECU 630 million. ACTS
succeeds RACE within the area of advanced communications
technologies as a platform for collaborative research and
development aimed specifically at developing application trials.</font><font
size="4"> </font></p>
<p><font size="3">Most projects which apply to the ACTS programme
are for large-scale co-operative R&amp;D. Successful candidates
will play a key role in building partnerships and elaborating the
technical means and applications which will drive the
construction of the information infrastructure required by Europe
to ensure greater productivity, social welfare and international
competitiveness.</font><font size="4"> </font></p>
<p><font size="3">However, there is a real need to consider the
relevance and practicalities of implementing the projects being
pursued throughout Europe in reference to the economic,
regulatory and technological framework in which such
implementation will take place. </font></p>
<p><font size="3">In this context, the current BIDS project was
conceived to provide a comprehensive analysis of the future of
broadband digital television and interactive multimedia services
across Europe It is intended to present an authoritative picture
of the market for the use of businesses, regulatory bodies and
legislators. </font></p>
<p><font size="3">In particular, the study explores:</font><font
size="4"> </font></p>
<ul>
    <li><font size="3">the impact of technological and regulatory
        factors on infrastructure, competition, service content
        and distribution;</font><font size="4"> </font></li>
    <li><font size="3">how regulatory structures should be
        changed to suit the requirements of a changing,
        converging market;</font><font size="4"> </font></li>
    <li><font size="3">the economics: the evolution and dynamics
        of demand, costs and revenues, investments and returns;
        and</font><font size="4"> </font></li>
    <li><font size="3">proposes a global strategy for the
        introduction of digital TV and multimedia services,
        identifying key parameters and bottlenecks.</font><font
        size="4"> </font></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2><a name="bA background">A background to BIDS' role in the
ACTS programme </a></h2>
<p><font size="3">Unlike the United States, where evolution of
the new infrastructure is being pursued by horizontally and
vertically integrated firms present across the entire territory
and financed mainly by direct payments by users (telephone, cable
and satellite subscribers, home video users, video games players,
cinema-goers etc.), the prevailing form of finance in Europe is
indirect, notably through licence fees and advertising air-time
sales, and highly fragmented. In addition, public service
television still largely predominates.</font><font size="4"> </font></p>
<p><font size="3">On-line multimedia products and services have
not yet developed to any significant extent; early adopters of
those services look largely to the US for both network facilities
and content.</font><font size="4"> </font></p>
<p><font size="3">Across Europe, moreover, the very different
situations that are encountered in terms of the nature and
relationship of the various distribution networks, with cable and
satellite, in particular, are at very different stages of growth
and with very different characteristics and outlooks.</font><font
size="4"> </font></p>
<p><font size="3">In short, potential providers of new services
face a panoply of different market conditions in terms of:</font><font
size="4"> </font></p>
<ul>
    <li><font size="3">technological characteristics, relating to
        capacity and the presence of or need for a return path;</font><font
        size="4"> </font></li>
    <li><font size="3">regulation, notably the relationship
        between telecommunications and broadcast networks;</font><font
        size="4"> </font></li>
    <li><font size="3">commercialisation, for example, the
        presence or absence of an installed subscriber base;</font><font
        size="4"> </font></li>
    <li><font size="3">structural factors, for example, whether
        network operation and service provision are carried out
        by the same firm or by different firms (with varying
        configurations, access conditions etc.); and</font><font
        size="4"> </font></li>
    <li><font size="3">financial considerations which vary, for
        example, for digital terrestrial television, digital
        satellite services and cable. </font></li>
</ul>
<p><font size="3">The strategy adopted by players will depend on
their perception of the evolution of market demand, with new
services bringing in new sources of revenue and new investment.
In the short term, digital transmission allows channels to
multiply and interactive multimedia services to develop. In the
medium term, the need for greater interactivity will necessitate
complementary investment in the technology infrastructure to
provide return paths.</font><font size="4"> </font></p>
<p><font size="3">Although global studies exist on the demand for
digital programmes and services, no study has yet taken account
of the structure of each market. Moreover, the BIDS consortium
has yet to identify a single study conducted on the competitive
situation of new distribution infrastructures as regards the
introduction of new services. In addition, no global studies yet
exist on the economics of those new services and the ability of
players to finance the necessary investment and how the sharing
out of the added value between different players will take place.</font><font
size="4"> </font></p>
<hr>
<h2><a name="bAims ">BIDS Aims </a></h2>
<p><font size="3">The BIDS project addresses the need for a
comparative analysis, based on a consistent and comprehensive
conceptual framework, capable of assessing the various digital TV
and interactive multimedia applications and the market for
services across and in each of the European Union's fifteen
member states.</font><font size="4"> </font></p>
<p><font size="3">BIDS' central objective will be to provide an
authoritative picture of market developments by examining the
emerging links between existing infrastructures in each country,
players' strategies, and the growth of IBC (Interactive Broadband
Communications) infrastructures. The project's added value will
be in establishing realistic scenarios for the introduction of
digital TV. </font></p>
<p><font size="3">The starting-point of the BIDS project is the
need to take into account the structure of each national market
in identifying the infrastructure available and required and
assessing the opportunities and obstacles for the development of
digital TV and interactive multimedia services. BIDS will also
address the competitive situations for the new distribution
infrastructure in each member state through identification of
technological and regulatory barriers which may impede the
establishment of necessary infrastructure, access and
interconnection. Finally, BIDS will provide an economic framework
within which to consider the potential for new digital TV and
interactive multimedia services and the infrastructure to support
them, the ability of players to invest in both infrastructure and
services, notably to permit the migration and evolution of
existing services into the new infrastructure, and the eventual
sharing out of added value between producers, publishers,
distributors, service providers and network operators. </font></p>
<hr>
<h2><a name="bStructure ">Structure of the BIDS project </a></h2>
<p><font size="3">The project started on 1 September 1995 for the
first year of a two-year study. It is structured as series of
work packages (WPs), each supervised by one of the consortium
partners. Approximately half of the work will be completed in the
first year.</font><font size="4"> </font></p>
<p><font size="3">Deliverables include a series of reports
covering the following topics for each member state, and on a
European-wide basis</font><font size="4"> </font></p>
<ul>
    <li><font size="3">WP2 addresses the competitive situation of
        the different broadband network infrastructures (TV,
        cable, satellite and telephony), applications and markets
        in the member states (Year 1);</font><font size="4"> </font></li>
    <li><font size="3">WP3 looks at the regulatory barriers
        affecting the convergence and implementation of telecoms
        and audio-visual services (Year 1);</font><font size="4"> </font></li>
    <li><font size="3">WP4 describes the structure of the
        television and interactive multimedia markets and
        assesses current strategies of the principal players
        (Year 1);</font><font size="4"> </font></li>
    <li><font size="3">WP5 provides a techno-economic analysis
        and modelling of digital TV and interactive multimedia
        services (Year 2);</font><font size="4"> </font></li>
    <li><font size="3">WP6 proposes scenarios for the evolution
        of market structures and the introduction of digital TV
        and interactive multimedia services (Year 2); </font></li>
</ul>
<p><font size="3">WP1 performs a co-ordinating role over the two
years. A central feature of the work package will be the
contributory role of BIDS project to the ACTS programme in
assisting application-led projects as follows:</font><font
size="4"> </font></p>
<ul>
    <li><font size="3">providing regulatory and market analysis
        information on the television and interactive multimedia
        sectors; and</font><font size="4"> </font></li>
    <li><font size="3">providing support to those ACTS consortia
        dedicated to consumer/residential end-user applications
        of digital television and interactive multimedia in the
        preparation of their trials. </font></li>
</ul>
<p><font size="3">Alongside BIDS, a number of other horizontal
projects (FAIR, HORIZON, PANEuropE, EPRIWATCH, INFOWIN, SMARTS)
will be supplying information and dissemination support to the
ACTS programme. BIDS is liaising with these other projects over
the sharing and organisation of common areas of data collection
and dissemination. In particular, BIDS has established a close
level of co-operation with FAIR (Forecast and Assessment of
Socio-Economic Impact of Advanced Communications and
Recommendations).</font><font size="4"> </font></p>
<p><font size="3">A commonly identified weakness of previous ACTS
projects was the tendency to fail to adopt common technical
standards proposed by Europe's Digital Video Broadcasting
project, or DVB. In response to this, the ACTS programme
requested that BIDS act as the principal link between the DVB
project and the ACTS programme. As numerous individual DVB
members are already participants across a range of ACTS projects,
they would have direct input to the BIDS project. It is in this
context that one of BIDS' aims will be to ensure the
dissemination of DVB developments and recommended technical
standards across the ACTS programme. Similar links are being
pursued with other relevant international organisations such as
DAVIC (the Digital Audio-Visual Council).</font><font size="4"> </font></p>
<hr>
<h2><a name="bDissemination ">Dissemination </a></h2>
<p><font size="3">The BIDS research findings will be made
available as individual reports through the Commission, in
industry publications, and on e-mail networks. A single report
conceived for policy-makers will also be made available. The
individual reports will be integrated into a final report, which
is expected to be presented in June 1997 to coincide with IDATE's
annual conference, along with a proposed series of workshops.</font><font
size="4"> </font></p>
<hr>
<h2><a name="bThe BIDS Consortium ">The BIDS Consortium </a></h2>
<p><font size="3">The BIDS consortium includes three leading
research organisations and an industry leader. Co-ordinating the
consortium is IDATE in France. The other partners include
FUNDESCO in Spain, London Economics in the UK and TDF in France.
All partners are experienced and well-respected for their work in
the audio-visual and telecommunications sectors, at both national
and international levels. On-going work covers industrial policy,
regulation, strategy, impact of new technologies and studies of
established and emerging markets. IDATE is a world leader in the
analysis of media corporations and markets. FUNDESCO has
unrivalled experience in the study of social and economic trends
in the media. London Economics has pioneered the modelling of
demand and employment in the audio-visual sector across Europe.
Our combined contributions will be complemented by TDF,
T&eacute;l&eacute;diffusion de France with its strengths in
research and its knowledge of the technical issues surrounding
digital services.</font><font size="4"> </font></p>
<p><font size="3">Under the ACTS programme's second call for
project proposals, extensions to the project from additional
contributors are under discussion, including an extension to
cover Central and Eastern European countries within the findings
generated by the BIDS project from September 1996. </font></p>
<hr>
<h2><a name="bFinancing ">Financing </a></h2>
<p><font size="3">The project has received 380,000 ECU in funding
from the European Commission over two years.</font><font size="4"> </font></p>
<hr>
<h2><a name="bAdditional Participants">Additional Participants to
the BIDS project </a></h2>
<p><font size="3">The ACTS programme is specifically aimed at
strengthening government/media industry co-operation. With the
backing of DGXIIIB, the BIDS consortium intends to extend
participation in the project to outside organisations and private
industry players, in exchange for access to the ACTS programme
and a wider forum in which to debate their concerns and
interests, as well as tailored reports, seminars, briefings and
presentations of BIDS' findings.</font><font size="4"> </font></p>
<hr>
