<html>
<head>
<title>Gambling for good causes</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Gambling for good causes</h2>
<p><i>In March 1992, the Government published a White Paper
containing plans to introduce a National Lottery in the UK in
support of &quot;good causes&quot;. </i></p>
<hr>
<p>Many people greet the proposed state lottery with a degree of
suspicion or distaste. The desire to make a lot of money with
minimal effort is hardly among the most desirable of human
motives, but this is an opportunity as well as a problem. </p>
<p>We are already tax smoking and drinking heavily, irrespective
of the health risks. We taxed tobacco heavily before there was
any suggestion that smoking harmed health. People do not mind be
in taxed so much when it is associated with activities which they
perceive as mildly sinful. Like smoking and drinking, gambling at
long odds is an activity which can be taxed heavily without
resistance or resentment. A national lottery would exploit that
puritanical streak and it would benefit both tax payers at large
and good causes. </p>
<p>London Economics has recently prepared a report on the
prospects of a national lottery in the UK. The report assesses
the potential of such a lottery against the background of
gambling more generally in the UK and in the light of the
experience of other countries. It explains how modern lotteries
work, how they might be run, estimate what such a lottery would
raise, who would participate, and review the arguments for and
against. </p>
<p>There are social problems associated with gambling. Some
participate beyond their means. For others - not necessarily poor
- gambling becomes addictive. Forms of gambling which tend to
attract this behaviour are those where the outcome emerges
rapidly and which allow many bets in a single session. Lotteries
are not like that, although modern lotteries are often designed
to have elements of it in their make up. It would be desirable
that such elements should be limited. But in the main,
participation in a national lottery would be innocuous if
unprofitable. </p>
<p>A national lottery might have damaging effects on other
established activities. It would imply substantial loss of
revenue for football Pools. It would also, in the form in which
it would prove most attractive to participants, be likely to
damage small lotteries. The fact that the introduction of a new
activity would damage old ones is not in itself a valid argument
against it. If this line were taken generally there would be no
new products, no new industries, and no new firms. </p>
<p>A ticket for a lottery is, in economic terms, a bad buy. Few
lotteries return more than half the taking in prizes to
participants although the evidence we have found suggests that
lottery promoters may be too greedy for their own good.
Economists have not found it easy to explain why people should
wish to enter lotteries. This seems mainly to be a difficulty for
economists, however - most people encounter no difficulty at all
in seeing why people choose to enter lotteries. The problem here
does indeed lie with economics rather than the world, and the
need to account for this apparently irrational behaviour has
indeed led to some rethinking of basic principles of economic
theory. There is evidence that many people over-estimate the
probabilities associated with unlikely events, and under-estimate
those that apply to probable events. That is why not enough
people back the favourite in a race, and betting on long shots
offers a particularly poor return. And many people enter
lotteries because they do not fully grasp that unlikely events
are indeed very unlikely. </p>
<p>However, participants derive pleasure from anticipating
outcomes even when these outcomes do not occur. It is that
pleasure that may have a social as well as a private function. It
is only the lottery or the Pools which enable most of the
population to continue to imagine that they might one day be
rich. </p>
<p>A central issue is the disposition of the revenues of a
lottery. There is widespread consensus that the proceeds of a
lottery should not simply disappear into the Exchequer, should
not substitute for central and popular items of public spending
like health and education, but should be devoted to items of the
kind suggested in the Government's White Paper - sports, the
arts, and heritage. But, why should the money not be used for
education spending, or for the reduction of the national debt and
the excessive public sector borrowing requirement? Most people
would feel that education spending, for example, was 'more
important' than arts expenditure. However, this is already rather
fully recognised in the fact that we spend much more public money
on education than on the arts. </p>
<p>A more relevant question, to which the answer is a good deal
less obvious, is whether a pound of additional spending on the
education system would generate more or less social benefit than
a pound of additional spending on the arts. It may be argued that
the rather general idea that 'education is more important' makes
it difficult to spend even marginal amounts on activities like
sports, arts and heritage. There is also a good deal to be said
for finding alternative mechanisms of public funding for
activities where it is important that there should be plurality
in decision making. This is particularly forceful in the arts,
where people necessarily have strong prejudices about what is
right and wrong, and the only certainty is that many of these
prejudices will in time prove to be mistaken. There is something
to be said for directing lottery revenues generally at activities
which are to a degree unfashionable. </p>
<p>For similar reasons, a lottery is a desirable form of funding
for one-off items, particularly capital projects (although this
need not exclude the provision of associated endowments for
running expenses). That makes it less likely that the proceeds of
a lottery would be directly substitutable for mainstream public
expenditure. </p>
<p>The popularity of a lottery in the United Kingdom is unlikely
ever to reach the levels achieved in Spain, where, particularly
at Christmas, entry is a national obsession. People give tickets
to each other, and the identity of the winner of the grand prize
is awaited as a national event akin to royal weddings and cup
finals. But in both its direct and indirect effects, a national
lottery would bring a little more brightness and a little more
sparkle into life. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
</body>
</html>
