http://www.londecon.co.uk:80/pubs/lottery/camelot.htm 194.193.150.111 19970111015403 text/html 10446
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 11 Jan 1997 01:48:40 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 10274
Last-modified: Sat, 14 Sep 1996 15:06:11 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Camelot - The Best Bet</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Camelot - The Best Bet</h2>
<p><i>The National Lottery will be launched in Britain this
autumn, to raise money for good causes. It is expected to raise
&#163;45bn a year in gross revenues. Eight consortia battled it
out to win the Licence to operate the Lottery, spending millions
of pounds putting their applications together. What did the
Director General of the Office of the National Lottery look for
when he assessed the bids? London Economics worked on the Camelot
bid, and this article explains the basic economics of lotteries.</i></p>
<hr>
<p>When the government passed its White Paper in 1992, setting
out its plans to launch the National Lottery, it decided to
franchise out the operation of the Lottery to the private sector.
It envisaged a regulatory body, the Office of the National
Lottery (OFLOT). In 1993, Peter Davis was appointed as its
Director General. </p>
<p>Peter Davis sent out his &quot;Invitation to Apply&quot; for
the Licence to run the Lottery in November 1993. The deadline for
applications was last February. After three months of
deliberation, he awarded the coveted Licence to a consortium
called Camelot. </p>
<p>Competition between the applicants was fierce. The leading
contenders were The Great British Lottery Company, which included
Granada and Associated Newspapers; LotCo, which included Rank;
and UK Lotteries, fronted by Richard Branson. Camelot's
consortium brought together Cadbury Schweppes, De La Rue, Gtech,
ICL and Racal. </p>
<p>London Economics has been involved in the National Lottery
since its inception. In 1992, we wrote a paper for the Calouste
Gulbenkian Foundation which assessed the likely impact of the
Lottery in the UK. And earlier this year, we provided economic
advice to Camelot, as they prepared their successful bid. We are
thus well placed to understand the issues the Director General
had to address in taking his decision. </p>
<h4>How to win the Lottery</h4>
<p>The Director General (DG) set out his objectives for the
running of the National Lottery in the Invitation to Apply. The
applicants first had to convince OFLOT of their unquestioned
probity, and that they would run the Lottery with due propriety.
Those applicants who met these conditions then competed for the
award of the Licence on the amount of revenue for good causes (to
be distributed via the National Lottery Distribution Fund NLDF)
that they promised to raise. So the applicants provided the DG
with details of every aspect of their business plan, including
financial statements for the period of the Licence (which runs
until 2001) under a variety of different market conditions. </p>
<p>These details included information on the applicants' game
strategies, on their security procedures, and on their customer
service commitments. This information assisted the DG in deciding
whether the bids met his probity objective. A more complex task
was to determine which applicant was likely to provide the
greatest revenues for good causes. </p>
<p>The amount of money raised for good causes is determined by: </p>
<ul>
    <li>the level of gross revenue, and </li>
    <li>the proportion of this revenue which is allocated to the
        NLDF. </li>
</ul>
<p>Whereas each applicant could control the proportion
contributed to the NLDF, they could only forecast the sales which
this proportion would be applied to. </p>
<p>Part of the DGs task was to evaluate the credibility of these
forecasts. Clearly, any applicant could offer a very large
apparent contribution to the NLDF, by basing it on an
overambitious <i>forecast </i>of revenues, rather than on a
generous <i>proportion</i>of revenues. So, in order to decide
which applicant would generate the largest contribution to the
NLDF, the DG had to decide which applicant was likely to generate
the most sales. Taking their sales forecasts at face value was
not enough. The DG looked at the details of the applicants'
plans, to assess which applicant was best prepared to run the
Lottery. </p>
<h4>How big is the pie?</h4>
<p>Nobody knows how successful the National Lottery will be in
Britain. We can, however, make an informed judgement. There may
not be any data on National Lotteries in this country, but we do
know about Lotteries in other countries. </p>
<p>We can guess which factors drive Lottery sales. For example,
we would expect that if 60p out of every &#163;1 goes to prizes,
more people will buy tickets than if only 50p goes to prizes. And
we would expect that more shops selling tickets will mean more
tickets being sold. We would also expect sales levels to be
influenced by a variety of economic, social, demographic and
cultural characteristics. </p>
<p>London Economics collected data on National Lotteries around
the world, to discover the main determinants of sales. We used
econometric techniques to determine the explanatory power of
variables such as the prize payout ratio, the number of terminals
per capita, and GDP per head. Our analysis indicated that all
these variables have a positive impact on sales. This type of
analysis can be used to estimate what sales might be in this
country, and thus to assess the credibility of the applicants'
sales forecasts. </p>
<h4>Playing the game</h4>
<p>Operators of National Lotteries nowadays employ stateoftheart
technology, to ensure reliability and security, and to control
the high volumes of ticket sales anticipated. Playing lotto might
seem simple enough. In the game which will be played in this
country, you mark 6 numbers between 1 and 49 on a game card, and
if your numbers match the ones chosen in the weekly draw, you win
a big prize. </p>
<p>When the retailer feeds your game card into the terminal, it
must read the card to check that you have marked it correctly. It
will then send your selected numbers to the central computer.
This must then record the transaction and store your numbers, and
send a confirmation signal back to the retailer's terminal, which
will issue a receipt with your numbers marked on it. The whole
transaction should be completed in a few seconds. </p>
<p>Competition between the applicants encouraged them to cut
their costs, in order to increase the proportions they could
offer to the NLDF and to prizes. Both of these would boost the
revenues they would generate for good causes. Given the
technological complexity of operating a National Lottery
efficiently and effectively, the applicants who were best placed
to keep costs down were those with the greatest hardware,
software, and communications expertise. </p>
<h4>Choosing a winner</h4>
<p>Several rainforests were sacrificed as the eight applicants
each submitted thousands of pages to OFLOT, for the Director
General and his teams of advisors to study. Richard Branson's bid
was the bookies' favourite to win the Licence. His bid captured
the public's imagination, by offering to give all the profits to
charity. And he forecast a higher contribution to the NLDF than
Camelot did. Why, then, did Peter Davis award the Licence to
Camelot? </p>
<p>The proceeds from Lottery ticket sales are split three ways,
after deducting tax: between the consumer (as prizes), the
government (as the NLDF contribution) and the operator (see
figure). The operator's cut covers its costs, including
retailers' commissions, and its profits. The applicants had to
juggle the allocation between the three groups, to maximise the
revenues generated for good causes. Increasing the proportion
contributed to the NLDF increases the money raised for good
causes. So does increasing the prize payout ratio, because of the
extra sales generated. </p>
<p>Branson's high contribution to the NLDF was based on a much
higher forecast of sales than Camelot's a forecast which London
Economics' analysis of worldwide Lotteries showed to be
overambitious. The <i>proportion</i> of gross revenues offered to
the NLDF in Branson's bid was very similar to Camelot's. </p>
<p>The technological expertise provided by Camelot's shareholders
Racal (data communications), ICL (computer systems for retailers)
and Gtech (lottery software) enabled the consortium to hold down
its costs. And by squeezing their profit margins, Camelot was
able to offer a greater proportion of sales to prizes and to the
NLDF. (Camelot's margin for operating costs plus profits was the
lowest of all the bidders.) </p>
<p>Camelot's decision to launch the National Lottery with lotto
was astute. An online lotto game has considerably greater novelty
value than scratch card games, which are already common in the
UK, and have had a low profile among the playing public. </p>
<p>London Economics' research into lotteries abroad provides
evidence that this novelty factor will increase the speed of
takeup of the National Lottery in this country. This is
exemplified by the early success of the New Zealand Lottery,
which launched with an online lotto game, compared with the
relatively slow takeup in Ireland, where the instant game was
launched first. </p>
<p>The credibility of the applicants' sales forecasts was central
to the DG's assessment of the bids. Camelot's efficiency, high
prize payout ratio, early launch date with lotto, retail
distribution plan, and marketing strategy combined to boost the
credibility of its forecasts. Superficially, Richard Branson's
bid may have appeared more attractive than Camelot's. But the
DG's decision implies that he believed that Camelot, and not
Branson, was likely to generate the most money for good causes.
Choosing Camelot, like picking Brian Lara for your cricket team,
may be a safe choice, but that does not mean that it is an
unexciting one. </p>
<p><i>Contact points: Alberto Pototschnig and Bill Robinson </i></p>
<hr>
