<head>
<title>Whose Money in the Pension Fund?</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Whose Money in the Pension Fund?</h2>
<p><strong><i>As controversy over the Maxwell company pension
funds continues to grow, it seems inevitable that the
relationship between pension funds and their parent companies
will come under close scrutiny. </i></strong></p>
<hr>
<p>The chances must now be high that a clearer separation between
the twin roles that executives often have as directors of their
company and trustees of its pension fund will now be imposed by
regulation. No sophisticated analysis is needed to see the need
for measures which prevent companies and individuals pocketing
the savings of their pensioners. Yet there is a more subtle issue
involved, one which affects every company, even if it is all too
evident in Mirror Group Newspapers. What is the relationship
between the financial exposure of the pension fund and that of
its parent? </p>
<p>Pension fund actuaries take a longrun view: they emphasise
that they do not vary their funding recommendations in response
to the short term fluctuations in stock market prices. Is their
caution wise? </p>
<p>Britain's leading clearing bank, Barclays, is now contributing
7.5% of salaries to its pension fund, for benefits costing other
companies 15% and above. Yet not long ago, Barclays had to
increase its contribution rate to 43% to bail out the large
pension deficit which it faced in the mid1970's. </p>
<p>A few months ago, Lucas became the first company to win
Occupational Pensions board approval to claw back &#163;150
million of its pension fund surplus for its own use. The &#163;90
million that the company will receive after tax will enable it to
reduce gearing. At least ten other applications for clawback are
now pending. </p>
<p>Some industrial companies are now making more profit from such
pension contributions &quot;holidays&quot; than they were from
manufacturing activity. Can the payment holidays last? We do not
know. The next twenty years will be no easier than the last
twenty for actuaries to forecast. Future uncertainties include
recent European Community case law developments requiring
equalisation for men and women. Risks which once appeared
negligible are already materialising. If present low levels of
inflation continue throughout the 1990's, the 5% cap on inflation
proofing of many vested pensions liabilities will no longer be
operative. With falling money investment returns, the real cost
of funding these liabilities will rise. </p>
<p>Finance directors are increasingly realising that factors like
this now compel management of a pension fund's financial risk
profile in more sophisticated ways than a triennial look at the
actuarial report. Recent legislative changes recognise the
company's role as &quot;residuary legatee&quot; (with
safeguards), of pension fund surpluses. Companies traditionally
accept a practical (though not legal) liability for funding any
deficits such as those of the 1970's. </p>
<p>So finance directors are right to be integrating pensions into
their overall assessment of onandoff balance sheet exposures. The
fact that pension fund risk exposures (on matters like inflation
or investment returns) are likely to be correlated negatively or
positively with nonpensionsrelated exposures provides a powerful
analytical tool for risk management. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
</body>
</html>
