Content-length: 4522
Last-modified: Sat, 14 Sep 1996 15:07:53 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Pension Blueprint</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Pension Blueprint</h2>
<p><i>&quot;Hard cases made bad law.&quot; That is the danger of
the Maxwell pensions affair. Robert Maxwell was a ruthless crook
who broke the law repeatedly and with impunity. But moral outrage
is a poor guide in the search for a more rational system of
occupational pensions regulations. What can be put in its place?</i></p>
<hr>
<p>A clear view was taken in Britain in general financial
services regulation in the mid-1980's. The City had done well
under a voluntary and informal regime of self-regulation. An era
of increasing competitive pressure brought widespread recognition
that a more formal regime would be necessary. The system then
created is neither cheap nor efficient at the retail level. Major
participants are now no longer able to agree on shouldering the
costs. Leading firms among the financial service providers have
very little interest in subsidising what is effectively quality
control, enabling their smaller competitors to undercut their own
competitive advantages derived from reputation and size. It is
increasingly recognised that self-regulation can really only work
in the wholesale markets, where the leading participants can work
in the wholesale markets, where the leading participants can
agree on maintaining their cheap and broadly effective (but
flexible) self-regulatory organisations. </p>
<p>For occupational pensions, at the &quot;wholesale&quot; level,
the need is for transparency and publicity in the investment
arrangements of company schemes. However, given the revealed
weakness in the oversight by scheme trustees, it seems likely
that the Occupational Pensions Board or some other supervisory
body will acquire broader powers of control. Certainly the
Investment Management Regulatory Organisation (IMRO) failed to
policy the investment that managers used to syphon funds into the
private Maxwell companies. </p>
<p>One problem with increased government oversight lies in the
implied guarantees at the retail (pensioner) level, and the
system of incentives this creates. Some of the potential problems
have been revealed by the state guarantees implemented in the US
Employment Retirement Income Security Act (ERISA) of 1975. The US
government effectively guarantees far more of the pension
entitlements that the (minimal) British guaranteed minimum
pensions under the social security contracting-out arrangements
(or than pensioners are likely to be able to obtain charitably or
bargain for politically in the aftermath of the Maxwell affair).
There is a considerable moral hazard to the US system: some firms
have effectively been able to juggle bankruptcy proceedings and
ERISA guarantees in order to force the US government effectively
to bail them out of their own mistakes. There have even been
alarmist warnings that the eventual liabilities could escalate to
the levels of the Savings and Load bail outs. We can do without
that kind of pensioner compensation scheme. </p>
<p>What is needed is a regulatory regime that maintains the
investment flexibility of the funds, but catches crooks. It
should also maintain the incentives of all partners to act
wisely, so that regulation is cheap. There will certainly be a
role for state guarantees, and for the criminal law. But what of
the private sector? Some firms are now appointing independent
trustees: effectively non-executive directors of their pension
fund. Private sector insurance- which in a few overseas markets
exists to compensate for pension fund fraud - has not yet offered
a solution. The best solution may be for a division of labour
between such private insurance and the assumption by the state of
the uninsurable risks. That way the incentive effects of
differential premiums could add another warning signal to our
armoury of risk detection. But it may be that nothing would have
stopped a villain like Maxwell before it was too late. Designing
a regulatory system to cope with hard cases may in the end do
more damage than a few successful rogues can do directly
themselves. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
