        <td align="center">45,000</td>
        <td align="center">54800</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Notional monetary cost<br>
        of all care</td>
        <td align="center">40,100</td>
        <td align="center">42,300</td>
        <td align="center">51,400</td>
        <td align="center">63,900</td>
        <td align="center">81,600</td>
    </tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<h4>Solutions</h4>
<p>The preponderance of informal care, and the importance of
making sure that the need for formal care does not reach
unsustainable levels, underline the need to support those who do
provide care for relatives or friends. Recent policy decisions,
such as the exemption from VAT of some types of care provided in
the home, have helped this process, but much more will need to be
done. </p>
<p>Whether to care for a relative is an intensely personal
decision, and although those that do provide great benefits to
society we cannot assume they will go on volunteering for ever.
Small expenditures to make life easier for these unsung heroes
(or, mostly, heroines) could make a large difference to their
willingness and ability to care. Research is needed into why
people choose to care for relatives and what determines this
choice. </p>
<h4>New savings products</h4>
<p>Whatever happens, there is no doubt that a substantial part of
the rising cost of formal care will need to be borne by
individuals and their families. This presents a challenge, and an
opportunity, to the financial services industry. </p>
<p>The creation of <i>new insurance vehicles</i>, partly
encouraged by the Budget measures, is likely to be a part of the
solution. In the United States, <i>Partnership Schemes </i>permit
those individuals who plan ahead to meet a proportion of
long-term care costs to retain assets even if they turn out to
need extensive care. </p>
<p>One solution currently being discussed is a <i>variable
pension. </i>Instead of paying into a pension throughout his or
her working life in order to receive an annual income upon
retirement, a plan member would be able to secure a higher income
stream in extreme old age. This could point the way towards the
development of a <i>combined product</i>. Such a product might
deliver a lower annual income than a conventional pension but<b> </b>might
also include long term care insurance. </p>
<p>The attraction of this solution is its simplicity. Many people
take out private pensions; this might increase the coverage of
long term care insurance and would encourage provision to be
taken out earlier in life. </p>
<p>Much thought will need to be given to how best to help
individuals provide for their own and for their family's needs;
to the development of appropriate financial products and to
corresponding changes in tax rules. Are simple savings and
investment vehicles most appropriate? Can we work out schemes
which incentivise people to insure? Are there ways of taking
charges over assets contingent on need? Can we help people decide
when in their lives they will be most able to put money aside?
What mix of tax incentives and social security rules will best
encourage a 'mixed economy' of formal care? </p>
<p><b>Contacts: </b><a href="mailto:nick@londecon.co.uk"><b>Nick
Morris</b></a><b> and </b><a href="mailto:tim@londecon.co.uk"><b>Tim
Wilsdon</b></a> </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1996 </p>
