<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>The Cost of Capital</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>The Cost of Capital</h2>
<p><i>Every company should know its cost of capital. But for
firms whose returns are regulated by reference to it such as
privatised utilities or firms bound by noncompetitive government
contracts estimates of the cost of capital are central to their
profitability. </i></p>
<hr>
<p>The cost of capital is relevant to every business. For those
subject to regulation, it sets what the regulator allows them to
recover. In a fully competitive market, it sets what a firm must
earn to survive and prosper in the market place. </p>
<p>Arguments over the cost of capital were critical issues when
'x' was set for regional electricity companies and when BT's
price cap was redetermined. The k factors applied to water
companies were based on the Department of the Environment's
estimates of their costs of capital. Now OFWAT has come up with
new, lower, figures and this would substantially affect both the
level of water charges and the profitability of water companies.</p>
<table border="1">
    <tr>
        <th colspan="2">Capital Asset Pricing Model</th>
        <th colspan="2">Dividend Growth Model</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Risk Free Rate</td>
        <td align="right">3%</td>
        <td>Current Dividend Yield</td>
        <td align="right">5.5%</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Beta</td>
        <td align="right">0.8</td>
        <td>Real Dividend Growth</td>
        <td align="right">5.0%</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Equity Premium</td>
        <td align="right">9%</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><b>Cost of Equity Capital</b></td>
        <td align="right"><b>10.2%</b></td>
        <td><b>Cost of Equity Capital</b></td>
        <td align="right"><b>10.5%</b></td>
    </tr>
</table>
<p><i>All figures real, after tax. This calculation is
illustrative and designed to illustrate the principles involved.</i> </p>
<h4>The Capital Asset Pricing Model</h4>
<p>The principal means of determining the cost of capital is
based on the capital asset pricing model. This model is the under
pinning of most modern financial theory. In the capital asset
pricing model there are two components to the cost of capital: </p>
<ul>
    <li>the risk free rate; and </li>
    <li>the equity premium. </li>
</ul>
<p>The risk free rate is what would be charged for wholly
riskless borrowing. Usually it is based on the government bond
rate for maturities matched to the time period of the related
investment. In Britain alone, the existence of an active market
in indexed government stock allows the calculation of both real
and nominal risk free rates of return. Today the yield curve for
indexed gilts is relatively flat, offering a 4% return in real
terms across a wide range of maturities. </p>
<p>The equity premium compensates shareholders for the additional
risks associated with equity investment. Studies have estimated
the average return on equity investment over an extended time
period. They point to a remarkably constant figure for this
premium, at around 9% after tax. For a stock whose price was
likely to follow the market index exactly this leads directly to
the cost of capital . A highly cyclical stock a capital goods
producer or a housebuilder will require a higher premium. A stock
with sound defensive properties a food retailer or brewer can
accept a lower premium. The Beta coefficient captures this
effect. A high Beta stock outperforms the market on the way up
and underperforms on the way down. The Beta of an individual
share will be influenced by the company's gearing, and we
distinguish equity and asset Betas. Estimates of Beta for UK
company shares are produced regularly by the London Business
School's risk measurement service. </p>
<p>The capital asset pricing model attributes the equity premium
entirely to market risk the risk associated with general economic
fluctuations. It discounts specific risk uncertainties such as
those associated with oil exploration or pharmaceutical research.
These specific risks should be fully diversified by investors who
hold a well spread portfolio, while market risks, by their
nature, cannot be. This central feature of the capital asset
pricing model is one which corporate managers, on whom specific
risks bear very heavily, often find difficult to accept. </p>
<h4>The Gordon growth model</h4>
<p>The second method of measuring the cost of capital is simply
to add the rate of expected dividend growth to the current
dividend yield. This gives the return which the company needs to
earn to meet shareholder expectations. </p>
<p>But how are shareholder expectations to be determined? There
is no objective measure of what dividend growth shareholders
expect the best indication is usually provided by the level of
the dividend yield itself. This leads to a real danger of a
circular process in which everyone market, company and regulator
is setting their policies by reference to each other's
expectations, and then deducting what they expect by reference to
what policies they adopt. The dividend growth model is best seen
as a check on the plausibility of cost of capital estimates
rather than a means of measuring it. </p>
<h4>Inflation and tax</h4>
<p>Two issues often cause confusion in assessing the cost of
capital: </p>
<ul>
    <li>real versus nominal rates of return; </li>
    <li>pre and post tax rates of return. </li>
</ul>
<p>A nominal rate of return is appropriate when all variables
profits, costs, dividends are measured in current money,
including the effects of inflation. A real rate of return should
be used when these variables are expressed in constant prices. It
is less important which is used than to ensure consistency
throughout. Since the tax system is firmly based on nominal
variables, it is often less confusing to approach the analysis in
this way. The proper introduction of tax effects is more complex
than it appears. It generally needs to be related specifically to
an individual company's tax history. Particular adjustments are
needed for risk assessments which cannot easily be incorporated
within the standard framework such as the regulatory risk faced
by privatised firms. </p>
<p>Rough estimates of the cost of capital should be part of every
financial manager's armoury. More precise estimates of the kind
needed to do battle with regulatory agencies are a matter of much
greater sophistication. In all the privatised industries, these
arguments are likely to rumble on. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1991 </p>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT11-B06-121</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA036-000712-B020-238</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.londecon.co.uk:80/pubs/privat/realreg.htm 194.193.150.111 19970111015647 text/html 5991
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 11 Jan 1997 01:51:34 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 5820
Last-modified: Sat, 14 Sep 1996 15:08:47 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>The Reality of Regulation</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>The Reality of Regulation</h2>
<p><strong><i>When privatisation occurred, the affected
industries were deeply involved in the negotiation of regulatory
rules and regulatory structures. They mostly though that, once
the heady but busy period of flotation was over, regulator would
be a much smaller portion of their concerns. They were wrong. If
anything, the pace of regulatory activity has increased, and the
degree of regulatory pressure has intensified.</i></strong></p>
<hr>
<h4>Telecommunications</h4>
<p>Telecommunications set the ground rules for British utility
regulation, and the architect of many of these ground rules, Sir
Bryan Carsber, is about to assume wider responsibilities as
Director-General of Fair Trading. BT initially faced one network
competitor - Mercury - but since the Duopoly Review entry is now
open to any firm with the capacity to provide service. The
(RPI-x) price control formula was first set for BT with x at 3.
Now x is 61/4, there are further price controls on individual
services, and the overall pricing formula is again under review. </p>
<h4>Gas</h4>
<p>British Gas believed it had achieved 'regulation with a light
rein'. That rein had become steadily tighter. Initially,
industrial supplies were outside the regulatory framework, but
investigations by the MMC and OFT first imposed restrictions on
the structure of gas prices, and have now forced a commitment to
relinquish a major share of the industrial gas market. Domestic
customers, whose tariffs are also governed and (RPI-x) formula,
have also benefited from substantial increases in the value of x. </p>
<h4>Water</h4>
<p>In the water industry, the regulator has shown his teeth. He
used the threat of interim determination to force most companies
to accept lower price increases than the K formula would have
permitted. He has argued that the rate of return assumptions on
which prices were based were much to generous. And he has already
begun the process of the first periodic review of the industry,
insisting that customers must be consulted in the future choice
between charges and service levels. Even in electricity, Offer
has signalled dissatisfaction with the operation of the power
pool as a competitive market. </p>
<p>The common elements in these developments are obvious.
Regulators have generally believed that, at flotation, the
industries they supervise got too favourable a deal.
Step-by-step, they have attempted to win ground back. And mostly,
they have been successful. The bargaining position of a regulated
utility is strongest at the moment of floatation, when government
needs to win the support of managers and the confidence of
investors. It will never enjoy that degree of political power and
influence again. </p>
<p>It is important that regulated industries understand that
fundamental reality. British Gas, it seems, learnt it rather too
slowly. Its aggressive behaviour in the industrial gas market,
and its hostile initial responses to regulatory intervention,
served it poorly in the long run. Some other firms have
understood better that monopoly utilities have few friends, and
that it is vital to retain those they have. </p>
<p>BT's sensible recognition that it was well worth its while to
invest substantial resources in dealing with public payphones is
a good example - the public relations benefits (in the broadest
and best sense of that term) far outweighed the cost. And BAA
wisely, and perhaps only just in time, appreciated that to
exploit its market position too fully would ultimately jeopardise
the whole basis of that position. The water industry would do
well to take extremely seriously the Director-General's requests
to consult consumers, and there are clear lessons for the
electricity generators as they consider how to take best
advantage of their dominance of the pool. </p>
<h4>The Role of the MMC</h4>
<p>So what of the future? The various privatising Acts gave the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission a role as arbiter in disputes
between regulator and regulatee. So far, that role has barely
been used. There have been some references on matters, such as
airport charges and water mergers, where consideration by the MMC
is required by statute. there has been only one case - that of
telephone chatline services - where the MMC has been asked to
adjudicate and, important though these services may be to
providers, users, and to their parents, this is not the central
ground of economic regulation. </p>
<p>But it is a virtual certainty that the MMC role will increase
in future, and with it the politicisation - or perhaps we should
see it as the repoliticisation - of regulation and utility
policies. So far, the utilities have mostly been willing, however
reluctantly, to give ground their regulatory battles, believing
that they are unlikely to be more successful in the more
acrimonious and more open forum of a public dispute. But the more
ground they feel they have already given, the less likely it is
that this will be true the next time around. </p>
<p>When privatisation occurred, there were some naive hopes that
regulation was simply a temporary phase; that market competition
would take its place and the firms concerned could then operate
like any other commercial business. The emerging reality is very
different. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
</body>
