<html>
<head>
<title>Is Privatisation Necessary?</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Is Privatisation Necessary?</h2>
<p><i>Britain's privatisation experiment is ten years old. While
there were some sales of public sector assets in the early
Thatcher years, it was a decade ago that the government decided
to embark on the first of the great utility privatisations the
sale of British Telecom. That is time enough for some preliminary
verdicts on the success of the process.</i></p>
<hr>
<p>For some, of course, the simple fact that it has happened at
all is the measure of success. That is true for many politicians,
and most of all for the bankers and others who earn their fees
from the consummation of transactions (London Economics has to
declare an interest here). And the programme has indeed changed
the political agenda, not only in Britain but around the world.
But the important test of privatisation's effectiveness is its
effect on the efficiency of the privatised concerns. What has
privatisation done for the costs of the services the firms
provide and for the prices and quality of service offered to
customers? </p>
<p>The best measure of efficiency is the <i>total factor
productivity </i>of the firm the amount of output per unit of
input that the firm produces. The table overleaf shows the
changes in total factor productivity across some of the
industries which were in public ownership in 1979. It includes
firms which have been brought to market and others which have
remained in the public sector throughout. </p>
<p>There are three principal lessons to be drawn from this table.
The first is that there has, indeed, been a clear improvement in
performance. The second is that the break in trend occurred about
ten years ago, and coincided with the development of the
privatisation programme. The third is that the improvement in
performance seems to be largely independent of whether the firms
concerned were privatised or not. </p>
<p>There is a coherent underlying explanation of these apparently
surprising facts. It is that exposure to competitive disciplines,
rather than ownership as such, which is the most important
influence on performance. </p>
<p>Some governments, imitating the British privatisation
programme, have been mostly concerned to raise as much revenue as
possible. Others, especially the less developed, would have
confronted industries so ill run that almost any alternative
structure would represent improvement. And the same is true in
Eastern Europe, where the urgent need is to dismantle a
monolithic state apparatus, while encouraging growth. But other
countries, such as Australia, France and Germany, have been
content to take a more considered view of the British experience,
and to learn from the problems which have been encountered. </p>
<p>Is the transfer of ownership necessary, or even useful, in
monopoly industries? Corporatisation the establishment of the
state's industrial activities as wholly distinct corporate
entities, free of political control but subject to explicit
regulation and clearly defined objectives is an alternative to
privatisation. Corporatisation allows explicit recognition that
monopoly utilities cannot be commercial businesses in a normal
sense, but do and should have public responsibilities as well as
obligations to make profits for their shareholders. But it raises
questions as to whether the divorce between politics and the
commercial activities of the state can ever be effective so long
as the state retains ownership and the power to hire and fire
managers. </p>
<p>A second issue is whether restructuring may be a necessary
preliminary to, or an activity more important than, privatisation
itself. In Britain it became clear in gas and telecommunications
that not enough had been done before flotation to introduce an
effective competitive framework. While a brave attempt was made
in electricity, there are also increasing doubts here as to the
adequacy of competition. Alternative approaches such as those
which retain infrastructure in public ownership and franchise
individual functions may offer more scope for real competition
and less abrasive relationships between company and regulator. </p>
<p>In the 1980s, Britain exported its privatisation experience
around the world. In the 1990s it is very likely that we shall
reimport experience from other countries which have learnt from
our trials and from our errors. We intend to be at the forefront
of that learning process. </p>
<table border="1">
    <tr>
        <th colspan="4">Total Factor Productivity in UK Public
        Sector<br>
        <font size="2">Rate of Change p.a. (%)</font></th>
    </tr>
