<html>
<head>
<title>Benchmarking</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Benchmarking</h2>
<p><i>When benchmarking, comparisons must be likewithlike.
Efficiency comparisons across firms are often problematic:
comparisons across countries make the challenge even greater.
London Economics tackled this issue recently, when a client asked
us to create robust and defensible performance indicators for its
electricity supply industry, to compare with international best
practice. </i></p>
<hr>
<p>The first stage was to develop acceptable performance
indicators within the country. These are being used for a variety
of purposes. They provide an overview of the productivity and
efficiency of the industry </p>
<ul>
    <li>relative to best practice </li>
    <li>for comparison between individual utilities </li>
    <li>for comparison between broad functions. </li>
</ul>
<p>They will enable management to identify how far from
&quot;best practice&quot; each part of their operation is, and to
prioritise where action is needed. Best practice assumes the best
available technology, minimisation of costs, optimal usage of
resources and market openings, and a dynamic administrative
system. </p>
<p>In order to create accurate indicators we are collecting data
from all major utilities in the country and business units for a
range of indicators, as illustrated below: </p>
<table border="1">
    <tr>
        <th>Financial</th>
        <th>Technical</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Return on assets/revenues</td>
        <td>Labour productivity: Value-weighted index of labour
        input</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Capital structure: debt/equity ratios</td>
        <td>Operating efficiency relative to technical
        specification of plant</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Return to government/shareholder</td>
        <td>Fuel cost per GWh, allowing for fuel mix and dispatch
        costs</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td></td>
        <td>Operating/maintenance costs</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td></td>
        <td>Efficient utilisation of existing capital stock</td>
    </tr>
</table>
<p>Questions about appropriateness of capital then have to be
faced. Given current technology costs, how does existing stock
diverge from leastcost? And how do expected technology costs
diverge from leastcost? </p>
<p>A later part of the project will require the appropriate
weighting of information, to achieve likewithlike. Comparing a
vertically integrated utility with a generation only utility is
obviously inappropriate. But operational structures, inherited
capital stock and transmission networks also vary considerably.
And international comparisons will also require an understanding
of, and allowing for, a host of national and local factors, to
establish each individual utility's operating conditions. These
will include customer mix, density of the customer base and
climate. </p>
<p>We are developing a &quot;long list&quot; of utilities
worldwide; a short list will then be established of useful
comparators for the local utilities. Technical knowledge of each
utility's operations will prove a vital component. Only then can
we establish a full picture of the operating environment of each
utility. London Economics has detailed experience of the UK
industry; and is gathering information about the USA, Canada, the
Pacific Rim, parts of Africa, Asia and South America. </p>
<p>Foreign exchange rates add another dimension. International
performance comparisons between electric utilities involve
comparisons of prices or costs of capital, labour and fuel. Even
technical efficiency measurements are influenced by the exchange
rate to the extent they include either costs or prices. So a
choice of appropriate exchange rate had to be made, between the
official rate, the appropriate shadow rate and a rate based on
purchase power parity. The latter is used in the study. </p>
<p>The development of our methodology was only the beginning.
Vast amounts of financial, technical and local data will be
studied, but treated confidentially. Only then will the client
industry have a full picture of relevant international best
practice. </p>
<hr>
