<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Benchmarking : The State of the Art</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Benchmarking : The State of the Art</h2>
<p><i>Benchmarking allows companies to compare the efficiency of
all or part of their activities with others doing the same
things. We introduced this important technique in </i><strong><i>Economics
in Action 1992/Three</i></strong><i>. London Economics is at the
forefront of &quot;best practice&quot; benchmarking in the UK and
abroad. Advanced techniques ensure efficiency comparisons are as
accurate and informative as possible. This article describes some
of the methods we use.</i></p>
<hr>
<p>Benchmarking is one step along the route to competitive
advantage as it: </p>
<ul>
    <li>identifies a company's strengths and weaknesses relative
        to &quot;best practice&quot;; </li>
    <li>improves management information; </li>
    <li>improves productivity through changed working practices. </li>
</ul>
<p>Benchmarking aims to answer the question: what is the
&quot;best practice&quot; frontier in my undertaking and how far
am I from it? It is vitally important to ensure that one is
comparing like with like. </p>
<h4>Identifying the frontier</h4>
<p>Consider the example of an electricity generator. For
simplicity, assume he needs only fuel and a turbine to produce
electricity. Obviously, the generator faces a number of options.
He can buy an old, cheap turbine which consumes a lot more fuel
or he could spend more on a modern, efficient turbine and save on
fuel expenses. </p>
<p>Each point (marked X) on the figure shows the turbine/fuel
combination used by different firms to produce 100 GWh of
electricity. Some of the more expensive turbines require less
fuel, while a cheaper turbine tends to cost more in fuel. The
generator can therefore trade off the turbine cost against the
fuel cost. The most efficient turbines are those that use less of
both inputs, ie near the bottom and left of the diagram. The
efficient frontier is created by joining TUVWYZ. The measure of
efficiency is the distance, AB, from this frontier. Usually there
are more than two inputs to a production process. Fitting the
frontier then becomes a complex mathematical problem. </p>
<p>In recent years, two main mathematical methods for identifying
the 'best practice frontier' have been developed. They approach
the problem of fitting a frontier to available data from
different directions. The first method is the <i>Data Envelopment
Analysis </i>approach, which is entirely driven by the data. The
second is to use the <i>Stochastic Frontiers</i> approach, which
uses the data in combination with some assumptions about
managerial behaviour to estimate the frontier. </p>
<h4>Data Envelopment Analysis (DEA)</h4>
<p>DEA uses the mathematical technique of linear programming to
'envelop' the dataset. The process is entirely driven by the
data. No assumptions are made about the way in which firms
combine inputs to produce a given level of output. Once the best
practice frontier is established, the efficiency of a firm that
is not on the frontier can be analysed. </p>
<h4>Stochastic Frontier Analysis (SFA)</h4>
<p>SFA requires that explicit assumptions are made about the
nature of the production function; ie the way inputs combine to
achieve a particular level of output. On the foundation of these
assumptions (all based in economic theory), a measure of the
efficiency of each firm can be made. </p>
<p>Both of these techniques provide valuable results for the
benchmarker: </p>
<ul>
    <li>how far you are from the frontier; </li>
    <li>who the benchmark firms for your company should be; </li>
    <li>the characteristics of a best practice firm. </li>
</ul>
<h4>Apples and Oranges ...</h4>
<p>In carrying out a benchmarking study, it is important to
compare like with like. There may be large differences in
performance between firms in the same industry, because of
external factors that are totally beyond managerial control. It
would be wrong to describe a company as best practice because its
performance is favoured by where it operates. For example,
comparisons of water company performance need to take into
account the fact that some companies have easier access to raw
water. If a company is in an area with high rainfall or natural
valleys that are easy to dam, its costs of gathering water are
lower than a company that has to sink boreholes and pump water
from underground. </p>
<p>These differences in operating environment can be built into
benchmarks, to ensure that all companies are compared on a level
playing field, allowing a proper <i>apples to apples </i>comparison. </p>
<p>The combination of frontier estimation techniques and the
adjustment for differences in operating environment comprise the
state of the art in benchmarking. They allow the identification
of performance black spots, and offer a way of overcoming them. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Back to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1994 </p>
</body>
