http://www.londecon.co.uk:80/pubs/privat/rightks.htm 194.193.150.111 19970111015811 text/html 10084
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 11 Jan 1997 01:53:04 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 9913
Last-modified: Sat, 14 Sep 1996 15:08:51 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>The Right Ks for the Water Industry</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>The Right &quot;Ks&quot; for the Water Industry</h2>
<p><strong><i>The Director General of OFWAT, Ian Byatt, has just
announced price limits for the water industry in England and
Wales for the next ten years. Will this prove a durable
settlement? There is room for doubt.</i></strong></p>
<hr>
<p>On 28 July 1994, the Director General of Water Services
announced the K factors for the water industry for the next ten
years. &quot;K&quot; is the annual average percentage increase in
prices which companies will be allowed, over and above the rate
of inflation. </p>
<p>The DG probably faced the most difficult task of all the
economic regulators in setting these price limits. He had to set
separate price limits for each of the thirtytwo companies in
England and Wales. And the process of setting K was, and remains,
highly controversial. All economic regulators have to balance the
interests of shareholders and customers. OFWAT has an additional
burden. It needs to coordinate economic regulation with
environmental issues, including drinking water standards and the
ways in which companies can dispose of treated sewage. </p>
<p>The DG claims to have been tough on the water companies.
Average Ks were set by the DoE in 1989 at 3.7% per annum for the
period 1995/6 to 1999/2000. They have been reduced to 1.4% per
annum in the new determination. The latest review did more than
lower Ks. The DG has not simply set revised price limits. He has
reopened the whole debate on the economic regulation of water.
And he has substantially revised the investment plans which the
companies will be permitted to follow over the next five or ten
years. The revised Ks, therefore, reflect both a totally new
regulatory regime and changed spending plans on the part of the
companies. </p>
<h4>A tighter regime</h4>
<p>The DG has subjected companies to a harsher regulatory
settlement than applied in 1989. He has </p>
<ul>
    <li><i>increased the efficiency targets </i>significantly.
        The industry is now expected to achieve an average 2%
        real cost reduction every year until the end of the
        decade. Some companies (which the DG has decided are
        particularly inefficient) will be expected to achieve
        3.5% per annum. </li>
    <li>taken the view that the <i>appropriate rate of return</i>for
        the water industry (which is a lowrisk industry) is <i>lower </i>than
        was assumed by the DoE when Ks were originally set. As a
        result, companies have been required to reduce their
        current cost operating profits to between 6% and 7% of
        their capital value over the next ten years. </li>
    <li>further reduced permitted profits by significantly
        reducing the capital values on which these calculations
        are made. </li>
</ul>
<p>The original values set by DoE in 1989 were based on
discounted cash flows (the economic value of their existing
assets), assuming that the regime existing prior to 1989 had
continued. This approach was intended to avoid companies making a
windfall gain on their existing assets. </p>
<p>The valuations placed on the companies by DoE are generally
recognised as arbitrary. They were often inconsistent (because
they perpetuated the anomalies in pricing existing at that time).
However, the approach at least had the virtue of being negotiated
and accepted by all companies in the industry. The new values
which the DG has now put in place are not seen as being obviously
superior. They have not received such widespread acceptance. </p>
<h4>Has the DG got it right?</h4>
<p>On balance, the DG does seem to have fulfilled his obligation
to ensure that the water companies can continue to finance their
functions. For the most part, companies see the new Ks as tough
but manageable. The DG will probably not be too concerned that
South West Water has decided to refer his decision to the MMC. If
none of the companies had challenged his decision, it might have
looked as if he had been too lenient. </p>
<p>Yet the DG has produced a system of regulation which is a long
way from the original RPIX concept first proposed by Professor
Littlechild. Furthermore, far from representing a happy
compromise between theory and practicality, it is likely that the
new approach to setting Ks will fail to satisfy anybody for long.
It may prove scarcely more durable than the approach taken by the
DoE in 1989. </p>
<h4>Uncertain future</h4>
<p>The theory of price cap regulation stresses the need for the
regulator to refrain from tampering with the system between
reviews. Companies must be allowed to determine their own
spending plans. In contrast to this, the DG has shown himself
willing to intervene between reviews to reduce Ks when he feels
company profits are becoming uncomfortably high. And, in the
review itself, he has subjected the companies to an intrusive
process of regulation. This detailed examination of all aspects
of capital and operating costs is similar to the process followed
by rate of return regulators in the US. </p>
<p>This approach creates a regulatory system that leaves the
companies not knowing what to expect from one review to the next.
Virtually no aspect of the DoE's original Ksetting methodology
has survived. Investment plans, company values and the allowable
rate of return have all been revised. Companies that had
previously been told that they were relatively efficient now find
themselves categorised as less efficient, because the DG took a
new approach to assessing relative efficiency which moved the
goalposts. </p>
<p>The DG can be said to have gone back on the regulatory
&quot;deal&quot; which was struck at the time of privatisation.
He has reduced the company valuations set by the DoE. This is a
dangerous precedent to set. It is an unsatisfactory state of
affairs in an industry characterised by the need to make
investment decisions on assets with exceptionally long lives
(like mains, sewers and reservoirs). To plan these investments,
companies need to predict the future, including the role
regulation will play in years to come. The approach of the DG
makes future regulation a key additional uncertainty in any
investment decision. </p>
<h4>Environmental issues</h4>
<p>One of the reasons for privatising the water industry was to
allow the private sector to finance significant investment in
improved quality. The public sector was unwilling to finance this
itself. The DG has failed to resolve the thorny problem of how to
reconcile this with economic regulation. The problem is to
balance encouragement of allocative and technical efficiency with
investment in service and water quality. </p>
<p>While the DG has no choice but to accept the legal
requirements for environmental standards set by Whitehall and
Brussels, he has chosen to drag his feet over other aspects of
the quality of service paid for by water and sewerage customers.
His overriding concern has been to keep bills down, not to
investigate the quality of service customers actually want, and
then allow water companies to provide this. </p>
<p>In 1993, the DG encouraged the companies to carry out the
&quot;Market Plan&quot; exercise, using market research to
soundout customer opinion on the appropriate price/quality
tradeoff. This was a positive step. Ultimately the DG has chosen
to ignore the findings of this work, and set Ks considerably
lower than those that emerged as customers' preferred options.
While he might be right to say that the Market Plan exercise was
flawed, his own choice of the price/quality mix effectively
ignores the issue of customers' willingness to pay for an
improved quality of product and service provided by the
companies. </p>
<h4>Where to from here?</h4>
<p>After the hectic activity of the Periodic Review, it would be
nice to think that the water industry had now arrived in a stable
regulatory environment. The key arguments could then be over
standards and quality, not over the framework of regulation
itself. Yet this seems unlikely. </p>
<p>In two years time, a new regulator will be appointed to take
over from Ian Byatt. The new DG will almost certainly want to
make a mark on the industry. The present lack of communication on
the current approach on rate of return or capital values may give
the new DG an opportunity to reopen this debate. This would have
significant potential for changing Kfactors, even if OFWAT's
overall methodology was not greatly altered. This would be
unfortunate, given the industry's need to fund &#163;24bn of new
investment over the next ten years, including &#163;6bn to meet
new European standards on the treatment of urban waste water. </p>
<p>Not all change would be unwelcome. There is a need for the
regulator to look again at the way the relative efficiency of
companies is measured. He needs to evolve a durable system that
is accepted by the industry, and is not subject to sudden
variations from year to year. Customers' true preferences over
quality and cost should also be addressed more seriously. The
economic regulator could work more closely with the bodies that
set environmental standards. </p>
<p>Solving these two issues alone should provide the DG with a
full agenda for some time to come. </p>
<p><i>Contact point: </i><a href="mailto:dan@londecon.co.uk"><i>Dan
Elliott</i> </a></p>
<hr>
