<html>
<head>
<title>New Alternatives to Privatisation</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>New Alternatives to Privatisation</h2>
<p><i>What should we do with publiclyowned organisations which
trade in the private sector? There are many organisations of this
kind, including some large highprofile bodies like the Post
Office and the BBC. In the 1980s, the conventional wisdom was
that they should all be privatised, and the sooner the better.
But in the debate about the future of the Post Office last
autumn, the alternative solution of giving publiclyowned
enterprises &quot;more commercial freedom within the public
sector&quot; was widely discussed. </i></p>
<hr>
<p>London Economics was asked to spell out precisely what that
might mean for the Post Office. As a direct result of that work,
we have been approached by a number of organisations in the
public sector who are seeking to clarify, or change, the rules
governing their behaviour. They are in widely different
businesses, but they all share a desire to operate more freely in
the commercial world, and are frustrated by the need to clear
commercial initiatives with their sponsoring Department in
Whitehall. </p>
<p>Their frustration is understandable. The government has
launched the Private Finance Initiative. Its main objective is to
encourage private enterprise into activities (notably
infrastructure provision) that have previously been regarded as
the exclusive domain of the public sector. But, although the
Treasury is energetically beating the drum for the PFI, other
Departments remain cautious about commercialisation. </p>
<p>The rules governing what enterprises in the public sector may
or may not do are discretionary, appear to be in a state of flux,
and may be interpreted differently by different Departments. So
we are frequently asked both for guidance on the rules, and for
help in getting the best out of them. </p>
<h4>Diminishing returns</h4>
<p>Wholesale privatisation is not the solution to all problems.
The transfer of ownership to the private sector was brilliant
innovation, but it has been going on for a long time, and is
subject to diminishing returns. The most promising candidates,
where the benefits clearly outweighed the costs, were privatised
first. But the balance of advantage has become slimmer with each
new privatisation, and it is time to consider alternatives that
could deliver the benefits of privatisation at a lower cost. </p>
<p>When the privatisation programme was launched, the public
sector contained many businesses like British Airways, British
Steel, or British Leyland, that were operating in a competitive
market place. It is hard now to remember what such businesses
were doing in the public sector in the first place. They were
privatised in the knowledge that the competitive process would
prevent them making excessive profits. </p>
<p>The same could not be said of the public utilities, most of
which were natural monopolies. There were worries about
transferring such enterprises and their monopoly rents intact
from public to private sector. But all the public utilities
especially telecommunications and water were starved of funds.
Privatisation and regulation has proved a workable formula for
getting costs down relative to prices. It has delivered a profit
margin which has enabled the utilities to tap into the capital
markets to finance investment. </p>
<h4>Treasury rules</h4>
<p>And this brings us to one of the key issues in the current
debate. The underlying rationale for privatisation is to improve
the efficiency with which enterprises<i> use</i> capital and
labour. But the main justification for some of the more
successful privatisations has been that it has taken
organisations like BT outside the Treasury rules, and given them
access to <i>more</i> capital. Which leads to the obvious
question: can we find other ways, short of full privatisation, to
increase access to capital given Treasury rules on public
borrowing? </p>
<p>Before seeking to mitigate the effect of the Treasury rules,
it is important to understand why they were put in place. All
public sector enterprises have an inherent tendency to make
unproductive investments. In the private sector, all investment
proposals are subject to the most intense scrutiny by providers
of capital, who stand to lose their own money if the investment
goes wrong. </p>
<p>That discipline is absent in the public sector. In the early
postwar period, bad investment decisions by the newly
nationalised industries became a major drain on the public purse.
To prevent that, the Treasury had to impose a regime of capital
rationing which has survived to this day. </p>
<p>That regime, though a necessary protection for the taxpayer,
starved some public sector businesses of capital. It was also a
less efficient way of allocating capital than allowing private
firms to choose the projects they believe to offer the best
prospective returns, and allowing the capital markets to back the
firms with the best track record. </p>
<p>The essential (Darwinian) condition for long term economic
success is that firms who make too many wrong choices must be
allowed to fail, and the investors who back them to lose their
money. If capital is allocated by the state, without the sanction
of bankruptcy for those who use the capital badly, the result is
the unproductive use of capital and slower growth. The extended
Communist experiment conclusively showed this. </p>
<p>When enterprises still in the public sector call for more
commercial freedom, what they usually mean is that they have some
good ideas in which they want to invest, but the Treasury won't
let them spend the money. As taxpayers, we should all be grateful
to the Treasury for preventing them from spending our money. But
as citizens, we should be concerned if there are rules which
prevent them from making profitable investments which the private
capital markets would willingly finance. </p>
<h4>The way forward</h4>
<p>If an enterprise in the public sector wishes to raise capital
and invest, it should be allowed to do so, subject to one
condition and one only: the money must be raised from a willing
lender in the private sector, who will get a belowaverage return
(or lose his money), if the project goes badly. The key is to
ringfence the investment, and ensure there is no
crosssubsidisation and no possibility of bail out by the
taxpayer. </p>
<p>Such ringfencing is achieved by privatisation. But that is not
the only possible method. The BBC, though in the public sector,
has a commercial arm and undertakes joint ventures with private
suppliers of capital (e.g. the Pearson deal). The Post Office is,
in theory, able to undertake joint ventures, though these still
require Ministerial approval. The PFI was explicitly framed to
permit joint ventures between public and private sector partners. </p>
<p>We are now more than a decade into the privatisation
programme. We should recognise that there may be good reasons why
the trading enterprises which are still in the public sector
should remain there. But there may be a great many commercial
ventures that such enterprises could undertake. Such ventures
should go forward on a project by project basis. Wholesale
privatisation of <i>enterprises </i>may be a thing of the past,
but the privatisation of <i>activities </i>will continue. </p>
<p><i>Contact Bill Robinson<br>
Edward Richards</i> </p>
<hr>
