<html>
<head>
<title>Regulation's long hot summer</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Regulation's long hot summer</h2>
<p><strong><i>In the last year the privatised utilities, in
particular water, electricity and gas have been subjected to an
exceptional degree of public criticism. The companies, the
regulators and the system of regulation have all been attacked,
but the calls for reform of utility governance are largely
misguided.</i></strong></p>
<hr>
<p>It has been an eventful summer. First Northern Electric's
offer of large extra payouts to its shareholders (to ward off the
bid from Trafalgar House) made Professor Littlechild suspect that
the industry was concealing significant potential cost savings.
He announced he would re-open his price review, sending
electricity share prices plunging the day after the Treasury had
sold another tranche of stock. The incident made the industry
look deceitful and the authorities incompetent. </p>
<p>Then as drought conditions brought the inevitable hosepipe
bans, public outrage turned on the water companies. The industry
is accused of pocketing higher charges without bothering to mend
leaky pipes, leaving it unable to deliver the product as required
and unwilling to make any refunds. </p>
<p>Meanwhile the simmering row over executive pay, though not
confined to the utilities, has put the spotlight on water and gas
chiefs. Executive pay, a drop in the ocean of total costs, does
not explain high charges. But it certainly has re-inforced the
public perception of utilities as greedy and inefficient. </p>
<p>Is this just silly season madness or are these fair
criticisms? And if so where does the fault lie? With the
companies? With the regulators? Or with a system of regulation
which sets prices for five years and allows companies to turn
efficiency gains, if better-than-expected, into profits? </p>
<p>In our view most of the present criticisms are misguided.
There is much to be said for an arms-length regulatory approach,
which sets a framework and allows the companies to run their
businesses without further interference. But the approach is not
without its problems. Over each five year period between
regulatory reviews, companies can make spectacular profits, as
the Regional Electricity Companies have done (they are now worth
4-5 times what they were originally sold for). Should the
regulator intervene to eliminate excessive profits? Or respect
the principle of a five-year run and await the next review? </p>
<p>Different regulators have adopted different approaches to this
issue. Reining back large profits is more likely to be
politically popular, but there is a lot to be said for not
changing the rules in the middle of the game. So it is
unfortunate that the MMC, which this summer has reported on the
price reviews of three companies, has endorsed a more intrusive
approach to regulation which may exacerbate some of the
weaknesses of the present situation. </p>
<h4>Accountability</h4>
<p>The calls for greater accountability of companies and
regulators seem particularly inappropriate and depend on a false
notion of accountability. When in the public sector, the
utilities were accountable daily to government. This hands-on
approach did not create efficient operations, run in the public
interest, but resulted in over-staffed, unresponsive
organisations that appeared to serve their employees better than
their customers. Far from delivering good governance, the daily
intrusion of government discouraged managers from taking
responsibility for important decisions. </p>
<p>The accountability that has resulted from privatisation is of
an entirely different nature and has been one of the success
stories of the policy. The management of the privatised utilities
are still accountable to the public, which is represented by the
regulators at OFWAT, OFFER, OFGAS and OFTEL. Every four to five
years the companies are reviewed and their price-caps
re-determined accordingly. In between they are left free to
manage their businesses as they see fit. </p>
<p>The consequence has been major strides in efficiency, mainly
through reductions in their manning levels. Giving freedom to the
companies to manage short-term, subject to regulatory control
over the medium term, has proved an effective formula. If the
efficiency gains are greater than expected, the shareholders
benefit in the short term. But the gains are passed on to the
customers at the next regulatory review. In the long run the
system delivers lower prices. </p>
<p>Calls for the utilities to become more accountable to their
customers would mean involving regulators and politicians more in
day-to-day management. In this context, the reaction to water
shortages in the present drought has been particularly alarming -
knee-jerk criticism of the water companies for failing to meet a
truly exceptional demand, and calls for intervention. </p>
<p>It would be quite wrong if managers were forced to spend more
on installing meters (the Government's response) or reducing
leaks (the Opposition's answer). We should ask only that the
water companies deliver enough water. Whether this is done most
efficiently by building more dams, plugging leaks or charging
heavily for hosepipes is a business decision for the water
experts, not the politicians, to take. These decisions have
already been incorporated in the companies' long-term investment
plans which have been reviewed by the regulator. If
accountability means making the companies respond to short-term
political pressures then their money will certainly be spent
unwisely - e.g. by over-investing to guarantee unlimited water
even in the most exceptional of conditions. </p>
<p>Calls for the regulators to be more accountable and less
individual in their approach seem equally misplaced. We can learn
from differences between the regulators. Their freedom to
innovate and develop regulation within a framework prescribed by
Parliament is the exact counterpart of giving independence and
direct responsibility to the utility managers. </p>
<p>Regulators, like managers, are more likely to perform well if
personally responsible for the process they oversee than if bound
by a rigid code. Like the companies, the regulators are given
short-term freedom to do what they think best and are then judged
every five years. If they do a good job they are re-appointed,
and not otherwise. The system works pretty well and should be
left alone. </p>
<h4>Profitability</h4>
<p>However, the debate about accountability would not have
occurred without a widespread feeling that the regulated
utilities are excessively profitable, and that the regulatory
system must have failed. </p>
<p>The profitability of the utilities has, it is true, increased
very significantly since privatisation. However, the main reason
for this is that the utilities were privatised on extremely
generous terms. Relatively lax price limits were set to make the
industries attractive to investors. Water profits for example,
though large, are no greater than predicted by the Department of
the Environment when the industry was privatised. So, if profits
are excessive, we should blame, not the system itself, but its
parameters - in this case the price targets set by the
politicians. The recent price reviews in water and electricity
have already sought to correct the problem by changing those
price targets so as to reduce profitability to more acceptable
levels. </p>
<h4>The incentive system</h4>
<p>Although much of the criticism of price regulation has missed
the point, the system is far from perfect. In particular the
incentives provided by price regulation for the utilities to
maximise efficiency gains and hence, in the long-run, to minimise
charges to customers, have not worked as well as they might. We
still observe huge differences in efficiency between companies in
electricity and water after five years of regulation. </p>
<p>In practice the biggest efficiency gains have occurred in
electricity generation and telecoms, where competition has been
introduced. In electricity distribution and water, where the
pressure for efficiency has come almost entirely from regulation,
the improvements have not been markedly greater than when the
companies were publicly-owned. </p>
<p>The method used by the regulators to improve efficiency is
known as comparative competition - the regulators stimulate
efficiency gains by comparing the utilities' performance against
each other, using the best performers as a benchmark towards
which the others should aspire. </p>
<p>If this process were working well we would expect to see the
financial performance of the regulated industries mimic those of
competitive industries. In a competitive market we would expect
to see the most efficient companies become more profitable than
others, while particularly inefficient companies might be
loss-making. </p>
<p>These badly run companies would then be the most likely
take-over targets, as outside interests identify the scope to
create shareholder value by improving their efficiency. In this
world, managers could relate their actions to clear financial
results. Changes that improve efficiency would lead to improved
profits. </p>
<p>However, the outcome of price regulation to date does not look
like this. There is no correlation between those companies the
regulators deem efficient and those that are most profitable. Nor
has there been sufficient stability in the process of judging
relative efficiency to allow utility managers to relate their
actions to measurable improvements in their efficiency ranking. </p>
<p>As a consequence the recent take-over activity in the utility
sector has not been particularly targeted on the most inefficient
companies. If the regulation of the utilities does not allow
efficient companies to earn higher profits than less efficient
companies then the incentive mechanism of regulation must be
called into question. Under the present system it is not clear
whether it is worthwhile for a company to be one of the most
efficient in its industry. </p>
<p>Unfortunately, the recent MMC investigations into utility
prices failed to address the issue of incentives. In fact, the
Commission dodged the whole issue of comparative competition,
preferring to focus in detail on the actual costs of the
companies. In so doing the Commission has given ammunition to the
voices calling for more intrusive regulation rather than take the
opportunity to fine-tune the existing regime to build on its
successes. </p>
<p><i>Contact </i><a href="mailto:dan@londecon.co.uk"><i>Dan
Elliott</i></a> </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1995 </p>
</body>
