Content-length: 6598
Last-modified: Sat, 14 Sep 1996 15:08:42 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Privatising infrastructure in Jamaica</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Privatising infrastructure in Jamaica</h2>
<p><strong><i>In Jamaica the population is increasing. The
country is also aware of rising environmental demands. Despite a
socialist government, Jamaica is now privatising its utilities.</i></strong></p>
<hr>
<p>Tourism is Jamaica's major industry, but keeping the beaches
pristine and the water sparkling needs big investments. A growing
population and a poor maintenance record mean major expenditure
is required in power, transport, and other infrastructure
services. Pot-holes and power cuts are turn-offs for tourists and
locals alike. </p>
<p>The Government's solution is privatisation. This is not an
ideological choice. The Peoples National Party are in power -
socialists who still address each other as `comrade' on formal
occasions. </p>
<p>But the Finance Minister, Dr. Omar Davis, needs to keep
spending down to safeguard the gains of Jamaica's IMF-supervised
stabilisation package. Other Cabinet members, notably the
Minister of Public Utilities, Robert Pickersgill, compare the
waste and inefficiency of Government enterprises with the
performance of the privatised Telecoms company, and wonder
whether Government should be in the utilities business at all. </p>
<p>Successful privatisation requires a credible regulatory
regime. The Government has just passed a new Office of Utilities
Regulation Act. This allows for politically independent economic
regulation, based on licences negotiated with each utility
operator. The Government called on London Economics to assist
with urgent changes to the law to make it more investor-friendly. </p>
<h4>Water</h4>
<p>Tourism in Jamaica uses vast quantities of water in the
jacuzzis, swimming pools and fountains of luxury hotels. The
National Water Commission (NWC) is universally acknowledged to be
badly run. Water shortages are frequent. Non-revenue water - that
is water, which either leaks away, or is used but not paid for -
is estimated at a staggering 70% of total water production. The
sewers in Kingston have deteriorated to the point that raw sewage
flows through downtown streets. </p>
<p>In May, following an investigation into corruption and
mismanagement, the Minister of Public Utilities asked for the
resignation of the entire NWC Board, and many of the senior
managers. He installed interim managers to curb corruption and
stave off bankruptcy. The Government needs a long term solution
to the water utility's problems, and asked London Economics to
develop options. A private water operating company, established
by a management contract or concession arrangement, is an
attractive solution - if the political obstacles can be overcome. </p>
<p>Any private operator in Jamaica would find it difficult. In
downtown Kingston, customers in ghetto communities like
Trenchtown simply refuse to pay for water or power. Disconnection
is no sanction, since illegal reconnection is rife. </p>
<p>Sometimes the disconnection teams themselves earn extra money
reconnecting customers they cut off earlier in the day. When the
electricity utility tried to cut all illegal connections in the
ghettos, it needed a military escort - and even so had only
temporary success. </p>
<p>Perhaps one reason for the payment difficulties is the price
of water, which is high by developing country standards, at
around US80c/cu.m. This has a positive side. If collection
problems and inefficiencies can be solved, water supply will be a
profitable business. </p>
<h4>Electricity</h4>
<p>The electricity utility has been state owned for years, but
was originally private. Locals say it has retained a more
business-like culture than the National Water Commission. Even
so, it suffers from over-staffing, difficulties in collecting
payment, and a lack of finance. A recent application for a tariff
increase was refused - the Public Utilities Commission said it
should cut costs instead. </p>
<p>In deciding to privatise the electricity utility, the
Government faced a difficult decision on industry structure. In
particular, how could the existing independent power producers be
protected? </p>
<p>At first the Government considered unbundling the industry,
with separate distribution and generation companies. This would
open the possibility of competition, and reassure the private
generators that they would not be savaged by a privately-owned,
vertically-integrated monopoly. </p>
<p>Unbundling raised costs. Each new company needed its own
administrative, finance and personnel staff. In addition, the
small size of Jamaica's power system meant that real competition
was unlikely. </p>
<p>US electricity companies approached the Government saying they
would like to buy the utility, but only as an integrated
business. Now the Jamaican electricity industry will be
privatised intact. Independent power producers will be protected
by regulation, and compete in supplying generating capacity. </p>
<h4>Institution building</h4>
<p>Jamaica's infrastructure problems stem from institutional
weaknesses. Because planners have not had the right incentives,
they do not appraise projects. Utilities neglect routine
maintenance. State-owned companies avoid the chore of debt
collection, knowing the Government will pick up the tab
eventually. </p>
<p>The international agencies are prepared to finance the work
London Economics is currently doing to help change Jamaican
institutions and the incentives for those who work in them. The
World Bank is helping the Government to improve utilities
management and increase private sector participation. USAID is
developing a private sector, community-based, water retailing
system. </p>
<p>The European Union is paying for the water company to twin
with a European counterpart. Thames Water won the twinning
contract, putting itself in pole position for any subsequent
management contract or concession. </p>
<p>With a growing demand for infrastructure services, a credible
regulatory system and privatisation in the air, the Jamaican
climate could become as attractive to investors as it is to
tourists. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1995 </p>
</body>
</html>
