<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT11-B06-129</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA036-000712-B021-252</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.londecon.co.uk:80/pubs/privat/discret.htm 194.193.150.111 19970111020008 text/html 10024
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 11 Jan 1997 01:55:01 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 9853
Last-modified: Sat, 14 Sep 1996 15:08:29 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Discretion rules, OK</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Discretion rules, OK</h2>
<p><b><i>In November 1995, Oftel held the first public hearing in
the history of UK utility regulation, on the proposal to
introduce a provision in operators' licences prohibiting
anti-competitive behaviour. Oftel's suggestions were opposed by
British Telecom, but supported by most other operators. Oftel
asked John Kay, Chairman of LE, to provide an independent
contribution to the debate. This is an edited text of what he
said.</i></b></p>
<hr>
<p>&quot;There are two issues in serious dispute. The first is
whether regulation is best conducted by reference to general
principles, with considerable discretion given to the regulator
in their application, or by means of specific rules. The other,
closely related, issue is whether the existing procedures for
challenging a regulatory decision are adequate. </p>
<p>Everyone must sympathise with the demand from regulated firms
for clarity and certainty in regulation. There would be much to
be said for a structure in which managers had full commercial
freedom within a framework of unambiguous rules. But in practice,
an attempt to lay down clear specific rules is likely to be more
intrusive in the commercial freedom of regulated companies than
the exercise of regulatory discretion. </p>
<p>Consider some of the issues with which a utility regulator is
faced, such as price discrimination or vertical restraints. Are
differences in tariffs which are not related to differences in
cost acceptable, or excessive? Are restrictions by suppliers on
the ways in which their goods can be resold anti-competitive or
pro-competitive in effect? What is the cost of capital to a
regulated utility? The answers to these questions necessarily
involve the exercise of judgement. Such questions have to be
answered from a deep and wide understanding of the commercial
context. If, for example, a company immediately matches a
competitor's low price, that decision may be pro-competitive in
some circumstances and anti-competitive in others. </p>
<p>There is a second aspect to this exercise of judgement. There
is what one might call a penumbra to all these decisions. Take,
for example, the issue of BT's cost of capital. A 15% real return
is obviously too high, and a 5% real return clearly too low. But
there is a range within which a reasonable regulator might choose
one figure or another. There can be no definitive right or wrong
answer. Similarly, some instances of price discrimination are
obviously unacceptable. But, in a business like
telecommunications it would be impracticable, even if it were
desirable, to relate the charge for every individual service
exactly to the cost of providing that service. </p>
<p>So there is really no hope that regulation can be conducted by
reference to a set of definitive rules. The attempt to achieve
this in the financial services industry was not successful and it
became necessary to retreat to a regime which allowed more
subjective interpretation. I believe that the process of defining
general objectives, and allowing their application to develop
over time, is not just the best way, but in practice the only
way, of undertaking the regulation of industry. Nor can we hope
to avoid the need for ad hoc investigation of particular cases.
This is particularly true in telecommunications, where rapidly
changing technology and the complexity of some of the issues mean
that attempts to prescribe in advance for all situations are
bound to fail. </p>
<h4>Judge or expert?</h4>
<p>The real issue is whether discretion should be exercised by
judicial process through the courts, or by an expert but
non-judicial body, such as a regulatory agency, with
investigative powers. From my own experience of judgements on
economic and commercial matters made in both types of
environment, I have very little doubt that they are better made
by an independent, expert agency with powers to seek its own
evidence and advice. Adversarial procedures, in which one side
argues that black is white and another that white is black, after
which a judge has to decide which of these preposterous
contentions is closer to the truth, are not an effective means of
resolving these kinds of issues. Despite the length and expense
of legal processes, there is no guarantee that the relevant
issues will emerge. There is a tendency for the result to be
influenced by the capabilities of the advocates, and hence by the
resources of the parties. </p>
<p>Moreover, contested process can only operate in circumstances
in which there is a competing contrary contention. In matters
such as the assessment of BT's costs of capital, there is not. I
therefore support Oftel's desire to regulate by reference to
general principles, rather than an ever-growing list of specific
prohibitions. I am also sure Oftel is right to prefer provisions
based on Articles 85 and 86 of the Treaty of Rome to the
development of British legislation within the context of the Fair
Trading Act. </p>
<p>However, Articles 85 and 86 of the Rome treaty were written 30
years ago, and we have learnt from experience. Article 86
prohibits abuse of a dominant position; I believe it is necessary
to be more specific about what is meant by abuse. Since BT's
dominance of many telecommunications markets is beyond dispute,
anything BT does might be interpreted as abuse of a dominant
position. </p>
<h4>Consumer unfriendly?</h4>
<p>Abuse is indicated by actions which are directly detrimental
to consumers, or by actions which have the intention or effect of
restricting the ability of efficient competitors to meet customer
needs. Since in general only a dominant firm could do these
things, the separate requirement to establish dominance serves
little purpose. </p>
<p>The second issue I identified at the beginning was the
adequacy of the system of appeal against the regulator's
decisions. British Telecom has put forward a list of eight
&quot;rights&quot; which it believes it should enjoy against its
regulator, starting with the proposition that no regulator should
be both judge and jury. I believe this analogy with the conduct
of criminal procedures is fundamentally misconceived. The
regulator is not a judge, but an executive agent, charged with
pursuit of a range of statutory obligations, such as the
development of competition and the promotion of an efficient
industry. </p>
<p>It is right that those who make decisions should be made
accountable for the consequences of their actions, but that is
not the same as saying that their processes should mimic the
proceedings of the Old Bailey. This situation would change if the
regulator were to be entrusted with judicial authority: if his
principal duty were to impose penalties for illegal actions. But
there is no suggestion of this kind in the Oftel proposals. </p>
<p>The need for accountability in such a framework does require
that a mechanism for challenging decisions should exist, but it
should be an exceptional rather than a routine mechanism. The
right of challenge should not be available simply because some
other person faced with the same facts might have come to a
different, equally reasonable, decision. It should be restricted
to decisions which are so bizarre as to lie outside the penumbra
within which reasonable men could come to different views. The
right of challenge should also relate to issues which are of such
central importance to regulation that there should be an
opportunity for full public debate and reconsideration. </p>
<p>The two appellate mechanisms which exist at present - the
threat of judicial review and the opportunity to debate licence
amendments before the MMC - are directly relevant. Indeed, the
scope of judicial review may now be rather too wide. Judges have
increasingly been ready to review the substantive merits of
decisions, rather than to apply the Wednesbury test of whether
they lie outside the bounds of reasonableness. While there have
been no successful judicial reviews of Oftel's decisions, the
threat of judicial review is exerting an increasingly paralysing
effect on public agencies. </p>
<p>However, regulatory decisions of major importance will not
always involve amendments to the licence. The MMC should (and
under existing powers could) be given a wider role. It may be
desirable to codify and extend the opportunities for broader
utility references, exemplified by the approach to British Gas.
Moreover, the appellate mechanism might be available to parties
other than licensees, notably consumers. </p>
<h4>Conclusions</h4>
<p>To summarise, therefore: I prefer general principles to
specific rules, and believe that Articles 85 and 86 of the Treaty
of Rome provide an appropriate basis. I do, however, think there
is a strong case for specifying the nature of practice which
should be deemed to constitute an abuse of a dominant market
position. </p>
<p>As to the question of appeal mechanisms, I am not persuaded
that there are fundamental weaknesses in the existing British
structure of regulation. Perhaps the most useful reform would be
to clarify and codify the opportunities for the MMC to become
involved in the process of utility regulation. In any event, some
standardisation of the different powers it has in different
industries would be desirable. </p>
<hr>
