<title>Cutting waste in wastewater</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Cutting waste in wastewater</h2>
<p><b><i>With 30 water companies in England and Wales, Ofwat is
better placed than most regulators to use comparative
benchmarking techniques to assess efficiency. It has pioneered
the rigorous and systematic collection of data and undertook a
major benchmarking exercise for the 1994 Periodic Review. This
was an important input into its determination of water prices for
the next five years.</i></b> </p>
<hr>
<p>Now Ofwat is considering new benchmarking techniques to
compare water companies' efficiency. In the course of previous
studies, Ofwat had found little evidence of economies of scale in
the treatment of sewage. This surprised industry experts, who
believe there is strong operational and engineering evidence for
scale economies. </p>
<p>London Economics recently compared the efficiency of a British
wastewater company with its peers, using some of the new
techniques Ofwat may be considering. To enhance the comparison,
LE drew on more recent data than Ofwat had used, and on data we
have collected from around the world. Our study showed that
overall economies of scale measured in two ways are statistically
significant, as the chart shows. </p>
<p>The study provided the client with significant re-ratings of
British companies' efficiency in sewage treatment and sewerage.
LE was also able to calculate potential savings on power, labour
and other costs for the client and other wastewater companies. </p>
<p><b>Contact: Mark Hull</b> </p>
