<head>
<title>The Economics of Product Liability</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>The Economics of Product Liability</h2>
<p><i>When should a manufacturer face liability for the injury
caused by his product? Should he be liable only when proven
negligent, or held strictly liable for any defect? Can the law
accurately discriminate between defective and dangerous products?</i></p>
<hr>
<p>These are only some of the issues which arise in the design of
product liability laws. </p>
<p>Product liability laws have a dual function: to encourage
product safety, and to provide adequate redress should accidents
occur. Traditional legal practice has emphasised the latter, the
fair compensation of losses. The economist analyses this aspect
of product liability as the demand for compensation or insurance,
but is more interested in the former, the control of risk and the
function of law in ensuring product safety more generally. </p>
<p>Liability rules give incentives for consumers and producers to
take care in the manufacture and handling of products. The
individual economic agents who face liability have an interest in
foreseeing risks and acting accordingly. So they have an interest
in investigating and researching product safety. </p>
<p>An economically efficient liability rule would shift liability
to the producer whenever the consumer misperceives the risk of
products; otherwise the consumer would have to bear the losses
himself. The key issue is the perception of risk by the consumer,
no the level of care of the manufacturer. A product is defective
if it does not exhibit the level of safety a consumer generally
expects. If the consumer is able to assess the trade-offs between
risk and cost, then it is efficient for him to bear any losses. </p>
<p>How close does the law come to economic efficiency? Leading
court cases have decide liability over injuries resulting from an
exploding lemonade bottle, a shattered windscreen or a nasty
accident involving an electric lawnmower; in individual cases a
judge can attempt to assess acceptable control of risk. </p>
<p>The investigation of product liability laws in Britain and
Germany in a research project sponsored by the Anglo-German
Foundation applied all these questions to the legal situation
before and after harmonisation of the product liability laws in
the European Community. </p>
<p>It found that although the two countries have very different
legal systems - one formal and laid down in statute, the other
informal and based on case precedents - inc practise, the
liability rules operated in both countries in a similar way. The
empirical analysis of over 300 court cases suggested, however,
that British courts on the whole took the ability of consumers to
observe and control product risk m ore explicitly into account,
whereas the German courts focused very much on the situation of
the manufacturer. </p>
<hr>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
</body>
</html>
