<html>
<head>
<title>Born to Shop on Sunday?</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Born to Shop on Sunday?</h2>
<p><i>The Sunday trading issue is in the news again. Retailers,
lobby groups and the Government all have their own preferred
options for reform.</i></p>
<hr>
<p>The main proposals are the Powell Bill, those put forward by
Marks and Spencer and the Shopping Hours Reform Council, and full
deregulation. London Economics' report shows how big an effect
each of them has on the extent of Sunday opening, prices,
employment and wages in the retail sector, and allows the reader
to judge their respective merits. </p>
<p>Widely divergent claims are made for these proposals. Those
who favour restrictions point to the congestion, shortterm costs
to retailers, and effects on employees of Sunday opening. Their
opponents cite increased consumer convenience and efficiency, and
possible increases in retail spending. </p>
<p>What is the balance between these arguments? In a study
commissioned by the Home Office, London Economics gives the first
impartial economic analysis of the four main proposals. </p>
<p>What is the current face of Sunday trading? Over a third of
shops now open on Sundays. Yet Sunday opening does not increase
overall retail sales. Sunday sales gained by one retailer are at
the expense of others, or of weekday sales. Retailing is also
undergoing a profound restructuring. </p>
<p>London Economics built a database, incorporating the cost
structures of over 700 firms, and a model of the retail sector.
This enabled us to predict: </p>
<ul>
    <li>the proportion of shops which would open on Sundays under
        each proposal, as a result of legal restrictions and
        profit considerations; </li>
    <li>the long run effect on retail prices and the cost of
        retail purchases to the average family; </li>
    <li>the long run effect on retail employment; and </li>
    <li>the effect on average retail wages. </li>
</ul>
<p>Each individual retailer is like a blind man who only feels
his part of the retailing &quot;elephant&quot;. So just adding up
individual responses will not show how each proposal might change
the market. Only modelling incorporates the overall behaviour of
the market how demand changes, and how consumers respond to
prices. </p>
<p>Each proposal had to be put on an equal footing not easy as
hours and size of store allowed to open varied in each proposal.
With some shops open and others closed, cost data had also to be
adjusted to a common &quot;starting line&quot;, with no Sunday
opening. And we wanted to be able to allow for changes in the
basic assumptions, for instance about wage premia on Sundays. </p>
<p>Research on retailing is bedevilled by lack of accurate data.
We painstakingly compiled data from confidential questionnaires
sent to over 500 firms, data from over 600 company reports, and a
survey of 2000 consumers. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Back to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1993 </p>
