Content-length: 7391
Last-modified: Sat, 14 Sep 1996 15:09:33 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Grocery retailers - heroes or villains?</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Grocery retailers - heroes or villains?</h2>
<p><i>Over the past few years leading grocery retailers have been
under attack. Firms like Tesco, Sainsbury's, Safeway and Asda
have been regularly accused of making excess profits, failing to
pass on price cuts, exploiting cheap labour and of ruining
Britain's town centres. </i></p>
<p><i>Guilty as charged? Or are major grocers among Britain's
most innovative, competitive and efficient industries?</i></p>
<hr>
<h4>The service sector</h4>
<p>There is a widespread, but wrong, belief that making things
(manufacturing) is inherently superior to doing things for people
(services). Yet all the successful modern economies are
characterised by strong service sectors. It is the richest
economies (e.g. the US) which have the <i>smallest</i> share of
national output in manufacturing. By contrast, in the former
Communist countries, where manufacturing is king, the poor
quality of life is legendary. The reason is that even East
Germany has not invested in the services that make modern life so
convenient. </p>
<p>Insufficient investment used to be a story more often told
about Britain than Germany. Yet investment in services was the
cornerstone of the UK's improved growth performance in the 1980s.
Much of that investment was in retailing, with major grocers
leading the field. New superstores sprang up all over the
country, mostly in convenient locations with good parking. The
number of product lines - including a wide range of fresh fruit
and vegetables - increased substantially. And check- out queues
shrank dramatically. </p>
<p>In short, the grocery retailers moved their service sharply
up-market. The improvements were the result of heavy investment,
notably in bar- coding technology, central warehousing
facilities, and better distribution systems (e.g. refrigerated
lorries). This in turn permitted rapid scanning (shorter
check-out queues), better stock control (more lines, always in
stock) and fresher produce (the sell-by date, which we now take
for granted, was a rarity in 1980). Moreover, these manifest
improvements in service were achieved with fewer staff, freeing
resources - including labour - for other productive activities. </p>
<p>The above picture, which most of us would recognise from our
own experience, is borne out by the statistics: average store
size up by 85 per cent; number of product lines up by 150 per
cent; turnover per employee up by 15 per cent. </p>
<h4>Gross margins</h4>
<p>Yet despite these achievements, the large grocers remain
unloved. One reason is that they are suspected of profiteering:
gross margins - the grocery retailers' mark-ups - have risen
since 1980, and by more than in other retail sectors. </p>
<p>Retail margins are effectively the price the retailers charge
for the service they provide. If the service is better, and more
costly to provide, it is not surprising that the price has also
gone up. A large grocery retailer, like the owner of a
refurbished restaurant with a new menu, needs to increase prices
to recoup their investment - and they can do so because the
public will pay more for a better-quality product. </p>
<p>But from another viewpoint, the retailers' story is much
better than that. The increase in retail margins has not been
achieved at the expense of the shopper. Gross margins have
widened not because prices have gone up but because staff numbers
and hence costs per unit of labour have come down. </p>
<p>These savings have benefited all the stakeholders in the
industry. Customers have benefited from lower prices. Employees
have enjoyed above-average wage increases. Lenders have been
given a safe return at market rates. The providers of risk
capital have seen dividends comfortably outperform the market. </p>
<p>These facts are well documented in a detailed analysis of the
accounts of 15 major companies who together account for nearly
two thirds of total grocery sales. That analysis shows that over
the period 1984 to 1992, a period in which real food prices were
falling, there was some widening in margins, which benefited
employees, the providers of loan capital, and (to a very small
extent) shareholders. The vast bulk of the benefit from lower
prices was passed on to customers. </p>
<h4>Prices</h4>
<p>It is worth exploring why this is not widely perceived - why
retailers are often accused of widening their margins by failing
to pass on the real falls in food prices that occurred in the
1980s. </p>
<p>It is undoubtedly true that the retail price of processed food
has not fallen as much, in real terms, as the price of
agricultural produce. But this is not because retailers have
widened their margins. Rather it is because the food
manufacturers have been processing the food more intensively. In
the average two-earner household neither partner has the time to
prepare food from scratch, while between them they can afford to
pay the extra cost of ready-made meals. The higher prices thus
reflect a great deal of added value to the consumer. </p>
<p>These developments can be documented statistically, using
official data on food prices at each stage of the value chain,
from farm to factory to store. The chart shows that farm prices
have fallen substantially in real terms since the late 1970s, but
only part of this has been passed on by manufacturers, who have
produced higher quality products. Retail prices have fallen in
real terms more or less in line with the output prices of food
manufacturers. So although grocery retailers have increased the
quality of their service, final consumer prices have clearly
fallen substantially and the consumer has benefited by more than
either the manufacturers or retailers of food. </p>
<h4>Social consequences</h4>
<p>We have witnessed a quiet revolution in the nation's shopping
habits over the past decade or two. The grocery retailers have
done a remarkable job in upgrading the service they provide to
the typical relatively affluent and invariably car-borne
household. They have invested heavily, in new stores, in
technology, and in car parking facilities, making the one-stop
shop a surprisingly agreeable chore, and giving the typical
family more time for leisure and for work. </p>
<p>But any revolution has its casualties. In an increasingly
car-oriented society, those without cars - mainly the elderly -
find that life gets more difficult. Their plight has prompted a
political backlash against the edge-of- town shopping centres
that serve so many of us so well. That is probably the main
reason why the large supermarket chains fail to inspire
affection. But it must be wrong to blame the large grocery
chains, which have been so successful in meeting the needs of the
car-borne majority, for the difficulties of the carless minority. </p>
<p><i>Contact: Edward Richards<br>
Bill Robinson</i> </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1995 </p>
</body>
</html>
