<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Retailing's Next Revolution?</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Retailing's Next Revolution?</h2>
<p><b><i>Terry Leahy of Tesco led the cast of experts debating
the future of retailing at LE's conference in February.</i></b> </p>
<hr>
<p>In February, London Economics held a conference in London on
the future of retailing, against the background of further
analysis by Nick Morris and Bill Robinson of the impact of the
change in the industry over the past decade (commissioned by
Tesco). Massive investment, changes in technology, changes in
types of employment, a different and greater mix of goods
available to customers had gone hand-in-hand with the advent of
out-of-town grocery superstores - characterised as both heroes
and villains of this revolution. The key conclusions on the
&quot;heroes&quot; side of the argument were that consumers had
gained, to the tune of &#163;300 per household per year, from
lower prices. Employees had gained, through a rise in real wages
in retailing financed by increased efficiency. Shareholders had
also gained, if more modestly than consumers, to the tune of
&#163;100m. But the conference also enabled the case against
&quot;villains&quot; to be discussed: the impact of the
revolution on corner shops, city centres and the still-large
minority of consumers who cannot shop by car. </p>
<p>Most interest was focused on future trends. LE's chairman,
John Kay, began by characterising the consumer's problem in
Hobbesian style. If their lives are no longer nasty, brutish and
short, they still suffer from disadvantages in the market place:
consumers are ignorant, small and immobile. &quot;Middlemen&quot;
are needed to solve these problems. They search and select,
bargain and buy, and get the goods to the customer. These are the
three key functions of retailing, carried out separately or
together. </p>
<p>Terry Leahy emphasised the scope for retailers to carry out
even greater search and selection in the future: &quot;Successful
retailing is all about guessing what people might want, trying it
out, and responding quickly to people's revealed
preferences.&quot; New micro-marketing techniques, he argued,
would mean that the retailers of the future will be much better
able respond to consumers - to spot and fill gaps in their
product range. Part of the experience of running a &quot;home
shopping&quot; television channel, articulated at the conference
by Richard Burrell of QVC, is of instant, powerful information on
customer preferences: best-seller or flop, live television gives
the verdict with brutally immediate frankness. </p>
<h4>Don't leave home?</h4>
<p>Electronic shopping offers the opportunity for home-based
search and more organised personal selection. Interactive systems
enable the customer to search databases of, for example,
second-hand cars or houses for sale, in a way which reflects
their own personal preferences rather than some rank-ordering
imposed by others in a printed publication. But even these
systems still provide no answer to the third of the consumer's
problems: immobility. While some services (travel agency,
financial advice) and even some products (video, learning
materials) can be delivered down a cable, you cannot be delivered
a pound of cheese or a new carpet that way. And &quot;virtual
shopping&quot; is still some way from the experience of seeing,
touching and feeling what you are going to buy. </p>
<p>But all speakers saw the potential for some further dramatic
shifts in retailing. Jim Rose of Nielsen pointed towards
diversification out of food. John Kay saw scope for full
&quot;retailing&quot; - firms bringing together the three key
functions - across a range of services currently outside the
retail sector. Terry Leahy told the conference to expect a
continual evolution in the format of outlets, ranging from large
food stores for car-borne shoppers to convenience express stores
for people shopping on their own two feet - and new schemes for
meeting the needs of those who cannot walk to the shops at all.
&quot;You should not expect us to go on opening large
edge-of-town stores largely after the need for new ones has
passed.&quot; </p>
<p>Nor can the retail industry expect to be allowed a free
development hand. William de Winton of Hoare, Govett, Keith Vaz,
the Shadow Minister for Planning and Regeneration and Sarah Hogg
of LE discussed the planning policy background, starting from the
latest state of thinking at the Department of the Environment.
This reflected a hierarchy of planning preferences for retailing,
running from city centres through edge-of-centre, with
out-of-town at the bottom of the list. But this should not be
allowed to fossilise city-centre high streets, when a number of
different locations might fulfil such planning criteria as good
transport connections and regeneration potential. </p>
<p>Contact: Nick Morris, Bill Robinson </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
