<html>
<head>
<title>Cigarette Bootlegging</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Cigarette Bootlegging</h2>
<p><i>Modelling work undertaken at London Economics suggests
bootlegging is likely to be more prevalent in Europe than it is
in the US, once border controls are removed.</i> </p>
<hr>
<p>As the EC moves towards an internal market, it aims to remove
all frontier controls between member states by the end of 1992.
Consumers will then be free to take advantage of price
differentials between countries by crossing frontiers to buy
goods more cheaply. </p>
<p>This is particularly important in the cigarette market where
differential tax rates across the EC have generated substantial
retail price differences. </p>
<h4>The Scrivener proposals</h4>
<p>The European Commission has proposed minimum rates of excise
duty and VAT for cigarettes from the end of 1992. These
&quot;Scrivener proposals&quot; seek to harmonise rates but fail
to reduce the present taxinduced spread of retail prices across
the member states sufficiently to remove incentives for cross
frontier shopping and bootlegging. </p>
<p>Failure to address this problem will result in many potential
gains of the internal market being lost. Trade flows across the
frontiers will be largely determined not by relative costs of
supply, but by tax rates. Multiple tax rates distort, and will
subvert the desired economic efficiency. </p>
<p>Individual governments also stand to lose tax revenue, as
cross border shoppers concentrate sales in lowtax countries.
Countries with densely populated, long land frontiers where the
population is highly mobile are most at risk, but such
bootlegging could easily take place between any two member
states, regardless of their geographical position. </p>
<p>Unless action is taken by the Commission the current range of
cigarette prices will provide incentives for illegal bootlegging
in bulk of truckloads from low to high tax countries. The
criminal underworld would gain a new and potentially lucrative
income. </p>
<h4>The US example</h4>
<p>The United States provides an example of how real this threat
is. There, multiple tax rates coexist with open frontiers between
states. It is estimated that there was a national net loss of tax
revenue of $179m in 1989. Much bootlegging is undertaken on an
organised crime basis, despite the $23m devoted by federal
authorities alone over the last ten years for contraband
lawenforcement. </p>
<p>Remove frontier controls and bootlegging is likely to be even
more prevalent in Europe than in the US, as differences in retail
prices are much greater. </p>
<h4>The solution</h4>
<p>To prevent this happening, the Commission needs to act
urgently to reduce tax induced price differentials. Modelling
simulations suggest that the Scrivener proposals are unlikely to
reduce significantly price differentials and that this would be
more successfully achieved by the application of a banded tax
system in which the EC specifies minimum and maximum tax yields
per thousand cigarettes. This reduces the effect of taxation on
the spread of retail prices, by acting directly on tax yields,
not tax rates. Moreover it would allow individual member states
relative freedom to determine their own preferred combination of
tax rates. </p>
<p>Such a system would reduce the quantity of crossfrontier
activity by reducing the spread of retail prices. The benefits of
free trade would not be undermined by tax revenue losses or the
development of illegal bootlegging. </p>
<hr>
