<html>
<head>
<title>Curbing Inflation in Turkmenistan</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Curbing Inflation in Turkmenistan</h2>
<p><i>London Economics' international macro team has been
participating in an ECfunded mission to examine the Turkmen tax
system and recommend practical reforms that will put the economy
on the path to steady growth with low inflation. The country
faces a formidable inflation problem which can be traced to an
unusual source.</i></p>
<hr>
<p>Turkmenistan is one of the less wellknown countries in the
Former Soviet Union (FSU). Though large in land area, it is
mainly desert (the Kara Khum) and the 4 million population mainly
inhabit the strip of fertile land in the south, bounded by the
great Kara Khum canal to the north, the Caspian Sea to the West,
and the Iranian mountains to the south. </p>
<p>Turkmenistan produces two exportable goods with hardcurrency
value: gas, distributed by pipeline to other former Soviet
provinces, and cotton. It seems well placed to escape the
difficulties that have beset the rest of the FSU. Yet it suffers
from all the familiar problems. Inflation is currently running at
2030 per cent per month. The new national currency, the manat,
launched in November 1993 at 2 to the dollar, is now trading at
200 on the free market. There is a large budget deficit. </p>
<p>At one level, it is not surprising that Turkmenistan should
have a serious inflation problem, because the whole of the former
Soviet Union has been suffering in recent years from price
increases of the order of 2030 per cent a month. Turkmenistan is
still intimately connected with the FSU. Around 70 per cent of
consumer goods are imported, mainly from the FSU, and with them
comes the inflation that is endemic there. </p>
<p>On the other hand, the Turkmen government now has an
independent currency, and can run its own fiscal and monetary
policy. Its gas exports should guarantee a strong balance of
payments. So why has it not escaped the problems that beset its
neighobours? </p>
<h4>Government deficits</h4>
<p>One important reason is that the bulk of Turkmen gas exports
go to the FSU (mainly to the Ukraine) who are unable to pay. This
has created serious problems for the government, who are
dependent on tax and royalties from the gas revenues to balance
the budget. The resulting budget deficit, financed by printing
manat, has been an important factor in taking the country to the
brink of hyperinflation. </p>
<p>The standard explanation of the inflationary process in the
FSU is that it is a function of excessive monetary growth, of
which the root cause is large public deficits (including deficits
of the stateowned enterprises). If the state spends more than it
receives in tax revenue, it is making claims on resources that
the private sector has not yielded up. If the deficit is financed
by borrowing from the central bank, the result is the creation of
monetary claims in excess of the value of goods available. The
result is a classic demandled inflation, with too much money
chasing too few goods. </p>
<p>In Turkmenistan, the deficits of the government and of state
owned enterprises are swollen, right across the economy, by the
knockon effects of the nonpayment of gas revenues. </p>
<p>Every inflation has a real (sociopolitical) cause underlying
the monetary cause. Inflation occurs because citizens have
expectations of a higher living standard than the system can
deliver. This was true of German hyperinflation of 1922 (when war
reparations left little foreign exchange available to buy
consumer goods). It was true of the milder inflation that hit the
West following the oil price hike in the mid1970s. It has been
true of the inflation in the FSU since the reforms, which have
caused a sharp reduction in output and living standards. </p>
<p>The current Turkmen inflation also reflects disappointed
expectations. But in the Turkmen case this is not because output
has fallen, but because they are not being paid for their gas.
The effect is the same, or even worse since gas resources are
depleted but no revenues are received. There are fewer goods and
services available in the Turkmen economy, and until the gas
revenues start to flow again, the economic system has to find a
way of making people consume less. </p>
<h4>The role of the exchange rate</h4>
<p>It is interesting to examine the role played by the exchange
rate in the inflationary process. The initial impetus comes from
the budget deficit and the resulting excess supply of manat,
which drives up the prices (in manat) of goods on the local
market. As long as the exchange rate is fixed, this makes foreign
goods increasingly attractive, so there is an increased demand
for dollars. The government then has two options, neither of them
attractive: </p>
<ul>
    <li><i>Hold the manat fixed at the official rate</i>. The
        consequence is that all the export earnings from oil and
        cotton are translated into manat at an increasingly
        unrealistic exchange rate. The government would find
        itself in a position where its outgoings were subject to
        the domestic rate of inflation, while its income was
        virtually fixed in manat terms. (Imagine how large the
        government's budget deficit would be if foreign exchange
        earnings from gas were still converted into manat at the
        original exchange rate of 2 to the dollar.) To protect
        its own revenue, therefore, the government is obliged,
        sooner or later, to: </li>
    <li><i>Devalue the official exchange rate for the manat</i>.
        This has the immediate consequence of boosting government
        revenue. But it also pushes up the manat price of
        imports, and since Turkmenistan meets some 70 per cent of
        its domestic needs with imports, the increase in their
        prices sets off another round of the inflationary spiral. </li>
</ul>
<p>How can the Turkmen authorities break into this vicious
circle? They have little alternative but to raise taxes and cut
spending so as to rein back demand to match the reduced level of
supply. In the absence of tough and unpopular measures, demand
and supply will continue to be balanced, as at present, by means
of the automatic emergency tax known as inflation. </p>
<p><i>Contact: Bill Robinson<br>
Alberto Pototschnig</i> </p>
<hr>
