<DOCOLDNO>IA036-000712-B023-146</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.londecon.co.uk:80/pubs/taxation/thebill.htm 194.193.150.111 19970111020443 text/html 7792
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 11 Jan 1997 01:58:57 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 7621
Last-modified: Sat, 14 Sep 1996 15:10:27 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Sharing the bill for lunch</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Sharing the bill for lunch</h2>
<p><b><i>Three years' experience, plus a squeeze on public
capital spending, have brought the Private Finance Initiative
into the consciousness of every Government department, and should
bring it on to the agenda of every company with an interest in
managing infrastructure projects or running public services. The
key issue in almost all of these is the allocation of risk
between public and private partners - an issue on which LE has
established expertise to offer. </i></b></p>
<hr>
<p>The Private Finance Initiative was intended to fill the gap
between privatisation - taking activities out of the public
sector altogether - and contracting out - the opportunity to
provide services for the public sector. Under the PFI, private
firms provide the capital asset (road, prison, hospital building)
as well as some or all of the services associated with it. The
potential was enormous. But when the PFI was launched in 1992,
sceptics expected to see only a handful of transport projects get
a - grudging - seal of Treasury approval. </p>
<p>And for a time, the PFI languished on the launch-pad, while
private industry complained about the obstacles in the way of
securing Treasury approval. The Treasury, too, was finding its
way up the learning curve, trying to prevent the initiative
degenerating into creative accounting, or stacking up
unmanageable future running costs. </p>
<p>Since then, however, the PFI approach has been spreading
beyond transport to health, education, prisons, defence, water
and sewerage, urban regeneration, information systems and
government property. (Even the Treasury decided to avail itself
of PFI techniques to finance the development of its own
inconvenient building - perhaps the most intriguing sign of
offical conversion to the initiative.) </p>
<p>Today, state-of-the-art PFI is opening up opportunities to any
who can put together balance sheet strength, operator skills, and
ability to design a project which meets public sector economic
and social criteria while offering a satisfactory rate of return.
Above all, that requires know-how in the economic analysis of
risk, to achieve a split between public and private sectors that
will pass through the eye of the Treasury needle. </p>
<p>Although proposals may still fail to escape the confines of
public expenditure (see box), some of the more cumbersome
pre-conditions have been removed. </p>
<p>The rules for &quot;value-for-money&quot; analysis have been
codified, and it is no longer necessary to construct and price an
artificial &quot;public sector comparator&quot; for a project
which was never going to go ahead out of public expenditure,
anyway. </p>
<h4>Three kinds of PFI</h4>
<ul>
    <li><b>Free-standing</b>. The public sector acts as
        &quot;enabler&quot;, dealing with outline planning,
        licensing, providing ancillary works, etc. The private
        sector finances the project, and recovers costs from
        charges to the user. But the public sector may still
        carry some residual risk, if - for example - the asset
        transfers back to it at the end of a certain period. <i>Example:
        Queen Elizabeth II Bridge (Dartford-Thurrock).</i> </li>
    <li><b>Service provider</b>. The public sector acts as
        &quot;customer&quot;, buying services from the managers
        of the PFI project, who finance its construction and run
        its operations. Alternatively, the public sector may
        lease the capital asset from the private sector. The
        public sector may continue to carry some operating risk,
        if it flows from changes in policy that might undermine
        the project's viability. <i>Examples: Northern Line
        trains, re-development of the Treasury, private prisons.</i> </li>
    <li><b>Joint venture</b>. The public sector meets part of the
        capital costs - normally in pursuit of a wider social
        objective than the private sector could be expected to
        meet. The private sector has to have effective control -
        otherwise the project will fall back into the category of
        &quot;public expenditure&quot;. But the public sector may
        have an equity stake, or a public body may be part of an
        arrangement with a private company - or it may merely
        contribute grants, loans or existing assets. The
        distribution of risk obviously depends on the mix. <i>Examples:
        Channel Tunnel Rail Link, Croydon Tramlink.</i> </li>
</ul>
<h4>Piggy-back business</h4>
<p>The Treasury's latest schedule of potential PFI projects runs
to a total of over 1,000, with a capital value of around &#163;25
billion. The estimated present value of the payments throughout
these projects' lives is &#163;40 billion or more. More important
than this official &quot;wish list&quot;, however, are the
signals to business to use PFI techniques in an innovative way. </p>
<p>In particular, these are opportunities to piggy-back further
business on a project for the public sector, by developing
private services in parallel, selling surplus capacity or
software systems, developing surplus land or buildings. The
gradual opening up of the local authority sector to PFI offers
particular scope for lateral business thinking. </p>
<p>To begin with, both the Treasury and private companies were
somewhat inclined to see the PFI as a free lunch, with the other
side bearing all the risk. Anxious to defend the purity of the
concept of public borrowing, the Treasury was reluctant to give
the seal of approval to a PFI scheme which involved any
public-sector risk. Meanwhile, private companies were equally
keen to design PFI projects which left as much risk as possible
in public hands. </p>
<p>On both sides, the debate has moved on. In its latest
handbook, the Treasury makes the crucial statement that &quot;the
aim is to achieve optimum risk allocation, not transfer for its
own sake&quot;. </p>
<p>Of course, that leaves plenty of scope for argument as to who
should &quot;optimally&quot; carry which kind of risk, and the
detail of the Treasury handbook makes it clear how much it
believes to be the private sector's business: design and
construction risk, taxation risk, project financing, most
operating risks, even regulatory risk if it is general in its
application. </p>
<h4>Paying for policy</h4>
<p>The only two categories which the Treasury leaves
unequivocally in the Government's court are the risk of criticism
(since the Home Office cannot escape the flak if something goes
amiss in a privately-run prison) or of a wrongly specified
requirement. Nevertheless, the Treasury has now opened the debate
on the allocation of other kinds of risk - and formally
acknowledged that government should carry the risk for some
policy-related shifts in demand. The ground rules for the debate
have therefore been more clearly established. Economic tools can
be used to apply them to individual projects with greater
certainty, efficiency - and speed. </p>
<p><b>Contacts: Sarah Hogg and Bill Robinson</b> </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1996 </p>
</body>
