<DOCNO>WT11-B06-138</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA036-000712-B023-211</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.londecon.co.uk:80/pubs/trans/tunnel.htm 194.193.150.111 19970111020535 text/html 9900
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 11 Jan 1997 02:00:14 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 9729
Last-modified: Sat, 14 Sep 1996 15:10:48 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Tunnelling for the Truth</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Tunnelling for the Truth</h2>
<p><strong><i>Despite substantial setbacks, services through the
Channel tunnel are now in operation. Eurostar is an attractive
new alternative mode on one of the most travelled air routes in
the world. Le Shuttle provides a smooth alternative to ferries
for holiday makers. These new market entrants provide a serious
challenge to the incumbents. Tunnelling for the truth about how
competition will unfold is a serious challenge to economists.
London Economics reports from the cutting edge.</i></strong></p>
<hr>
<p>The Channel tunnel is one of the greatest engineering feats of
all time. But its construction and launch have been severely
troubled. It cost about &#163;1.5bn more to build than was
predicted. Train engines have been catching fire; and the day the
press were invited to try the Eurostar service to Paris, the
train was an hour late leaving Waterloo International.
Shareholders have been talking up their free trips as
Eurotunnel's share price has sunk almost to the depths of the
tunnel itself. </p>
<p>But the troubles are increasingly becoming a thing of the
past, as <i>Le Shuttle</i> and Eurostar's services begin to
approach full operational levels. Leaving aside freight, the
Channel tunnel serves two markets: one for cars (and their
contents) and one for passengers. The former are mostly families
on holidays, whose main priority is to cross cheaply. The latter
are mostly businessmen and women, whose main priority is to get
to their destination quickly. </p>
<p>Until recently Union Railways was a subsidiary of British
Rail. Its job was to award the licence to build and operate the
fast link from London to the tunnel. It asked London Economics to
research the medium and longterm future of the crosschannel
market, focusing on questions such as: </p>
<ul>
    <li>How will the airlines respond to competition with
        Eurostar? </li>
    <li>Will there be a price war? </li>
    <li>How will the market carve up in 2000 and beyond? </li>
</ul>
<h4>Likely scenarios</h4>
<p>But first the carmarket. Time is not allimportant, and market
shares will mainly be determined by price. <i>Le Shuttle</i> is
not prone to the vagaries of the channel weather (as its &quot;35
minutes <i>flat</i>&quot; advertisement emphasises) but the ferry
offers an agreeable break from the car. There are question marks
in the public's mind about the safety of both modes. How the
market divides will depend largely on pricing policies. It is
clear that the tunnel operators, totally committed to the market
by their huge sunk costs, will be formidable competitors. They
have lower marginal costs than the ferries, and can afford to
undercut the competition. As their novelty value dwindles, they
may elect to do so. </p>
<p>Competition between air and Eurostar in the passenger market
is even more intriguing. In 1993, 4.8 million people flew between
London and Paris or Brussels. Eurostar's potential capacity is
around 25 million. Even though much of this is off peak, it must
be enough to start airlines worrying. </p>
<p>In 1991, London to Paris traffic comprised about 20% of
passengers making connecting flights (&quot;interlining&quot;),
and the other 80% split evenly between business and leisure.
London to Brussels traffic was about 20% interlining passengers,
60% business, and 20% leisure. Of course, revenues will be much
higher from business travellers. So business travellers are going
to hold the key to this market. </p>
<p>The service Eurostar offers is potentially very attractive,
particularly to business travellers. It is a smooth,
uninterrupted, 3 hour journey (2.5 hours when the fast link is
complete) from city centre to city centre. To a business
traveller, this is potential for 3 hours of work. The journey by
air, as well as being longer overall, is broken into several
segments: from city to airport, then the flight, then the
connection at the other end. Not much chance of getting any work
done, even on a day when nothing goes wrong. </p>
<p>The success of the TGV against air on similar length journeys
in the ParisLyon corridor will do nothing to alleviate airlines'
concerns: on shorthaul trips such as these, rail has clear
advantages over air. </p>
<h4>The airlines' response</h4>
<p>It would seem that the airlines have got to think hard about
their competitive strategy. One possibility is to compete with
Eurostar on price, in order to fight for market share. If this
happens, marginal costs will be crucial. Eurostar has the
advantage here: the marginal cost per passenger on a train is
lower than on an aeroplane. So it would seem likely that Eurostar
will fare better in a price war. </p>
<p>The table shows how much it costs to travel from London to
Paris at the moment. Eurostar is offering business travellers a
cheaper deal; air and rail economy fares are very similar. These
are early days. We would expect to see air fares fall as
Eurostar's operation comes up to speed, and its market share
begins to build. </p>
<p>Airlines could cut their marginal costs by offering a nofrills
shuttle service. This becomes increasingly likely as competition
within the air sector heats up, and the cheaper fringe airlines
become stronger competitive forces. In this situation, Eurostar
would become the premium brand, with air offering a cheaper, but
nastier, alternative. This scenario would look good for Eurostar,
since business travellers are not too worried about how much they
pay, as long as they get to their destinations quickly. The
airlines would in effect be concentrated on the nonbusiness
market, including their captive market of interlining passengers. </p>
<p>Capacity constraints could be a saving grace for airlines.
Business travellers tend to want to travel at the beginning or
end of the working day. Although Eurostar has a large overall
capacity, there is a limit to the number of trains it can supply
at these times. </p>
<h4>Estimation and modelling</h4>
<p>We wanted a model that would enable us to simulate scenarios
such as these. But how does one estimate traffic in a market with
a completely new product, for which there are no data on which to
base a model? The approach commonly used by transport economists
is to use the socalled Logit demand model, which is normally
based on the `revealed preferences of actual travellers'. But
when a new mode is involved, data have to be collected via market
research, by asking passengers whether they would choose, say,
Eurostar or air, given a number of characteristics of each,
including time and price. </p>
<p>Logit is good at handling data from such surveys, and the
resulting models are full of detail on journeys between many
originating points and destinations, and on many different market
segments. However, the model can generate counterintuitive
results that are not applicable in practice. Moreover, this
approach focuses mainly on demand, taking little account of
supplyside behaviour. </p>
<p>To get round this, London Economics built a model that </p>
<ul>
    <li>is firmly based in economic theory; </li>
    <li>takes into account both demand and supply; </li>
    <li>shows what might happen in the market without drowning
        the user in a sea of detail; and </li>
    <li>can simulate different competitive scenarios within modes
        of transport. </li>
</ul>
<p>We simulated the strategic responses of the modes as they
competed with one another. These &quot;reaction functions&quot;
show how airlines will choose to set their prices in response to
the price set by Eurostar, and vice versa, as they seek to
maximise profits given the underlying characteristics of demand,
and the cost structure they face. </p>
<p>The model allows us to vary the important assumptions
concerning competition <i>within</i> each mode. It can therefore
simulate an outcome of an increasingly competitive air sector
competing with a monopoly Eurostar service. Or it can simulate
how competition within the rail sector might affect competition
between air and rail. This becomes relevant following the
European Court's decision to force BR and SNCF to hand over 25%
of their tunnel capacity to other operators who are prepared to
pay for it. The London Economics model suggests that an
oligopolostic airline market will mean that Eurostar is cheaper
than air travel (as it is now), whereas a competitive air market
would lead to Eurostar pricing at a relative premium. </p>
<p>However the market develops in the near future, Eurostar will
become even more attractive when the fast link is completed
(probably around 2002/3). Two things seem certain: consumers on
both sides of the Channel who do not suffer from tunnelphobia are
bound to gain; airlines are bound to reconsider their strategy.
Is the LondonParis link essential because of the interconnections
it provides on airlines' wider networks? Or are there more
profitable uses for their scarce takeoff and landing slots? As
the market develops, we will be using the London Economics model
to investigate questions like these. </p>
<p><i>Contact: Stephen Banks<br>
Robert Laslett<br>
Alberto Pototschnig</i> </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1995 </p>
</body>
</html>
