<html>
<head>
<title>Drought in the Rain</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Drought in the Rain</h2>
<p><i>As the rain falls its usual intensity over most of England
this winter, thoughts of drought and hose-pipe bans seem out of
place. Incongruous as it seems however water companies throughout
the South of England are spending this winter devising ways to
cope with water shortages.</i></p>
<hr>
<p>Recent drought increased demands for water, while preventing
the replenishment of the underground aquifers that supply much of
the South's water. This winter's rain may fill the rivers, but it
will take time before the aquifers are back to their normal
levels. Population and economic growth have increased demand,
while water supply remains relatively fixed. </p>
<p>Forecasting water demand over the 20-30 year planning horizon
needed for investments in reservoirs and similar long-lived
assets is a difficult business, and many companies have been
surprised by the fall-off in demand resulting from the recession.
Nevertheless, on current projections and policies, water
shortages in the South are likely to get worse, not better. </p>
<p>The traditional response to water shortages have been to build
new reservoirs, or increase the amount of water taken from rivers
and aquifers. Concerns about preserving the countryside and the
flow of rivers have prompted companies to widen the options they
consider, in an attempt to find the most efficient and
environmentally friendly way of keeping water demand and supply
in balance. </p>
<p>Some companies are considering installing more water meters to
reduce demand. Large investment programmes have pushed up water
bills recently, but customers have no incentive to save water,
using less will not be cheaper. Metering may seem an answer, but
the cost of universal metering is such that this doesn't seem to
make economic sense. </p>
<p>On the supply side companies are integrating their
distribution systems, so that shortages in one area can be met
with supplies from another. In many cases relatively small
investments could now link together large parts of the South's
supply system. There have been discussions of a water `National
Grid', to bring the North's plentiful supplies South, and British
Waterways have commissioned a study into using the canal network
for this purpose. </p>
<p>Reducing the amount of water which leaks out of the system
might allow companies to meet demand without building new
reservoirs or installing meters. Companies are reducing leakage
by speeding up mains-renewal, improving leak-detection, and
investing in pressure-reduction technology. But a substantial
part of leakage is from customers' own supply pipes. </p>
<p>With such diverse options to consider, all the water companies
in the South of England will spend the winter planning. The basis
of this must be sound forecasting demand. London Economics is
developing new methods of demand forecasting, using disaggregated
analysis rather than large econometric models or the
extrapolation of past trends. </p>
<p>Meeting forecast demand most efficiently is simple in theory.
Companies should develop the option with the lowest cost per
extra unit of water available. Over time this strategy would
bring the marginal costs of all options into line. Then companies
would be able to pursue a balanced mix of options. </p>
<p>The hard point is to measure the cost of supplying an extra
unit of water from building reservoirs and pipelines controlling
leakage or reducing consumption through metering. London
Economics has build software models which allow the complex
theoretical concepts involved to be translated into practical
reality. With these tools, water companies in the South are able
to tackle their problems with renewed accuracy and confidence. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Back to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1992 </p>
