<html>
<head>
<title>The Dash for Gas</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>The Dash for Gas</h2>
<p><i>Since the privatisation of the electricity industry in
1989/90, 8.6 GW of new gas fired power stations have been
commissioned. This represents some 15% of current total
generating capacity. At the same time, the plans of the old CEGB
for the construction of further coal-fired plant have been
shelved, and the closure of around 5GW of coal-fired generating
plant has been implemented or announced. The so-called &quot;dash
for gas&quot; is equally matched by a decline in demand for coal
in our power stations. </i></p>
<hr>
<p>At present, National Power and PowerGen purchase 65 million
tons of coal a year from British Coal. These contracts expire at
the end of March 1993. So far National Power and PowerGen have
offered to purchase only 30 million tons p.a. from British Coal,
with the balance of their reduced requirements made up from
imports. </p>
<p>The consequences for Britain's coal industry has prompted an
inquiry by the parliamentary Select Committee and an energy
policy review by the Department of Trade and Industry. In
addition, London Economics has been asked by the Office of
Electricity Regulation (Offer) to assess whether the contracts
signed by the Regional Electricity Companies for the purchase of
power from new gas fired stations are &quot;economic&quot;. The
RECs are responsible for 60% of the new gas-fired stations. </p>
<h4>The Pool</h4>
<p>The key problem for Offer, and the government, is that the
economics of the new gas-fired stations hinges on the comparable
costs of purchasing power from the Pool (the wholesale spot
market). But the Pool by itself does not provide competitively
determined bench-mark prices; it is dominated by National power
and PowerGen. </p>
<p>In this way, any review of the economics of the dash for gas
should necessarily turn into a review of the economics of power
generation more generally. But in so doing, the government must
choose between satisfying the coal-miners, the shareholders of
the generating companies and the RECs and the electricity
consumer. It hardly seems possible for the government to satisfy
all three. </p>
<hr>
