<html>
<head>
<title>Energy Strategy in the Former Soviet Union</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Energy Strategy in the Former Soviet Union</h2>
<p><i>One legacy of central planning is an economic structure
based on absurdly cheap energy. London Economics is working on
two large projects funded under the EC's programme of Technical
Assistance to the Commonwealth of Independent States (TACIS).
These help newlyindependent countries develop economic strategies
to raise their energy prices to world levels, and deal with the
farreaching economic consequences. The challenges are typical of
those facing many of the countries in the region.</i></p>
<hr>
<h4>The problem</h4>
<p>In the former Soviet Union, energy was traded internally at
prices far below world levels. This led to highly energyintensive
practices in: </p>
<ul>
    <li>industry, because energy saving investments which would
        have been worthwhile at world prices were not attractive;
        and </li>
    <li>households, because services like central heating were
        provided at a low fixed charge, and consumers had no
        control over them. </li>
</ul>
<p>The countries which emerged from the breakup of the USSR often
have good energy production technology. But their energy
suppliers are monopolists faced with quantitative supply goals
and no financial constraints. They have little incentive for
further improvement. </p>
<p>Russia, under pressure from international agencies and facing
macroeconomic problems, is attempting to maximise its hard
currency earnings from energy. It has moved towards a marketbased
energy sector. This puts pressure on other CIS countries to do
the same. </p>
<p>Energyimporting countries, such as the Baltic States and
Ukraine, are facing higher prices for imports, and have to pay in
hard currency. Their energy utilities are not financially viable,
so they are raising their output prices. This affects the
competitive position of industry, and hits lowincome households.
As demand falls, investment plans may need to be extensively
revised. </p>
<p>Energyexporting countries, such as Azerbaijan, Kazakhstan and
Turkmenistan, also face shocks. They depend on Russian pipelines
and ports for their access to markets. Only when alternatives
develop will they benefit fully from higher export prices and
attract foreign investment. And when they do, they may face the
&quot;Dutch disease&quot; of currencies overvalued by resource
exports making agricultural and manufacturing sectors unable to
compete. </p>
<h4>Towards a solution</h4>
<p>Marketbased prices for energy would help to correct the
incentive problems, but rapid price increases create problems of
their own: </p>
<ul>
    <li>where consumers have no control over consumption, they
        can be seriously overcharged. Some may refuse to pay, and
        widespread arrears develop; </li>
    <li>households may be too poor to afford full market prices
        in the short run, and may not be protected by existing
        social protection measures; and </li>
    <li>businesses may simply pass higher energy costs on to
        their consumers, or to the banks. </li>
</ul>
<p>So price reform has to be accompanied by analysis of: </p>
<ul>
    <li>its impact on consumers and the appropriate transition
        and protection measures; </li>
    <li>energy demand and its likely response to prices; </li>
    <li>institutional reforms necessary to give energy
        enterprises commercial freedom while ensuring effective
        regulation; and </li>
    <li>the economics of energy metering and conservation. </li>
</ul>
<h4>Typical LE projects</h4>
<p>One example is in a state which is an energy importer, with
the additional special problem of supply security, due to its
neartotal dependency on Russia for energy supplies for the
foreseeable future. Though relatively prosperous, higher energy
costs depress the level of economic activity. Sector reform is
crucial to the country's macroeconomic recovery. LE is leading a
comprehensive energy strategy study, to identify the best options
for investment, pricing and structural reform. The project
centres on the role of the electricity and district heating
systems. </p>
<p>Another project, by contrast, concerns a state which is moving
towards selfsufficiency in oil and net exports of gas. It has the
largest concentration of lowincome households of any of the newly
independent states, and is especially concerned about the impact
of energy prices on poor households. LE is leading work to
improve the analytical basis for assessing price impacts and for
targeting subsidies to the worst affected households. </p>
<h4>How LE can help</h4>
<p>LE offers the full range of skills needed for these global
projects. We have established strengths in the analysis of
economic pricing for energy systems, in the institutional reform
of the energy sector, and in the assessment of investment
strategies. We also offer skills in inputoutput analysis, needed
to assess effects on industry, and in social impact analysis. </p>
<p>London Economics has already worked on projects in Belarus,
Kazakhstan, Lithuania, Moldova, Ukraine, and Uzbekistan. We
expect to be able to apply these skills even more widely in the
region and elsewhere in the future. </p>
<p><i>Contact point: Robert Laslett</i> </p>
<hr>
