<html>
<head>
<title>Unleashing India's Power Sector</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Unleashing India's Power Sector</h2>
<p><strong><i>India was the archetypal nonaligned developing
country. Its historical links with the West through the British
Raj were balanced by the strong influence of the former Soviet
Union on its northern borders. So the Indian political economy
was a classic mixed economy with a strong dirigiste element in
certain sectors, notably power, which shares some but not all of
the problems of Eastern Europe. </i></strong></p>
<hr>
<p>However, the worldwide trend towards a more market oriented,
deregulated style of economic management has not passed India by.
Economic growth accelerated dramatically in the 1980s. The West
has, in its excitement about the economic potential of the Far
East, and more recently China, tended to overlook the Indian
success story. Yet, if it remains on its present growth path, the
Indian economy will (on a purchasing power basis) be larger than
Germany's before the year 2000. </p>
<p>In this brave new future, the structure of India's power
sector, run by State Electricity Boards (SEBs) since India's
Independence in 1948, is simply unsustainable. Electricity is
seriously underpriced and, as growth has accelerated, in
increasingly short supply. Expansion is an urgent priority, but
until new suppliers can be guaranteed an adequate return,
financing leastcost expansion will be problematic. </p>
<p>This is the background ag ainst which LE is applying its know
ledge of India, and of power sector re structuring world wide, to
advise one of the largest and most efficient SEBs as it
transforms itself into a marketoriented corporation. </p>
<h4>Power of the State</h4>
<p>Since 1948, the generation, transmission and distribution of
electricity in India have been with few exceptions reserved for
the public sector. The SEBs' mandate is to supply electricity in
an economical and efficient manner, with particular reference to
areas not adequately supplied. But their Boards, appointed by
State Governments, have sweeping powers to intervene in their
prices and op erations. They have used them to undertake am
bitious programmes of rural elec trification with sub sidised
power for agricultural users. In the Punjab, over half of
electricity is sold to agricultural consumers. </p>
<p>This has distorted incentives for instance encouraging
industry to relocate in rural areas. It has also penalised the
SEBs financially. Many of them failed to meet their target of a
3% return on assets, and some are technically bankrupt. Links to
other state companies particularly Coal India have increased
costs and undermined operational performance. And the SEBs have
not been able to combat problems of network losses and nonpayment
by consumers. </p>
<p>All this has resulted in widespread dissatisfaction with the
power system. In a recent survey of households in Bangalore,
under 10% were satisfied with the level of service. They cited as
major irritants supply shortages, excess billing and lack of
communication with the SEB. </p>
<h4>New directions</h4>
<p>As India began to experience more rapid economic growth in
recent years, under the stimulus of government deregulation and
privatisation initiatives, these arrangements came under further
strain. India's power sector has to change, or it will constrain
an economy that has grown at over 5% a year since 1980. </p>
<p>As in many other countries, the ob stacle to change has been
shortage of cash. With their current prices, the SEBs cannot
afford the billions of dollars needed to finance new power
plants. Nor can private investors such as independent power
producers (IPPs) be attracted into the sector without guarantees
from the Central Government itself. </p>
<p>To solve this problem, the government has started to
experiment with restructuring the power sector, to allow the SEBs
freedom to operate in a commercial manner, setting prices that
will remunerate private investors in the sector. Obviously such a
transition cannot be undertaken without serious analysis and
consideration, as the attendant price changes could severely
affect existing power users. </p>
<h4>The three Rs</h4>
<p>LE has gained a wide knowledge of the opportunities and
pitfalls in the &quot;three Rs&quot;: restructuring, regulation
and reform of prices the key issues in the electricity sector.
This knowledge has been gained from our work over a wide range of
countries from the UK, Norway and other countries in Western
Europe through to the newlyprivatised power sectors of Chile,
Bolivia and Peru. In several of these countries, we are helping
to assess the situation for private investors. </p>
<p>Our extensive portfolio of projects in the Indian power sector
ranges from an analysis of long term issues, conducted for the
World Bank in 1991, through to current work on distribution
projects for the Power Finance Corporation with the ODA. LE has
therefore built up an awareness of the typical problems of the
SEBs. </p>
<p>In particular, we know that any structure must be designed
around the particular needs of the country in question.
Consultants all too often recommend the wholesale import of ideas
developed for entirely different contexts. The immediate
importation of electricity spot markets would be inappropriate to
a country like India, where electricity is rationed, there is one
dominant fuel supplier, and grid discipline is weak. LE
understands why such &quot;solutions&quot; do not work. </p>
<p>So we felt confident, when we were approached earlier this
year by one of the largest and most efficient of the SEBs, that
we would be able to throw useful light on their problems, and
suggest solutions of real value. These will have to include
reductions in the level of political control, to reassure private
investors that they will not face intervention. They will also
have to address the issue of electricity prices. </p>
<p>Previous attempts to reduce the State Government's role in
price setting have met with little success. The task is to design
a form of independent price regulation that will work in India,
giving incentives for efficiency, and providing real autonomy for
the regulator. </p>
<p>The challenge for LE is to ensure that this project and others
like it in India will have a real influence on policy. If that
aim can be met, our analysis will avoid the fate of the many
consultancy studies on India's power sector which are now
gathering dust on shelves in Delhi. </p>
<p><i>Contact point: Jamie Carstairs</i> </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1995 </p>
