<html>
<head>
<title>Dealing with Challenges in Australia</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>Dealing with Challenges in Australia</h2>
<p><b><i>Five different Governments, covering a population the
size of greater London in a continent larger than the United
States: that is the challenge posed by Australia.</i></b></p>
<hr>
<p>London Economics began work in Australia in 1992, setting up
an Australian office with a staff of 2. Today the Australian
office has a full time staff of 8, led by Managing Director Sam
Lovick, and Deputy Director Danny Price. From our Melbourne
office we provide economic consulting services throughout
Australia and New Zealand. </p>
<p>We work hand in glove with our London colleagues. Modern
technology allows us to be in constant communication despite the
18,000 miles that separate us. There is a constant interchange of
staff, skills and experience from both sides. For example, our
advanced modelling skills are used in our London office, and we
benefit from the London office's experience of regulatory
periodic reviews. </p>
<p>Australia is undergoing a period of utility reform not unlike
the UK experience of the 1980s. But many of the issues are unique
to Australia. Imagine, for example, constructing an electricity
pool from 5 independent state systems; or encouraging competition
in telecommunications where distances are so vast. </p>
<h4>The case of Pacific Power</h4>
<p>Pacific Power, the New South Wales generator, is Australia's
largest generator with one third of all capacity. The NSW
Government was concerned about its ability to exercise market
power in the proposed pool, and asked LE Australia how to deal
with it. </p>
<p>LE Australia tested their likely behaviour using game theory.
This was done by including Nash gaming capabilities in our
electricity market model, PoolMod. This is the first time such an
approach has been used to solve a practical problem in a
transmission constrained electricity system. </p>
<p>The results were unambiguous - Pacific Power has market power
in all cases. We concluded that the best way to deal with this
issue of market power is to split Pacific Power into a number of
competing generators. And it looks as though the NSW Government
will follow our recommendations. </p>
<h4>It isn't all utilities ...</h4>
<p>The Australian Government was concerned about whether it was
spending its money wisely in the charitable sector, and asked us
to find out. Is the money going to the most efficient charities? </p>
<p>It was challenging! What are the outputs of a charity? How
should we think about the charities' inputs? What is the best way
to compare a large number of individual and distinct
organisations carrying out a multitude of tasks? </p>
<p>We found the answer in Data Envelopment Analysis (DEA). This
economic performance indicator allowed us to take into account
special features of the charitable sector, such as the variety of
services they offered, factors that might make a particular
charity's work more difficult, and the quality of the care
offered. And the conclusion: for charities above a certain size,
the more money they receive from the Australian Government the
less efficient they are likely to be. Larger charities that
depend on private donations are more likely to be efficient. </p>
<p><b>Contact: Sam Lovick, London Economics Australia</b> </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Back to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1996 </p>
</body>
</html>
