<html>
<head>
<title>California's new frontiers</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>California's new frontiers</h2>
<p><b><i>As 1995 ended, the Public Utilities Commission of
California set out its long-awaited vision for the future of the
power industry in America's largest state. As 1996 has
progressed, London Economics has found itself increasingly
involved in the design of competitive power markets in the United
States.</i></b> </p>
<hr>
<p>The Energy Policy Act of 1992 set the scene for the
long-awaited reform of the power industry in the United States.
The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission then began developing
plans requiring all private electric utilities to open up
transmission access. </p>
<p>The centrepiece of the Californian vision is the introduction
of consumer choice through the establishment of a Power Exchange
to facilitate open competition among generators. This is now a
fairly standard element in power sector reform, not just in the
UK but also in New Zealand, Australia, Argentina and Scandinavia.
However the US approach, while potentially solving some problems
not yet properly tackled in these earlier examples of reform,
also throws up some interesting new issues. </p>
<h4>Transition costs</h4>
<p>The transition to competitive markets exposes the
uncompetitiveness of many of the inherited assets constructed
under a more lenient regulatory regime. In the United Kingdom,
the asset values of the Central Electricity Generating Board were
written down prior to privatisation of the successor companies.
British Gas currently finds itself exposed to substantial
liabilities from its commitment to gas purchase contracts which
were signed before the introduction of competition in gas
retailing, and which are no longer competitively priced. </p>
<p>However these inherited problems are dwarfed by some estimates
of the costs of uneconomic generation, contracts and other
regulatory assets in California. The utilities themselves have
suggested costs as high as $30 bn, while other more conservative
estimates have still reached figures of around $10 bn. These
estimates compare with a market capitalisation for National Power
of around $8 bn. </p>
<p>Determining the exact scale of the costs of transition to
competition in California and deciding how they should be split
between consumers and shareholders are issues which will cloud
the vision of competitively priced power for many years to come. </p>
<p>American free-market culture is forcing out the frontiers of
accepted practices in power market liberalisation. Many industry
participants were horrified to learn that in power markets such
as Britain, generators are compelled to sell all their power into
the Pool (the United Kingdom's own spot market for electricity). </p>
<p>This they saw as an unacceptable constraint on commercial
freedoms. So in California, the Public Utility Commission has
proposed the continuation of a bilateral contract market between
generator and final consumer, alongside a voluntary Power
Exchange. Moreover, to emphasise the voluntary nature of the
Power Exchange, it will be separate from the Independent System
Operator (who, given the physical characteristics of electricity,
must have sole responsibility for matching supply and demand
minute by minute over the network). </p>
<p>Norway provides the only example of a bilateral contract
market existing alongside a daily spot market. But in Norway
hydropower accounts for virtually all generation, which means
that balancing supply and demand at the margin is a simple matter
of water release. This allows easy co-ordination of the contract
and spot markets. The problems of co-ordination in a
predominantly thermal-based system are only just beginning to be
realised. </p>
<h4>Trading between regional markets</h4>
<p>The reforms in California are only the first steps towards a
wider liberalisation of power markets across all of the US.
Market liberalisation will allow generators full access to the
markets of neighbouring and even more distant states. This opens
up significant trading opportunities. For example, utilities as
far away as British Columbia are already sizing up the potential
to profit from their low-cost hydro output by selling it into the
new California Power Exchange. </p>
<p>Other players in the United States have been quick to see that
the scale and risks associated with these trades present
opportunities for them as well. In January, NYMEX received
regulatory approval to trade electricity futures and options
based on delivery at the Palo Verde switchyard in Arizona and on
delivery at the California-Oregon border. Trading electricity in
the United States will be quite unlike trades in the much more
constrained British market. </p>
<h4>Implementing reform</h4>
<p>Lastly, the reform process itself in the US will be quite
unlike that of other countries which have liberalised their power
markets. In the United Kingdom, New Zealand, Argentina and
Australia, the government owned 100% of the industry undergoing
reform. As a result, the government was itself able to have the
final say on the detailed implementation of the reform and so
speed the process along. In the United States, ownership of the
industry is mainly private sector. Moreover reforms have to be
sanctioned not just by the Public Utility Commissions but also by
state legislatures and the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
Gaining approval of the final reform package is likely to prove
to be a tortuous process. </p>
<h4>Global ambitions</h4>
<p>The new focus on competition will no doubt further stoke the
ambitions of American electric utilities and other industry
participants in the global push towards private finance and
operation of power systems. American electric utilities have
already purchased a British regional electricity company and
distribution and generation assets in Australia, New Zealand,
Britain and Germany. </p>
<p>American companies are also major investors in private power
development worldwide: in India, China, Indonesia, Chile and
elsewhere in the developing world. </p>
<h4>LE's role</h4>
<p>London Economics is currently assisting utilities in
California and across the United States to understand how
competitive power markets work, and how best to develop their own
plans and strategies for the new market. </p>
<p>Our new Boston office is providing on-going advice for two of
the largest utilities in the United States, Pacific Gas and
Electric and Duke Power, and assistance to other American
electricity companies on purchasing major assets elsewhere in the
world, notably in the United Kingdom and Australia. </p>
<p><b>Contact: Robin Cohen</b> </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Back to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1996 </p>
</body>
</html>
