<head>
<title>The Case for Twelve</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="../../images/backgrnd.jpg" text="#000080">
<h2>The Case for Twelve</h2>
<p><em><strong>In November 1987, LE completed a landmark report
for the twelve electricity area boards. Most of them - indeed, 11
out of 12 - wished to challenge the prevailing notion that they
should be privatised en bloc. LE provided them with the economic
ammunition.</strong></em></p>
<hr>
<p>The report advanced a series of arguments as to why separate
flotation would benefit customers, the regions and the
electricity distribution industry. It replicated analysis of
American utilities, which had shown that economic efficiency did
not depend simply on size. Other factors, such as customer
density, were more important. LE refuted the common argument that
a fragmented distribution industry would be at a bargaining
disadvantage relative to the generators, arguing that the
distribution companies would hold the balance of power because
they would control access to consumers. So far as generation was
concerned, the terms of access to the Grid would be crucial.
&#147;Boards wishing to enter large-scale generation will not be
disadvantaged if they are small in terms of their asset base:
risks can be spread by joining consortia.&#148;<img
src="../../images/elect12.gif" align="right" hspace="0"
width="222" height="222"></p>
<p>More positively, the report argued that the regions would gain
- as they did in the United States - from the presence of large
utility companies rooted in, and contributing to, the local
economy. And, most strongly of all, LE advanced the arguments
based on competition: even if the companies were not direct
competitors, yardstick comparisons between them would be a spur
to performance - and could be deployed by the regulator, who
could rule on prices more effectively if he was able to compare
the costs and efficiency gains of 12 companies.</p>
<p>So, LE pointed out, the main arguments for an amalgamated
sell-off were derived from &#147;the financial problems
associated with multiple flotations, not from a consideration of
economic efficiency and benefits to the consumer&#148;; and
concluded that these were perfectly soluble: if 10 water
authorities (which it had already been decided to privatise
separately), why not 12 electricity boards? &#147;The City should
confront these problems for the sake of the industry and all
electricity consumers.&#148; For those, or its own good reasons,
that in the end is, of course, just what the City did.</p>
<p>When LE was working on this report, the Energy Secretary had
indicated that it was highly unlikely that the industry would be
privatised as a single entity. But most of the argument had
focused on the generating side, with much less attention paid to
distribution. It was broadly assumed that the boards would be
bundled into a single holding company, or at most a small number
of amalgamated distributors. &#147;The Case for 12&#148; helped
to break the bundle - if not the mould - of electricity
privatisation. </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="../../index.html">[Return to Home Page]</a></p>
<p>&#169; Copyright London Economics 1996 </p>
</body>
</html>
